<HEADLINE>
SOWARD GOES TO JAGUARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC receiver R. Jay Soward is all about speed, and
last winter was no exception. Soward spent four months running
furious 40-yard dashes for NFL scouts _ and running away from his
past. Inconsistent and temperamental with the Trojans, he knew the
fastest way into the first round of Saturday's NFL Draft was to
show maturity and dedication during the scouting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew NFL people had questions about my work ethic,'' Soward
said. ``So I made sure to prove them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward made a believer of Jacksonville, which selected him with
the 29th pick of the first round. He'll play for one of the
league's best coaches, Tom Coughlin, and alongside one of the top
quarterbacks, Mark Brunell. He'll join a Super Bowl contender in a
warm-weather city with a former Trojan, tackle Tony Boselli, on the
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony and I don't know each other personally, but we know of
each other and we've sent messages through other people,'' said
Soward, who joined USC guard Travis Claridge (second round) as the
only local players selected Saturday. ``I'm thrilled about playing
with him. The draft went the way I wanted. It was a great day.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5-9 and 177 pounds, Soward is small and not very strong.
Buthe has blazing speed, he can return punts and kicks, and he has
a knack for big plays. During practices for the Senior Bowl and the
East-West Shrine game _ and at the important NFL Scouting Combine
in February _ he was disciplined, hard-working and humble. He ran
precise routes and eliminated the drops that plagued his USC
career. He also ran a blazing 40-yard dash (4.32 seconds, he said)
during a personal workout for Coughlin at USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is that it's impossible to replicate
speed like his, and it's hard to find someone with the double
ability to be a returner and a receiver,'' said Soward's agent,
Leigh Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing standing between R. Jay and going even higher
(in the first round) was a question about his work habits. But he
handled the scouting process beautifully. The entire procedure
consisted of him being reliable. He really dedicated himself, and
he did a terrific job. He went a long way towards restoring himself
as a first-round pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward scored 23 touchdowns and averaged 16.6 yards per catch at
USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted more playmakers,'' Coughlin told ESPN. ``We felt
like (Soward) was a key acquisition.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville was one of the teams interested in Claridge, who
instead went to Atlanta with the sixth pick of the second round
(37th overall). Claridge played guard for three years at USC, then
switched to tackle for his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Falcons asked me what I wanted to play,'' Claridge said.
``I told them I'd play whatever position would get me on the field
the fastest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little surprised about Atlanta. I had a lot of
indication that Jacksonville would take me, but they took R. Jay
instead.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA receiver Danny Farmer, expected to go in the middle rounds,
was not drafted Saturday. He'll probably be selected this morning
in either the fourth or fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny's only problem was he was compared to (Denver's) Ed
McCaffrey,'' said Steinberg, who also represents Farmer and
Claridge. ``There's a tendency to stereotype some receivers as big
and slow, but Danny ran well in individual workouts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
