<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS RUN OUT OF GAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It finally caught up to them -- the two months of
spring training, the cross-country road trip into Montreal and New
York, and the San Francisco series made longer by the suspended
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were due for a letdown, and although Gary Sheffield
and Eric Gagne did their best to delay it, it was unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Taubensee's career-high-tying four RBI, coming on a home
run and double, offset Sheffield's three-run homer and lifted
Cincinnati to a5-4 victory before 51,179.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us probably slept too much last night trying to
regroup,'' manager Davey Johnson said. ``It was still a heck of a
well played ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers entered the game having won five in a row and
batting .276, third-best in the league. Sheffield had hit in all
previous 10 games this season and 16 in a row dating back to Sept.
25. His fifth-inning three-run shot off starter Denny Neagle
extended that.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first eight innings Saturday, the Dodgers managed
just five hits against four Reds pitchers, including just one
between the sixth and eighth. Sheffield's shot was the only hit in
nine at-bats for the 3-4-5 hitters, to go with five walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers awoke in the ninth with two hits and a run off Danny
Graves, and they had Devon White at third with two out. But Graves
earned his -- and the team's -- first save by getting Shawn Green
to ground out (ending his nine-game hit streak) and, after walking
Sheffield, retiring Eric Karros on a grounder to second.
</P>
<P>
   The winning pitcher, Scott Williamson (1-1), struck out two of
the three batters he faced. He relieved Neagle, who gave up four
hits with five walks and five strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Alan Mills (0-1) gave up two runs on Taubensee's
seventh-inning double.
</P>
<P>
   Taubensee is showing Mike Piazza isn't the only catcher who can
bat cleanup. He batted fourth a team-high 64 times in 1998 and,
although never batting in that spot last year, hit 21 homers and
drove in 87 runs, both highs for a catcher since Johnny Bench's 24
homers in 1980 and 109 RBI in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pretty good clutch hitter,'' Reds manager Jack McKeon
said.``He's one of the guys who gets hot for a week or two and
carries you.''
</P>
<P>
   This type of performance was just what the Reds needed, since
Ken Griffey Jr. had been driving in most of the runs. Griffey had
14 RBI in eight games but failed to drive in a run for the second
straight game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow, (Taubensee) will be there, I know that,'' McKeon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Dodger not showing signs of fatigue was starter Gagne,
which was understandable since was in Albuquerque until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He originally was slated as the team's fourth starter, but after
going 0-2 with a 15.63 ERA this spring, Gagne found himself
demoted. He threw six shutout innings in his one start for the
Dukes, then got the call after Kevin Brown broke a pinky.
</P>
<P>
   His performance Saturday is what the Dodgers wanted from him all
along: five innings, three hits, two earned runs, three walks and
five strikeouts. His one blemish was a first-inning home run to
Taubensee, who became just the eighth player to homer into the
second deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing was to go back to Triple-A,'' Gagne said,
``just to my thinking back together, get positive and throw the
ball like I could.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
