<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ'S ABSENCE PROVES HIS WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's a good thing Shaquille O'Neal sat out a game
this week, because without him, everyone got to see how closely the
Lakers resemble... the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who doubted that O'Neal is the hands-down winner for Most
Valuable Player should have been convinced by how average the
Lakers looked without him.
</P>
<P>
   He is on his way to becoming the first NBA player since Wilt
Chamberlain to lead the league in scoring and rebounding since the
1962-63 season. He even might have won the award if Michael Jordan
had played this season. Well, let's not go too far.
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal leading the way, let's hand out some season-ending
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Most Valuable Player: O'Neal. Not even a close call. Other
players had stellar seasons, like Utah's Karl Malone, Miami's
Alonzo Mourning and Detroit's Grant Hill, but they were all playing
in O'Neal's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the Year: Elton Brand, Bulls. No one gave Brand much
respect in November, but he's left every other rookie in the dust,
capped off by his 44-point effort this week. He's the only rookie
averaging a double-double (19.5 points, 10.0 rebounds) and he's
been far more consistent than the two runners-up: Rockets point
guard Steve Francis and Clippers forward Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the Year: Phil Jackson, Lakers. OK, maybe he wouldn't
be doing much if he coached in Vancouver, but the guy knows how to
handle pampered superstars. He found a way to get Shaq and Kobe to
co-exist, and has even managed to keep Glen Rice in line. It's a
far cry from last year's finger-pointing and underachieving.
</P>
<P>
   The shame of awarding Jackson this honor is that it overlooks
what Doc Rivers did in Orlando. He's got little real talent but has
somehow turned the Magic into a playoff contender. Utah's Jerry
Sloan deserves honorable mention for keeping the Jazz among the
NBA's elite, even though the team was written off for being too
old.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth Man: Rodney Rogers, Suns. Let's see, he was 35 pounds
overweight last season with the Clippers but has resurrected his
career in Phoenix. What changed? Probably the fact he joined a
first-class organization dedicated to winning. Nah, that couldn't
be it.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Jerome Williams gave the Pistons a boost but wasn't as
consistent as Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Most Improved Player: Dirk Nowitzki, Mavericks. The German
wunderkind finally lived up to his hype this season (17.8 ppg),
although not in time to save Don Nelson's job. He has become a more
talented version of Toni Kukoc, although he's too soft defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Others deserving consideration were Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse
and Vancouver's Michael Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive Player of the Year: Alonzo Mourning, Heat. They play
defense in this league? Mourning leads the NBA in blocked shots,
even though he's a 6-9 center. Seattle's Gary Payton remains the
best defensive guard, but he doesn't take the physical beating
Mourning withstands on a nightly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Executive of the Year: Glen Grunwald, Raptors. He convinced
Charles Oakley to re-sign last summer, didn't trade Tracy McGrady
during the season and didn't fire coach Butch Carter. All of those
moves make the Raptors a lot more than Vince Carter, and gives
Toronto a great chance to win at least one round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Truth patrol: Charles Barkley debuted his new Internet talk show
this week on Nike.com, complete with studio and guests.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Barkley to show why he was one of the
most refreshing voices in the NBA. Here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   On Indiana coach Bobby Knight: ``I just want him to grab the
wrong person one day. I would pay a million dollars for him to grab
me. Then, I'd beat him to a pulp.''
</P>
<P>
   He blamed NBA commissioner David Stern for the decline in
television ratings: ``He's over-marketed the league. He's got too
many young players who aren't ready for prime time.... The league
has made a star out of every player who thinks he can play. Vince
Carter is a nice kid and has a lot of talent. But NBC can't make
him Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   He criticized the league for being too happy to select Carter
for the Olympic team after Tom Gugliotta was injured. ``Stern did
cartwheels when Gugliotta hurt his knee 'cause he could put Carter
on the team. That noise y'all heard wasn't MIR (the Russian space
station) crashing. That was the league office in New York cheering
when poor Tom went down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bold move: Paul Westphal's ``Mr. Nice Guy'' image took a hit in
Seattle, but earned him a lot more respect as a coach, after he
benched starters Vin Baker, Brent Barry and Ruben Patterson before
this week's game with Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal inserted second-year players Rashard Lewis and Shammond
Williams and someone named Lazaro Borrell into the Sonics' lineup.
Seattle promptly went out and beat the Timberwolves by 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just lost nine of 11 and I thought we needed to shake
things up,'' Westphal said. ``Vin's been taking a lot of criticism
and he hasn't been playing up to his expectations or anybody
else's. So sometimes if you change things, it might make a
difference and that's what we tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker did his best to hide his displeasure over being benched,
especially after a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect coach (Westphal),'' Baker said. ``The thing with me
is I'm a team player. It's more disappointing to me the way I've
been playing. But I'll be back in a couple of days. I'm not worried
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   No hope: The embarrassment known as the Clippers finally made
the cover of Sports Illustrated, under the headline ``The Worst
Franchise in Sports History.''
</P>
<P>
   A fan of the article was former Clipper Rodney Rogers of the
Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' Rogers said. ``The owner (Donald Sterling)
doesn't care. It's a hobby for him, and it will never change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
