<HEADER>
A8309 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR &LR;      04-16 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIELD TRIP TO THE CAPITAL
 OF GRATITUDE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By E.J. MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - It's not fair that I get to walk into Liz Duncan's
classroom at Valley View school and see the faces of her students.
</P>
<P>
   It should be you.
</P>
<P>
   But you're busy earning a living, and the kids want to say
thanks to someone before they leave. All I have to do to free up
some time is ignore the world's rotten news for a little while,
which is easy.
</P>
<P>
   It's lunch hour Friday when I arrive. Pizza boxes are stacked on
a table just inside the classroom. Before we get there, we can
smell the pepperoni and hear soda cans popping and the sounds of
seventh- and eighth-grade boys and girls laughing and talking.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan has met me near the princi pal's office at Valley View, a
small elementary school tucked away in the low desert of south
Phoenix, from which the skyscrapers of downtown have slipped below
the horizon like the masts of tall ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are really excited,'' Liz says.
</P>
<P>
   She opens the door, and in a big, smiling chorus the students
say, ``Thank you!''
</P>
<P>
   You're the one who should be hearing this, not me. All I did was
tell you about them.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Duncan's class, a mix of main stream students and those with
physical and mental difficulties, was trying to collect enough
money to go on a field trip to Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost was $27,000. The students had spent every weekend
and many school nights since Octo ber operating carwashes and
holding raffles and setting up bake sales.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, as the deadline for making their final payment ap
proached, the class was still $6,000 short.
</P>
<P>
   Liz called to tell me about her students and how hard they'd
worked and how great they were. And I told you.
</P>
<P>
   By 7 the morning the newspaper article appeared, 11 people had
telephoned Liz offering to help. By 8:30 a.m., there were 160
calls, and pledges of nearly $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long after that, they'd erased the $6,000 deficit, with
enough extra cash to pay an unexpected $700 surcharge on the tour
package.
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't stop.
</P>
<P>
   People at a trucking company baked 40 cakes, drove Liz and 10
students to a truck stop, set up a bake sale and even bought the
children and their teacher breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Some high school students in Scotts dale donated money for
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   And more and more people tele phoned. Eventually, Liz Duncan's
class received enough donations to take three additional kids on
the trip, students who were new to the class.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Friday, their last day of school before the five-day
sight-see ing adventure in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many of you have never been on a plane before?'' Liz says.
Nearly half the students raise their hands. They'd be heading to
Washington early Sunday morning. To them, even the prospect of a
two-hour layover in Cleveland is exciting.
</P>
<P>
   All through lunch, they say how nice it was of people they've
never met to help them. They're polite and grate ful for all you've
done. They're happy, optimistic, curious about the world and still
under the wonderfully mistaken belief that the local com munity has
given them a gift _ when just the opposite is true.
</P>
<P>
   You'd know this if you could see them. As it is, the kids get
five days in Washington and I get an hour or so with them at Valley
View. Some snapshots are made before I leave of me and the kids and
their teacher. If I could, I'd send one of those pictures to each
of you with this note scribbled on back:
</P>
<P>
   Having a wonderful time. Wish you were here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
