r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     04-16 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY BEATS DALLAS 2-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Dallas couldn't of scripted a better scenario to end
its five-game losing streak against the Galaxy at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn, off to the best start in the MLS, faced a Galaxy cast
without five players, including starters Ezra Hendrickson (World
Cup qualifier), Simon Elliott (attending his sister's wedding), and
super-sub Sasha Victorine (U.S. U-23 Olympic training).
</P>
<P>
   But the Galaxy, boasting a bunch a reserves that would start on
many teams in the MLS, received a rare goal from rare starter Paul
Caligiuri early in the first half. Clint Mathis, playing
sensational the past few weeks, provided another goal in the second
half as Los Angeles held off the Burn, 2-1, Saturday in front of
16,244.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas striker Ariel Graziani provided a small scare, scoring in
the 83rd minute to cut the Galaxy's lead in half. He finished a mad
scramble in front of the net, but L.A. was able to hold on.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, which had trailed in their previous two matches
against New England and Columbus before rallying to earn draws,
remained unbeaten (3-0-2) to wrestle the MLS' best record away from
Dallas (3-2-0).
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid talked about the importance of getting
ahead early.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the last things we said in the locker room was that we
were not going to play catch-up this week,'' said Schmid. ``We were
going to score the first goal, score again and make our goals stand
up and impact the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set a goal that we wanted six points in this homestand. We
got three tonight and we want three more next week (against
Miami).''
</P>
<P>
   Caligiuri may have provided the early spark, but Galaxy
defenders Robin Fraser and Greg Vanney handled the dangerous duo of
Graziani and MLS MVP Jason Kreis, limiting the two strikers to rare
chances in front of the net before Graziani's late strike, his
fourth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Caligiuri, starting only his second game of the hear, handled a
beautiful free kick from Mauricio Cienfuegos to give the Galaxy a
1-0 lead in the 17th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, taking a free kick a few yards past the penalty area
to the left side, caught Dallas by surprise when he decided not to
take a shot on goal. Instead, Cienfuegos made eye contact with
Caligiuri, and as Caligiuri cut in front of the net, Cienfuegos
sent a quick pass in front. Caligiuri one-touched it running away
from the goal with the outside of his foot, barely sneaking the
ball inside the near post for his first goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play was something we work on in practice,'' said
Caligiuri. ``I couldn't believe they left the near space open
without a zonal player there. Mauricio put a great ball in there
and it was my job to finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Caligiuri, who helped with the game tying assist against
Columbus last week, is making the most of his limited minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for everyone when they get their opportunities
to capitalize and contribute to the team,'' he said. ``It means a
lot personally, but it's important to win our games at home,
especially against teams like Dallas who you figure to meet again
down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had a good chance to draw even in the 31st minute. Oscar
Pareja passed a ball back over his head in front of the Galaxy goal
for Chad Deering. Instead of looking for a shot, Deering headed the
ball across the goal area for Graziani, but the Argentine striker
headed his shot inches over the cross bar from a few yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had a few other chances to even the game, but the Galaxy
doubled its lead in the 65th minute as Mathis notched his third
goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   From just past midfield, Zak Ibsen sent a ball wide to Cobi
Jones. Jones, looking for cutters, spotted Mathis splitting two
Dallas defenders as he headed toward the goal. Jones hit Mathis on
the run and Mathis finished with a one-touch volley directly in
front of Dallas' net, freezing goalkeeper Matt Jordan, who had no
time to react.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
