<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8315 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-HNS &LR;      04-16 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cleveland adds a Brown; Redskins get Arrington, Samuels
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ The top portion of the NFL draft went according to form
until the New York Jets made the first of their record-setting four
No. 1 draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   On a Saturday when there were no first-round trades for the
first time in two decades, Oakland owner Al Davis pulled the
biggest surprise by using the 17th pick on Florida State kicker
Sebastian Janikowski.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a felony charge of trying to bribe a police officer,
Janikowski has a May 3 court date in Tallahassee, Fla., to see if
he can keep from being deported back to Poland, his native country.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Cleveland used the top pick on Penn State defensive
end Courtney Brown after he agreed to a seven-year contract that
could be worth $45 million, including a $10.1 million signing
bonus. The last year of the deal is voidable if Brown reaches
certain incentives that could push his total income to $57 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an emotional roller coaster,'' said Brown, who is
represented by Marvin Demoff and Houston's Sean Jones. ``It feels
so good to have everything said and done. Now I'm ready to play
some football.''
</P>
<P>
   With the second and third picks, Washington didn't rock the
boat. The Redskins selected Penn State outside linebacker LaVar
Arrington and Alabama offensive tackle Chris Samuels.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have the needs we had, it was very fortunate for
us,'' Redskins director of player personnel Vinny Cerrato said.
``The impact guys were there, and we really needed them. It fell
right into our laps.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in history that teammates were the first
and second picks. Brown and Arrington joined Michigan State's Bubba
Smith (Baltimore) and Clint Jones (Minnesota) in 1967 and
Nebraska's Irving Fryar (New England) and Dean Steinkuhler
(Houston) in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no disappointment for me seeing Courtney going No.
1,'' says Arrington, who is represented by Houston's Carl Poston.
``I couldn't have been picked behind a better guy. He was the
natural pick for them, and he deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati listened to a lot of offers for the fourth pick, but
the Bengals drafted Florida State receiver Peter Warrick, the
highest-rated prospect, according to National Scouting Combine.
They plan to play Warrick opposite Darnay Scott and get rid of Carl
Pickens, assuming anyone will take him with his big contract and
bad attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks had been predicted when Baltimore made the fifth pick,
but the Ravens declined trade offers and selected Tennessee running
back Jamal Lewis, who ran the 40-yard dash in 4.38 seconds for
them. The Ravens had the second-best draft Saturday behind
Washington. With the 10th pick in the first round, they got the
receiver they wanted, Travis Taylor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia and Arizona didn't pull any surprises by drafting
Florida State defensive tackle Corey Simon and Virginia running
back Thomas Jones in the next two spots.
</P>
<P>
   With the eighth pick, Pittsburgh considered drafting Marshall
quarterback Chad Pennington. But Bill Cowher's job is on the line
next season, and he doesn't have time to watch a quarterback
develop. By drafting Michigan State's Plaxico Burress, the Steelers
took a receiver in the first round for the second consecutive year.
If they don't have a quarterback who can throw the ball to Burress
and Troy Edwards, last year's first-round pick, it could be a
wasted pick.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago wanted the 6-foot-5 Burress because the NFC Central is
loaded with such tall receivers as Randy Moss (Minnesota), Keyshawn
Johnson (Tampa Bay) and Herman Moore (Detroit). But the Bears
didn't shed a tear by settling on New Mexico outside linebacker
Brian Urlacher, the best athlete in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Urlacher joins cornerback Thomas Smith and defensive end Phillip
Daniels, both of whom were signed as high-paid free agents, as the
latest addition to a Bears defense that should be vastly improved.
</P>
<P>
   After Baltimore took Taylor and the New York Giants selected Ron
Dayne, the Heisman Trophy-winning running back from Wisconsin, it
was time for the Jets to make their first pick.
</P>
<P>
   With Bill Parcells calling the shots for first-year head coach
Al Groh, the Jets chose Tennessee defensive end Shaun Ellis and
South Carolina outside linebacker John Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   With back-to-back picks, Parcells was able to strengthen the
defense for Groh, a longtime defensive coach. Once the Jets took
Ellis and Abraham, who were coveted by Green Bay and Denver,
respectively, very little went according to form.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers settled for Miami tight end Bubba Franks, and the
Broncos took California cornerback Deltha O'Neal. Franks should
replace Mark Chmura, the Packers' veteran tight end who was charged
with sexual assault last week. Even if Chmura is cleared or the
charges are dropped, don't expect him back in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Denver coach Mike Shanahan reached for O'Neal because starting
cornerback Dale Carter has been suspended for the season after
violating the league's substance-abuse policy.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco will be desperate for a quarterback if Steve Young
doesn't return, as is expected, but the 49ers used their No. 1 pick
on Michigan State outside linebacker Julian Peterson. After Oakland
took Janikowski, the Jets were on the board for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   With Vinny Testaverde the starter at quarterback and Ray Lucas
the backup, the Jets selected Pennington. He was the best
quarterback in the draft, and he will be given time to develop.
</P>
<P>
   With their last pick in the first round, the Jets solved a need
by taking West Virginia tight end Anthony Becht.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom portion of the opening round, there were a couple
surprises. Seattle thought Alabama running back Shaun Alexander was
too good to pass up. The Seahawks used their second No. 1 pick on
Wisconsin offensive tackle Chris McIntosh.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers also had two No. 1 picks. They solved their most
pressing need by taking Ohio State cornerback Ahmed Plummer in the
24th spot. Their defense got another boost in the second round when
they were fortunate to get Virginia Tech defensive end John
Engleberger, projected to be a first-round pick in almost every
mock draft, and Texas A&AMP;M cornerback Jason Webster.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
