<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMINGTON CALM IN EYE OF STORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fife Symington has sat in a U.S. Bankruptcy Court while one of
Phoenix's top attorneys has branded him a liar and a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, the former Arizona governor has endured the
pounding with remarkable composure; he has been combative when on
the stand and stoic when off. He has chatted and joked with friends
and reporters after each day's grilling. He has been unfailingly
upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Symington became belligerent only once: the day pension-fund
attorney Michael Manning closed in on him on the witness stand.
Symington stood up and vehemently defended his real estate deals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with most of the scheduled testimony behind him, evidence
is stacking up against Symington. It's clear he provided a
seriously flawed financial statement to union pension fund managers
in 1990 who then gave him a $10 million loan for the Mercado
project in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   What's not clear is whether the statement made a difference.
Symington's attorney argues that fund managers weren't interested
in the numbers and would have made the loan anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The standard for Judge George Nielsen, who is expected to decide
the case by summer's end, is clear. Debts obtained through fraud
cannot be wiped out by bankruptcy. At stake is $18 million, the
total the loan debt has reached with interest.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the way Symington envisioned beginning the
millennium. A decade ago, he was Arizona's golden boy.
</P>
<P>
   He charged to the governorship on a quest to rescue his state
from the zany unpredictability of then-Gov. Evan Mecham.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to guide government with the same steady hand he used
to build what seemed to be a thriving real estate business.
</P>
<P>
   VAST HORIZONS VANISH
</P>
<P>
   After he became governor in 1991, his political horizons seemed
so vast that a business partner offered to wipe out part of a debt
if Symington won the presidency this year.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of grooming himself for the White House, Symington
is on trial, accused of bankruptcy fraud, and waiting to hear if he
must face yet another trial in his federal criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, in the middle of his second term as governor, a federal
jury convicted him of criminal bank fraud and he resigned his
office in disgrace. An appeals court threw out his conviction last
year, ruling that a juror was improperly dismissed, and prosecutors
must decide soon whether to retry the case.
</P>
<P>
   Symington claims to be calm as he awaits the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally out of my hands,'' said Symington, whose business
and political careers spawned bookloads of stories about his fierce
desire for control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sitting back and obsessing about this,'' he said.
``The fear is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington admits now what he never would acknowledge before,
that he was often miserable during the federal investigation that
led to his indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't imagine what it's like getting up in the
morning and knowing that your friends are being slammed into the
grand jury,'' he said. ``I can't begin to explain the trauma that
Ann and I went through.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann, Symington's wife, is the anchor of a family that he says
has become stronger under the stress of the bankruptcy, conviction
and resignation.
</P>
<P>
   An heiress to the Olin chemical fortune, she also picks up much
of the tab for the multimillion-dollar attorneys fees generated by
her husband's legal woes.
</P>
<P>
   Family wealth made it possible for Symington to wait out his
appeal at culinary school. There, he learned the skills that have
made him an apprentice chef at Franco's Trattoria in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGE IN THE KITCHEN
</P>
<P>
   Symington, who loved the prestige and trappings of elective
office, says he has found refuge in the kitchen. He talks of his
comfort within the rich aromas, the clanging pans and simmering
sauces of the upscale restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Once the proud developer of $60 million office buildings, he is
now concocting $5.50 deserts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make a great tiramisu,'' he boasts. He offers a tip: ``Use
imported mascarpone cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington has built for himself a new routine not often
available to bankrupt real estate moguls whose legal bills have
passed the $5 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   But then, not many can take a European vacation right before
they flee to the protection of Bankruptcy Court. Symington, who was
in his second term as governor at the time, shrugged off the howls
of criticism. He said the 1995 trip was a present from his wife for
his 50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   He is a man born to privilege. His great-grandfather was
Pittsburgh steel baron Henry Clay Frick, who in 1892 survived an
assassination attempt during his union-busting crackdown on the
notoriously bloody Homestead Strike.
</P>
<P>
   That history sets Symington's trial against an ironic
background. It is the working class, the Teamsters and masons and
carpenters who own the pension funds, who are pursuing this
patrician son of Harvard in Bankruptcy Court.
</P>
<P>
   Symington claims to be baffled by their lawsuit. He says that
even if the pension funds prevail, they will have accomplished
little more than enriching Manning.
</P>
<P>
   He scoffed at Manning's contention that Symington is in line to
inherit a fortune following the death of an uncle.
</P>
<P>
   `NO POT OF GOLD'
</P>
<P>
   The cold-steel glare once familiar to political foes was back in
his eyes as he refused to answer questions about any coming
inheritance. He said only, ``There will be no pot of gold at the
end of the rainbow.''
</P>
<P>
   There certainly was no fortune in the Mercado, the Mexican
village-themed retail and office center that Symington touted as a
can't-miss addition to downtown Phoenix. Symington lost the project
to the real estate recession that claimed all his properties.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn began shortly before Symington's 1989 announcement
that he would run for governor. It overwhelmed him slowly, drowning
him in unmanageable debts on buildings with too few tenants.
</P>
<P>
   His most painful loss was the Camelback Esplanade, where the
Ritz-Carlton and two office towers are now thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived in the mid-1980s, the Esplanade brought Symington his
first political notoriety as he orchestrated a glitzy,
spare-no-expense public relations campaign to get the project
approved by the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of his partners on that project, Jerry Hirsch, who
offered to forgive part of a personal debt if Symington had won the
White House by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Symington says that the covenant ``was completely Hirsch's
idea,'' and insists that he never really aspired to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch's attorney at the time takes a somewhat different view.
``I think Jerry viewed that as a sort of humorous statement about
Fife's ambition,'' Paul Meyer said. ``I think Jerry believed that
it was Fife's ambition to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington says his only desire now is to extricate himself from
all legal entanglements and get on with his culinary career. His
fate in Bankruptcy Court depends on a legal standard different from
what prevailed at his criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   A MORE DIFFICULT BURDEN
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors merely had to show that Symington
deliberately falsified financial statements that could have
deceived his lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Manning and the pension funds carry a more difficult burden.
They are attempting to establish not only that Symington was
deliberately deceitful in claiming a net worth of $12 million, but
also that the pension funds ``reasonably relied'' on that financial
statement when they made the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Shull, Symington's bankruptcy attorney, says he will put the
pension funds' directors on trial when Manning's case is done. He
claims the funds did little more with the financial statement than
stuff it into a file. Beyond that, he claims the funds committed
themselves three years earlier to make the loan.
</P>
<P>
   With that defense, Shull says, Symington can endure Manning's
relentless assault on the 1990 financial statement, the focal point
of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Manning has laid siege to the statement. He has demolished
Symington's reckoning that his ownership share in 16 commercial
properties gave him a $12 million net worth.
</P>
<P>
   TRIAL A PLAY-WITHIN-A-PLAY
</P>
<P>
   Symington's apparent equilibrium during the assault, his
patrician insistence that all is well, is the substance of the
play-within-the play at Symington's trial.
</P>
<P>
   This is a trial, after all, about how Symington presented
himself during a time of withering stress. It is about allegations
that he constructed a facade of financial dynamism at a time when
his real estate was falling on his head.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, when Manning moved close to Symington's
witness-stand perch to direct his attention to a blow-up of the
financial statement, the former governor stunned the court with his
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to tell Judge Nielsen that his back was hurting,
Symington asked for permission to stand and stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen assented and Symington sprang to his feet. He locked his
hands defiantly on his hips and put a hostile edge on his responses
to Manning's questions.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, a former linebacker at Emporia State University in
Kansas, calmly held his ground. The strange tableau lasted for
about 10 minutes, until Manning moved back to the lectern and
Symington sat down.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, Symington was still energized by the
faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he had sought to accomplish in the confrontation, he
responded with the pugnacious delight he once carried into
political battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit there and have him glower down at me,''
he said. ``I'm going to stand up to him, and I'm going to look him
right in the eye, and we're going to go at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington expressed surprise when he was asked if the scene lent
credence to Manning's claim that he lied so that he could appear
worthy of a big loan.
</P>
<P>
   Symington said he indeed had back pain. He said it was the
lingering effect of tumbling into a street as he fought off a
knife-wielding mugger during a trip to Spain last year with his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   A PAIN IN THE . . . HIP
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't lie to the judge,'' Symington said. ``The truth of
the matter is that I have a sore hip. So, I needed to stand up and
stretch. But I also stood up to Manning. So, it was a two-fer.''
</P>
<P>
   Symington professes disdain for Manning and his interrogation,
which will continue next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an effort to try to wear me down, and exactly the
opposite is happening,'' he declared to the usual end-of-day wedge
of cameras, recorders and notepads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly the opposite is happening. I feel like I'm getting
stronger.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
