<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BATS GIVE MARTINEZ A BREATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This was the no-frills Pedro Martinez Experience for a
sellout crowd of 33,122 at Fenway Park Saturday afternoon. This was
not the IMAX theater, sensory overload version in which it's all
Pedro, all the time, in 360-degree Technicolor.
</P>
<P>
   That's not going to happen on occasions such as this, when the
Sox beat the Oakland A's, 14-2, after giving their ace a 7-1 lead
two innings into the game. Christmas, to borrow Mo Vaughn's
phrasing from a week ago, was canceled yet again.
</P>
<P>
   No tinsel. No ornaments. Just straight-ahead Martinez, who threw
an economical 94 pitches in seven innings in dispatching the A's,
perhaps the most patient hitting club in the majors but one that
had no choice but to swing at Martinez's offerings after falling
hopelessly behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a lead like that, you pretty much go out there and
throw strikes and make it happen,'' said Martinez, who ran his
record to 3-0 and lowered his ERA to 1.27 but with nine strikeouts
saw his streak of 10-K games end at 10. ``I got away with some
cheap outs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the view of the A's, Martinez shouldn't have gotten away with
hitting Miguel Tejada with a fastball in the back of the shoulder
in the third inning. There was little to suggest Martinez hit
Tejada on purpose. The two are buddies from the Dominican Republic,
said Martinez, who tipped his cap in apology to the A's shortstop
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He dives a little (over the plate), but that pitch was
completely out of control,'' Martinez said. ``He's a good friend
from the Dominican; we hang out a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, sensitive to any suggestions that he throws at people,
bristled when someone wondered whether Tejada was a target because
he'd hit a home run off Martinez last August. ``You can write that
if you want,'' he said. ``I think we've done enough talking.''
</P>
<P>
   But privately, there was grumbling in the A's clubhouse because
no one, especially A's reliever Ron Mahay, retaliated against a Red
Sox hitter. The A's remember last season, when Martinez drilled A's
infielder Olmedo Saenz, and the closest the A's came to answering
back was when ``Nutty'' Buddy Groom threw a pitch behind Nomar
Garciaparra. Groom was gone after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Mahay, who was plucked off waivers from the Red Sox by the A's a
year ago last March, won a spot as the fifth starter coming out of
camp this spring. But his turn was skipped this go-round and his
hold on the job appears tenuous. Saturday, Mahay threw one pitch
under Brian Daubach's chin in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved some guys off the plate,'' Mahay told Oakland
reporters afterward, apparently unaware that some uniformed A's
were seething.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez hasn't lost in 14 appearances, including a dozen
starts, since falling to the A's and their prized young pitcher,
Tim Hudson, last Aug. 19. The rematch was Mike Tyson-Peter
McNeeley, as Hudson was chased with two outs in the second inning
after yielding six hits, four walks, and seven runs. Hit the rewind
button, and Hudson was Sox pitcher Brian Rose the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, like Rose, was looking at flags blowing in his face.
That can play mind games with a young pitcher, said Sox center
fielder Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it does,'' he said. ``They know they can't make a lot of
mistakes when the wind is blowing out. I'm not a pitcher, but to me
you have to bear down and be more aggressive, get ahead in the
count, because when you get behind you're going to get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really comes down to pitching. (Friday night), Brian was
struggling a little bit and today their guy was struggling. (Kevin)
Appier was on his A game (Friday), and Pedro had his A game today.
They also made some mistakes defensively (four Oakland errors) and
those turned into runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach doubled home a run in the first and two more in the
second, an inning that began with Manny Alexander's triple and
climaxed with Carl Everett's two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, serving as designated hitter, had four RBIs. He hit a
sacrifice fly in the first, blooped a double to start the Sox'
two-run sixth, and singled home a run and scored in the Sox'
three-run seventh. Everyone in the Boston lineup scored at least
one run, on an afternoon that began with Trot Nixon bunting on his
own in the first inning after Jose Offerman hit a leadoff single.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, you don't see Trot bunting in the first inning,''
said Daubach, who has been on base six times in two games against
the A's. ``We tried to play for one run, and we scored seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when it was 9-2, there was Lewis, racing from second to
third on a ground ball to the left side, arriving safely with a
headfirst slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never let up,'' Lewis said. ``You have to play the
game the same way, start to finish. A seven-run lead in this
ballpark and the wind blowing out, anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reason why this team has success. Everybody takes
the same approach, no matter what.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
