<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8318 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-PULLOVER-AZR &LR;      04-16 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULLOVER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, GET OUT OF THE ROAD!
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY LAURA TRUJILLO 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Three seconds after Troy Arthur rushes his firetruck out of
Station 25, a white Ford Escort zips in front of him, ignoring his
flashing lights and hollering siren.
</P>
<P>
   This is frustrating, but routine, Ar thur laments, moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer cars pull to the side of the road these days when fire
engine lights flash by.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, it took 3{ minutes on average to get to most
emergencies in Phoenix. Now it takes almost five. Fire captains
blame rude drivers as well as growing gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In five years driving a Phoenix fire engine, Arthur has seen a
Toyota rear-end a firetruck, a Buick refuse to budge from its lane
and a Honda hug a truck's bumper to maneuver crowded streets.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix ranked third in the nation for dangerous driving
incidents last year and third again on a list of metro areas with
high aggressive-driving death rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel stressed for time, they don't want to give up
their spot. They think, `If I pull over and stop, five cars will
pass me,' '' says Capt. Mark Burdick of the Glendale Fire
Department. ``It's like the Indy 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix slowly has become a big city, Deputy Chief Bob Khan
says. ``People have just become insensitive to the job we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists try to understand what they say is a disappointing
trend. The lure of firefighters still exists, as they still lead
parades and wave at children.
</P>
<P>
   So, psychologists doubt the refusal to pull over is a lack of
respect.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that ``so many people have become absorbed with their
own psyches that they lose touch with what's going on outside of
their car windows,'' says Michael Hurd, a psychologist and host of
``Solutions _ Not Excuses'' on KFNX-AM (1100).
</P>
<P>
   ``People cut each other off on the road for no good reason,''
Hurd says. ``People don't hold the door for others, even when it's
easy or appropriate to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychology Professor Leon James says rudeness is learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grow up being driven around by aggressive drivers,'' says
the road rage expert at the University of Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   So, firetruck engineers or drivers must learn to anticipate
motorists who don't stop.
</P>
<P>
   It's frustrating, firetruck engineers say, to see drivers who
forget what to do when they hear the sirens, such as those who pull
to the center turning lane or who don't pull to the right and stop.
Or those who, in their insulated worlds of rolled-up win dows,
air-conditioning and loud ra dios, don't hear the sirens.
</P>
<P>
   Even Burdick, the fire captain, ad mits singing to the radio,
then spying a firetruck in his rearview mirror, lights and sirens
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' he says, noting that he had a bumper
sticker identi fying himself as a firefighter on his car.
</P>
<P>
   But what really upsets him are people who simply refuse to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I`ll have my lights on, stopping at a red light and the cars
with the green will take off. I'm there, 30,000-some pounds with a
siren and lights, and they go in front of me,'' Arthur says. ``It's
like they just see an open lane, they take it. They don't care.
Every body's in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Burdick says, ``You pull up, and people just look at you. It
flabber gasts you. It's almost like a chal lenge, and you can't
stop and yell at them. You have to get to your call.''
</P>
<P>
   Police, who say people still pull over for them, can cite
drivers who fail to yield, but it's rare that they catch them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually, I guess you might say, the people in the higher
income brackets, the Mercedeses. I don't want to sound
inappropriate,'' says Scott Frey, a captain for Rural/Met ro's
Station 16 in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   But 13 years on a Phoenix firetruck has taught Capt. Elby
Bushong that everyone is in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will plead innocence,'' he says. ``But in my mind . . .
it's more important for them to get where they're going than for us
to respond to someone's tragedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
