<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON'S LOSS IS BOSTON'S GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ So, what exactly were the Houston Astros thinking when
they shipped Carl Everett to Boston in exchange for minor league
prospects Adam Everett and Greg Miller?
</P>
<P>
   Everett had three more hits and four RBIs in Saturday's 14-2
rout of the Oakland A's. In 10 games with the Red Sox, he's hitting
.444 with a team-high four homers and 13 RBIs. He's a 28-year-old
switch-hitting center fielder with speed who hit .325 last season
with 25 homers and 108 RBIs, playing half his games in the
cavernous Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   What were the 'Stros thinking? Season ticket-holders should
bombard the club switchboard and tell general manager Gerry
Hunsicker, ``Houston, we have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to cut pay,'' said Everett. ``But it's hard to
insult me. I let everybody have the benefit. I don't get
embarrassed or offended.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros should be embarrassed, and at long last perhaps there
is revenge for Jeff Bagwell. In the worst day of his professional
life, Uncle Lou Gorman traded minor leaguer Bagwell to the Astros
for journeyman pitcher Larry Andersen in 1990. It was the Sox'
worst deal since you-know-who was traded you-know-where for sheet
music to ``No, No, Nanette''!
</P>
<P>
   But now the Sox have pilfered Everett because the Astros
committed their cash to Messrs. Bagwell, Biggio, and Alou. And the
early reviews are boffo.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when the Celtics got Robert Parish? When the Bruins got
Anson Carter? Sometimes a Boston team picks up a talented guy who's
been suppressed elsewhere and blossoms in New England. Everett is
beginning to look like one of those players.
</P>
<P>
   As longtime coach of the Expos, Boston coach Tommy Harper saw
Everett evolve with the Marlins, Mets, and Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't play much in those early years and it was difficult
to tell,'' said Harper. ``Then in Houston, they gave him the
at-bats and you could tell he was coming on. He changed his
approach a little. He became better equipped to handle the offspeed
pitch. The first changeup we threw him in Montreal last year he hit
very far. I said, `We gotta change the book on this guy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Boston manager Jimy Williams employed Everett as designated
hitter Saturday. It was the second time he gave Everett a day to
rest his legs.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of Pedro Martinez's first Fenway start since the
1999 Octoberfest rout of Roger and the Yankees, fans were lined up
on Yawkey Way halfway to Van Ness Street at 9 a.m. Jimmy Fund
patient Brendan Smith of Beverly Farms fired a strike for the
ceremonial first pitch, and then Everett put the game out of reach
with a two-run second-inning double.
</P>
<P>
   Batting lefthanded against Oakland's Tim Hudson, Everett bonged
his first ball off the Wall in left. He was keenly aware that the
hit would have been a routine out in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   From the left side, Everett has one of those classic inside-out
swings that enables him to utilize the Monster to left and
left-center. Fred Lynn and Wade Boggs made a living out there and
Carl Yastrzemski and Pete Runnels also took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I'm a pull hitter, but I'm not,'' said Everett.
``I'm an inside-out hitter. I try to hit inside the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't aim for the Wall during batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to hit the ball to shortstop in batting practice. I'm
the ugliest BP hitter you'll find.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse than Eddie Murray?
</P>
<P>
   ``Worse than Manny (Ramirez) in Cleveland,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox fans won't care. They come to see Everett hit in the
games and it's hard to believe what they're seeing. Everett is
already a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear 'em, but I don't let it affect me in any way,'' he
said. ``I don't think it helps me positively or negatively. I just
like to play hard and you can see they enjoy it when you play hard.
These people support you whether you're winning or losing. In
Houston, they didn't support you even when you were winning.''
</P>
<P>
   He made a lot of friends with Sox fans in Fort Myers, Fla., in
spring training and found some familiar faces in the seats at
Fenway. He says his Opening Day commuting horrors are behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've felt good since the season started,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to see it getting any better than this. Red Sox fans
already are comparing him to the golden Lynn of 1975 and he seems
to like Boston more than a Kenyan marathoner.
</P>
<P>
   Revenge fo Bagwell?
</P>
<P>
   ``Baggy wants to come back here,'' said Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Great. Get Hunsicker on the phone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
