<HEADER>
A8322 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     04-16 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-RATE EFFORT BY PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They did the best they could, which is all
you can ask of an organization.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody will know for some time whether the players Bill
Belichick selected in his first day running the Patriots' draft
will turn out to be impact players, but this much can be said of
what he accomplished Saturday _ he got all he could from where he
was sitting.
</P>
<P>
   With no first-round pick there was little Belichick could
predict about what he would be facing when it came time for the
46th pick, but he was sure someone would be there he didn't expect
and he was right.
</P>
<P>
   Who was there was a 307-pound offensive tackle out of Hawaii
named Adrian Klemm, a player many teams felt would be a first-round
selection. The fact he was not doesn't reflect badly on him because
only three offensive linemen were taken in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day Belichick followed his draft board,
preferring to go with the best player available according to the
team rather than taking a running back right away. He was gambling
that somehow he could take care of that crucial matter later on.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick turned out to be right on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   First, he got a huge and athletic offensive lineman who could
start as a guard but be able to move to left tackle, the spot Bruce
Armstrong has filled so ably for the past 13 years. Then he got the
running back he wanted all along when Arizona State's J.R. Redmond
fell to the Patriots at No. 76.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond was Arizona State's offensive MVP the last three years
and rushed for 1,085 yards in 1999 despite being suspended for one
game by the NCAA in a bizarre cell phone scam. It led to Redmond
briefly marrying a woman who worked part time in the ASU football
department because she told him he could avoid any NCAA penalties
if he did.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage was annulled and Redmond went on to complete his
season in fairly strong fashion. He did well enough that many
scouting services had him listed as the fifth-best back in the
draft behind the big four of Jamal Lewis, Thomas Jones, Ron Dayne,
and Shaun Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   As things turned out, Trung Canidate and Travis Prentice were
taken ahead of Redmond as well, but his abilities as a receiver out
of the backfield, inside runner on first and second down, and as a
kick and punt returner made him particularly attractive and useful
to the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Had Belichick not landed a high-profile back he might have been
criticized for taking Klemm first, but when it came time to make
his first pick, Belichick took one look at his draft board and the
move he needed to make was clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of good players on the board at the time but
Adrian was clearly the top player we had on the board,'' Belichick
said. ``There was a big gap between him and the next one in value
on the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was clearly the highest-rated player on our board. For us,
he was the top value.''
</P>
<P>
   The same was true with Redmond. In fact, the Patriots were
talking with Redmond on the phone and preparing to take him in the
second round when it became clear Klemm would still be available.
Redmond was put on hold with the belief that he would be gone by
the time New England picked again.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, he was not and so the same situation existed
with Redmond that did with Klemm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to take Klemm but J.R. was the next consideration,''
Belichick said. ``We felt the value was there for Klemm. The same
was true with J.R. He was the clear choice (on the draft board). We
had him on the phone 20 minutes before we selected him.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the first day of the first draft of Bill Belichick's
second chance ended with his team getting the rights to two players
he believes can come in and help in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   If they do, he and his staff will have had an impact already on
the fortunes of the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, Belichick can still go to bed knowing he got all
he could out of the situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
