<HEADLINE>
BABA ON TARGET IN OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Imad Baba took a cross pass along the right
side and all the Revolution midfielder could see in front of him
was the goal. He never saw the D.C. United goaltender Tom Presthus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I shot it, I didn't even see the ball when I hit it,''
said Baba, who scored the winning goal in overtime in the
Revolution's 2-1 win Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at Foxboro Stadium. ``I just
heard it go off the post. I didn't know it went in until I saw it
in the other corner.''
</P>
<P>
   The pass came from forward Wolde Harris, with William Sunsing
touching the ball just before him. ``I was yelling and luckily
(Harris) handed it off to the right,'' said Baba, who scored his
second goal of the game in the 97th minute. ``I just wanted to hit
it on target. I didn't care where the keeper was. I just wanted to
get it on target.''
</P>
<P>
   Baba called the winning goal ``probably one of the biggest'' he
has ever scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the ball come to the other side of the goal, I was
in awe,'' said Baba. ``I heard my teammates and the crowd, it was a
great feeling, something you don't think will ever happen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Baba registered the Revolution's first goal on a penalty kick in
the 72d minute when Sunsing got fouled in the box by United
defender Jeff Agoos. Baba wanted to take the shot and wasn't going
to allow anyone else to take it.
</P>
<P>
   He blasted a shot into the lower left corner, tying the game at
1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation, I don't think anything but goal,'' said
Baba, who has three goals this season. ``For me, there's no die.
You have to score that, that's what you play for. When the ball's
hit, the goalie moves. Both of us moved at the same time. He
guessed right but I just hit it in the corner. You pick your spot
and hit it hard. Your main decision is before you even kick it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Revolution's first victory of the season, coming
before a home-opening crowd of 15,175.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win with a lot of fans coming out to enjoy a good
soccer game and we gave them their money's worth,'' said Baba.
``Hopefully, we can just feed off this win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution didn't play well in the first half, but came on
strong in the second when United turned defensive-minded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to take advantage of the extra man,'' said Baba,
referring to the ejection of United's Judah Cook who received two
yellow cards in the first half. ``We wanted to attack them when we
had the chance. We needed a win and we wanted to win. We played
well all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept playing our game, trying to get the ball inside with
some crosses. We were patient and it went all the way to sudden
death.''
</P>
<P>
   When Baba provided sudden victory for the Revolutiuon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8324 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-UNITED     04-16 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-UNITED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION UPEND UNITED IN OT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution found some winning
combinations Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. They played with a man advantage for
64 minutes, found an offensive rhythm in a 3-5-2 alignment, and
took a 2-1 victory over D.C. United in golden goal overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Imad Baba converted a second-half penalty and drilled the
deciding goal in the 97th minute as the Revolution won for the
first time this season. It was also their first three-point victory
over United since July 20, 1996, and vaulted them into second place
in the Eastern Division with five points in five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution discovered an effective midfield mix in the
second half as they pressed forward to capitalize on the 33d-minute
expulsion of D.C. defender Judah Cooks. Mauricio Ramos moved to a
more central midfield role, where he took charge, actively calling
for the ball, commanding attention, directing traffic, and
distributing to the wings and through the middle. He ignited the
play on the winning goal, driving forward from the halfway line,
then flaring a pass to Ted Chronopoulos on the left wing.
Chronopoulos's cross ended up at the feet of William Sunsing, who
laid the ball off to Wolde Harris, who found Baba on the right
side. Baba, who had tied the game with a penalty kick in the 72d
minute, one-timed a hard drive into the far side of the net,
leaving goalkeeper Tom Presthus with no chance.
</P>
<P>
   Sunsing, who replaced Mike Burns in the 65th minute, enabled the
Revolution to play a five-man midfield and his dynamism and
unpredictability kept the United defense off balance.
</P>
<P>
   Seven minutes after entering the match, Sunsing drew a penalty
in a collision with Jeff Agoos. Harris held possession against
three defenders and threaded a soft ball into the penalty area for
Sunsing, who fell head-first after being bumped by Agoos.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Ali Saheli, who handed out seven cautions, six to D.C.
players, awarded the penalty. And Baba converted into the left side
of the net, easily beating Presthus.
</P>
<P>
   That goal energized the Revolution, who had held the lead in
only one game this season and have only eight regulation-time
victories in their last 37 matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, everyone was nervous, nobody wanted to make
a mistake,'' Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo said. ``I told
everyone to start releasing the ball quicker and play simple, go
forward and take chances. We took command in the second half. You
can say it was against 10 men but I've seen teams play better with
10 players.''
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United has won the Major League Soccer Cup twice at Foxboro
Stadium and entered the match with only one regulation-time loss in
nine games at the stadium. And United acted like the home team,
receiving a break when Cooks appeared to handle the ball in the
penalty area in the fifth minute.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th minute, United appeared to receive another break as
linesman Roger Itaya allowed play to continue as at least two
United players appeared to be offside, and Jaime Moreno easily
scored on a shot past Jeff Causey. Revolution defender Dan
Calichman went face-to-face with the linesman and continued the
discussion even after the kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   In the 33d minute, Cooks was caught out of positon on a
Revolution throw-in and again deliberately handled the ball. This
time, Saheli issued a second yellow card and an ejection.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the first half, Marco Etcheverry was omnipresent
with threatening touches and lethal free kicks, plus a 55-yard
attempt, into the wind, which Causey stopped with his chest.
Meanwhile, the Revolution displayed little poise offensively in the
first half, seldom making the incisive passes necessary to unlock
the D.C. defense.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in the second half as Ramos, who has been a close
friend and rival of Etcheverry since they were 8-year-olds in Santa
Cruz, Bolivia, took charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
