<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8325 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-ROY-TARPLEY-RUSSI     04-16 2128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROY-TARPLEY-RUSSIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MAVERICKS STAR ROY TARPLEY BOUNCES BACK IN AN UNLIKELY
PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE MONTGOMERY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERM, Russia _ Roy Tarpley's ninth-floor apartment is barren of
memorabilia from his roller-coaster career with the Dallas
Mavericks, except for one item.
</P>
<P>
   It's a video from the 1988 season, when Tarpley earned pro
basketball's coveted Sixth Man Award and helped propel the
Mavericks into the conference finals for the first time in team
history. Those were heady days, back before his career sank under a
fog of cocaine, alcohol and arrogant excess.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary is called ``Bouncing Back,'' a title that also
neatly encapsulates Tarpley's life here in Perm, a gray factory
town at the southern foothills of the Ural Mountains and a half a
world away from the glitz of the NBA and the bright lights of
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   These days, No. 42 from the Dallas Mavericks is No. 22 on the
Ural Great, a respected Russian professional basketball team. Five
years after he was bounced from the NBA for drug and alcohol abuse,
Roy James Tarpley Jr. is grasping for a rebound in a city that was
closed to foreigners until just 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy. The cultural differences are immense, the
language barrier foreboding. Tarpley was sidelined because of an
off-court injury, and coaches call his performance erratic.
Moreover, his salary _ he won't say how much _ is only a fraction
of the $26 million, six-year contract that he signed with the
Mavericks in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, say those who know him, this Roy Tarpley is not
the same wayward star who bounced in and out of jail and rehab
programs, skipped practices and ultimately became the first NBA
player in league history to be ejected twice in his career for
substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a happy man today,'' Tarpley said in an hourlong interview
recently, reflecting on his days in Dallas and his new life in
Perm. ``I know it sounds corny, but that's how I am today. I'm
corny. I'm tired of being so cool, you know what I mean, as far as
drugs and getting high. People, they ask me, `Do you get high or
something?' I say, `I'm 7 feet tall. That's high enough.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Roy Tarpley who rose from the bench two Wednesday nights
ago, six minutes into a much-anticipated game against a superior
Moscow team, bore a strong resemblance to old No. 42 of the 1988
Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   As a sellout home crowd of 7,000 waved light sticks and flooded
the stadium with a deafening ``Oo-RAL Grea-a-t,'' Tarpley sank a
basket three minutes after entering the game, then quickly
completed a free throw.
</P>
<P>
   His team lost, but Tarpley went on to compile a
``double-double'' that distinguished his Dallas days: Double digit
points (18, the second highest for his team) and double-digit
rebounds (13, the highest of either side).
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked like the old Roy,'' he beamed proudly after the game.
``This is the most I've played since I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley describes himself as ``older and wiser,'' a man who
prays every day, asking God to help him control his temper. He also
draws strength from his girlfriend, Calandra Campbell of Arlington,
who accompanied him on his journey to the edge of Siberia. Tarpley
calls her ``my backbone.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia, where vodka is a national institution and beer kiosks
never close, is hardly the best environment for someone with a
history of addiction. Teammates say that Tarpley drinks beer and
goes to nightclubs on road trips, but there has been no evidence
that his wildly unpredictable past is reappearing. He shows up
regularly for practices and gets along with other players and team
officials, all of whom know about his personal problems and
turbulent history in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   At 35, Tarpley is the oldest player on the team. Although he has
become an instant leader since joining nearly five months ago,
coaches say he has still not developed to full potential. He missed
nearly two months of play when he slipped on the ice and broke his
shooting hand.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, general manager Sergei Kushenko and coach Sergei
Belov both say they sense an inner turmoil in Tarpley, possibly a
lingering hangover from his Dallas days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a very lonely man,'' Belov said. ``He's very
important to our team, but we cannot say we're satisfied entirely
in his playing. He plays one game very well and another game not so
well. He is not so stable inside, and the slightest thing makes him
nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley acknowledges that he is often nagged by ``butterflies in
my stomach,'' whether he is playing basketball or just sitting
idly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a roller-coaster ride,'' he said. ``It just comes
and goes, going up and down _ maybe a couple of curves.''
</P>
<P>
   He grapples with insomnia and often stays up until dawn watching
American movies on the VCR. When he sleeps, he tosses and turns,
sometimes dreaming of confrontation on the basketball court. But,
at the same time, he also claims a personal contentment which he
says was lacking during his days of multimillion-dollar stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have all the money in the world, you can have all
these people in your pocket coming at you from all angles and
directions and you can be the most miserable guy in the world with
all the money, the fame, the stardom,'' he said. ``I'm a lot
stronger now.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Tarpley believes he was treated unfairly by the
NBA and contends the league's testing program was an overly harsh
``invasion of privacy'' that produced distorted results. But does
he deny taking drugs?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to talk about it. That's my past. That's like
the president of the United States: `I tried marijuana once, but I
didn't inhale it.' Who hasn't grown up and tried a joint? Who
hasn't drunk a beer?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Tarpley also acknowledges that his downfall was
self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of bad decisions. I felt, you know, that every
day was a party. Out all night with women and all that stuff just
caught up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   If he could take those 10 years back, he says, ``I'd have been
more serious about my life and my career. You never really miss
something until you don't have it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Tarpley has now is a new opportunity in a place he surely
never envisioned himself during his much-traveled childhood in New
York, Alabama or Detroit. He never read about a place called Perm,
even in geography books, and his only knowledge of Russia came from
Cold War-era newscasts or from the '60s James Bond thriller, From
Russia with Love.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural clashes erupt constantly. Slavic teammates, as well as
fans and townfolk, are still adjusting to an outspoken, 7-foot-tall
African-American who wears a mink coat and yellow suits, a gold
earring and a neatly trimmed Shakespeare-style beard.
</P>
<P>
   And Tarpley, in turn, says he might never adjust to the bleak,
six-month-long winters and drab lifestyle in his new city of
residence. Sometimes, he says, he confronts what he perceives as
subtle displays of racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the store and a guy bumped into me and looked at me
ugly, and I would ignore it,'' Tarpley said. ``You've got to be
really stupid or crazy to mess with a 7-footer.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to other Perm residents, who scrape by on an average of
about $40 a month, Tarpley and other team members live a pampered
existence. Rookies make as little as $500 per month, but others
average around $100,000 per year, and some, presumably including
Tarpley, make far more. Tarpley and Campbell share a spacious
four-room apartment provided by the team, along with a chauffeured
Jeep Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   But they long for the simple pleasures of America _ fast food, a
wide selection of trendy restaurants, friends who speak their own
language. Tarpley's Russian vocabulary hasn't evolved beyond ``da''
(yes) and ``nyet'' (no).
</P>
<P>
   ``The honest truth, I'm just bored,'' Tarpley said. ``It's OK.
I'm not going to say it's great. It's very hard and difficult to
stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the bigger cities of Moscow and St. Petersburg, which
boast a vibrant nightlife and Western-style amenities, Perm has
been to slow to break from its Soviet past.
</P>
<P>
   A working-class city of just more than 1 million, it was closed
to foreigners until 1989 because of strategic defense production.
For 17 years, until 1957, it was called Molotov, after a Stalin-era
foreign minister whose name inspired the Molotov cocktail. A statue
of Lenin still presides over the town square. And less than 100
miles to the east lies Perm 36, an infamous labor camp that
operated until 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Perm is also an unlikely breeding ground for one of Russia's
hottest basketball properties _ the Ural Great, founded just five
years ago by five young businessmen, all former classmates and
amateur athletes who jointly amassed a string of lucrative holdings
with the invasion of post-Soviet capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   The team's guiding force is Kushenko, the 38-year-old general
director who has sought top-flight players throughout Europe.
Belov, the coach, is a renowned athlete who led Russia's national
team to victory over the United States in the 1972 Olympics and
later was inducted into America's Basketball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kushenko, Ural Great boasts such NBA-style attractions as
comely cheerleaders, halftime contests and stylish ad campaigns, as
well as a roster of talent good enough to compete with top-flight
U.S. universities and European teams. Ural Great defeated the
University of Nebraska during a U.S. exhibition tour.
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley joined the team in November after beginning a comeback
in 1999, first with the Apollon Limassol in Cyprus, and then with a
first-division Greek team, the Dafni Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Ural Great needed a center, and Tarpley seemed ideal. Team
officials explored every good, bad and ugly detail of Tarpley's
life through meticulous research on the Internet and concluded that
his potential overshadowed the risk. Kushenko also saw something of
himself in Tarpley's past.
</P>
<P>
   When he was in his late 20s, Kushenko recalled, he drank
excessively and hitchhiked from place to place, with no ambition or
goal. Friends helped straighten him out, planting him on the road
to financial success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down one time, too,'' he said, comparing himself to
Tarpley.
</P>
<P>
   Tarpley agreed to move from the warmth of the Mediterranean to
the heartland of Russia, but he quickly discovered that Ural Great
is a long way from the NBA. On his first road trip, the team
assigned him to a train compartment with a bewildered Russian woman
carrying a baby. The next leg of the trip was a five-hour adventure
over Russian roads, on a rented bus filled with smoke and exhaust
fumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like Dorothy in The Wizard of Oz,'' Tarpley recalled.
``I wanted to click my heels together and say, `I want to go home.'
''
</P>
<P>
   The former Mavericks star has bonded with the only other
African-American on the team, Donnell Thomas, a 6-foot-5 native of
Chicago who played in New Zealand, Spain, Portugal and Holland
before coming to Perm in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy has been kind of a crutch for me and a kind of a mentor,''
Thomas said. ``And I've been kind of a crutch for him, so we've
been good for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   During a typical practice last week, Tarpley and Thomas stood
toward the side of the court as coaches explained the drills in
Russian, waiting patiently for a translation from an assistant
coach who speaks passable English. Russian team members say they
like and respect Tarpley but some feel uncomfortable with his brash
American-style tendency to talk back to the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   In the dressing room after last week's game against Moscow CSKA,
Tarpley openly grumbled when informed that team members were
expected to show up for photographers the following morning, a
scheduled day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``A day off is a day off,'' Tarpley said. ``We're seeing too
much of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the discomforts, however, Tarpley believes his stay here
has demonstrated a resiliency and ``mental toughness'' that can
keep him on the court for another three or four years, regardless
of where he winds up. He has no desire to return to the NBA after
that ``mess with them.'' But he knows he wants to keep playing, and
he is guided by advice he once received from former Mavericks owner
Don Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `You can either be a rising star or a falling
star,' and that stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Which one is Roy Tarpley?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no falling star,'' he said. ``I never look down on myself.
I keep my head up. We all learn from our mistakes, and I feel like
I have. That's why I have so much to give.''
</P>
<P>
   {Dave Montgomery of the Star-Telegram is on extended assignment
as Moscow bureau chief for Knight Ridder newspapers.}
dmontgomery\Nkrwashington.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
