<HEADLINE>
REID'S CUP VISIT LEADS TO FULL PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ One of the endearing rituals of the Stanley Cup is that
every member of the winning squad is entitled to spend at least a
day at home with it over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Hockey Hall of Fame in Toronto polishes it up, secures it in
its custom carrying case, and sends it out with a Hall
representative as protector/chaperone. The Cup has been all over
the world and has been known to be a real party animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hall officials) like guys like me who are married,'' said
ex-Bruin Dave Reid, a member of the Dallas Stars last June when
they won the Cup. ``Some of the single guys, well, they maybe could
get in a little trouble with it. But the guy who brought it to my
house, he got a lot of sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid, pursuing another Cup this spring, this time with the
Colorado Avalanche, benefited by a slight scheduling snafu last
summer. Prior to it being shipped to his summer home in Ontario,
the Cup was delayed in Quebec en route from a visit with Guy
Carbonneau. The Hall rewarded Reid's patience by allowing him to
keep the Cup for two days instead of one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took it everywhere,'' said Reid, reciting an itinerary that
included the local police department, the Sears store, even the
garage where a longtime friend fixes his car. ``My wife's cousin
owns a golf course, and we took it there for a three-hour party.
It's just a great chance for everyone to see it, and mostly it's a
photo thing. You spend most of your time smiling, with one arm
around the Cup and the other around whoever it is next to you who
wants their picture taken.''
</P>
<P>
   On Day 2, Reid headed into Toronto, the Cup in the back seat of
his car, and trooped it around town _ a favor to his father, whose
business clients were eager to touch hockey's holy grail. At one
point, it became far more efficient to park the car and just walk
from office to office. So there was Reid, scooting from one street
to the next, from Bloor to Yonge to Adelaide, with hockey's most
cherished trophy hoisted high on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were moving at a pretty good clip, so it wasn't like people
came running out of buildings to see it,'' said Reid. ``But people
we'd pass on the sidewalk, they'd stop and ask, `Hey, is that
really the Stanley Cup?' I mean, when you think about it, why would
someone be walking down the street with it, right? But I'd be there
saying, `Yeah, it's the Cup, all right.' And either people would
just stand and stare, or they'd say, `Nah, that's not the Cup.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The names of the Dallas Stars weren't etched into the Cup until
later in the summer. During the Christmas break, Reid finally got
to see his name on it, when the Hall let him bring it home for a
second visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just unbelievable to see your name there,'' said Reid,
who broke into the NHL with the Bruins in 1983-84. ``And it would
so great for it to happen to Ray (Bourque) now. I know he'd give up
all his Norris Trophies (five) for that. Anyone would. And for the
rest of us, that's all the more incentive to win it here, for Ray
to have that chance. We've talked about that since he got here,
maybe not to his face, but kind of behind his back. I don't think
he'd mind. Do you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's no longer in the Hub, but he's not forgotten in the
Bruins' pro shop on Causeway Street. According to shop boss Lauma
Cerlins, Bourque's No. 77 replica sweater in black and gold, at
$140 a pop, remains a very hot item. ``People come in and ask,
`When are you going to mark down the Bourque stuff?' '' said
Cerlins. ``And the answer is: Never. It's still selling great.''
The hottest non-Boston item in the pro shop is anything related to
the Avalanche, Boston's home hockey team now that Bourque wears his
No. 77 in Colorado. ``At one point after the trade, we sold out of
all Avs stuff,'' said Cerlins. ``We had to search high and low to
find some more hats.'' Avalanche sweaters sell for $75, but the pro
shop doesn't process custom orders _ either with number or name _
for out-of-town sweaters . . . As widely predicted, ex-Bruins coach
Brian Sutter walked the plank in Calgary last week, along with
general manager Al Coates. Sutter: ``I have nothing to be ashamed
of. None of our coaches have anything to be ashamed of. None of our
players have anything to be ashamed of.'' In fact, the Flames can
be proud they remained in a hunt for a playoff spot to the very
end, probably eight weeks longer than could be reasonably expected
given the lack of roster depth . . . Rumors continue that Mark
Messier will end up back on Broadway once the Canucks issue him the
$2 million that will buy out the last year of his deal. Don't bet
on Wrentham's Garth Snow being back in British Columbia either. His
deal calls for just under $2 million next season and the Canucks
won't want to pay that kind of money for a Felix Potvin backup . .
. It's still a long way to the Cup finals, but Avalanche captain
Joe Sakic is jumping around like a rookie and a first-round victory
over the Coyotes undoubtedly will earn him mention as the potential
Conn Smythe (playoff MVP) winner. Sakic won it when Colorado
clinched the Cup in '96. Only five players have been two-time
Smythe winners: goalies Patrick Roy and Bernie Parent; forwards
Wayne Gretzky and Mario Lemieux and defenseman Bobby Orr . . .
Don't be surprised if ex-Bruin Andy Brickley ends up right back
where he belongs, working in a Bruins' broadcast booth. He could
even end up right back at Ch. 38 . . . The Coyotes have to hope
Sean Burke tightens up in their net. He allowed a couple of cream
puffs to get by him in Game 1 vs. Colorado, no doubt bringing a
smile to the face of Nikolai Khabibulin, who wouldn't play in
Phoenix this season for a long-term deal worth more than $3 million
year. Burke went into Saturday's matinee with only one playoff
victory since fronting the New Jersey net in the '88 semifinals vs.
the Bruins . . . The Black 'n' Gold faithful flocked to the Vault
this season. Final attendance: 669,237, for an average of 16,323
(92.9 percent capacity), with 14 sellouts (17,565).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The State House might have to consider a class-action suit, now
that the Blues have launched a Golden Dome approach for the
playoffs. Rather than grow playoff beards, four of the Blues (Craig
Conroy, Marc Bergevin, Jamal Mayers, and Jamie McLennan) opted to
dye their hair bright yellow for the postseason run. Mayers, who
routinely shaves his head, tinged his eyebrows, fashioning tiger
stripes. ``If it was just myself, I'd look like an idiot,'' said
Mayers, who tuned up in the minors with Worcester (AHL). St. Louis
coach Joel Quenneville, 41, didn't opt for anything that radical:
``The only dye I'm going to have is Grecian Formula.'' . . . What a
beating (7-0) the Capitals took in their playoff opener with the
Penguins Thursday. Part of what stoked the thumping was a remark by
Washington coach Ron Wilson earlier in the week: ``We'll go (to
Pittsburgh) and beat 'em anyway.'' He was referring to the
Capitals' having to play Game 2 in Pittsburgh because of a
scheduling conflict in D.C. The Penguins slapped Wilson's quote on
their dressing room wall and then went out and handed the Capitals
their worst postseason defeat ever. ``It definitely made us
angry,'' said Penguins troublemaker Matthew Barnaby. ``You want to
be taken seriously.'' . . . Headin' south: the Flames called a news
conference Friday and made it clear they will go up for sale June
30 if season tickets aren't boosted from 9,000 to 14,000 in the
next 10 weeks. Club owners say they've lost $37 million over five
years and project to lose at least $58 million over the next four.
If the numbers aren't met, look for the franchise to end up in
Portland, Ore., or Houston . . . Flyers coach Roger Neilson,
recovering from multiple myeloma, watched Philadelphia's playoff
opener vs. Buffalo from a luxury box. Reports had Eric Lindros,
still recovering from a Grade 2 concussion, nowhere to be seen at
the First Union Center. Neilson left Saturday for a vacation in
Texas, doctors advising him to get more rest. He remains hopeful to
return behind the bench if the Flyers advance to the second round .
. . Alain Vigneault did an admirable job behind the Montreal bench,
his Canadiens losing more than 500 man-games to injury. That said,
Vigneault could be gone if ownership gives GM Rejean Houle the
gate, the Canadiens missing the playoffs for a second straight year
for the first time since the early-'20s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens to the Devils this postseason, look for
Slava Fetisov to become their coach next season. Larry Robinson
played the good soldier, moving to the top job when GM Lou
Lamoriello gave Robbie Ftorek the heave-ho, but he made it clear
upon leaving Los Angeles that he didn't want to be a top man
anywhere again . . . Ex-Bruin Charlie Simmer, now a TV color man
with the Coyotes, said he and his Triple Crown partners, Dave
Taylor and Marcel Dionne, get no feelers for card shows or promos
these days. ``Out of sight, out of mind,'' said Simmer. Taylor is
GM of the Kings. Dionne, according to Simmer, runs a business that
manufactures miniature hockey sticks as novelty items . . . The red
in the Hurricanes' uniforms is nothing compared to the bloodletting
club owner Peter Karmanos has witnessed with his Compuware Corp. in
recent months. Consider: Compuware was trading at a one-year high
of $40 a share around Christmas, making the company worth some
$14.4 billion. It was pounded last week, dropping one day from $20
to $12 per share, and closed Friday at 12 1/8. In a little more
than 100 days, Compuware's value has dropped slightly more than $10
billion _ a drop of about $100 million a day. That, folks, is one
miserable plus-minus . . . First casualty of the playoffs:
Toronto's Yanic Perreault banged up a knee in Game 1 vs. the
Senators, tearing two ligaments and finishing him for the year.
Perreault, remember, initially was mentioned in trade talks when
the Bruins shoveled Dmitri Khristich's rights to the Maple Leafs
early this season . . . Open days weren't easy for the
Penguins-Capitals to secure in Pittsburgh, either. The rink already
had dates booked with the World Wrestling Federation, an ice show,
and a Latin dance contest . . . Just like in Boston, where Bruins
players' pledged their allegiance to head coach Pat Burns as soon
as the season ended, Blackhawks players faithfully endorsed Lorne
Molleken as they departed for the summer. Blackhawks GM and
Vineyard resident, Mike Smith, sounded less than swayed by the
sentiment. To wit: ``Unless I missed it, maybe it happened the last
couple of years I was on Martha's Vineyard and I didn't read it,
but I didn't know the hockey business became a democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
