<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE HAVING TIME OF HIS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ There are minutes, and then there are minutes. Ray
Bourque played another half-hour Saturday, the ex-Hub icon rolling
over the boards every other shift in Colorado's 3-1 (ho-hum)
playoff victory over the overmatched Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   But, for all those minutes, the 39-year-old Bourque barely
looked out of breath in the thin, chilled air of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good here,'' said Bourque, his Avalanche now with a
cushy 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven series. ``It's the same
minutes, the same role. But when you're out there with Joe (Sakic)
and Peter (Forsberg), they're working the defensemen in the other
end. I'm probably not spending as much time in my own end.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't exactly a retirement job for Bourque. After all, 30
minutes of playoff hockey, even if it were all spent in the neutral
zone, is still a test for anyone. But Bourque is surrounded by so
much other talent, and the Avalanche's game plan is so built around
speed and transition, that Bourque can look at the game straight
ahead, rather than constantly check his rear-view mirror as he digs
the puck out of his own end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd get the chance to play with him,'' said
Boston University product Chris Drury, who potted Colorado's first
goal, opening a 1-0 lead only 3:31 into the first. ``Growing up in
New England (Trumbull, Conn.) and going to BU and everything, I
just always assumed he'd be a Bruin for life. Every game he has
played here has been just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque assisted on the Drury strike, which came on a
five-on-three power play, giving the veteran blue-liner his third
assist this postseason. He now has 128 playoff assists, fourth all
time _ behind Wayne Gretzky (260), Mark Messier (186), and Paul
Coffey (137).
</P>
<P>
   Just what does the ex-Bruins captain mean in Colorado's overall
scheme? Consider: They breezed to this win, with Bourque finishing
with but one shot _ a slapper on the power play midway through the
third period. In his Boston days, Bourque could be penciled in for
at least four shots a night. On the rare night that he didn't get
them, Boston's chances of winning went from break-even to little
hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get space and time, I'll shoot it,'' he said. ``But
they're doing a good job out there of getting on me pretty quick,
and that usually means someone else is open. Hey, I don't mind
giving up the puck to these guys and letting them shoot it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche moved out to a 2-0 lead with only 4:27 gone, this
time with another former Bruin, Dave Andreychuk, providing a key
assist on an Alex Tanguay short-range sweep under the crossbar.
Andreychuk, whose game fell off badly in the second half with
Boston, finished with six shots; teammate Sandis Ozolinsh had a
game-high seven. Andreychuk also was on the ice when the Avalanche
scored their third goal, another five-on-three strike with 9:32
gone in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Benoit Hogue scored the only Phoenix goal. The Coyotes' two top
offensive performers, Bostonians Keith Tkachuk and Jeremy Roenick,
have been silenced thus far.
</P>
<P>
   For two games, the Coyotes have applied little pressure on
goalie Patrick Roy. The Avalanche will allow the long shot, but
quickly close into the slot and smother the odd rebound that Roy
allows. If Phoenix does manage a short-range shot on net (rare),
Bourque &AMP; Co. not only take care of it, but often flip it ahead and
begin the lightning-like transition up ice. If the Coyotes are
going to get back in this series, they first have to find a way to
prevent the Colorado attack from turning around on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's impressed me most since getting here is the way this
team plays away from the puck,'' said Bourque, now with eight goals
and nine assists in the 16 games since coming from Boston. ``We
have a lot of offense, but we also pay attention to the details
when we're not attacking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
