<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' GREER LIKELY TO MISS 4-6 WEEKS AFTER ANKLE SURGERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Rangers left fielder Rusty Greer has decided to
undergo arthroscopic surgery to remove bone chips from his right
ankle and is expected to miss four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Greer made the decision yesterday after the Rangers decided to
put him on the disabled list with a strained left hamstring. The
Rangers medical staff also felt surgery would be a good idea now
because there is a strong suspicion the ankle, which has been
bothering Greer since spring training, contributed to the hamstring
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like this is the time to get it done,'' trainer Danny
Wheat said. ``It was gradually getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgery has been scheduled for today and will be performed
by Dr. Charles Cook in Dallas. This is the first time in Greer's
major-league career he has gone on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy having to do this, but it will relieve some
anxiety in my mind knowing the pain will be gone,'' Greer said.
``But having to miss two weeks being on the disabled list and
another two weeks because of this is frustrating. I signed up to
play. Not being able to do so is frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also believed that, if Greer didn't have the
surgery, it would cause problems over the course of the season and
he would miss a significant amount of time. He missed a week in
spring training and required a cortisone shot to ease the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been bad at times,'' Greer said. ``It's not that I can't
go out there and play, but I can't go out there and play the way
I'm capable and help the ballclub, because I don't know when it's
going to grab.''
</P>
<P>
   The hamstring injury, which Greer suffered Thursday in New York,
was going to cause him to miss a week. That's why the Rangers
decided to put him on the disabled list instead of Frank
Catalanotto, who remains sidelined with a strained groin muscle.
The Rangers are hoping Catalanotto can at least pinch hit today and
be at full speed by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers determined Greer wouldn't be able to pinch hit for a
week, which led to the decision to put him on the disabled list.
That led to Greer's decision to have the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the right decision,'' Greer said. ``It's not a snap
decision. It's something we talked about all morning. I didn't want
to get into July or August and tell them I couldn't play or need to
miss every other day.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said Chad Curtis will take over in left
field, and switch-hitting outfielder Jason McDonald was called up
from Triple-A Oklahoma to serve as the fourth outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to lose a key player,'' Oates said. ``But all
spring I don't think Rusty has been running well. If we can get him
back by the first of June, we'll have four solid months where he
can play the way he's capable.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin said this is why the Rangers traded
for Curtis, and Melvin sees no reason to look for front-line
outfield help outside the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that concerns you is if you get another
outfielder injured,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin acquired Curtis from the New York Yankees during the
winter meetings for minor-league pitchers Brandon Knight and Sam
Marsonek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be able to go with a guy with experience,''
Melvin said. ``He plays the game the right way and knows how to
play it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
