<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8329 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-DRAFT-TEX     04-16 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-DRAFT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR COWBOYS, 49 IS REALLY FINE PICK: VOLUNTEERS' GOODRICH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ After a more than seven-hour wait because of the
absence of a first-round pick in this weekend's NFL Draft, the
Cowboys were richly rewarded last night when they were able to land
Tennessee cornerback Dwayne Goodrich with the 49th pick overall.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich, a three-year starter for the 1998 national champion
Volunteers, earned a 5-rating by the Cowboys, which is their
highest, based on the results of a player's physical, intellectual
and psychological testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my wildest dreams, I didn't think he would drop down to
us,'' said Cowboys coach Dave Campo immediately after Goodrich was
grabbed off the board at 6:10 p.m. _ exactly seven hours, 10
minutes after the NFL draft had begun in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never wavered on \Rpicking\S him,'' Campo said. ``You're
talking about a 5-foot-11, 198-pound corner who has been timed in a
4.38-second 40 and who played in the Southeast Conference week in
and week out against quality players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys filled a top-priority need by drafting a cornerback
higher than they have done since 1992, when they took Kevin Smith
in the first round (24th overall) out of Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a break in this draft,'' said Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones, referring to the Cowboys' lone first-day pick after trading
away their first- and third-round selections to Seattle for wide
receivers Joey Galloway and James McKnight, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no secret if we were drafting for position, it would be
cornerback,'' Jones added. ``And then to see Dwayne Goodrich
sitting there ... well, this was a very easy decision. I've never
been more comfortable in making a pick.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 10 minutes that the Cowboys were on the clock, they
entertained offers from both the Pittsburgh Steelers and Tampa Bay
Buccaneers to move down a few spots and pick up an extra
fourth-round selection.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich's presence on the board forced Jones to wave off both
proposed deals, even though the Cowboys were interested in picking
up an extra selection since they presently have only five picks,
including four today as the NFL draft concludes with Rounds 4-7.
</P>
<P>
   Jones admitted that there were only two other players still on
the board who would have caused the Cowboys to select rather than
trade down. One of them was Kansas State linebacker Mark Simoneau,
who was taken by Atlanta in the third round (68th overall). The
other, a cornerback, remains on the board, but Jones was careful
not to tip his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich, seen by the Cowboys as a ``bigger Kevin Smith'' with
similarly long arms and equally good instincts for the ball, will
be given a chance to start at Deion Sanders' right cornerback spot.
Sanders is expected to be released June 2 for salary-cap reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, cornerbacks Smith and Kevin Mathis have missed a
combined 21 games over the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to put any pressure on \RGoodrich\S,'' said
Jones. ``But in my mind, he needs to come in and do it right now.
He will have a learning curve ... but times have changed in the NFL
because of the cap system and bonuses. We don't have time \Rto
wait\S.''
</P>
<P>
   The main reasons Goodrich fell into second round are thought to
be his drop-off in performance from his junior year. A disc problem
in his lower back, which resulted in a summer weight-room injury,
was partly to blame, along with Tennessee's defensive scheme
changing from mostly man-to-man to 50-percent zone with blitz
packages.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich has been diagnosed with a heart condition, similar to a
murmur, although the Cowboys discounted the seriousness of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had no bearing on us giving him a 5-rating,'' said Jones,
calling it reminiscent to a condition belonging to former Cowboys
running back Sherman Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich was the sixth cornerback taken yesterday. He grew up in
Oak Lawn, Ill., where he was a Cowboys fan and remembers losing $10
on the Cowboys in 1985 when the Chicago Bears beat his favorite
team, 44-0.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich missed one game last season after being arrested for
disorderly conduct outside a campus convenience store Sept. 26. The
charge was later dismissed when Goodrich complied with court terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had to sit yesterday and watch each of their four
NFC East rivals make picks in the top 11 overall. Washington,
favored to repeat as divisional champion, took Penn State
linebacker LaVar Arrington and Alabama offensive left tackle Chris
Samuels with the second and third picks; Philadelphia, Florida
State defensive tackle Corey Simon with the sixth; Arizona,
Virginia running back Thomas Jones with the seventh, and the New
York Giants, Heisman Trophy-winning running back Ron Dayne of
Wisconsin with the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be at Nieman-Marcus all day long and not have any
money on you,'' quipped Larry Lacewell, Cowboys director of pro and
college scouting, who actually took a cat nap at one point during
the Cowboys' long wait, which began with war room participants
showing up at Valley Ranch at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little frustrating to me to see all our of division
rival sitting right up there at the top of the draft and getting
the very best players in the draft,'' admitted Jones, quickly
adding that there is more to winning a Super Bowl than coming up
big on draft day. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
