<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD FLASHING HIS OLD MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``One thing that's left to do that really intrigues me
is to be able to put a team together. That would be fun.'' _ Larry
Bird
</P>
<P>
   Is he sending us signals again? In February, Larry Bird let it
be known he could, and would, put together a group to buy the
Celtics in a nanosecond. It took a nanosecond for that idea to
bomb, but the always calculating Bird lit a flame of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's finishing up his third year coaching the Pacers. He
insists there won't be a fourth. He's insistent there is nothing
else on his plate. He has a chance to move into the front office
and build a team where he is. He doesn't want to.
</P>
<P>
   Or, we should say, he doesn't want to do it there.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with the Globe's Bob Ryan, Bird offered
some read-between-the-lines observations that seem to indicate he
knows what he wants to do. He wants to put a team together? Where
else would he do it but in Boston?
</P>
<P>
   Retirement in Naples? C'mon. He doesn't want to go back there
and live the life of the Florida squire. Been there, done that. He
said as much in the interview. He says three years is enough for a
coach, exempting two people: Pat Riley and Jerry Sloan. (You may
have noted which coach is missing from that list.)
</P>
<P>
   The only conclusion we can draw from this _ Larry is not the
type to come out and say what he really wants _ is it's time for
Bird to come back to Boston and run the Celtics. He may be a
Hoosier by birth, but he's a Celtic by blood. Could it happen? Why
not? Yes, there would have to be accommodations on all fronts,
starting with Bird's relationship with the Celtics' chairman of the
board.
</P>
<P>
   Bird has not been a fan of Paul Gaston and has said so, both in
recent oeuvre and in comments about buying the team. Then again, we
know from the present situation that being buddies with the owner
is not a prerequisite for the job. Gaston is, above all else, a
businessman. He cannot like what he sees right now from a business
standpoint: empty seats, no playoffs, and a payroll significantly
higher than a number of playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Bird back is a business no-brainer. Yes, Bird would
inevitably be judged by the product on the floor, but he has shown
to be a pretty good judge of talent and chemistry. Gaston and Bird
would have to bury their respective hatchets for the good of the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The second impediment would be Rick Pitino. He and Bird could
not work in tandem. That much we know. Pitino's contract calls for
the final say in all basketball matters. But he also has to run
these decisions by Gaston. Who's to say that Bird couldn't be hired
as a consultant to the owner? Or as the owner's adviser? Or as the
owner's receptionist? As long as he had Gaston's ear _ and Gaston
agreed to listen.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are obstacles. There always are when there are egos
at stake. But I believe it was Pitino who first said, ``The ends
justify the means.'' The Celtics are defined mostly by utter
apathy. Only when Mt. St. Pitino erupts does the team get any face
time. Bird wants to put a team together. We don't think he was
referring to Vancouver. There's no time _ or place _ like the
present.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The season ends Wednesday and it's time to make the annual
All-This and All-That selections. This clearly has been the Year of
the Laker and it will be reflected in various categories.
</P>
<P>
   MOST VALUABLE PLAYER &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, LA Lakers. The ballot calls for five
selections, but this could, and should, be unanimous. Shaq finally
has matched his overwhelming talent with his overwhelming ego and
the results have been, well, overwhelming. The only question is why
it took him this long to realize he had it in him. If he starts to
enjoy this, the league could be in for another dynasty. Selections
2-5 are Kevin Garnett, Alonzo Mourning, Karl Malone, and Tim
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   COACH OF THE YEAR &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson, LA Lakers. Yeah, sure, we knew it was the coaching
all the time in LA. No one saw this coming, except, perhaps, the
always prescient Big Chief Triangle. Jackson's no dummy. He saw in
LA exactly what he saw in Chicago: a team that had the personnel to
win, but didn't have a clue how to do it. He pushed all the right
buttons and, voila! The Lakers may be an abdominal strain away from
elimination, but they're also the prohibitive choice to go all the
way. Doc Rivers will get a lot of support and he should. He's done
a wonderful job with what he has. But his team may not even make
the playoffs. Sloan? He's getting to be an afterthought, which is
too bad because he simply does it every year. So does Riley.
</P>
<P>
   ROOKIE OF THE YEAR &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Francis, Houston. This has basically boiled down to a
two-man race, even though Lamar Odom may turn out to be the best of
the lot once liberated from Clipper Hell. Francis gets the nod for
a couple reasons. First, he plays the most difficult position for a
rookie (point guard). Second, he isn't accumulating stats on a
truly awful team, which is the case with Chicago's Elton Brand
(although it's clearly not his fault). The Rockets have had some
quality wins while the Bulls and Clippers have been uniformly
horrible.
</P>
<P>
   SIXTH MAN OF THE YEAR &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Rogers, Phoenix. The Suns are still making noise even
with two of their top players (and 2000 Olympians) not around.
Rogers has been a key to their success and also has adapted to the
role off the bench. Jerome Williams would be an excellent choice as
well, for he truly defines the concept with his energy off the
bench. But the Suns could end up with the fifth- or sixth-best
record in the league and Rogers played a big part.
</P>
<P>
   MOST IMPROVED PLAYER &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose, Indiana. This won't be unanimous because of the
candidates. But is there anyone who has upgraded his game more than
the Pacers swingman? He has taken over Reggie Miller's role as the
de facto Man at Indiana (although Bird still would like to see
Miller take the big shot). He's also turned into a most valuable
free agent. Other candidates include the Mavericks' Dirk Nowitzki,
who is going to be a terrific player, the Grizzlies' Michael
Dickerson and Rose's teammate, Austin Croshere. Pitino's choice:
Shaq. But the award is designed to honor an ``up-and-coming''
player who made a ``dramatic improvement'' from previous seasons.
Shaq was pretty good last year, too.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE PLAYER &QC;
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal. The Lakers are the best defensive team in the league and
have been all season. Shaq has gone from indifferent to dominant on
defense; he's third in blocked shots. The Lakers might have had 82
shutouts if they kept Eddie Jones, who, along with Mourning, are
good choices as well. But why not honor the best defensive player
on the best defensive team?
</P>
<P>
   ALL-NBA TEAM &QC;
</P>
<P>
   First team: C O'Neal, F Garnett, F Duncan, G Jason Kidd, G Gary
Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Second team: C Mourning, F Grant Hill, F Malone, G Kobe Bryant,
G Stephon Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   Third team: C David Robinson, F Vince Carter, F Chris Webber, G
Allen Iverson, G Michael Finley.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest selection was finding a legitimate No. 3 center.
Robinson wins by default; the only other serious candidates are
Patrick Ewing and Vlade Divac. I put Iverson on the third team
because he makes Antoine Walker look like a discriminating shooter.
Finley wins out over worthy candidates such as Jones and Jerry
Stackhouse. The Mavericks' minutes man is almost indestructible,
not to mention good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One more piece of evidence as to the dramatic difference between
the East and West this season: not a single team from the Eastern
Conference looks like it will have a winning road record. Wow. That
must be a first, right? Wrong. If you think winning on the road is
tough now, you should go back to the late 1970s, when it was almost
unprecedented. In the 1976-77 season, the year Portland upset the
power-packed Sixers in the NBA Finals, not a single team had a
winning record on the road. (The Lakers had the best record at
53-29, but were 16-25 on the road.) The following year, only the
Blazers, who had that memorable 50-10 start, were better than .500
on the road. In 1978-79, only two (the Bullets and Sonics) managed
the feat. This year, five teams in the West will finish better than
.500 on the road while Phoenix needs only to win at Golden State,
and Seattle needs to win two of its last three to turn the trick.
The only Eastern team with a shot is Toronto, which must win
Tuesday in Miami and Wednesday in Orlando to finish 21-20 on the
road . . . Pitino is guaranteeing a winning season in the Shaw
Summer League . . . Dikembe Mutombo hopes to hear from the Atlanta
Hawks before they make any moves this summer. ``I'm praying for
that,'' said the Hawks center, who called this season ``the most
disappointing ever for me.'' That's not the way it was last year
when they unloaded Mookie Blaylock and Steve Smith. Mutombo said he
heard about the deals on the radio. ``Whatever does happen, I'm
just hoping I get a phone call and ask me what I think instead of
hearing about it afterwards. That's pretty tough.'' As for the
season, Mutombo says he can't conceive of not making the playoffs.
``I can't look at the standings in the papers anymore,'' he said.
``I used to see 50 wins. Now, I see 50 losses.'' Mutombo has spoken
with Lenny Wilkens over the coach's charge in a recent Sports
Illustrated article that Wilkens didn't consider Mutombo a leader.
``Everywhere I have been, I have been a leader,'' Mutombo says.
``In my country. In my home. In my family. I've always looked at
myself as a leader, a role model. I think it would be hard for
someone to say I am not a leader. Anyone who sees me working would
have to judge me as a leader. Whatever I have, I leave it on the
floor.'' . . . The consensus winners from the recent Portsmouth
Invitational Tournament were MVP Mike Smith of Louisiana-Monroe and
Reed Rawlings of Samford. Both are in the 6-foot-7-inch, 6-8 range
and have excellent shooting range. ``They could take an escalator
ride in the draft,'' said Celtics GM Chris Wallace. ``They've gone
from being lucky to being drafted, to where are they going to be
drafted.'' Portsmouth produced two first-rounders last year, Jeff
Foster and Devean George. The Nike Desert Classic concludes this
weekend, the second of the three big predraft roundups with the
third in early June in Chicago . . . Looking at Ron Mercer since he
joined Orlando, it's hard not to see a guy who may be in for a big
shock this summer. His shooting, always his strong suit, is awful.
How can he be anything more than an insurance policy for Orlando?
If the Magic can't get Jones or Hill, they might turn to Mercer. If
they get either one, where will Mercer go and what does he thinks
he's worth? More and more, it's looking like the $28 million he
turned down in Boston (over four years) will never come his way
again. The Magic aren't going to spend for the sake of spending
this summer, and don't be surprised if as many as nine players on
their current roster are back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
