<HEADLINE>
ASU'S REDMOND ANSWERS CALL FOR RUNNING BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots put character issues aside and
patiently waited to draft a running back Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. After
passing on Arizona State's J.R. Redmond with their second-round
pick, they found him there with the 76th overall selection.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the draft saw the Patriots take an offensive
lineman and a running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think considering where we started it was good where we
ended up,'' said coach Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond was suspended for one game last season for violating
NCAA rules by using a cell phone belonging to a woman who worked in
the Arizona State athletic department. The woman suggested that in
order to avoid a rules violation they needed to be married. The two
were married, but when the story came out, Redmond was punished by
the NCAA and the marriage was annulled.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond addressed the issue Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in a conference
call, saying he learned a valuable lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a decision to seek advice and help from your
closest friends during those times,'' said Redmond, who credited
his father with assisting him through those difficult days.
</P>
<P>
   The Redmond story actually broke when the Patriots were in
Arizona last Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots researched it and Belichick interviewed Redmond
about the problems last week when Redmond came to Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any trouble surrounding J.R.,'' said
Belichick. ``He made a bad decision. We've all made bad decisions.
I don't think it'll happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond is a tailback who can also be a top returner. He was
timed at 4.44 in the 40-yard dash, but dropped to No. 76 because of
his off-the-field problem as well as the fact that some teams
consider him a third-down back/returner rather than an every-down
back.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond is known for his outside running ability but has decent
cutback moves and can run up the middle. He's third in ASU history
with 3,210 yards on 616 carries. He also racked up 5,522 career
all-purpose yards, second in school history behind Whizzer White.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be a four-down player,'' said Belichick. ``There were
times he was flanked out. He has good hands, can really catch the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said he was on the phone with Redmond when he was
about to choose Adrian Klemm with the team's first pick. Belichick
said he would have taken Redmond had Klemm not been there when the
Patriots selected 46th.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said his staff, including Scott Pioli, the new
assistant director of player personnel, figured the teams choosing
before the Patriots in Round 3 would not be going for running
backs. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had him on the phone the second time and J.R. wanted to see
his name on TV before he believed it,'' said Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said of Redmond, ``He's a sharp guy who looks you
straight in the eye. I think he's a very focused kid. The people at
Arizona State think the world of him. He's a hard worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond will likely be the front runner for the starting
halfback job. He'll compete with Raymont Harris and Kevin Faulk and
will also give Faulk a run for his money as the lead kick returner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 0150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
