<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8332 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KLEMM-BO     04-16 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KLEMM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS HAD A LINE ON KLEMM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ After telling one and all that they
preferred to take an offensive linemen later in the draft, the
Patriots Saturday grabbed the University of Hawaii's Adrian Klemm
with the 46th pick of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Klemm was projected as a late-first-round pick, but a few
offensive linemen lasted until the second round after only three _
Chris Samuels, who went to Washington with the third pick; Stockar
McDougle, who went to Detroit with the 20th pick; and Chris
McIntosh from Wisconsin, who went to the Seahawks with the 22d _
went in the first.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots passed on Arizona State running back J.R. Redmond
(although they picked him up a round later) and Miami of Ohio's
back Travis Prentice. They also passed on receivers Dez White
(Georgia Tech) and Jerry Porter (West Virginia).
</P>
<P>
   Klemm, a 6-foot-3-inch, 292-pounder from Santa Monica, Calif.,
played left tackle and led a Rainbows offense that ranked third in
the conference in passing, averaging 328.7 yards per game. He
allowed 4.5 sacks while also collecting 75 knockdowns and graded
84.9 (out of 100) for blocking consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Klemm is considered one of the fastest offensive linemen in the
country, timed at 4.98 in the 40-yard dash. He's considered a mean
player at the line of scrimmage, often going right after defensive
linemen. Pass protection is his strength, but he has the quickness
to be a decent run blocker.
</P>
<P>
   The physical education major played tight end for part of his
junior season before switching back to tackle in coach June Jones's
run-and-shoot offense.
</P>
<P>
   New Patriots coach Bill Belichick, who was in the war room with
vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier, scout Larry Cook,
and Robert and Jonathan Kraft, as well as coaches and other
administrative personnel, said he took the best player on the
board, indicating there wasn't a debate about taking a running
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Adrian in for a visit last week and put him through two
workouts,'' said Belichick. ``We're excited to get him. There were
a lot of good players on the board, but Adrian was clearly
higher-rated than the rest of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said Klemm may not stay at tackle; he could be
switched to guard. He added that he wanted Klemm to get to New
England as soon as possible to begin learning the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said that how Klemm was able to lose 40 pounds in a
summer to switch from tackle to tight end was impressive. Klemm
said he lost the weight with extra running and diet. Belichick said
the Patriots won't be asking him to move to tight end, but he will
be in the hunt for a guard or tackle spot with Max Lane, Ed Ellis,
Todd Rucci, Grant Williams, Lance Scott, and Derrick Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel relieved that it finally came through,'' said Klemm.
``One of the coaches told me they thought the Patriots might take
me one or two picks before (it happened).''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident I can play at the next level,'' Klemm added. ``I
figure with coaching, and by increasing my strength, I can do it.
I'm familiar with everybody there. I have a pretty decent
relationship with them. I think my strength is my pass blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were looking at several second-tier offensive
linemen, a few decent receivers, a couple of backup defensive
linemen, and the running backs, when they were up.
</P>
<P>
   The top four backs _ Jamal Lewis (Baltimore at 5), Thomas Jones
(Arizona at 7), Heisman Trophy winner Ron Dayne (the Giants at 11),
and Shaun Alexander (Seattle at 19), went early. At that point
there was a sense the Patriots were sweating it out on Redmond and
Prentice. But not as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   As the late first round approached it appeared the Patriots
would have to make a deal to get one of the two backs, but what
helped them was a run on cornerbacks, linebackers, and defensive
linemen late in the round.
</P>
<P>
   Also helping matters were projected second-rounders like kicker
Sebastian Janikowski (17th to Oakland), tight end Anthony Becht
(27th to the Jets), cornerback Rashard Anderson (23d to Carolina),
and wide receiver R. Jay Soward (29th to Jacksonville) all going in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots didn't pull off a trade. The Bengals were offering
running back Corey Dillon around, and spoke to the Kansas City, who
walked away from a deal, according to Chiefs general manager Carl
Peterson. Kansas City didn't even go for a running back. They
picked wide receiver Sylvester Morris from Jackson State at 21.
</P>
<P>
   A deal that had been speculated on involving the Patriots
getting running back Priest Holmes from the Ravens never developed.
</P>
<P>
   The other surprise right at the end of the first round was Super
Bowl champion St. Louis taking running back Trung Canidate of
Arizona with the 31st pick. Canidate was one of the fastest runners
in the draft, but he was projected behind Redmond and Prentice. The
Rams, taking a chance, which champions can do, had been expected to
take an offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   The early second round was a free-for-all for the leftover
projected first-rounders. The Browns took Arizona wide receiver
Dennis Northcutt, whom some draft experts had earmarked for New
England. The Saints, with their first pick of the draft, took
Kansas State's Darren Howard, a defensive end, and the Bengals went
with Louisiana State cornerback/safety Mark Roman.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots hoped a running back would be there for them in the
third round and they got their man when Redmond fell into their
laps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
