<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-HOVAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC'S HOVAN LANDS IN MINNESOTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The day began as all such days begin for those players
who are not mortal locks to be one of the first five picks of the
National Football League draft.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous anticipation was the way Rose Mary Hovan described it
Saturday morning from her home in Rocky River, Ohio. ``It's going
to be that way all day until we hear something.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chris Hovan, the youngest of Rose Mary and Dennis Hovan's
three sons, the effort to make Saturday normal was almost
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   His brothers, Craig and Matthew, had come home for the weekend.
A few uncles and aunts were also gathering for a mini-family
reunion they hoped would turn into a celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours and 25 minutes into the draft, it turned out that way
when the Minnesota Vikings selected Hovan, the 6-foot-2 1/2-inch
defensive tackle from Boston College, with the 25th pick of the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone had been telling us Chris would go anywhere from 10
to 25,'' said Dennis Hovan with a relieved laugh Saturday
afternoon. ``We didn't think it would be right at No. 25.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings' call came from deep left field. Minnesota was not
one of the teams that had expressed an early interest in Hovan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams like Carolina, the Raiders had talked to him,'' said
Dennis Hovan, who was in charge of transportation late Saturday
afternoon _ the Vikings wanted Chris in Minneapolis as soon as
possible, so Dennis Hovan rushed his son into the shower so he
could catch a 6:40 flight out of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Hovan said he was delighted _ to be picked and to be going to
the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   But as generally is the case with Hovan, who became as well
known at Boston College for painting black triangles on his face on
game day as for his prowess as a defensive tackle, the reasons were
not obvious. He is now on the same team as John Randle, the
defensive lineman who just happens to paint black triangles on his
face and sometimes says outrageous things.
</P>
<P>
   Hovan said it doesn't matter where he plays, although he figures
he will play a lot. The Vikings were ranked 27th defensively in the
NFL last season.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College coach Tom O'Brien, who watched Hovan anchor his
defensive line for the past three seasons, including last year when
he had 11 quarterback sacks and 20 tackles for losses, called the
pick ``a steal.''
</P>
<P>
   There already has been speculation Hovan will play defensive
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my natural position is inside,'' he said. ``But they
play me at end. I think I have great quickness and great
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Vikings defensive coordinator Emmitt Thomas offered an immediate
compliment. ``You can see some of Randle in him,'' said Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   When he talked to the Minnesota media, Hovan was asked about his
development from an undersized 240-pound defensive end to a
305-pound monster mash defensive tackle. ``A great weight training
program at BC,'' he said. ``And I want to thank my parents for
giving me enough money to buy food.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hovan had been told he was more likely to be picked
in the lower half of the first round than the upper half, it did
nothing to decrease the game-day butterflies he felt Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He left the house in the morning with his brothers and father
for breakfast, just to get out of the house, knowing that sitting
in front of the television watching ESPN and tracking the draft
might take a while.
</P>
<P>
   His nerves started to jump around 4 o'clock when Seattle, which
made no secret of its need for help on the defensive line, came up
for its second pick of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks had chosen Alabama running back Shaun Alexander
with their first pick of the first round at No. 19. The speculation
on the second pick at No. 22 centered on Wisconsin offensive tackle
Chris McIntosh. But when the NFL's Gene Washington came up to the
podium to announce the Seahawks' pick, the entire room at the Hovan
house went silent for a moment when he said, ``The Seattle Seahawks
select Chris . . . McIntosh.''
</P>
<P>
   The waiting continued.
</P>
<P>
   Not for too much longer. A few minutes later, the Vikings called
to tell Hovan they were going to pick him with the 25th pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tenacious player,'' said Vikings coach Dennis Green.
``He's exactly the kind of guy we need.''
</P>
<P>
   With the pick, the celebration in the Hovan family room began.
The food, which had been picked at all afternoon, tasted better.
The phone started to ring, with calls from friends and members of
the media, in Minneapolis and Boston. Hovan's agent, Tom Condon,
called with words of encouragement and advice.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was a mad rush to the airport, with a couple of
suits, a few changes of underwear, but unlimited ambition for what
the future will bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like a fairy tale,'' said Rose Mary Hovan. ``Things
couldn't have worked out better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
