</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USOLYMPICCOMMITTEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USOC BOARD PONDERS BLAKE'S IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The speculation had been swirling among the sports
governing bodies for weeks, ever since the US Olympic Committee
began talking about bottom lines and money-for-medals. Swimming
will be fine. Biathlon is in trouble. Men's field hockey is
history. Et cetera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone fears change,'' US Fencing Association executive
director Michael Massik said Saturday, as USOC board members
pondered new CEO Norman Blake's controversial idea to link future
funding to performance at the Games. ``Unknown is scary. Until the
plan is revealed, everyone is going to be afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Blake has pointedly avoided singling out any sports, he's
made it clear that the age of entitlement, of governing bodies
getting dollars without strings, is over. That's welcome news to
some sports, bad tidings for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it,'' said USA Gymnastics president Bob Colarossi,
whose federation stands to prosper under the new philosophy. ``I
like the business emphasis. I like the accountability. I like the
focus on athletes. It's the same message I've been giving my board
for the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   While Blake's abrupt shift in emphasis is ``incredibly bold,''
said USA Wrestling executive director Jim Scherr, most governing
body officials polled Saturday were waiting to see more details
before ringing alarm bells. ``One of the things we need to keep in
mind is, he's unveiling a plan that isn't finished,'' said Massik.
``He's still working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The USOC and its new ``account managers'' won't start hammering
out business plans with sports bodies until this summer and may not
be finished until after the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City.
But the essence of Blake's message is unmistakable. ``You should
have a game plan for how you're going to get your athletes into
medal contention,'' said Colarossi.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the sports bodies say they have no problem being judged
on performance. ``That's what it's all about,'' said US Rowing
president Monk Terry, who won a silver medal with the US men's
eight in 1972. ``That's totally in line with what we're trying to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is whether the USOC's bottom-line approach will
recognize that performance is relative, that what is abject failure
for basketball is a historic achievement for team handball. ``If
the account managers are good,'' said Terry, ``they'll understand
and help us come up with realistic goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the sports bodies face potentially divisive internal
wrangles about where the money should go. The freestyle wrestlers
win decidedly more medals than the greco-roman wrestlers do. Will
the federation now feel obliged to tilt toward freestyle? ``That
obviously is a fear,'' conceded Scherr, who said USA Wrestling
still will support both sides equally.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sports bodies that may never win a medal will be
trying to convince the USOC of their intangible value. ``Remember
Ping-Pong diplomacy?,'' USA Table Tennis president Sheri Pittman
said. ``It opened the door to China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
