<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      04-16 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING ISN'T EVERYTHING, BUT IT'S OLYMPIC THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The next minefield in the road for the US Olympic
Committee and its new hardcore emphasis on performance is whether
America will continue to send a full team to the Games. That's
always been considered a divine right, even though no other country
does it. But a hefty minority, if not a majority of the US squad,
has little chance at a medal and many can't crack the top 20 in
their event. At the 1998 Winter Games, no cross-country skier or
biathlete finished in the top 30 and no jumper made the top 25.
That's not likely to change at Salt Lake City two years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Blake, the USOC's new bottom-line CEO, believes just
making it to Olympus isn't good enough anymore. ``It's being there
and winning,'' he said. All but a few countries send only athletes
they feel can make an Olympic final because they can't afford to
subsidize ``no-hopers.'' That's never been an issue for the
Americans, but it will be after this quadrennium. ``You can't make
everyone happy and have a winning team at the Games,'' said Blake.
``We're not the US government, which can print money. We have a
finite amount of resources.''
</P>
<P>
   A dollar spent on a no-hoper is a dollar taken away from a
potential medalist. ``Nobody wants to touch that issue, but it's
staring us right in the face,'' said Blake. So the USOC will likely
pressure its national governing bodies to send only those who can
be competitive. If the NGBs insist on dispatching 35-year-olds on
self-fulfillment quests to finish 50th in their fourth appearance
at Olympus, they'll be doing it on their own dime.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though the new US Anti-Doping Agency won't be up and running
until after the Sydney Games, it's a major credibility boost for
the Americans, who want to lead the global fight against banned
drugs. As long as the USOC tested its own athletes, the rest of the
world dismissed the Yanks as hypocrites. USADA will do the testing
and oversee the appeal process. Terry Madden, who was named CEO
Friday, says the agency will perform 5,000 doping tests next year,
half without notice. The board chairman will be Frank Shorter, the
1972 Olympic marathon champion who is convinced he lost to a doped
runner (East Germany's Waldemar Cierpinski) in 1976 . . . Back on
the track Sunday for the first time since she pulled out of last
summer's world championships with a back strain will be sprinter
Marion Jones, who'll run the 400 at the Mt. SAC Relays in
California. Jones won't run the event at the Olympic trials, but
she's hoping a fast time will get her a spot on the 4 x 400 relay
at Sydney, one of five possible gold medals for her . . . The
Golden League track organizers may be handing out 50 kilos of gold
ingots to athletes who win six of their seven meets this year, but
the cash value is only half of last year's $1 million jackpot. At
least they're not paying off in euros . . . First international
test for the US Olympic women's gymnastics hopefuls under Bela
Karolyi comes this next week in New Zealand against the Chinese and
Australians and 10 other nations in the Pacific Alliance meet. If
the Americans can make the top two, it'll be a sign of improvement
since last year's sixth-place finish at the world meet. On the
squad are Amy Chow, Vanessa Atler, Elise Ray, Morgan White, Erinn
Dooley and Marie Fjordholm . . . Second chance (of three) to earn
Olympic boxing spots comes this week for light flyweight Brian
Viloria, welterweight Dante Craig, and light heavyweight Michael
Simms Jr. at the regional qualifier in Mexico. The other nine squad
members already got their tickets punched at the first qualifier in
Tampa last month. Since lightweight Marshall Martinez has left the
team for personal reasons, alternate David Jackson will have to
earn back the spot. Last chance comes in late May in Argentina . .
. The failure of the US women's field hockey team to qualify for
the Olympics (for only the second time) continues a gradual
downward spiral from a World Cup bronze in 1994 to fifth in the
Olympics to eighth in the 1998 World Cup to out of the 10-team
Olympic field. The Americans, who needed to finish in the top five
at the recent qualifier in England, lost the fifth-place match,
2-0, to China, which had never made it to Olympus. ``We just need
to learn how to finish teams and put our opportunities away,'' said
captain Tracey Fuchs, whose mates scored just eight goals in six
matches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One yardstick for how much US men's soccer has developed since
the 1994 World Cup here: All but one of the 18 members of the
under-23 team, which will play in this month's Olympic regional
qualifier in Hershey, Pa., are professionals, 13 with MLS squads
(including the Revolution's Brian Dunseth). The Americans, who'll
meet Honduras and Canada in the prelims, need to make the finals of
the six-team tournament to get to Sydney . . . US women's soccer
team captain Carla Overbeck isn't the only prominent athlete who's
had to contend with Graves' disease (overactive thyroid). Sprinter
Gail Devers was diagnosed in 1988 and came back to win Olympic gold
medals in both 1992 and 1996. Overbeck's spot on the Olympic team
is all but automatic. ``I told Carla that she did not have anything
to prove to me,'' said coach April Heinrichs . . . Last chance for
a Sydney ticket for the US women's water polo team comes next week
in Sicily, where they'll have to finish in the top two at the
qualification tournament. Their top rivals will be Italy, Hungary,
and Russia. If an Asian team doesn't make the final eight (out of
13), the Americans can make it by placing third. The US males
earned their spot by winning last summer's Pan American Games . . .
One of the problems with holding the Olympics on an island (albeit
a continent) is marine life. Recent shark assaults on rowboats in
Sydney's harbor has some folks worried about holding the swimming
leg of the triathlon there, although there hasn't been a fatal
attack in the area in three decades. And migrating whales, passing
through on the way to Antarctica, could disrupt the sailing events.
While the whales aren't eligible to compete, they do have right of
way . . . Bridge as a winter Olympic sport? Why not, said Marc
Hodler, the octogenarian IOC member from Switzerland. ``The human
brain is at least as important as muscles,'' said Hodler, who wants
it as a demonstration sport at Salt Lake City. Only problem is, the
tables would have to be on ice or snow. Them's the rules at the
Winter Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
