<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIGLEY FINALLY COMES OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He was ready to give it up, quit, put the clubs in the
closet, and take a rest. Then the thought of missing a tournament _
just three rounds of golf _ nearly made him nauseous, so Dana
Quigley hopped on a plane, got to Indianapolis Thursday morning,
played in a pro-am that afternoon, and took part in the Comfort
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   OK, he didn't play well, but Quigley dreaded the call he had to
make to the good doctor. ``I was afraid to talk to (Dr. Bob)
Rotella about it. I didn't want to tell him,'' said Quigley, who
had promised the sports psychologist he'd take the week off. ``He
called me and said, `I heard you're playing,' and I said, `Yeah.'
He said, `Well, I'm proud of you. You took three days off.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That was last September, but Quigley related the story after
shooting 69 Thursday in the first round of the PGA Seniors'
Championship at PGA National in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla. He enjoys
telling that story because it serves as the perfect framework to
what he is all about. Which is? ``No one can understand that I do
not get mentally or physically tired by playing golf,'' he said.
``I get such a joy and such a pleasure out of competing against
these guys that it really, really pumps me up. You know, I may be a
strange bird, but that's the way it is for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley turned 53 Friday, but acts like a 23-year-old because
he's getting a chance to live the life he felt he should have had
when he was 30 years younger. He was an aspiring Tour professional
back then, with long hair and bell-bottom pants, but for one reason
or another, it did not work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the amount of money I'm making now, that's got to be
a reflection of missed opportunity,'' he said. ``I worked so many
years without making anything _ I'm making up for lost time in that
area.''
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, said Quigley, the reason the PGA Seniors'
Championship marks his 100th consecutive start (for which he's been
eligible) has to do with more than money. ``As for the passion for
playing golf,'' he said, ``that's been inside me forever.''
</P>
<P>
   He made his Senior Tour debut in this event just four days after
turning 50 in 1997 and Quigley has taken time off only in the
offseason. There was that memorable playoff victory in Long Island
in late 1997, a joy tempered by the news of his father's death, and
a pair of victories in 1998 as Quigley cracked the million-dollar
mark in season earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he teed it up in 38 events, finished second twice,
third three times, and was in the top 10 an astounding 18 times. It
was another million-dollar season _ $1,327,658 to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I used to play when 100 or 200 bucks was a good
prize,'' said a grateful Quigley of his days that revolved around
state opens and New England pro-ams. He won virtually everything,
but probably spent most of his prize money traveling from Maine to
Rhode Island and everywhere in between. So now, when purses are
routinely more than $1 million, why wouldn't he be out there?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I continue to have the enjoyment I'm getting from it, I
don't know when it will ever stop,'' said Quigley, who has been
second twice among five top 10 finishes in nine starts this year.
Another million-dollar campaign seems certain, though Quigley was
asked if it is frustrating being close to, but not inside, the
winner's circle in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because I was poor for 50 years and I enjoy making money
out here. There's a lot of money for second, third, fourth, and
fifth as well as for winning. I have never, ever given it a thought
whether I'll win again or not. It doesn't absolutely matter at all
to me. What I've done already _ I'm still in shock from what I've
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Refreshingly honest, but for good reason. Quigley only dreamed
of the spotlight many of his current colleagues _ Jack Nicklaus,
Hale Irwin, Lanny Wadkins, Tom Kite, Tom Watson _ embraced
seemingly with ease, and it took Quigley a long time to gain the
confidence to play on the Senior Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared me to death that I would be back out when I was 50
and trying to beat these guys who I couldn't beat back when I was
20 or 30,'' said Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   Along these lines, Rotella proved crucial. Quigley met him in
1996 through his fellow Rhode Islander, Brad Faxon, who worked with
Rotella for years. ``(Rotella) had a lot of respect for my game for
some reason,'' said Quigley. ``Somehow I bought into what he was
saying and I just came out and believed in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a belief that paid off handsomely. It may pay off with a
win at this weekend's major championship, but if it results in
another top 10 finish, or even less, no worries, said Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to the next tournament and getting on site of the next
week is what pumps me back up. I'm excited when I go to these. I
can't wait to get to (next week's Las Vegas Senior Classic)
already.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   US Amateur champion David Gossett, a sophomore at the University
of Texas, has a decision to make regarding his future. ``I can play
here with these guys,'' said Gossett, the only amateur to make the
cut at the Masters. ``I just need to sharpen a few things up.''
Gossett shot 75-71-79-78 to tie Jack Nicklaus at 303, but making
the cut at the Masters and playing on Tour are different animals.
He returned to college, but there are some marquee events on his
schedule _ the Memorial in May, the US Open in June, the British
Open in July _ and a decision will be made this summer. ``For 20
years old, I like where I'm at.'' . . . Nicklaus, who played the
final round of the Masters with Gossett, was asked for his rookie
recollections of Augusta. ``I remember hitting 31 greens in
regulation (out of 36 holes), having eight three-putts, and
shooting 150. Arnold Palmer hit about 19 greens and shot 141. I
knew then that it isn't how many greens you hit, it's how you get
it in the hole.'' Because it was a spur-of-the-moment answer, it
seemed appropriate to check Nicklaus's memory. Sure enough, in
1959, he shot 76-74 and missed the cut. Palmer shot 71-70 . . .
After he completed his first Masters, Padraig Harrington was
greeted by a small, but loyal group of fellow Irishmen off the 18th
green. ``I enjoyed the experience tremendously,'' said Harrington,
who qualified for the Masters because he was in the top 50 in the
World Rankings as of Jan. 1. He has fallen since, which kept him
out of The Players Championship, but give him credit for
dedication. He went to South America for two events (he finished
second and first) and was exhausted when he finally made it to
Augusta. And Augusta National is not an easy course to figure out.
``It's a far different course, mentally speaking, than I've ever
seen. You doubt your yardages, you doubt your distances. It's
tricky _ and I like that.'' . . . Pssst, if you are looking for a
Masters darkhorse next year, you could do worse than Carlos Franco.
In two starts at Augusta, the talented gent from Paraguay has
finished T-6 and T-7. He opened with a 79 this year, but shot three
straight sub-par rounds _ 68-70-69 _ to finish eight shots back. In
eight rounds, Franco has been under par four times, even twice, and
1 over once . . . Then there's Tim Herron, who missed the cut for
the third time in four starts at Augusta. In 10 rounds, Herron has
broken par once. He's shot 75 or higher seven times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Daly continues to struggle. Tuesday night, he reportedly
had an altercation with his girlfriend in front of a McDonald's in
Auburn, Ala. When police arrived at the scene, Daly reportedly was
tossing clothes out of a van. Earlier in the day, Daly played in a
celebrity pro-am . . . Kite has committed to the FleetBoston
Classic Aug. 25-27 at Nashawtuc CC in Concord. He will help kick
off festivities as the featured guest at a breakfast Aug. 22 at
Boston's Radisson Hotel. The breakfast will be limited to 250
people and tickets are $50. For information, call 978-371-0116 . .
. USA Network's ratings for the Thursday-Friday coverage of the
Masters were 24 percent higher than in 1999, earning a 2.6 . . .
Peter Kostis, on Australian amateur Aaron Baddeley: ``At age 19, I
feel like he's a more complete and accomplished player than Tiger
Woods was at 19. Now, we'll have to see if he continues his
development as Tiger has, but, boy, he is a special player.'' . . .
Entries for the Mass. Open must be in by April 27. The tournament
is June 19-21 at the Country Club of Pittsfield, with qualifiers
scheduled at six sites May 30-31. On-line registration for many MGA
events is available at MGAlinks.org . . . Former two-time
heavyweight champ George Foreman will visit South Shore CC in
Hingham Wednesday for the Eamonn Coghlan-Neal Cusack Marathon Golf
Classic, which benefits Our Lady's Hospital for Sick Children in
Dublin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
