<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VARGAS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING IMPRESSED WITH VARGAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS - Don King on Saturday night was full of talk, which,
for the man with the electric hair, was no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   King was among the 6,631 people who witnessed the coming out
party of Oxnard's Fernando Vargas, who not only withstood every
serious challenge by Ike Quartey, but had Quartey looking
completely beaten up, his right eye nearly swollen shut.
</P>
<P>
   In winning a convincing unanimous decision over Quartey to
retain his International Boxing Federation junior middleweight
belt, Vargas jumped right into super stardom, though he would
probably say he was already there.
</P>
<P>
   After the fight, Vargas (19-0, 17 KOs) said he wanted Felix
``Tito'' Trinidad, the WBA champion, next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show Trinidad how a real Mexican fights,'' said
Vargas, obviously alluding to Oscar De La Hoya, who ran away and
hid from Trinidad in their bout last September, losing his WBC
welterweight belt in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Vargas was a fighter's fighter Saturday. Everything
Quartey did, Vargas did better, and stronger. And was King ever
impressed afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great opportunity for Fernando Vargas to prove
himself,'' said King, who said he is hopeful of beginning
negotiations for a Trinidad-Vargas bout as soon as possible. ``And
we think Vargas proved himself tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people might say that Quartey had not fought in 14 months
or whatever, and that may be true. But you can't take nothing away
from Fernando Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got caught, he was still there. He didn't get on his
bicycle and make like Carl Lewis or Jesse Owens. I think the kid
did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Another obvious shot at De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   King said that Main Events Chief Operating Officer Gary Shaw,
who promotes Vargas, already has approached him about a unification
bout, which could be held in October at Caesars Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no deal in place, but Gary Shaw had asked me if Vargas
won, would we make this fight,'' King said. ``So let's see now if
he can talk that talk and walk that walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Shaw: ``We are ready, willing and able to fight Felix
Trinidad.''EP Added Shelly Finkel, co-manager for Vargas: ``I just
talked to Don King, and hopefully this week we can start serious
negotiations. I am going to make Vargas-Trinidad.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, complimentary as he was about Vargas, King made no
bones who he believes is the best fighter not only in the division,
but the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Felix ``Tito'' Trinidad is the best fighter
anywhere,'' King said. ``He doesn't run from no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by Vargas' performance, neither will he once the two
warriors get ready to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   Only minutes after the bout had ended, and while Quartey was
leaning on the ropes, his face battered and his ego bruised, Vargas
talked to Trinidad through a television camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tito, you are a great fighter,'' Vargas said. ``I think you
are the only one who will step up and unify the division.''
</P>
<P>
   The queston is, who else but Trinidad would have a shot at
defeating Vargas, who was obviously in the best shape of his life,
and fought like it, too?
</P>
<P>
   There is one hurdle for Vargas to clear, however. His trial on
felony assault charges begins Monday in Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fight of a different kind, to be sure. But if Vargas,
King and Trinidad are to realize their dreams, a victory in court
for Vargas would be very helpful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
