<HEADER>
A8346 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-COACHES-ICONS-LOST-TE     04-16 2330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACHES-ICONS-LOST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL OF THE LEGENDS: POSITION OF COACH HAS LOST ITS STATURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vince Lombardi must be rolling over in his grave.
</P>
<P>
   And no doubt Vince McMahon is dancing atop it.
</P>
<P>
   Once a throne reserved for hard-nosed icons to persevere by
preaching prose and teaching Xs and Os, the coaching profession of
the 21st century is downsizing into faceless figureheads forced to
passively motivate millionaires, pacify fans infatuated with glitzy
instant gratification, and appease corporate owners demanding a
healthy bottom line and a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   While players push contracts into an unfathomable nine digits,
coaches are paying the price.
</P>
<P>
   Saddled with more pressure, less respect and shorter leashes,
coaches in all sports are struggling to keep jobs for 29 months,
rendering Tom Landry's 29 ``years'' with the Dallas Cowboys as
untouchable as Joe DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The erosion of the coach's stature is an alarming problem,''
said sports psychologist Dr. Don Beck, director of the National
Values Center in Denton. ``The profession has been overwhelmed by
two deep trends. One, the idea of `good authority' has gone out the
window. Two, the financial pressure to win-or-else has politicized
coaches from role models into selfish entrepreneurs. We've lost
longevity, followed by trust. When you lose trust, coaches no
longer have the proper control.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: Goodbye, Woody Hayes; Hello, P.J. Carlesimo. The
macho mojo has migrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret players have the power today, not the
coaches,'' said Red Auerbach, who coached the Celtics for 20 years
and has been with the Boston organization for 50. ``Players are
getting coaches fired instead of vice-versa. \RPlayers\S realize
there are pots of gold at the end of the rainbow other than just
winning as a team. And some of them, like all these million-dollar
endorsement deals, have little or nothing to do with listening to
your coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Stars coach Ken Hitchcock, ``Coaches aren't the show,
players are the show.''
</P>
<P>
   The towering hub of the sports world flowchart from Pop Warner
football to the World Series, ``Coach'' was often loved, sometimes
loathed, always respected. But in this knee-jerk era of greed,
quick fixes and sound bytes, coaches are getting less time to make
their first impressions last.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of the current coaching landscape reveals that 77 of
the 118 head coaches in the four major-league sports have been with
their teams three years or less. Barely a half-century removed from
Connie Mack's unthinkable 50-year reign as manager of the
Philadelphia Athletics, no current coach in any of the four major
sports has had the same employer longer than Tom Kelly's 15 years
with the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL _ once ruled by larger-than-life 25-year icons like
Landry and Miami's Don Shula _ only 16 coaches hired since the 1970
merger have stuck with their first teams more than eight years. In
the NHL, where a coach's average tenure is 2.4 years, there have
been six firings since the start of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are dinosaur careers like North Carolina's Dean Smith (34
years) and the Los Angeles Dodgers' Tom Lasorda (21), about as
likely to return as eight-tracks and busy signals. And, as
remaining sideline stars like Penn State's Joe Paterno (34) and
Indiana's Bob Knight (30) run out of lifelines, coaching will
continue the trend away from George ``Papa Bear'' Halas and toward
Craig T. Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never see another Landry or another Shula, forget it,''
said New York Giants longtime general manager George Young. ``It's
a different world now. The prices of the franchises are higher, the
odds are greater, the stakes are more lucrative and the focus on
the teams is more intense. I think there's more pressure on coaches
today than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys recently promoted Dave Campo and the Mavericks are
expected to soon hire a new coach. But it doesn't take a 1040
short-form expert to deduce that neither will be here long.
</P>
<P>
   Since Landry's firing in 1989, the Cowboys have been through
four coaches. The Mavericks, led by Dick Motta in their first seven
years, are looking to hire their ninth coach in 13 years if Don
Nelson's successor is selected in the off-season, as expected.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only underachievers like the Cowboys' Chan Gailey or
one-year blunders like the Mavericks' Quinn Buckner and the
Dodgers' Glenn Hoffman who are signing contracts that far outlive
their tainted tenures. Whether it's the Florida Marlins' Jim
Leyland having his team dismantled because of budget, the Cowboys'
Jimmy Johnson and the Chicago Bulls' Phil Jackson leaving due to
ego clashes with management or the St. Louis Rams' Dick Vermeil
finally running out of years if not tears, simply winning is no
longer enough for even championship coaches to keep coaching.
</P>
<P>
   This off-season alone, four NFL coaches with Super Bowl rings
(Vermeil, Miami's Jimmy Johnson, the New York Jets' Bill Parcells
and the New Orleans Saints' Mike Ditka) stepped off coaching's
carousel. Only Ditka was fired. Vermeil first retired 18 years ago
as the Philadelphia Eagles' coach, citing ``burnout.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize what a stressful job coaching is,'' said
Leon Barmore, the Louisiana Tech women's coach who announced his
retirement earlier this month after 18 years. ``I'm scared to
death. This has been my life. But one thing I won't miss is the
stress. It's taken its toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Barmore has more to give, however. On Thursday, he
announced he was coming out of retirement to finish his contract at
Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   But for every Barmore who stubbornly endures, there's a Clyde
Drexler in Houston or a Danny Ainge in Phoenix who voluntarily gets
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our league, it's have 10 good years and then one bad one
and you're fired,'' said Nelson, the sixth winningest coach in NBA
history during his 20 seasons. ``The only thing different now is
it's a fair trade-off because we're paid so well. In the old days,
we were in that same predicament for little or no money.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether a side-effect of a society obsessed with how much
instead of how, or simply a vanishing of respect coinciding with
the perceived status of money, the legacy and longevity of the head
coach are diminishing. There's still a Scotty Bowman in Detroit, a
Pat Summitt at Tennessee, a Bobby Bowden at Florida State, a Robert
Hughes at Dunbar and a Gene Hackman in ``Hoosiers'', but coaching's
Old School is about to close its doors.
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not, today's sports environment idolizes Wrestling's
``The Rock'' more than Notre Dame's Rockne, and craves McMahon's
XFL style just as much as Lombardi's Green Bay substance.
 &LR; subheds:JUST WIN _ NOW _ BABY! Unlike the loyal backers who
cheered Alabama's Paul ``Bear'' Bryant in the '70s, DePaul's Ray
Meyer in the '80s and even the Yankees' Joe Torre in the '90s,
fans, boosters and owners have lost the art of patience.
</P>
<P>
   Energized by modern technology and the Internet, they no longer
wait for preheating ovens, last night's late scores or 6-8 weeks to
allow delivery of their K-Tel albums. Instead, they pop dinner in
the microwave, turn on ESPN and download their favorite song from a
web site before it's time to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, they don't have time to wait for a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like you want to win now,'' Campo said. ``I think
\Rowner\S Jerry Jones wants to win now. I want to win now. He puts
an awful lot of money in what he does and he expects a positive
return on his investment. And the fans don't want a five-year plan,
they want results now. Is that pressure? Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches, like Rangers manager Johnny Oates, sense the
increased pressure from a dramatic change at the top of
organizations now run by bottom-line committees instead of
soft-hearted individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of ownership has changed,'' said Oates, beginning
his sixth season in Arlington. ``These are people who made their
money outside of baseball and they're used to the corporate world.
I remember when John McMullen fired Bob Watson as the Astros'
general manager. He said he thought it was a good idea to change
people around every two years so things don't get stale. You make
changes whether it's necessary or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a comparison of annual rainfall in the Farmer's Almanac, no
team better illustrates the dehydrated coaching climate than the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   After posting a record of 18-38 in his first four years as
Cowboys coach, Landry was awarded a 10-year contract extension by
owner Clint Murchison Jr. After posting a record of 18-16 and two
playoff berths in two years, Gailey was fired by Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that NASDAQ-volatile mix yearly roster changes via free
agency, salary cap squeezes and early departures from college, and
the pressure to win is growing faster than the list of dot.com
millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there are smaller windows,'' Campo said. ``You've
got a great team one year and you're expected to take that next
step. But all of a sudden, one guy is gone, your chemistry is
changed, and you're out of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obstacles, there are still a precious few coaches
who can harness Regis Philbin's power and Mark Cuban's money.
Parcells wrote his own ticket, as has Phil Jackson. With a unique
perspective and an abundance of talent to work with, Jackson has
the Los Angeles Lakers on the verge of 70 victories and his image
comfortably two steps in front of the on-rushing critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at it as some sort of miracle,'' said Lakers owner
Jerry Buss of his first-year coach. ``He probably has some
characteristics of somebody from outer space. I don't think anybody
expected the instant success that he's had. We thought it would
take more time. It usually does.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an era of endorsements, egos and exaggerated bank
accounts, there is much more chagrin than Zen.
</P>
<P>
   Even more daunting than the task of winning for today's coach is
the challenge of keeping players' minds on their play and off their
pay. With athletes comparing stacks of dead presidents and
listening to agents diagram marketable end-zone dances instead
listening to coaches instructing them how to actually score
touchdowns, it's no wonder most coaches claim money is the root of
the player-coach communication meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't coach the money anymore,'' Hitchcock said. ``But you
can't be afraid of it, either.''  &LR; subheds:TALENT OVER TEACHING Red
Holzman's 18-year stint with the New York Knicks is as dead as the
hook shot because owners are finally learning what racetrack
bettors paid dearly to acquire long ago: the reality that a bad
horse with a good jockey is still a bad horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any magic, none of us do,'' said Knicks coach
Jeff Van Gundy, who has seen 47 NBA coaching coaches during his
five seasons in New York. ``You have no chance if you don't have
great players and, at heart, good people. Some teams just keep
going through coaches when what they need to do is get new players.
Look at Phil \RJackson\S. He gets to start with the best player
\RMichael Jordan\S in the game. He went from being a maverick to a
genius. But if you start with the Clippers, everyone assumes you
can't coach.''
</P>
<P>
   In football, it was Kurt Warner, Marshall Faulk and a healthy
Isaac Bruce that turned the Rams' Vermeil into a champion this year
after a combined 9-23 record the two previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Further decreasing the importance of coaches, owners also
realize that fans don't pay to see the Donna Karan bikini; they pay
to see Heidi Klum make it move. And they don't pay to see Jackson's
Triangle offense; they pay to see Kobe Bryant use it to get free
for a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches _ like Nebraska's Tom Osborne (24 seasons), the
Pittsburgh Steelers' Chuck Noll (23) and the Twins' Tom Kelly (15)
_ were fortunate to succeed without changing expression, much less
changing. But Landry began failing because he resisted change, a
stubbornness the aging icons realize they must avoid to fight off
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you have to change your strategies and you have to
change how you present them,'' Jackson said. ``What you don't ever
have to change are your principles. That's what you stand on.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches realize the only two types of species are those that
have been fired and those that will be. They acknowledge that the
career footsteps of Frank Broyles' 19 seasons at Arkansas and
Darrell Royal's 20 at Texas aren't likely to be traced. But they're
also alarmed that Jim Cleamons was fired by the Mavericks after
only 98 games, Ray Rhodes by the Packers after one season and
Robbie Ftorek by the New Jersey Devils despite his team being in
first place in the Eastern Conference with a month left in the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Once strong-armed by larger-than-life legends such as John
Wooden, Bryant and Lasorda, today it's easier to name the members
of 'N Sync than the head coaches of UCLA basketball (Steve Lavin),
Alabama football (Mike DuBose) and the Dodgers' manager (Davey
Johnson).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame, but it's to the point where coaching has to be
rewarding on a season-to-season basis rather than over a long
career,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   To remain vital, the coaching fraternity is tweaking its image
by implementing computers, cozying up to administrators, visiting
inner cities, adding assistants and considering minorities as
legitimate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The face of coaching doesn't need a complete makeover. Purdue's
Gene Keady can keep his intense comb-over, the Miami Heat's Pat
Riley can maintain his cool slickback and Florida's Steve Spurrier
can continue hurling his visor. But staring down a crisis that has
seen them lose control, authority and longevity, coaches are
realizing they have to at least call minor audibles in order to
keep what they desperately want:
</P>
<P>
   And that's Lombardi's legacy alive, and McMahon's influence in
check. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
