<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8347 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-LEBRETON-COACHES-TEX     04-16 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBRETON-COACHES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH BIGGER THAN LIFE ON AMERICAN LANDSCAPE 
WITH COACHES-ICONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was the coach of our basketball team, and we loathed him.
</P>
<P>
   He screamed at us. He belittled us. He called us stupid. In the
vernacular of the time, he said we played like a girl.
</P>
<P>
   We were 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   His name is unimportant, because you don't know him. He never
amounted to anything as a coach, beyond the dozens of
now-inconsequential games that he always won at our local
playground level.
</P>
<P>
   The memories fade. We forget our parents' anniversary. We forget
our third-grade teacher. We forget the name of the girl that we
asked to the prom.
</P>
<P>
   But we don't forget a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Long after the youthful tears dry, we remember his stinging
words. His temper. The way our stomachs churned, knowing we would
have to face him in practice.
</P>
<P>
   To most of us, the coach is the first contentious authority
figure that we encounter outside of home. Teachers are loved and
compassionate. Their anger passes.
</P>
<P>
   But the coach is a master of his domain. He controls the flow of
perspiration and of tears. He can demand that you change your
tackling style. He can sit you on the bench. He controls both the
carrot and the stick.
</P>
<P>
   From our early days, we are steered into sports. The coach
teaches us the rules. He becomes our sharpest critic.
</P>
<P>
   All too often, a child forms his lasting impressions of a sport
_ and sometimes of athletics, in general _ solely because of his or
her first coach. The responsibility is seldom acknowledged. To a
coach, the players are the expendable ones.
</P>
<P>
   But there is only one coach.
</P>
<P>
   At the higher levels, television cameras fixate on him.
Newspapers rush to quote him. Alumni pine to play golf with him.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Royal, Tom Landry, Paul ``Bear'' Bryant, John Wooden,
Woody Hayes _ they all ascended to a higher coaching plane. When a
coach wins, his words and ways can take on an aura of
infallibility. There is no madness in his methods.
</P>
<P>
   It is no mere coincidence that the punching incident that felled
Hayes' Ohio State coaching career did not come in the 1978 Rose
Bowl, but in the less-alumni-pleasing Gator Bowl. In Indiana, with
no recent Final Fours to buffer the basketball coach's foul words,
the heat is even being turned up on the loutish Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Because sports is so ingrained in the fabric of our society, the
coach invariably casts a broad shadow in the community.
Consequently, he can be both revered and reviled, lauded and
loathed _ sometimes all in the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After all, we all have an opinion about the coach. The cab
driver on his way from the airport, the hairdresser at the beauty
shop, the neighbor next door _ they all have their own ready
assessments of the town's Don Nelson and its Johnny Oates.
</P>
<P>
   A bad coach can ruin a Friday night. A good coach can launch a
parade and a civic holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The good coach gets a house on the lake. The bad coach gets a
``For Sale'' sign planted in his front yard.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Cowboys' Chan Gailey seemed to be fired as much
for his insipid style as his playoff lapses. Any teller at the bank
will tell you that.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, however, was a victim of the changing times. Whereas
Landry coached for an owner who gave him a 10-year contract
extension following a losing season, coaches today often have to
answer to an owner or athletic director who has many millions of
dollars at stake.
</P>
<P>
   For owner Jerry Jones, Gailey became a tough sell. Nelson was
walking that same plank, until the NBA Mavericks mustered a spring
surge.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's new boss, Mark Cuban, paid $280 million to buy the
Mavericks. Rangers owner Tom Hicks, who employs Oates, has 49,200
seats to fill every night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Where a coach's primary pressure used to be winning, in other
words, he now has to pull his weight in a business with a bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than a decade, what was once perhaps the most
glamorous job in sports _ head coach of the Dallas Cowboys _ has
become a seat far too uncomfortable to easily fill. The line of
succession runs from the Hall of Famer Landry to two-time Super
Bowl winner Jimmy Johnson, to the previously underemployed Barry
Switzer, to overmatched and career-long assistant Gailey, and now
to Dave Campo, who has never been a pro or Division I college head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   In Landry's day, he was a symbol of the franchise, just as
Bryant was at Alabama, Royal at Texas and Frank Broyles at
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The list of latter-day coaching ``gods,'' however, has grown
slim. Florida State's Bobby Bowden and Joe Paterno of Penn State
may be the only two football coaches left whose patriarchal
presences dominate their universities. The ``patriarch'' coach can
operate his program both under the table and above the law. Critics
are discouraged. Resistance is futile.
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, the phenomenon is uniquely American. We are a
nation dominated like no other by team sports. And the coach of the
team _ the hometown team, usually _ inevitably assumes a golden
space on the sporting landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Americans enjoy following golf and tennis, for instance, but few
could name any golf or tennis coaches. Gymnastics' Bela Karolyi,
who rose to prominence on the Olympic stage, may be the one coach
who has found notoriety in non-team sports.
</P>
<P>
   From our earliest days, we are channeled into signing up for
``the team.'' We try on the uniform. We meet the coach.
</P>
<P>
   For a parent, the unwritten contract is taken far too lightly.
Several youth leagues now run background checks on their
prospective coaches. Nearly all youth associations require their
coaches to be registered and tested, at least in the most
fundamental skills.
</P>
<P>
   It's a start, but most parents know little or nothing about
their kid's coach, his or her playing experience or whether he or
she can teach your child even the basic skills. In the eyes of most
parents, sadly, the coach's competence is directly related to how
often their own child gets to play.
</P>
<P>
   I spent eight years coaching my son. I tried to teach the
fundamentals. I labored to make our baseball practices fun. Before
the start of each season, I would announce to the parents that
every boy would get to play and every boy, including the coach's
son, would take his turn to sit.
</P>
<P>
   To some parents, it still wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   But we made a lot of happy memories. When our scrappy little,
overachieving fifth-grade basketball team used its final timeout of
the season to hold a group hug, there wasn't a dry eye amongst the
coaching staff. And when our rawest beginner, a smiling young man
named Clay, got the first base hit of his life late in one baseball
season, the glow on his face sent a chill up my jaded spine.
</P>
<P>
   We are all coaches at heart. Maybe that's why we have so many
strong opinions about the men and women who coach the teams we
love.
</P>
<P>
   We don't forget a coach.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, I was reading my hometown paper when I saw the
obituary for my old, original basketball coach. The screamer. The
one who called us 10-year-olds stupid and teased us when he made us
cry.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't send flowers.  &LR; tagtop:Gil LeBreton, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:lebreton &LR; star-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
