r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     04-16 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS LOSE IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After clinching the top seed for next month's NBA
Draft lottery with Friday's convincing loss at Phoenix, the
Clippers earned the luxury of breaking character.
</P>
<P>
   With no additional pressure to get clobbered, they might have
eased up on the lousiness throttle Saturday night and took a big
swing at the Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   They even had a victory precedent, having tagged the Nuggets as
their most recent (March 14) victims.
</P>
<P>
   So, rather than back into the lottery, the Clippers pushed
Denver to overtime before losing, 115-114, before 17,738 at Staples
Center. Rookie Lamar Odom, who received a rare benefit of a
doubtful call on a drive at the end of overtime, missed the second
of two free throws with .5 seconds before the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed a free throw to lose the game,'' said Odom, who
finished with 13 points and 13 rebounds. ``This one probably hurts
me more than if we lost by 30.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Anderson rallied from back-spasm agony to produce 31
points for the Clips, while Tyrone Nesby added 25 and 8 rebounds.
But the home tag team was trumped by Denver's 1-2 punch, with Nick
Van Exel getting 44 points and 8 assists, while Antonio McDyess
rang up 30 points and 20 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Van Exel ... he's not bad,'' said Clips interim coach Jim Todd
while studying the stat sheet. ``I told our guys that this just
goes to show how good you guys actually could be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers began game No. 80 with 15 consecutive losses and
the fresh glory of a Sports Illustrated cover story branding the
franchise as the worst in the history of franchises. Perhaps the
most frightening element to this ``worst'' aftermath is the
collective belief in Clipperville that the story could have been
even more damning.
</P>
<P>
   Chew on that a moment. Being judged only the worst ever is
considered a minor victory, because the historical assault on
Donald T. Sterling was believed to be relatively tame.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling, an infrequent Staples spectator of late, attended
Saturday's game, as did free-agent threats Anderson and Maurice
Taylor, who missed a pair of road games this week. Taylor (sore
ankle) didn't suit up vs. Denver, but Anderson (back spasms) had
the good fortune of feeling fit enough to play against a team he's
interested in playing for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow, I'll be sore as hell,'' Anderson said. ``I'll be in
treatment all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's audition produced a 9-point effort in the second
quarter, during which the Clips outscored Denver, 28-21, to take a
55-50 lead at intermission. It was their first halftime lead in
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers coughed up a 7-point lead in the third period, but
Anderson poured in another 7 to close the quarter with the home
team in front, 79-78.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter produced four lead changes before Van Exel
nailed a 3-pointer off a jump ball with 19.3 seconds left to send
the game into overtime at 98-98.
</P>
<P>
   Denver led by as many as five points in OT, but a 3-pointer by
Nesby put the Clips in range at 113-111, Nuggets, with 19.5 to
play. Before Odom's close, Van Exel missed 2 of 4 free throws,
while Anderson dropped 2 of 2. Odom followed Van Exel's last miss
with a baseline drive that was challenged by McDyess, who was
called for a phantom foul.
</P>
<P>
   Odom made the first shot, missed the second and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be the best loss we've had,'' Anderson explained,
``because we finished the game. I liked this game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
