<HEADER>
A8351 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-COACHES-OATES-SLUG-TE     04-16 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACHES-OATES-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RANGERS MANAGER REFLECTS ON HOW HE MANAGES THE COACHING LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY OATES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   {Johnny Oates has managed the Texas Rangers since 1995 and has
led the Rangers to division titles three of the past four years.}
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, a long time ago, so many things have happened to me
where in my mind, I said, why me?
</P>
<P>
   I can remember back playing Little League and the Junior League
team was short. They were getting ready to leave the complex at
Myrtle Beach, S.C., and the coach came over and asked me to play
with the 13-year-olds. I don't know why he picked me because there
were better players there than me.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a sophomore at Virginia Tech, we had a senior who was
the catcher all through the preseason drills. I just stayed in the
background; he did everything.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when we went to play North Carolina in our first game, not
only was I in the starting lineup but I was hitting fourth. Nobody
had ever given me an indication that was going to happen and to
this day, I don't know why.
</P>
<P>
   I've spent so much of my time asking why. Now I try to get past
that and just be thankful for what I have and not take it for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is part of this job. Where I used to get pressure from,
when I first became a manager, was trying to please everybody. I
played in the big leagues and I had no idea of the demands put on a
manager's time. I realized they had to do a lot of extra stuff but
I never imagined how much.
</P>
<P>
   I had to learn the press was not my enemy. That's where my
stress came from. Not from the game, not from trying to win. When
it comes time for the game to start, I love that part.
</P>
<P>
   I think I'm getting better with the press. At first I was a fish
out of water because I thought every question was not for
information but ``why did you do that you, dummy?'' Now that I look
back on it, the questions are the same now _ and some of them will
bug me after the third and fourth time _ but I think I'm getting
better every day in handling the media.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle is the self. Because I am a perfectionist,
I expect things to be done right. I don't expect to win every
ballgame but I expect things to be done right.
</P>
<P>
   I find it a challenge dealing with players and I tell them right
up front I don't treat them all the same. But I treat them all
fairly. I really believe I treat them all fairly.
</P>
<P>
   I may give Rafael Palmeiro privileges I don't give Ruben Mateo.
I might give John Wetteland privileges that I might not give
Francisco Cordero. I'm a little bit of the old school, I think you
earn privileges. But we all have boundaries regardless if you're a
Wetteland or a Scottie Sheldon or Mike Lamb. Because if you don't
have boundaries, there's chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly I've had disagreements with them, I've had
disagreements with Rusty Greer and it is pretty hard to believe
that you could have a disagreement with him. I've had a couple of
disagreements, believe it or not, over the past 33 years with my
wife Gloria. And I love her dearly. So those things are going to
happen. You just try to do it in-house and don't let those
disagreements become public.
</P>
<P>
   I realize I'm judged on my won-loss record. That's the job.
Everybody is judged on something. If Rusty doesn't hit, he's
probably going to be out of the big leagues. If Wetteland doesn't
pitch, he's going to be out of the big leagues. If we don't win,
I'm going to be out of the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   At the very beginning, I felt a whole lot of pressure to win. I
was so much focused on winning and pleasing people, I think that
was a lot of my problem. Now I know I can't please everybody so I
quit trying that.
</P>
<P>
   I was trying to please everybody and I found out the people I
was probably hurting the most were the people who loved me the
most, trying to please the people who could care less. Once I got
those priorities in order, I was able to let go some other things.
</P>
<P>
   I get frustrated and I hurt after a tough loss. I struggle
mentally when we lose a ballgame I feel we should have won. But I
think I'm able to put it away quicker than I used to and get ready
to come back the next day. If I do the best of my ability to manage
this ballclub, then the won-loss record is out of my control.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally I'd like to say I don't worry about it but I do think
about it. I think what can I do, what button can I push, what can I
say to someone to motivate them, what changes in the batting order
can I make, how can I create some offense.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's just walking through a clubhouse with my head up
after a tough loss letting everybody know it's going to be all OK.
The last thing the crew of a ship wants to see is their captain
start panicking.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
