<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COLUMBINE-GUNS0417-CO     04-16 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-GUNS0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed gun control legislation abounds in Columbine aftermath
 &HT;    By Shannon Joyce Neal
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ More than 20 gun-related bills have been
filed during the current session of the Legislature, the first full
session since the shootings at Columbine High School. They make up
a small fraction of the more than 700 bills filed, but for many,
they carry the promise of righting a horrible wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Their passage, some say, would somehow ease the pain inflicted
when two teen-agers April 20, 1999, killed 12 students and one
teacher before taking their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   While that might be debatable, it is certain that the shootings
catapulted Colorado's gun laws into the national spotlight, pitting
the ferocious defense of a constitutional right against those
calling on the Legislature to control access to a product that, in
the wrong hands, can devastate a community.
</P>
<P>
   Two Grand Junction residents for whom the Columbine killings
evoked particular horror typified the gun debate. They were among
the more than 100 western Coloradans who responded to the The Grand
Junction Daily Sentinel's request for thoughts and comments about
the first-year anniversary of the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot understand the resistance to the idea of a waiting
period and background check before every gun sale,'' wrote Carolyn
Latham, whose daughter was murdered. ``This should include gun
shows. Any law-abiding citizen with a conscience should be in favor
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The highest law was on the mind of Ron Taylor, whose nephew was
a student who escaped uninjured from Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law-abiding gun owners don't need to have their constitutional
rights infringed further, the lawbreakers and all those who misuse
firearms need to have the existing laws enforced and applied and to
be come down upon like the fist of God,'' Taylor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has drawn the attention of President Clinton, who
campaigned in Colorado last week for tighter gun control, including
a proposed voter initiative that would close the ``gun-show
loophole.'' Despite it having the support of Republican Gov. Bill
Owens, the GOP-controlled Legislature earlier this session rejected
a bill that would have required all buyers of guns at gun shows to
undergo a criminal background check.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the gun bills introduced since the Columbine
shootings have met the same fate. At least two _ including one
approved last week that would make it a misdemeanor to give someone
under 18 a gun without their parents' permission _ have made it to
Owens' desk to be signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the bills first came to the Legislature
(www.state.co.us/govdir/stateleg.html) before Columbine, such as
one that would create specific statewide standards for concealed
weapons permits and another that would prevent the state and local
governments from suing gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Gayle Berry, R-Grand Junction, said many of the gun
control and Columbine-related bills wouldn't have prevented what
happened at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Legislature has done some reasonable legislation
around the Columbine issue,'' Berry said. ``But not specifically
gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Pascoe, executive director of Sane Alternatives to the
Firearms Epidemic, or SAFE Colorado (www.safe.org), said many
people in the state saw the Columbine shootings as a wake-up call
for more gun control. While many of the bills would not have
prevented the Columbine tragedy, some may have made a difference,
Pascoe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just SAFE, the people of Colorado are clamoring for
gun laws,'' Pascoe said. ``The Legislature has turned a deaf ear
toward that effort.''
</P>
<P>
   SAFE member Tom Mauser, whose son Daniel was killed at
Columbine, said two statewide polls conducted after the shootings
showed up to 94 percent of Coloradans support mandatory background
checks for gun-show buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the attack, support was about 60 percent, according to
Marshall Kaplan, director of the Institute for Public Policy
</P>
<P>
   Gun-rights advocates, meanwhile, say it has been more difficult
to campaign for their cause in wake of Columbine, but it has helped
solidify their position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun owners are between a rock and a hard place here,'' said
Dudley Brown, executive director of Rocky Mountain Gun Owners
(www.rmgo.org).
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to go through an election cycle and see what
happens,'' he said. ``I think November will be a huge test for gun
rights in Colorado and across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   SAFE is leading the effort to get the gun-show loophole proposal
on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would require a background check on all gun show
sales. Under current laws, background checks are required only for
gun show sales by a federally licensed dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Anderson, who purchased one of the guns used in the
Columbine shootings at a Denver gun show, told a state House
committee she would not have bought the gun if she had had to go
through a background check.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the political debate, guns really aren't the problem,
some Grand Valley residents said.
</P>
<P>
   If gunmen Klebold and Harris hadn't had guns, they would have
found another way to kill, such as the bombs they planted around
the school, wrote Tony R. Martinez of Grand Junction, who said more
gun control would be only an ``emotional response.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we take a look at why so many people are becoming
violent in the first place and then maybe we can deal with the real
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents of gun control say the state already has too many
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Linn Armstrong, of the Pro-Second Amendment Committee in Grand
Junction, said Americans wouldn't tolerate such restrictions on
other freedoms guaranteed in the Bill of Rights. Such laws only
chip away at the rights of the law-abiding citizens and their
ability to protect themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But to come away from such a tragedy and do nothing to try to
prevent it from happening again is a greater wrong, wrote Dave
Murphy of Grand Junction.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the issue of handgun control, very little is clear except
for this: in 1996, handguns were used to murder two people in New
Zealand, 15 in Japan, 30 in Great Britain, 106 in Canada and 9,390
in the United States. In 1997, 10,369 people were murdered with
firearms in this country, and in the same year there were only 190
justifiable handgun homicides by private citizens in the United
States,'' Murphy said, citing Justice Department figures and
statistics from similar agencies in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want our elected leaders to do something proactively to
protect my child from getting her head blown off under a table in a
high school library. I don't expect or even want all that much from
my government, but I do expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
