 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, April 17, 2000:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-PROTEST (Washington) _ Developments as protesters try to
shut down World Bank meeting. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-VOICES (Washington) _ Travels with one of the protesters.
By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-FUND (Washington) _ The International Monetary Fund
discusses ways to update its organization. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-FOOD (Gode, Ethiopia) _ A look at the developing food
shortages that are threatening millions of Ethiopians. By Ian
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-LAND-DISPUTE (Johannesburg, South Africa) _
Developments in the standoff between white farmers and black
squatters in a government plan to take and redistribute land. By
Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Developments in peace
negotiations with the Palestinians as Prime Minister Ehud Barak
meets with his cabinet. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-MORDECHAI (Jerusalem) _ Israeli police recommend that
Transportation Minister Yitzhak Mordechai be prosecuted on three
counts of sexual assault, dealing a blow to a former general who
last year ran for prime minister as the first Sephardic Jewish
candidate in Israel's history. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TRIMBLE (ULSTER, Northern Ireland) _ In a determined
move to free himself from growing internal opposition to the
Northern Ireland peace agreement, David Trimble, leader of the
Ulster Unionists, says that he would rid his ruling council of
members of the traditionally militant Orange Order. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   ANDES-CRISIS (Undated) _ All over the Andes _ from Peru to
Colombia, Venezuela to Ecuador and Bolivia _ people are expressing
their anger at regimes that have not delivered. By Larry Rohter and
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-RUSHDIE (New Dehli) _ An interview with Salman Rushdie,
who has returned to his native India for the first time in more
than a decade since his novel ``The Satanic Verses'' was banned
there. By Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-SUPPORTERS (Miami) _ Night and day, a core of
supporters keep aflame the cult of Elian outside the home in Little
Havana. These are the true believers, the fanatics and worshipers
who have turned the boy into an icon. They are the ones with long
memories of Cuba before Castro, they are religious and zealous. We
spent time, even in the middle of the night, with this crowd and
let them voice their hope and fervor. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY-POLITICOS (Miami) _ Inside the political rivalries at
play in the Elian case, pitting the mayor of Miami-Dade against the
mayor of the city of Miami (a much smaller constituency) and other
south Florida politicians jockeying for power and using the Elian
case as a stepping stone. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY-HAVANA (Havana) _ Thousands turn out for more
demonstrations as the island waits for a decision in the United
States. Random interviews show less of a united front than that
given by the state-controlled media. By Randal C. Archibold.
</P>
<P>
   STUDENT-DRUG-TESTS (Lockney, Texas) _ For three years, people in
this tiny farming town fretted that stopping the local drug problem
was like trying to lasso the winds that blow day and night off the
flat Texas plains. Eventually, the school board enacted what is
considered the toughest school drug testing policy in the nation.
It requires that all of the 388 junior and senior high school
students take a mandatory drug test. Now, with more and more school
districts across the country instituting drug tests, Lockney, with
only 2,200 residents, has become an unlikely constitutional
battleground. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   HITECH-JANITORS (San Jose, Calif.) _ From 6 p.m. to 2 a.m. each
night, Guadalupe Herrera vacuums carpets and cleans bathrooms at
that pinnacle of high-technology success, Cisco Systems, and then
she heads home to the garage where she, her husband and two sons
live. When Maria Godinez returns late each night from her
$8-an-hour janitor's job at Sun Microsystems, she slips quietly
into the bedroom she shares with her husband and five children _
all part of a single-family house where four families and 22 people
live. High-flying companies like Cisco and Sun can rightfully boast
that they have created a new class of millionaires, but they have
spawned another class of workers: the invisible, nonstock-optioned
high-tech toilers, for the most part janitors, who earn too little
to afford decent housing in a booming region. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBINE-LITTLETON (Littleton, Colo.) _ The school shootings a
year ago had an impact on the nation, but the most lasting effect,
and the most dramatic, has taken place in the suburban town where
it happened. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   VICTIMS-SHIRTS (New Orleans) _ In New Orleans, where death is an
occasion for music and dancing on the streets, a new trend: the
making and selling of T-shirts emblazoned with the faces of murder
victims, not just any murder victims. The trend is so hot it's the
subject of a rap song by hiphop star Master P.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-VOUCHERS (Redwood City, Calif.) _ Once again a Silicon
Valley entrepreneur jumps into California's voter initiative
process as Timothy Draper presses for measure to give $4,000 school
vouchers for every child. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-INVESTIGATIONS (Undated) _ Why crash investigators are
having an increasingly harder time investigating plane crashes. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEMOCRATS (Washington) _ The similarities of the Bush
campaign with the Clinton campaign of 1996 go far beyond the mirror
image events to tactics. Clinton outflanked the new Republican
congressional majority by signing the GOP's welfare overhaul bill,
coming up with his own family values agenda, and agreeing that the
federal budget should be balanced. Now it is Bush who boldly talks
about issues usually associated with Democrats, thus making it
harder for Democrats to mount some of their usual lines of attack
against the Republicans. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CLINTON (Hollywood) _ For the first time since December,
Gore and Clinton are together on the same stage, raising money in a
place that adores the president, Hollywood. Not only did the two
raised $2.8 million, more than the night before in Silicon Valley,
but they lavished each other with praise and affection. Gore was
especially flattering, tying himself closely to the president, a
departure from Gore's campaign tactic of putting some distance
between himself and Clinton. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Dateline to come) _ ``Essay'' by William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Dateline to come) _ ``In America'' by Bob
Herbert.
</P>
