<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, April
17:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-PRIZE (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook: Rem
Koolhaas, perhaps the most influential architect of his generation,
has been awarded the Pritzker Architecture Prize for 2000, the
Hyatt Foundation, sponsors of the award, will announce on Monday.
The prize, which includes a $100,000 grant, will be presented in
Jerusalem on May 17. The choice of Koolhaas, 56, brings distinction
to the Pritzker Prize as well as to the architect. Founded in 1979,
the prize has been described as architecture's Nobel. By Herbert
Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-THEATER-AWARDS (Undated) _ The Prenilo Europa theater
awards in Sicily. By Cornelia Bessie
</P>
<P>
   SIEGFRIED-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ Wagner's ``Siegfried'' at
the Metropolitan Opera. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   KABBALAH-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Richard Bernstein reviews
``Dreams of Being Eaten Alive: The Literary Core of the Kabbalah,''
by David Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews ``Jesus
Christ Superstar'' at the Ford Center for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   THE MARKET:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-STRATEGY (Undated) _ What stock market strategists
predict will happen with the market when it opens on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-ASSESS (New York) _ News Analysis: How much of the
tech-stock down draft matters, in terms of the forward progress of
the New Economy? By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Nearly 13 years ago, investors
stunned by the worst stock market week in memory spent the weekend
pondering whether a great bull market was over. On the following
Monday, so many of them decided to sell that the Dow Jones
industrial average plunged 22.6 percent, or 508 points. Oct. 19,
1997, became known as Black Monday. In the years since, there have
been many bad days for the stock market, but no week as stunning in
its devastation as the past week. Now, as then, investors have
large profits they could choose to protect by fleeing a market that
had seemed so promising only weeks before. The decisions made over
the weekend by investors will largely determine whether last week's
slide in stock prices continues. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-MOOD (Undated) _ The mood across America concerning the
stock market's future course.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-INTERNET (London) _ The backlash is just beginning and
the messenger is getting the blame. As the technology-heavy NASDAQ
continues to tumble, the personal investors who plowed billions
into the market during its enormous run-up while cheering media
reports of it awesome rise are now blaming the media for their
misfortune as they watch their paper fortunes quickly vanish. By
Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-ASIA (Singapore) _ Asian markets brace for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER FINANCIAL NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TECHJOBS (Paris) _ Despite high levels of unemployment in
Europe, many technical jobs are going begging. The phenomenon is
opening up a touchy debate about whether Europeans should relax
some of their strict immigration policies. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-SPEEDUP (San Francisco) _ Anyone who has ever watched a
complex Web page paint itself onto the computer screen, image by
grudgingly slow image, can attest: The World Wide Web should be
faster. On that simple proposition there is virtually unanimous
agreement. Where the unanimity breaks down is on how to accomplish
this worthy goal _ and how to get paid for doing it. And on that,
the Web-performance industry splits into two factions, whose
leaders are divided by technologies and an entire continent:
Inktomi, in Silicon Valley, and Akamai, based in Cambridge, Mass.
By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The New Economy column: Assessing
BMG's curious, let-a-thousand-flowers-bloom approach to digital
music. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: So-called
affinity Web portals _ gateways to the Web intended for people with
common interests, like members of the AFL-CIO _ are not achieving
the success once predicted for them. But new ones keep being
created, like one that iBelong is creating for a national
association of scuba divers. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   SEINFELD-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Advertising column: Almost
