<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HEAT-DEATHS0417-COX     04-16 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-DEATHS0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heat deaths linked to medicationsBy Steve Bennish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Findings from health authorities have doubled the
number of deaths related to psychiatric medications taken by the
mentally ill during last summer's fierce Midwestern heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   New figures from the U.S. Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta
and the Cook County Medical Examiner's Office in Chicago show that
at least 23 of the estimated 300 dead were mentally ill people who
took medicines that made them especially vulnerable to death from
intense summer heat. The total number could be higher still since
not all coroners where heat deaths occurred performed toxicology
tests.
</P>
<P>
   A Dayton Daily News review of coroner reports immediately
following the July 21 to Aug. 3 heat wave found that at least 10
who died from heat stroke in Ohio, Missouri, Wisconsin and Kentucky
took such medications. The medications interfere with the body's
thermo-regulatory system, hazards known to physicians but seldom
publicized.
</P>
<P>
   Toxicology results from autopsies of 86 of the 116 reported dead
in Chicago _ test results not available last summer _ found that 10
had anti-psychotic or anti-depressant medications in their
bloodstreams at the time of death. Common drugs included Mellaril,
Elavil, Prozac and Zoloft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question people on anti-psychotic drugs have to be
more cautious in the sun and heat,'' Chicago chief medical examiner
Edmund Donoghue said. ``They are vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   The test results also found 20 with alcohol in their systems,
four with cocaine, and two with morphine.
</P>
<P>
   In Cincinnati, a case study by the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control examined 17 of the 18 reported heat deaths. It found that
four of the dead had prescriptions for medication with heat risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Results of a case-control study showed a particularly high
risk among young people with mental problems,'' the CDC report
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had four people on medication that can cause heat stroke,''
said Carl Parrott, Hamilton County Coroner. ``The goal now is to
help refine the response to these heat emergencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The CDC found that all of the Cincinnati dead had known risk
factors besides mental illness, including social isolation and no
air conditioning at their residence. None of the victims had
visited an official or private cooling shelter.
</P>
<P>
   In all, eight of the 17 had mental problems, the CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's 24 fatalities prompted Ohio Rep. Samuel Britton,
D-Cincinnati, to propose a bill requiring air conditioning in group
and nursing homes and assisted living centers. The bill also
requires air conditioning in housing for those older than 65. House
Bill 474 is currently awaiting action in the house Health,
Retirement and Aging Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC report recommended an emphasis on tracking people at
risk and increasing outreach, tightening regulations to limit
temperatures in assisted care facilities, and providing more
training for those who deal with heat-sensitive people.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Rubin, acting chief of the CDC's Health Studies Branch,
said air conditioning is a key factor in surviving a heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the one overwhelmingly protective factor,'' she said.
``Even limited exposure to air conditioning. It's part of most city
heat plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Health Commissioner Adcock, who requested the CDC
study, said he supports Britton's legislation because a deadly heat
stroke can suddenly affect those on medication without many obvious
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the lessons we learned is that it is not enough to
simply monitor,'' he said. ``We need a preventive strategy that
would allow temperatures to be maintained appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   As yet, the state Department of Health, which inspects group
homes, hasn't taken a position on Britton's bill. Marijean Siehl,
director of public affairs, said the department is concerned air
conditioning could cost group home operators too much and that
residents might squabble over the air conditioning and that the
department would also have to inspect the air conditioning units.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
