<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      04-16 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIGAR AFICIONADO TRIES A NEW BLEND 
FIRST STEPHEN KING. NOW VLADIMIR PUTIN. 
FASHION EDITOR TO LEAVE FOR ARTISTS' HIVE
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes a cigar is just a cigar, and sometimes a cigar
magazine, confronting the disappearing cigar-smoking fad, has to
make the word ``cigar'' almost disappear from its title.
</P>
<P>
   With the dwindling cigar market in mind, Marvin R. Shanken, the
founder, editor and publisher of Cigar Aficionado _ a magazine for
men who smoke cigars _ has redesigned the monthly. First published
in 1992, Cigar Aficionado became a hot title and won a National
Magazine Award for best Web site in 1999. But circulation peaked in
1997 at 384,000, and has since dropped to 291,000.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the June issue, which arrives on newsstands this
week, the title of the magazine has been altered: The word
``cigar,'' which was once about as big and fat as a Hoyo de
Monterrey Double Corona, is now barely the size of a half-smoked
cheroot. The word ``Aficionado'' dominates the cover, and Shanken
has added a new subtitle, ``The Good Life Magazine for Men.''
Coverage of cigars is relegated to its own penned-off section; the
June issue features an article about ``nine great spas,'' an
article by Camille Paglia on women in politics, and an essay by
Erica Jong on dogs. (``Poochkin died on the vet's operating table
... On rainy nights I seem to hear him scratching at the back door
to be let in.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that a lot of people, men, were not picking up the
magazine and giving it a chance because the name that came out was
Cigar, and Aficionado was underplayed,'' Shanken said. ``We wanted
to reposition it so that if you are a man who seeks the joys of the
good life you would at least give us a look. This way, if you're in
an airport and you're walking by, what jumps out at you is
`Aficionado.'''
</P>
<P>
   Shanken said that he would not rule out removing ``cigar''
completely from the magazine's cover.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Goldman, a consumer products analyst at Merrill Lynch
and an observer of Cigar Aficionado magazine, said that cigar sales
have slumped dramatically in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bloom is off the cigar rose,'' Goldman said. ``It was a
huge fad that peaked about two years ago. And as far as I can tell,
the size of the word `cigar' on the cover of the magazine is
proportional to cigar sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanken said last week that he had not yet shown the redesign to
tobacco advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They trust us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   First Stephen King. Now Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   First came horror, then instant history: Russia's new president
Vladimir Putin is taking an electronic page from Stephen King and
is preparing to issue his translated memoirs in a digital book that
will be available at the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   The new age Russian president and former KGB spy is also
considering another technical innovation to drop the veil on the
facts of his own life: chat room discussions with Internet users on
the MSNBC Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way things are going,'' said Peter Osnos, Putin's
American publisher at PublicAffairs. ``The new president of Russia
is publishing in the U.S. through this array of digital channels
that represents how the world is changing.''
</P>
<P>
   To publish the book in bytes, PublicAffairs struck a deal with
netLibrary, the Boulder, Colo.-based digital bookseller. NetLibrary
obtained the exclusive rights to issue Putin's memoirs, ``First
Person'' in electronic form. That means that the book will be
available for reading online on a personal computer or on a Palm
Pilot or similar device from netLibrary's Peanut Press Web site.
</P>
<P>
   NetLibrary is also in final discussions to sell titles through
other e-book manufacturers that offer portable devices for reading.
And with this alliance to publish Putin's memoirs, the company is
poised to spend over $250,000 to market the book, a sum that a
small company like PublicAffairs could not afford.
</P>
<P>
   The book is not a weighty tome of history but a chatty personal
memoir that seeks to humanize the Russian president with
information on everything from his KGB past to his wife's shopping
habits to quality time with his young daughters, Masha and Katya
(``They see him more often on television than at home.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this was absolutely the best way to show the true
power of an e-book,'' said netLibrary's chief marketing officer,
David Melancon. But that's just the English version; the wait for
the original Russian translation could last much longer than a
Moscow winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian version?'' said Melancon. ``I can tell you right
now that serving something in Cyrillic is not something we're able
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   Fashion Editor To Leave For Artists' Hive
</P>
<P>
   John Cheever once wrote that Yaddo, the 107-year-old artists'
colony in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., attracted ``all kinds _ lushes
down on their luck, men and women at the top of their powers,
nervous breakdowns, thieves, geniuses, cranky noblemen, and poets
who ate their peas off a knife.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, all those nervous breakdowns and pea-eating poets are going
to have a new president: Elaina Richardson, the editor in chief of
Elle magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Come again? The editor of a fashion magazine is going to run the
country's most august arts colony and temporary home to writers,
artists and composers like Truman Capote, Dorothy Parker, Aaron
Copland and Eudora Welty?
</P>
<P>
   Linda Collins, the head of the Yaddo search committee, points
out that Richardson, 38, has advanced degrees in literature from
Edinburgh University and Oxford University. And though her
credentials are a little different from those of Yaddo's current
president, Michael G. Sundell, who is retiring _ he is a former
English professor _ Collins said that no one had doubts after they
met with Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the fashion magazines go, Elle is really the most
intellectual and artistic of them,'' Collins said. ``But some of us
did stop to think: `But what about the fashion world. Is that what
we want?' But her background, her true nature and her personality
are intellectual. Just to be with her and hear her talk, we felt
that she was one of us, not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Also important, Richardson convinced the group that she had
innovative ideas about fund-raising for Yaddo, which must
supplement its endowment every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said some interesting things that made us all sit up
straight on the subject of fund-raising,'' Collins said. ``We
thought, `Gosh, we are babes in the woods compared to this
woman.'''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said that she would stay at Elle until September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this might have appeared strange if I had come up
through the fashion side of the magazine world,'' Richardson said.
``But my background is much more from the arts and culture side of
things. I first found out about Yaddo from knowing a lot of the
attending artists, so I have always felt close to the ideas of the
place and what it is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Cheever, a writer who regularly attends Yaddo, said that
she could not anticipate any opposition to Richardson. ``There are
a lot of old fogies at Yaddo, but they're not fogies in that way,''
said Cheever, the daughter of John Cheever. ``They're writers, for
heaven's sake. It's not a bank!''
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
