<HEADER>
A8452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TRASH-TALK-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      04-16 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRASH-TALK-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOMAN'S TALE OF CHILDHOOD NEGLECT SURPRISES HER PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The article ``Party's Over,'' in the April issue of Allure, is a
rich tale, full of family intrigue, sex and alcohol abuse. It reads
with the breathy pace of a Danielle Steele novel, complete with
liquor-soaked boat excursions in the Caribbean and a heroine who
wakes up woozily in a series of strangers' beds on expensive
linens.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, Taylor Stein _ blonde habitue of the Manhattan
party circuit, daughter of the nightclub owner Howard Stein and
granddaughter of Charles (Ruby) Stein, a loan shark connected to
the mob _ speaks at length about how the childhood neglect she
suffered at the hands of her parents contributed to her alcoholism.
As told by Judith Newman, a veteran magazine writer who has written
for publications like Harper's and Mademoiselle, it is a sad story,
woven with family history and psychological abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one question of journalism ethics raised by the
article: The magazine never checked out Stein's stories with her
parents, and in fact, as it points out in the article, obtained the
interview on the condition that it would not do so. Now both
parents charge that the piece is a fabrication by their daughter, a
cynical bid for attention in a world where any press _ no matter
how embarrassing _ is considered good press.
</P>
<P>
   Allure's editor in chief, Linda Wells, said the agreement was
legitimate under the circumstances and that it checked her story
with other sources ``in a position to know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our real objective was to provide readers a piece about one
woman's triumph over alcoholism,'' she said. ``The intention was to
have her point of view and recollections come through.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges leveled by Stein vary. She is quoted saying her
father was a playboy and ``every woman, every celebrity, every
hooker came first.'' Stein characterized her mother as an abusive
adulterer whom the pre-adolescent Stein once found in the living
room at 4 a.m., music blaring, dancing with a man other than Stein.
When she was 13, she said, after two months away from home, her
parents neglected to pick her up from the summer-camp bus, and she
walked home to an empty apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Stein said in the article that she began drinking soon after,
sneaking alcohol to school in her ``Herbie Rides Again'' thermos.
And when her drinking problem got serious her parents appeared to
ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   It is an eventually inspirational story _ Stein attended
Alcoholics Anonymous and says she no longer drinks _ even if the
allegations against her parents are harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, a restaurateur and nightclub owner who owns Au Bar, said
that the article took him completely by surprise. He said he was
most shocked by the fact that the magazine agreed to publish
``terrible, horrifying things'' about him, without considering
whether his daughter was angry or disturbed or had a vendetta
against her parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete fiction,'' Stein said. ``It's so depressing
that people who don't know me will think that this is the kind of
father I was, and that Helen was that kind of mother.'' Stein said
that the story about summer camp was ``hallucinatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein, the article reads, ``had a taste for'' liquor, ``but he
was always in control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't `have a taste for' liquor, with all that phrase
implies,'' Stein said. ``I drink one cognac after dinner with a
cigar as I have done for 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The article said, ``Stein grew up in a drinking family,'' where
she says, two or three bottles of wine were consumed at meals.
Stein said he did not drink wine, nor was wine a staple at family
meals.
</P>
<P>
   The Steins are now divorced, and the former Mrs. Stein, Helen
Glasser, lives in Puerto Rico. She did not hear about the article
until her son called her from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a state of shock,'' Glasser said. ``This all makes me
very sad, and I do not want to fight with my daughter. She made us
sound like uncaring, unsupervising parents, and I wish someone from
the magazine had called us to check that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stein, Stein's brother, said that he and his sister were
raised in a largely happy home, its security only threatened by the
divorce of their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then we had a wonderful stepfather,'' he said. Michael
Stein offered a psychological explanation for his sister's stories:
``I think the problem is that she runs with a crowd where
publicity, of any kind, has a certain value.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stein stood her ground last week, and said she had no
intention of hurting her parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to an Alcoholics Anonymous meeting, you tell your
story and people don't question whether it is true or whether it is
not true,'' she said. ``It is just your story. I did not lie, and
my parents have a right to defend themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein did not answer a question about why they were not allowed
to defend themselves in the article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
