u f BC-CANADA-PUBLISHER-MEDI     04-16 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-PUBLISHER-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN PRESS BARON ASSAILS BISHOP AS WELL AS STRIKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)  (Eds., $17,000 figure is CQ; amount is U.S. dollars) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Conrad Black, Canada's mightiest press baron,
has long delighted in a muscular give-and-take of insults. But in
his latest round, he may have overreached, going beyond usual
left-wing and unionist targets, and landing a punch on the
hierarchy of his adopted faith, Roman Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   In his newspaper here, The Calgary Herald, Black wrote early
this month that the local bishop was a Leninist-style ``useful
idiot,'' telling readers: ``If your jumped-up little twerp of a
bishop thinks I'm not a very good Catholic, I think he's a prime
candidate for exorcism.''
</P>
<P>
   The sin of the bishop, Frederick B. Henry, was to publicly urge
Black to negotiate with workers in a five-month strike at the
newspaper. Joining the attack, The National Post, Black's new
national newspaper, printed a column by Ted Byfield, a conservative
western Canadian journalist, calling the bishop ``Red Freddy'' and
bemoaning, ``The west seems fated to have at least one pinko
bishop.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Calgary's Christian leaders said in a statement
Wednesday: ``We condemn that defamatory and libelous statement
calling Bishop Fred Henry a `jumped-up twerp,' an `idiot,' and a
`pinko Commie'. These statements are so outrageous and un-Christian
as to merit no further comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Canada's oil-boom city, a conservative stronghold, the
strike at Black's newspaper has become a cause celebre of labor _
overshadowing even the grievances of the 206 striking workers.
</P>
<P>
   A lightning rod for liberal Canadians who detest Black's caustic
conservatism, the picket line has drawn the novelist Margaret
Atwood; Maude Barlow, chairwoman of the Council of Canadians, a
nationalist group, and leaders of the left-wing New Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   The press lord has obliged the left by playing the role of
capitalist ogre. When Andy Marshall, a striking Herald reporter,
asked Black, on a visit here, why ``do you insult your once-valued
employees?'' Black responded: ``We're not. We're amputating
gangrenous limbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Canada, union members and their allies have called for a
boycott of The Calgary Herald and The National Post, Black's
18-month-old paper. Unmoved, Black wrote a letter in January to Jim
Sinclair, British Columbia's top union leader, saying, ``If you
wish to cancel a subscription to The National Post (presumably as a
result of lip strain after too ambitious a foray into bisyllabic
reading), contact its circulation department.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from London, Black said ``the
commercial impact of the strike is virtually zero,'' far below the
25 percent drop in circulation union leaders here have claimed. He
added, ``We have not lost any of the advertising, except for some
from happy-clappy '60s churchmen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bishop overreached by sticking his episcopal nose in
things he didn't know anything about,'' he asserted. As for the
labor dispute, he predicted, ``The strike will go for two years and
then we won't have to keep their jobs anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Accustomed to using great leverage over union, corporate and
political opponents, Black, 55, operates from a formidable power
base. His Southam chain owns 61 Canadian daily newspapers, or 57
percent of the total number, the largest concentration of newspaper
ownership in any major Western nation.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the religious leaders' press conference here showed, he
increasingly encounters checks on his press power. Last June, Prime
Minister Jean Chretien moved to block Queen Elizabeth II from
granting a lifetime peerage to Black, who holds dual
Canadian-British citizenship. Outraged, the billionaire press baron
sued the prime minister for about $17,000, charging abuse of power
in denying him the chance to sit in the British House of Lords.
Last month, an Ontario judge dismissed Black's claim, but he is
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Black recognized limits on his ability to expand in
Canada when he turned down an opportunity to buy The Winnipeg Free
Press, the largest of five Canadian newspapers put up for sale by
Thomson Corp. Acknowledging that the newspaper would be ``a nice
fit,'' he told analysts, ``but I think in general we don't need
more political controversy than we already have.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Black, who also owns The Daily Telegraph of London
and The Jerusalem Post, aborted a foray into the New York newspaper
world when he abandoned an attempt to buy The New York Observer. In
the interview, he said, ``Just before we were going to get serious
about an agreement, we got a good look at the numbers, and they
were in stark contrast to how they had been presented.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Arthur L. Carter, publisher of The Observer, said:
``It's hard to believe, because he knew the numbers for six months.
I think the issue dealt around editorial control.''
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, Black, though awaiting audits, said The Post had
passed The Globe and Mail of Toronto in national sales, going over
the 300,000 mark. The new paper's losses have dropped in half, he
said, predicting that it would turn a profit in the last quarter of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Strikers here charge that the Southam chain subsidizes The Post,
much the way that Gannett subsidized USA Today until it turned a
profit, a decade after its appearance in 1982. Referring to Black's
Hollinger Corp., the owner of the Southam chain, Marshall charged:
``The Herald has been a cash cow for Hollinger in Canada. They bled
it, and they intend to bleed it, for The National Post.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Dan Gaynor, publisher of The Calgary Herald, said
at the newspaper's modern new building here, ``Southam and
Hollinger have had significant profits, certainly enough to launch
a successful new product.''
</P>
<P>
   By Gaynor's count, 40 percent of the striking workers have
returned to work. But the attack on local church people seems to
have given those who are on strike a fresh ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly is very aggressive and he usually gets his way so
he was surprised to see a bishop stand up to him,'' said Bishop
Henry, the spiritual leader of 200,000 Catholics in southern
Alberta. ``But, so far he hasn't been able to intimidate me. And I
have not backed down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
