<HEADER>
A8468 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0417-COX     04-16 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PIVOTAL WEEK IN ELIAN CASE HAS PAINFUL ANNIVERSARIES
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ What could be a pivotal week in the long-running Elian
Gonzalez saga will also be a week of painful anniversaries for the
main players in the drama, with both sides hoping they won't add a
new unpleasant date to their calendars.
</P>
<P>
   With the stalemate on hold awaiting a key court ruling, Cuban
exiles will pause Monday to recall the failed U.S.-backed invasion
of Cuba at the Bay of Pigs, a disaster that took place on April 17,
1961, leaving 200 invaders dead and 1,200 captured.
</P>
<P>
   The exiles have already been reminding Attorney General Janet
Reno of the April 19, 1993 tragedy at Waco, Texas, when Reno
ordered FBI agents to storm the compound of the Branch Davidian
religious cult. A horrible fire ensued, killing about 75 Davidians
</P>
<P>
   The two black days in U.S. history have come together in the
Elian saga in a strange nexus, at least for the exiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans don't know about the history and the reality of
Cuba,'' said Eliseo Rodriguez(cq), a former Cuban political
prisoner who has joined the protests outside Elian's Little Havana
home. ``They don't understand what a big mistake the government is
making. But I fear what will happen if they try to force things.
There will be trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno has made it clear she wants to avoid any confrontation over
the boy, and even flew to Miami last week to try to broker a
compromise by negotiating personally with the Florida family.
</P>
<P>
   But her bid failed, and both sides are now awaiting a ruling by
the U.S. 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta, which could set
the stage for a resolution to the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, the court issued a temporary ban on Elian's
removal from the United States. The court is expected to rule early
this week on whether the ban should stay in force until a May 11
hearing stemming from the Miami family's lawsuit in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have asked the court to order the family to
turn Elian over to his father, even if the court rules that the boy
should remain in the United States pending the outcome of the May
11 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father, who has been living in the home of a top Cuban
diplomat in the Washington, D.C. area since April 6, has promised
in court documents to remain in the United States until after the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Atlanta court grants the government's request,
the Miami relatives insist they will never take Elian out of their
Little Havana home, although they won't resist if federal officers
come for him.
</P>
<P>
   That sets up a potentially violent confrontation with vehement
Cuban exile protestors who have maintained a vigil near the home
for months, and vow to form a human chain to protect Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when Reno's first deadline for handing over the boy
approached, thousands of protestors packed the streets surrounding
the house, creating a nightmare scenario for any extraction effort.
The deadline fell moot after the Atlanta court issued its temporary
ban on Elian's removal from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for a compromise remain dim, as key players for both sides
held to their positions in Sunday television interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to try to do this in a peaceful manner,'' White House
Chief of Staff John Podesta told CNN. ``But ultimately the rule of
law must prevail and the administration is prepared to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials have reportedly been preparing a
plan to take the boy from the house should the family continue
refusing to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   But the family shows no signs of backing down.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Reno's insistence that Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro
Gonzalez, is now violating the law by withholding the boy, the
family believes it is within its rights, said Spencer Eig, one of
their attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lazaro Gonzalez will comply with the law,'' Eig said. ``He
will stand aside and cry and his heart will break if they come for
Elian. But he is a legal resident of this country and he can't be
ordered to do their dirty work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the bad blood between the branches of the family
continues to simmer.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami family has outraged Elian's father by accusing him of
abusing Elian and the boy's mother. They also released a
controversial home video showing the boy telling his father he
doesn't want to go back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Elian's father say the Miami family has made it
difficult for Gonzalez to talk to his son by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Miami relatives allowed a Miami Herald reporter
into their home while Elian spoke with his father in a call. They
boy spent 20 minutes talking with his father, and then blew kisses
into the telephone as he hung up, the Herald reported.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Juan Miguel Gonzales, attended church services in
Washington on Sunday and, speaking in Spanish through an
interpreter, thanked parishioners for their support.
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams can be reached by e-mail at:
mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
