u i BC-ISRAEL-MORDECHAI-NYT     04-16 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MORDECHAI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI MINISTER COULD FACE SEXUAL ASSAULT CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli police Sunday recommended that
Transportation Minister Yitzhak Mordechai be prosecuted on three
counts of sexual assault, dealing a humiliating blow to the former
general, who ran for prime minister last year as the first
Sephardic candidate in Israel's history.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, 55, stepped down temporarily from his post when the
police began their investigation of a complaint by a 23-year-old
employee in the Transportation Ministry. He said Sunday that he
would resign from the cabinet if the attorney general followed the
police recommendation to file charges against him. That is
considered likely but not definite.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sad tumble for Mordechai, an Iraqi-born career soldier
who fought his way up through the ranks, facing down discrimination
against Middle Eastern immigrants, until he reached the pinnacle:
army chief of staff and then defense minister.
</P>
<P>
   He is the leader of the new Center Party, a group of six members
of parliament who chose him as their candidate for prime minister
in a failed attempt to break the hold of the two major parties,
Labor and Likud. Mordechai, expecting a very poor showing, bowed
out of the race at the 11th hour and threw his support behind Ehud
Barak, the Labor candidate and now the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am innocent and guiltless,'' Mordechai said in a statement
Sunday. ``I intend to fight with all my might for justice and my
good name.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli police began their investigation with the complaint
by the woman, who had worked as Mordechai's subordinate. When their
investigation became public, they received many other allegations
that Mordechai had ``forcibly performed indecent acts'' on women
during his army career and subsequent political life, the police
report said.
</P>
<P>
   In several instances, the statute of limitations had expired,
the police said. But they gathered evidence that seemed to validate
claims by three women. Two involved alleged assaults that took
place in Mordechai's home, one in 1996, when he was already defense
minister, and the other in 1992, when he was a general. The third
was the Transportation Ministry worker. The women said Mordechai
had attempted to force himself on them, kissing them and trying to
fondle them.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-old-woman originally turned for help to Zehava Gal-on, a
leftist lawmaker. Gal-on and Avraham Burg, the speaker of
parliament, urged the woman to file a complaint with the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has done two things,'' Gal-on said of the woman. ``She has
strengthened herself. And she has conveyed a message to women that
you have to complain, that things are not to be swept under the
carpet any longer, that the rules of the game have changed _ one
may not attack women simply because one is in a senior position and
no one would dare file a complaint.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
