<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-930(2     04-16 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ECONOMY COLUMN: DEVELOPING TECHNOLOGY FOR INTERNET MUSIC
SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The major record companies BMG and Sony Music Entertainment
recently announced long-awaited plans to sell their music online
via digital downloads. But the fine print suggests that mainstream
Internet users are not going to buy their music digitally any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the promise of digital downloads for the masses, the
technical challenges could continue to confine the audience mainly
to that breed of technology-minded, time-wealthy human known as the
college student.
</P>
<P>
   Take the statement from BMG, which focused on the fact that the
company had selected a half-dozen _ count 'em, six _ different
technology partners to put its music online and to protect it from
pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Even describing BMG's approach is rather complicated. But if you
can imagine having to download a different piece of software,
depending on whether you want to buy a digital single by Christina
Aguilera, Dave Matthews or Carlos Santana, then you begin to get a
sense of the friction-free digital economy, BMG-style. (By the way,
the portable devices for playing the music in the various
anti-piracy formats are not yet widely available.)
</P>
<P>
   The record companies, though, say they have no choice but to
concede such complications if they want to start making music
available online. ``We want to make sure our artists' music is
widely available, accessible and protected,'' said Kevin Conroy,
senior vice president of new technology for BMG. ``We don't believe
that any single technology can deliver on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not, the record companies are under pressure to make
their music available over the Internet. They need to be responsive
to investors, to take advantage of a potentially huge market
opportunity, and to head off the persistent problem of online music
piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing the issue are some Internet users who are freely
trafficking in copyrighted music online, seemingly oblivious to the
concept of theft. The music labels say that such trafficking _
often involving copyrighted music that is digitally copied and
distributed via the Internet's infiniteness _ costs the labels and
the recording artists tens of millions of dollars a year in lost
sales and royalties.
</P>
<P>
   College students, while not the only ones to blame, have become
piracy's poster children. They have motive: an abiding interest in
recorded music. And they have the opportunity: the time and
technical skills to navigate the Net for music, download it and
``rip'' their own CDs to place on the Net for others in an easily
traded software format called MP3.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the record industry has been to find a way to
encode its own intellectual property so that, once paid for and
downloaded by a buyer, the music can be stored and listened to only
by the buyer. In other words, it cannot be easily pirated.
</P>
<P>
   Developing this copyright protection turns out to be no small
technological challenge. The record industry, in concert with
electronics makers in a forum called the Secure Digital Music
Initiative, has spent over a year working out technical standards
to achieve such a goal. The real fruits of that effort are
scheduled to be on the market in the next six months in the form of
portable devices that will not play songs that have been pirated.
</P>
<P>
   So it represents no small victory for record labels and fans of
their mainstream music that Sony and BMG have decided that they are
ready to start selling music online. Sony Music, home to Pearl Jam
and Lauryn Hill, among others, plans to start selling singles from
its Web site later this month. The songs will cost $2.49 to $3.49,
roughly equivalent to prices of singles on CD or tape.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, BMG says it plans to sell singles online by this
summer, with entire albums to be available later in the year. BMG
has not disclosed pricing, but in its tests and promotions in
recent months singles have sold for $1.99.
</P>
<P>
   But for customers, at least in the early going, the psychic
costs could be much higher. BMG announced that it would make music
available in three different copyright-protecting formats from
three competing companies: IBM, InterTrust Technologies and
Microsoft. To process secure sales transactions, BMG chose to
license competing technologies from Reciprocal and Digital World
Services.
</P>
<P>
   The BMG announcement drew criticism from operators of Web sites
that both sell songs and offer them free in the MP3 format. These
sites do not traffic in pirated material but in music from
independent artists who are worried more about building an audience
than about preventing piracy. Operators of these sites contend that
the record labels are trying to treat consumers as guinea pigs for
testing different secure formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to support three different word-processor programs
on your computer?'' said Gene Hoffman, president and chief
executive of e-music, a Web site that sells MP3 songs for 99 cents
a song and $2.99 an album. ``It's great they're entering the
market,'' Hoffman said. ``But they make it very confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy of BMG conceded that, for the near term, consumers might
need to have software capable of processing more than one format,
depending on which one any given song is encoded in. But longer
term, he said, ``we want to move as quickly as possible into
narrowing the choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he said the consumer could win, because the keepers of
the different formats will be forced to compete to prove they offer
the most user-friendly and secure way of downloading and buying
music.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit of a bake-off,'' said Andrea Cook Fleming, vice
president of Liquid Audio, the sixth of BMG's technology partners
in digital music. BMG has licensed Liquid Audio to merge the
different digital rights systems under a single umbrella system to
make it easier for BMG to coordinate the various formats. ``They
want to create a competitive marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   All this raises the question of what Sony's technical plans are.
For its part, Sony chose to go with a single digital rights
management system, Microsoft Windows Media, and a single
transaction company, Reciprocal. Sony's rationale is that the
Windows Media system is the only one now supported by a portable
device that complies with the Secure Digital Music Initiative
approach. Incidentally, that device is made by Sony.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, the prototype that Sony is showing off seems
relatively simple to use. Consumers so inclined can point and click
their way to music downloads as easily as they might order a book
on Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sony Music officials said that as more devices emerge, they
would support other secure formats favored by the various
manufacturers, potentially creating confusion for consumers and
online retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's promise to publish music in other formats may sound more
like a threat. But Al Smith, a senior vice president at Sony Music
Entertainment, predicted that before long, users will not care
about the type of format in which music is digitally compressed and
encoded, because the devices will probably have a common interface.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can only hope he is right. Otherwise the music
industry can expect to continue to do business mainly on that
bastion of time-wealthy, technology-wise, format-forgiving
humanity: the college campus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
