<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLUMBINE-LITTLETON-A     04-16 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-LITTLETON-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR AFTER SCHOOL SHOOTINGS, STUDENTS AND RESIDENTS FIND WAYS TO
COPE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Almost a year has passed since a killing rampage here
by two students thrust an ordinary high school into the vortex of
national debates over gun rights, parental responsibilities,
cultural violence and the nature of evil.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the discourse, as well as the symbolism of 15 deaths
_ including the shooters, who killed themselves _ inside a school,
little beyond the walls of Columbine High School in suburban Denver
has changed since last April 20. Congress is still wrestling with
how to reduce the wrongful use of guns. The parents of the killers
have not spoken publicly about what happened. Disagreements remain
over the influence of violent movies, television, lyrics and
computer games in the everyday life of teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Here, though, the world changed forever.
</P>
<P>
   Scarcely a day goes by without some reminder of the carnage
caused by Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris, who ended their own lives
after killing 12 students and a teacher and wounding 23 other
people, several of whom are confined to wheelchairs. Columbine is
now more than a school; it is part of the lexicon, a new shorthand
for the terror of kids killing kids.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Denver's daily newspapers, The Denver Post and The Rocky
Mountain News, won Pulitzer prizes last week for their coverage of
the shootings. But, as editors at both papers said, the honor was
bittersweet. As a further measure of the tragedy's impact,
relatives of victims asked news organizations not to mention the
killers' names in anniversary stories. Some agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not going to be a normal year,'' said Frank DeAngelis,
principal at Columbine. ``I think if people felt just because we
walked into this building and it had different paint, it had
different floor coverings, that everything was going to be back to
normal. Then, I think they were very unrealistic. What I told the
students last April 21 was that what we have experienced in the
last 24 hours is something that will remain with us for a lifetime.
We have learned to cope.''
</P>
<P>
   Coping has been hampered by a continuing search for answers and
an unlikely series of wrenching events in the months following the
shootings. Last fall, the mother of Anne Marie Hochhalter, a
student who was paralyzed below the waist by the shooters,
committed suicide by shooting herself inside a pawnshop after she
had asked to see a handgun. Around the same time, the high school
was closed for a day after a Florida teen-ager sent an e-mail
message to a Columbine student, threatening ``to finish the job''
started by the killers.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, two other Columbine students were shot and
killed in a sandwich shop just blocks from the school.
</P>
<P>
   All this, in a middle-to-upper-class neighborhood of spacious
homes and tree-lined streets _ a snapshot of American aspirations
fulfilled. Yet now, tour buses glide by the school, filled with the
ghoulishly curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to move on when you see vanloads of people on the
parking lot, asking where the library is so that they can take a
picture of family reunions on places where people died,'' said
Sarah Bay, a senior who lost three friends in the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Students, teachers and administrators say the shootings changed
the fabric of the school, drawing them all together by the shared
experience of tragedy. DeAngelis said it has not been uncommon for
students to hug in hallways, even to tell each other, ``I love
you.''
</P>
<P>
   But strength in numbers has not reached every corner of emotion
for many of the school's 2,000 students. Courtney Shakowski, a
senior, said she now only feels safe ``with help from my parents
and teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey White, another senior, said she did not feel in danger,
``but my trust factor has gone down. I don't trust very many things
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Katie Beer, a 10th-grader, said quietly, ``I feel like my bubble
is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Leland Andres, a music teacher at Columbine since it opened in
1973, said many students have had trouble concentrating in class
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Trauma experts say these are common feelings, even this long
after the event. ``With adults, we have an idea of what the world
is like, and that world includes bad things, your car getting
stolen, sexual assaults, muggings,'' said Robin Fudge Finegan, a
consultant who has worked with victims of mass tragedy, including
Columbine and the Oklahoma City bombing five years ago. ``A kid
hasn't really formed that definition of the world. To blast them
with that seriousness of life, it's a more intense violation.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some in the Columbine community have turned the shootings into a
cause. Tom Mauser, a former state transportation official whose
son, Daniel, was killed in the shootings, took a leave from his job
to lobby state lawmakers for tighter gun-control measures. He has
become a highly visible figure in Colorado, and even nationally. He
sat in the gallery as President Clinton gave his last State of the
Union Address, a guest of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Al and Phyllis Velasquez, whose son, Kyle, was killed, are
selling silver pins they designed that say, ``Never Forgotten,''
and donating the money to helping turn the library, where most of
the students were killed, into an atrium. ``It's a very personal
journey,'' said Mrs. Velasquez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take each day as it comes, and you move forward,'' she
continued. ``We're walking through unfamiliar landscape and we're
looking for something that is familiar. You just take one day at a
time. You get over the morning, and if you've made it through that
day, you congratulate yourself for making it through one more
day.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Members of most of the victims' families have been visible in
some way since the shootings, offering opinions on a range of
developments, like the release of videotapes on which the two
shooters displayed their weapons and hatreds. It is less clear how
the parents of the killers are enduring the aftermath of the
shootings, given that many in the Columbine community hold them at
least partly responsible for their sons' actions. The parents of
one victim, Isaiah Shoels, have filed a wrongful death lawsuit
against the Klebolds and Harrises.
</P>
<P>
   Both couples issued statements last week through their
respective lawyers but conveyed little about how the last 12 months
have passed for them. Tom and Susan Klebold apologized for their
son's role in the killings and said, ``The pain of others compounds
our own as we struggle to live a life without the son we
cherished.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne and Kathy Harris, whose son kept weapons and ammunition
stored in his bedroom, echoed those sentiments. And, perhaps, with
the Shoelses' lawsuit in mind, they made it clear they knew nothing
of their son's plan for causing mayhem, saying they ``search our
souls daily for some glimmer of a reason why he would have done
such a horrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   They added, ``What he did was unforgivable and beyond our
capacity to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Kechter, whose son, Matthew, was among those killed, said
she could imagine a time that the Klebold and Harris families might
be forgiven by others. ``I know that they are suffering a lot of
pain and, I'm sure, a lot of guilt,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But time might bring more important changes, she said, changes
that could provide benefits well beyond one traumatized community.
``People need to get back to basics of society, family and God,''
she said. ``It sounds like I'm grand-standing, but Columbine has
caused a lot of people to look inward to say, `Am I doing the right
thing as a parent? Am I spending enough time with my children?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have lost that innocence in their eyes.'' She added.
``Yet they have this wisdom. I think there is going to be a
generation of change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ARCHITECTURE-PRIZE-50     04-16 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-PRIZE-500&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REM KOOLHAAS WINS TOP ARCHITECTURE PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rem Koolhaas, perhaps the most influential architect of his
generation, has been awarded the Pritzker Architecture Prize for
2000, which the Hyatt Foundation, sponsors of the award, plans to
announce Monday. The prize includes a $100,000 grant and will be
presented in Jerusalem on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Koolhaas, 56, brings distinction to the Pritzker
Prize as well as to the architect. Founded in 1979, the prize has
been described as architecture's Nobel. Previous recipients include
Philip Johnson, Luis Barragan, Richard Meier, I.M. Pei, Aldo Rossi
and Tadao Ando. In recent years the Pritzker jury has ventured
cautiously toward recognizing the work of architects born since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Christian de Portzamparc and Ando, who received the prize in
1994 and 1995, respectively, are architects of considerable talent
whose work has had scant influence on their peers. Koolhaas, by
contrast, has been a guiding figure in architecture since 1978,
when he published ``Delirious New York,'' an urban history of the
20th century's capital city. Reissued in 1994, the book changed the
way many architects, students and historians regard modern
architecture. While some architects were prepared to dismiss the
modern movement as a conspiracy to replace everything with glass
boxes, Koolhaas reinterpreted modern New York from a contemporary
point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``S, M, L, XL,'' a book he published in 1994, also provided an
excursion into the architect's sensibility, but this time
illustrated with work by Koolhaas and his firm, the Office for
Metropolitan Architecture, based in Rotterdam, the Netherlands. As
advertised by its title, the book presented projects ranging in
scale from private houses to the convention hall and master plan
for Euralille, a trade and transportation center in Lille, France.
Designs for the Netherlands Dance Theater (1987) and the Rotterdam
Kunsthal (1992) helped fill out the middle range.
</P>
<P>
   In many projects Koolhaas creates a unique sense of space by
combining spiral and three-dimensional grid forms within a single
building. One of the strongest examples of this is the Jussieu
Library, an unbuilt project for the Left Bank in Paris. He
conceived the building's floors as an interior street, made from a
squared-off spiral of sloping ramps. The Rotterdam Kunsthal uses a
similar device.
</P>
<P>
   These and other projects show the influence of Ludwig Mies van
der Rohe and Wallace K. Harrison, who helped inspire Koolhaas'
formal vocabulary. The rigor of Mies' Seagram Building in Manhattan
and the theatricality of the Trylon and Perisphere, designed by
Harrison for the 1939 World's Fair in New York, are polar opposites
that Koolhaas has sought to reconcile. In 1980 he organized the
first retrospective of Harrison's work at the Institute for
Architecture and Urban Studies in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Since the publication of ``S, M, L, XL,'' Koolhaas has received
commissions to design an expansion of the Universal City complex in
Los Angeles, the new public library in Seattle and a student center
for the Illinois Institute of Technology in Chicago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Koolhaas has been a local hero in New York since the 1970s. This
is partly because of the grace with which he has reconciled the
values of the '60s counterculture with the reality of professional
practice in changing times.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a social reformer. Some are repelled, in fact, by his
acceptance of the more dubious aspects of urban life. ``Delirious
New York'' celebrated what he called the culture of congestion, a
phenomenon unlikely to be cheered by New Yorkers stuck in rush-hour
traffic. Today he takes evident delight in the global monoculture
and the proliferation of its characteristic building types:
convention centers, hotels, airports, malls and such. Koolhaas
would make a bad poster boy for protesters against the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund. (An exchange between architect
and protesters could be fruitful for both.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as Mies put it, the new era exists. It is a fact,
regardless of our yes or no. Of course our new era differs from
that of Mies. It presents different opportunities, different
challenges and the possibility of different forms. What makes
Koolhaas exceptional is his developed awareness of these
differences and the talent that enables him to translate this
awareness into architectural form. For Mies, the era was defined by
the rationalism of the Industrial Age, to which he brought the
value of formal clarity derived from the neoclassical architecture
of the 18th-century Enlightenment. For Koolhaas the era is defined
by the irrationalism of the Information Age. To it, he brings the
analytic tools developed by Marx and Freud.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Harvard Guide to Shopping,'' scheduled for publication
later this year, Koolhaas uses these tools to explore the
phenomenon of mass consumption. A team project, the work was
produced by students in an urban studies course he leads each year
at the Harvard Graduate School of Design. This volume, produced in
1998, is obsessive, smart, hilarious. There are chapters on the
history of the escalator, on Frank O. Gehry's background in mall
design and the economic struggle between urban and suburban
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Like a Borges story, the ``Harvard Guide'' takes reason to the
point of insanity. This was a standard practice of the Surrealists,
whose work also drew on social and psychological analysis in an
effort to merge the two. But the extension of reason into madness
is also standard practice for advanced capitalism, which has
largely reduced rationalism to corporate accounting. The bottom
line, in turn, has recomposed reality into the incoherent,
fragmented world that we experience in dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The Surrealists wanted to change consciousness. In this sense,
Koolhaas is a social reformer. Though he may embrace monocultural
institutions, he insists that architecture is a medium for
heightening our awareness of them. It can be used to render rather
than disguise their destabilizing effects.
</P>
<P>
   Some institutions, even culturally enlightened ones, feel
threatened by this insistence. This is the disheartening moral to
be drawn from an episode that occurred in April 1997, when Koolhaas
was eliminated from a competition to design the expansion of the
Museum of Modern Art. Invited, along with nine other architects, to
submit an initial proposal that would focus on concepts rather than
forms, he responded with a precise analysis of the institution that
apparently offended some members of the selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal included an analysis of what he called the aura of
the Modern. By this he meant the museum's power to confer aesthetic
value on particular artists, movements and interpretations, and the
conversion of that value, in turn, into prestige, fame and other
worldly forms of currency. In one diagram, Koolhaas depicted the
aura as a golden rectangle at the top of an office tower. Evidently
this feature did not go over well at the Modern.
</P>
<P>
   But for anyone who has tracked this architect's work, the
proposal was classic Koolhaas. Like others of his generation he has
a complicated relationship to authority. He is by turns playful,
blunt, skeptical and romantic. His clients have found this a useful
combination for producing designs of great integrity.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a clear explanation for Koolhaas' influence, it is
his determination to bridge the gap between architecture and city
planning. This was the founding mission of the Office for
Metropolitan Architecture, established in London in 1975 by
Koolhaas, Madelon Vriesendorp and Elias and Zoe Zenghelis. It is
also the goal of the research projects Koolhaas directs at Harvard.
The projects focus on the impact of globalization in individual
cities worldwide. A study of Lagos, Nigeria, is also scheduled for
publication. These are not touristic celebrations of foreign
places, but efforts to demystify the built environment by exploring
topics like security devices, economic segregation and
transportation systems.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this year's Pritzker selection will trigger another
much-needed study on the decline of New York as a center for
outstanding building. Indeed, the entire roster of Pritzker
laureates can be seen as an index of this decline. The prize was
established by the Pritzker family of Chicago, owner of the Hyatt
hotel chain. Of the 22 Pritzker laureates, only six have completed
major projects in New York. (Koolhaas has done two projects in
Manhattan: the interior for the Second Stage Theater last year and
the Lehmann Maupin Gallery in SoHo in 1996.) Most of these six are
over 70 or dead.
</P>
<P>
   A New York project by Rossi, a seventh winner, will be completed
posthumously this year. Until the completion last year of
Portzamparc's LVMH Tower on East 57th Street, Manhattan had not
seen a first-rate skyscraper in decades. But a new millennium is
here, and the Pritzker jury has stepped into it boldly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
