<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CABALA-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     04-16 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABALA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIDDEN WAYS OF GOD IN THE MYSTICAL CABALA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Note change in slug) 
(Publication notes at end of review) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cabala is not easy and it wasn't meant to be. The name
itself, standing for the various strands of Jewish mysticism,
suggests something deep and esoteric, something that one knows more
by experience than by the intellect. Comprehension is not made easy
by the nature of the main books that make up the cabala, especially
the five-volume Zohar. A 13th-century forgery of a supposedly much
earlier masterwork, the Zohar contains a bewildering mixture of
rabbinical sayings, diagrams of divine emanations, Talmudic
commentaries, myths and fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason alone those who want to grasp the cabala might
well look with hope to David Rosenberg's new book, ``Dreams of
Being Eaten Alive.'' Rosenberg is a poet and translator of biblical
texts _ his best-known work is ``The Book of J,'' which he wrote
with Harold Bloom _ and he promises to give us the ``literary
core'' of the cabala. Or, as Rosenberg puts it, to translate
cabalistic excerpts that will reveal ``the body beneath the garment
of its own text.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg explains this further: ``I have attempted a form of
dream, a serial narrative, in which episodes are woven together by
threads of similar intensity, focus and bearing.'' It is a worthy
ambition, but unfortunately Rosenberg produces at best a mixed
result. It is illuminating in an appropriately mystical way to read
some of the passages that he has rendered into English, and his
commentaries, which precede and follow the translations, contain
useful insights. But his explication of the text is more often than
not pretentious, self-indulgent and in places downright
unfathomable.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it is not clear if the cabalistic texts he
presents are really translations or quirky, personal re-imaginings
inspired by his theories. Not that I have anything against quirky
personal re-imaginings. Still, one wants to know if Rosenberg is
revealing the literary core of the cabala or the self-consciously
postmodern core of Rosenberg himself, and not knowing that produces
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   The main text that Rosenberg uses is the Zohar _ meaning
radiance _ which most scholars attribute to a 13th-century Spanish
cabalist named Moses de Leon, but which de Leon presented as a
long-lost manuscript composed a millennium earlier by the legendary
rabbi Shimon ben Yohai. Thus, as Rosenberg puts it, the Zohar is
``purposefully in disguise'' and that adds to its mystical nature.
Acknowledged but underplayed in Rosenberg's analysis is that the
Zohar is a religious document aimed at showing the hidden ways in
which God is revealed in the Jewish canon, in particular the Torah,
the first five books of the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   For Rosenberg, the cabalists were ``our first postmodern
writers,'' and to substantiate this notion he presents a medley of
fashionable concepts _ the importance of the body in literary
criticism, the Freudian interpretation of dreams, what Rosenberg
describes as a cabalistic ``evolutionary ecology,'' and others. He
lays out his view in an introduction in which the occasional
arresting insight alternates with New Ageish pronouncements on such
things as the interconnectedness of all things and the way ``the
creation of souls is seen as the offspring of a divine
intercourse.'' For Rosenberg, in other words, the cabala is less
about the search for God than about expressing our deepest and
wildest fears, especially about sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cabala is obsessed with failed sex, especially the
spilling of semen in sleep or masturbation,'' Rosenberg writes
early on. It reveals, he says a few pages later, ``that sex is
messianic, future-oriented, and that it is a yearning for unity and
for the body of the mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there is sexual imagery in the cabala, as well as
stories of seduction of the patriarchs by sexual demons, and an
erotic symbolism connected with the Tree of Life. Still, when
Rosenberg declares that the cabala ``sexualized the soul long
before our current scientific attempts,'' one suspects more an
eagerness to be intellectually hip than to plumb the true meaning
of a 13th-century text.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Rosenberg's psychologically tuned-in vision is accurate,
the passages he offers to demonstrate his view _ passages about
Adam and Eve, Isaac and Rebecca and the female and male evil
spirits Lilith and Samael _ seem closer to ``Pulp Fiction'' than,
say, to the secret names of God. The stories are of dismemberment,
the eating of infants (hence Rosenberg's title), procreation with
snakes, a good deal of released semen and various sexual fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg gives no exact references for the source of these
passages, unlike other passages that he translates, and, indeed,
one isn't sure if he is translating texts or imaginatively
extending them to encompass his sexualized vision. ``I have
elaborated the scene of dream interpretation by folding the dreams
into a further narrative layer,'' he writes, explaining a passage
of translation in which the patriarch Isaac dreams that he has a
child by a kind of she-demon and the matriarch Rebecca cuts up the
infant and serves her for dinner. This ``further narrative layer''
has passages of dialogue right out of a bad screenplay:
</P>
<P>
   ``As Rebecca put down her fork, her brows were knit. `But,
Isaac, this is dangerous. You should not think of it. Put it out of
your mind.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gershom Sholem called the Zohar ``in some measure inaccessible
and silent,'' which, as Rosenberg sensibly avers, creates a problem
for ``any translator or interpreter.'' Rosenberg's solution is to
see the cabala as a way of reading ``in a more natural or wild way,
unconfined by the inhibitions of human culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, to demonstrate what he calls ``creative cabala''
and ``frontier cabala,'' he cites a bizarre host of contemporary
cultural figures, from Jacques Derrida to Oprah Winfrey to Buffy
the Vampire Slayer. My feeling is that to cite Buffy the Vampire
Slayer as a way of making the cabala speak to us today is to take
something sublime, if difficult, and make it into something
accessible but ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   DREAMS OF BEING EATEN ALIVE
</P>
<P>
   The Literary Core of the Cabala
</P>
<P>
   By David Rosenberg
</P>
<P>
   205 pages. Harmony Books. $22.
</P>
<P>
   An audio interview with Diane Johnson, author of ``Le Mariage,''
is available from The New York Times on the Web:
www.nytimes.com/books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
