</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-MINORITIES-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS STRUGGLE TO INCREASE ETHNIC MIX OF NEWSROOMS
</HEADLINE>
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Rodriguez, the executive editor of The Sacramento Bee, got
the bad news shortly after arriving at the annual convention of the
American Society of Newspaper Editors last week. Twice in the last
few months he had fended off competitors who wanted to hire away
one of his best young reporters; now the same reporter was calling
to say he was leaving to join a flourishing magazine, with salaries
much higher than The Bee's.
</P>
<P>
   For Rodriguez, as a former head of the editors' task force on
diversity, the phone call crystallized all the worry and talk that
were again a dominant theme of the annual editors' convention. The
reporter in question is black; his departure means The Bee _ where
minority journalists make up 28 percent of the newsroom _ will be
that much further from reflecting the demographics of its
community. Sacramento County is about 37 percent nonwhite.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's fight to hold on to his staff reflects the inherent
frustrations of editors trying to fulfill their organization's
commitment to make America's newsrooms reflect the country's ethnic
and demographic mix by the year 2025.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is a two-pronged attack,'' Rodriguez said in an
interview. ``You have to develop new journalists and you have to
retain them.''
</P>
<P>
   The same simple prescription also undergirded the announcements
by two major journalism foundations _ the Freedom Forum and the
John S. and James L. Knight Foundation _ that they are underwriting
at least $5.5 million of new efforts to widen the pipeline of
black, Asian-American, Native American and Latino journalists
entering the profession.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Forum, an organization based in Arlington, Va., that
was established nine years ago as a successor to the Gannett
Foundation, has placed 128 young minority journalists in summer
intern jobs around the country, and is paying the $350 weekly
salary of 33 of them. These 33 reporters are being placed at
medium- and small-sized newspapers that have already committed to
hire other interns from the program, in part to ease possible
feelings of isolations in communities like Huntington, W.Va. or
Lafayette, La.
</P>
<P>
   That commitment, along with the establishment of a journalism
training program at Vanderbilt University, represents a commitment
of at least $5 million by the Freedom Forum, including $1 million
earmarked for a minority recruitment program in partnership with
ASNE and the Associated Press Managing Editors organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Knight Foundation last week pledged $500,000 to the editors'
group _ with a possible $4.5 million to follow _ to design programs
to reinvigorate high school journalism.
</P>
<P>
   N. Christian Anderson 3rd, the publisher of The Orange County
Register, and the president of the editors' group, said at a press
conference, ``As we looked at this issue over the past three or
four years, we found kids are not being exposed to journalism in
high school because high school newspapers are fading away.''
</P>
<P>
   He also argued that ``unless you increase the pipeline, there is
just no way'' for newsrooms to mirror the diversity of their
readership.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of change, however, was not just frustrating but
infuriating for one group, the National Association of Black
Journalists. In the last year, while minority employment in
newsrooms overall rose three-tenths of a percent, to 11.85 percent,
or 6,700 people, in a work force of 56,200 journalists, the
percentage of black journalists declined for the first time, from
5.4 percent to 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows a crisis of confidence in the newspaper industry,''
said Will Sutton, the president of NABJ and a managing editor of
The Raleigh News and Observer in North Carolina. A failure to
increase the number of black reporters, he said, will mean coverage
less likely to appeal to black readers. In turn, the young people
among those readers will be less interested in journalism, he
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young black folks are thinking about other''
professions, he said. ``They are not thinking about media and
certainly not about newspapers.'' A Freedom Forum survey, released
at the beginning of last week's meeting, showed that, given the
industry's current hiring and retention rates, one of every two
journalists hired for the next 24 years would have to be a member
of a minority group for the industry to meet its stated goals.
</P>
<P>
   Among other minority groups, the annual employment survey did
show progress. The percentage of Hispanic journalists rose to 3.7
from 3.5 in 1999; Asian-American journalists made up 2.4 percent of
the work force this year compared with 2.3 percent in 1999. Native
Americans are now 0.5 percent of the country's journalists, up 0.1
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
