<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA MAKES GAINS IN SPURRING GROWTH 
BY CRAIG S. SMITH  
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China's economy showed surprising signs of
strength in the first quarter, suggesting that a slide in the
nation's economic growth rate may be ending.
</P>
<P>
   The gross domestic product grew 8.1 percent in the first three
months of the year compared with figures in the quarter a year
earlier, a senior government official said Sunday. That rate of
growth is up sharply from the 6.8 percent registered in the fourth
quarter of last year. For all of 1999, the Chinese economy grew 7.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The upturn in the nation's economic growth is a vindication for
China's chief economic planner, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, who many
Western economists doubted could stave off the effects of the Asian
economic crisis. Two years ago, economists talked of the sorry
state of China's banks, which remain technically insolvent, and
some press reports contended that the nation's economy was
deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year so far, the Chinese economy has maintained good
momentum,'' said Li Rongrong, vice chairman of the State Economic
and Trade Commission, speaking at the World Economic Forum in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   While the growth rate sounds impressive, actual growth is spread
unevenly across the country. Most economic activity is concentrated
in a handful of large cities and along the eastern coast.
</P>
<P>
   Large pockets of the country have slipped into recession, and
many economists warn that if growth falls much further, the
government could face significant unrest in the industrial
northeast, where unemployment exceeds 30 percent in some places.
Protests there are not rare. In February, the army quelled a riot
by an estimated 20,000 miners after the government closed a
bankrupt mine.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has vigorously tried to revive economic growth for more
than two years by pouring money into huge infrastructure projects.
It has also cut bank-deposit rates, increased government workers'
salaries and lengthened national holidays to encourage consumer
spending. Such spending remains weak, but retail sales have picked
up, and a two-year slide in prices appears to be ending, partly
because of government-imposed price controls.
</P>
<P>
   Exports and foreign investment are driving the faster economic
growth: exports, which slumped after the Asian crisis, leaped 39
percent in the first quarter, giving China a $5.2 billion trade
surplus for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment rose 10 percent in March, compared with
figures in the month a year earlier, one of the first monthly
increases since the regional downturn scared investors. And the
value of contracts signed for future foreign investment surged 27
percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The revival in export revenue and foreign investment seems to
have removed the threat of a Chinese currency devaluation. Fears
that China would devalue the yuan to increase export revenue had
haunted regional markets for much of the last two years, despite
Beijing's frequent pledges to hold the currency firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese economy still has deep structural problems, but a
revival of the growth rate gives the government leeway to push
ahead with stalled economic reforms. Sunday, for example, a
government research group advised the liquidation of public
holdings in listed state companies, with the proceeds to be used
for workers' pensions.
</P>
<P>
   China's underfinanced and spotty national pension scheme has
left millions of workers without adequate retirement benefits.
Protests by disgruntled pensioners have become a common occurrence
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The government has already begun reducing its stake in listed
companies, the first step in what could turn into privatization on
a grand scale. At the end of last year, the state owned about 68
percent of the 285 billion outstanding shares in China's 1,007
listed companies, according to the official China Daily's business
weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
