<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      04-16 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAT ROOMS PIN THE BLAME ON ANALYSTS AND THE MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET-STRATEGY, MARKET-ASSESS, MARKET-MARKETPLACE,
MARKET-MOOD, MARKET-ASIA) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the technology-heavy Nasdaq market rose to stratospheric
heights, nowhere was the cheering harder than in the investing chat
rooms on the Internet. The many investors who helped propel new
Internet shares to great heights crowed about their trading
successes in these online forums.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many of those same stocks have tumbled, and the mood in the
chat rooms has shifted. Web sites like Silicon Investor, a
financial site that serves as an online water cooler of sorts, are
full of angry commentary about falling prices. And over the last
week, chat rooms and message boards on the Internet have begun to
fill with investors chastising television channels like CNBC and
CNNfn for hyping the change in sentiment among investors that has
caused a bear market for technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a simple and healthy correction in tech stocks, or
a correction due to problems with fundamentals. It is a
media-induced selling panic,'' said a note on one of Yahoo's
message boards by a user identified only as ``full-of-bull-2000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time the tech stocks start a small recovery, CNBC puts
on another bearish analyst that smears all tech and dot-com stocks
as being overvalued,'' full-of-bull-2000 added.
</P>
<P>
   Another investor, identified as ``porsche947,'' chimed in,
``Turn to another channel. I only look at the charts and cut out
the TV press. The charts don't lie and have no editorial hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Another user, ``Night Owl Creative,'' added: ``In general, the
media treats viewers as if they are dumb and it is their job to
show them what to think.''
</P>
<P>
   The influx of novice investors during the market's climb may be
one reason for the outcry against the media; many investors began
to rely on the media for stock tips and market advice, several
market analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural that the media has been a market cheerleader,''
said Robert J. Shiller, an economics professor at Yale and author
of ``Irrational Exuberance'' (Princeton University Press). ``There
was always this intuitive feeling that the media should keep that
warm feeling going about the market _ like it was almost
unpatriotic not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Shiller, a self-described bear, was scheduled to appear on CNBC
last Friday to promote his book. As the market plummeted, he
appeared as scheduled but was also asked to appear a second time
during the network's prime-time market wrapup. Shiller acknowledged
that appearances by people like him ``have an impact on the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Cohen, senior vice president for business news for CNBC,
said that the network's coverage was not slanted. ``We're not
cheering it up or down,'' he said. ``Sure we're concerned about
anybody losing money, but we believe more information is better
than less. People have blamed the messenger for centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors in chat rooms are also blaming industry analysts at
brokerage houses for the decline. ``A lot of people got hurt in the
process, a lot of lives ruined JUST BECAUSE some of these fund
managers wanted to get some of their tech stock cheap resulting in
a retail blood bath,'' a user called ``ciVic'' wrote on a message
board on Silicon Investor. ``This recent market
correction/crash/valuation _ whatever you want to call it _ had A
LOT to do with the media and analyst comments.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of investors believe the market's downturn was a result
of predictions of a market downturn,'' said Jill Munden, a
spokeswoman for Silicon Investor, referring to many in the chat
rooms. ``They want to blame somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Shiller argued that even if they complained, ``most
people will do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only the few who are on Prozac that have the impulse to
trade,'' he said. ``They are the ones who are most overconfident in
their own abilities. They typically think the market has to go
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many investors who frequent chat rooms and Internet
message boards try to use the medium to bolster their stocks. A
user called ``telecomguy'' said on a message board devoted to Cisco
Systems on Silicon Investor: ``I still firmly believe high-tech is
THE growth industry to be in for the foreseeable future. I will be
scavenging for more buys in the High-Tech VALUE sector (which will
be less of an oxymoron as the good companies will be punished along
with the flakes in the next few months!).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BARNESANDNOBLE-MEDIA-     04-16 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNESANDNOBLE-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERSTORE'S ONLINE UNIT SEEKS STABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 BY DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost a year after Barnes &AMP; Noble became the first traditional
book retailer to spin off its Internet store and take it public,
the online bookseller is searching for a new chief executive and
peace and stability within its own ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the recent plunge in technology stocks, Barnes &AMP;
Noble.com's stock price had plummeted. It ended on Friday at $8.50
_ well off the $26.625 high the stock reached shortly after the
company's $18-a-share initial public offering last May.
</P>
<P>
   And while it hunts for a new chief to replace the three that
came before, the second-ranked online bookstore is also coping with
an exodus of employees in what has been an overheated New York
market for new media workers.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties have tested the stoic alliance of the
electronic venture's partners _ Barnes &AMP; Noble and the media
conglomerate, Bertelsmann. On Wall Street, the problems have also
created the perception of a leadership vacuum, as investors have
been eagerly waiting for a permanent replacement for Jonathan
Bulkeley, the company's chief executive who left abruptly in
February and was paid almost $11 million for his one million stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it will help if they can bring in a chief executive
with vision who can move them to the next level to gain more market
share,'' said Mark J. Rowen, a senior analyst who tracks e-commerce
for Prudential Securities and who is recommending the stock and
considers it undervalued. ``I think that until there's actually
somebody in place, investors consider it out of sight, out of mind.
There's a perception there's a void there.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to the company's parent, Barnes &AMP; Noble, the
online bookseller is simply taking its time to anoint a new leader
who can offer a long-range solution in a market where many Internet
retailers are trading below their opening prices.
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding in 1997, Barnes &AMP; Noble.com has had a habit
of shuffling its executives like a sheaf of pages. There have been
four chief financial officers, including one who lasted about four
months. And three people have handled the chief executive duties,
including Bulkeley who left after about a year on the job.
Bulkeley, who declined to comment on his departure, announced in
January that he would leave the following month. But the strains
with the top leadership of the parent company were such that he was
asked to leave sooner than he intended, according to Barnes &AMP;
Noble.com employees and former employees.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the company's vice-president for technical
infrastructure departed for a new job. And within the last four
weeks at least eight technology employees have resigned, trailing
employees in corporate communications, community services and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those departures may reflect the intensifying
competition among Internet companies for employees in New York,
where the Internet workforce has more than doubled since 1997 to
250,000, according to a recent survey by the New York New Media
Association. But some former Barnes &AMP; Noble.com employees, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, also said it was trying and
exhausting to work through so many shifts in the upper ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, control of the online operation is firmly in the
hands of executives from the bookstore chain. Stephen Riggio _ the
founder of the online bookstore and a former chief operating
officer at Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. _ is the acting head of the company,
which employs a staff of more than 1,200 employees at the Manhattan
office and the distribution warehouse in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   His brother is Leonard Riggio, the chief executive of Barnes &AMP;
Noble Inc., who declined to be interviewed directly about the
online bookseller, but issued a statement that the search continues
for ``someone very, very capable, and we are in no hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize the CEO search is an element in our stock price,
but we are seeking a long-term solution, not a short-term patch,''
Riggio said, adding that his brother ``is brilliant, and no one in
this world knows the Internet better than he does. The employees
are delighted he is in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Barnes &AMP; Noble spun off its electronic offspring in a
public offering after the media conglomerate, Bertelsmann, bought a
50 percent stake in the unit for $200 million. After the offering,
the partners each kept about a 41 percent stake in the online
venture and Barnes &AMP; Noble took operating control. (Barnes &AMP; Noble,
as part of its online presence, has a business tie to The New York
Times, selling books through links from the newspaper's Web site.)
</P>
<P>
   But with the decline in the online company's stock price, the
strains have been building within Bertelsmann to take a more active
role, according to some executives. They note privately that there
are three options: maintain the status quo, sell out, or seek a way
to participate more aggressively in the operation of a company that
it considers a gateway into the electronic future.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, on May 1, Barnes &AMP; Noble.com has scheduled a
conference call to discuss its first-quarter financial results. But
it is not clear whether the company will have any announcement
about a new chief executive. Publishing executives said that talks
had stalled with Jonathan Newcomb, the chief executive of Simon &AMP;
Schuster, whose name emerged as a potential candidate almost
immediately after Bulkeley resigned.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to evaluate the partnership, Bertelsmann's chief
executive, Thomas Middelhoff declined to comment about Barnes &AMP;
Noble.com or the search for a new chief executive. He is one of
three Bertelsmann executives on the board of Barnes &AMP; Noble.com
with a personal investment of more than $500,000, that he made at
the time the stock was selling for $18 a share.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past, Middelhoff has lavished praise on the online
bookstore's financial progress, which for the quarter that ended in
December reported sales of $82 million _ more than double the
amount for the comparable period a year earlier. Its annual sales
for 1999 were $203 million, up from $62 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com still remains the dominant leader in the online book
market, with more than fives times the revenue that Barnes &AMP;
Noble.com has. But the analysts who cover Barnes &AMP; Noble.com
generally recommend its stock and say the company is steadily
chipping away at its archrival's market share.
</P>
<P>
   Rowen, of Prudential, said that he was impressed with the online
bookseller's progress, noting that its share of the combined book
revenues for Barnes &AMP; Noble.com and Amazon grew to 19 percent in
its most recent quarter, up from 16 percent in the previous
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan B. Alexander, an analyst with Wit Capital Corp., said that
he also took comfort from Barnes &AMP; Noble.com's relationship with
Bertelsmann, which provides the company with ``inherent advantages
over strict booksellers.'' He noted that Bertelsmann boasts a list
of millions of book club customers and that Barnes &AMP; Noble.com had
the support to leverage an existing brand and mindshare that's been
previously established with customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Riggio said that this same alliance also offered an
explanation why morale issues did not plague Barnes &AMP; Noble.com as
much as at other e-commerce companies. Employees, he said, ``know
Barnes &AMP; Noble and Bertelsmann are not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a number of former employees who spoke on the condition
of anonymity said that they felt pushed and pulled by a variety of
forces.
</P>
<P>
   With their stock options worth less with present prices, they
said it was a temptation to move to other Internet companies where
jobs are plentiful and compensation is higher. To account for that,
in February Barnes &AMP; Noble.com actually repriced almost 6,000
outstanding options from an exercise price of almost $16 to $8.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to compensation issues, others said they left in
part because of working conditions that they described as chaotic
because of revolving executives at the upper tiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your public relations people are leaving and chief
operating officers are rolling out, how can you have a consistent
voice?'' said one former employee who left this year. ``The first
wave of people started leaving in June and July, and then it
started to seem like three or four people a week were leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   When top executives leave it has even larger ripple effect. Last
summer the company's chief technology officer, John Kristie, left
for the same position at Online Retail Partners in New York. Online
Retail has recruited more than 25 former Barnes &AMP; Noble.com
employees who now work in almost every department from senior
management and production to technology and development.
</P>
<P>
   Another wave, about 12 departures, followed Robert Dykman's
shift in March from vice president of technical infrastructure at
Barnes &AMP; Noble.com to Saks Direct, where he also became chief
technology officer.
</P>
<P>
   Riggio said that all Internet companies _ particularly in New
York's Silicon Alley _ may face shortages of Internet engineers.
But he said the market conditions may actually help the company in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there remains considerable job-hopping among this
group,'' he said, ``we believe the current fall-out in the market
bodes to our advantage. This is to say that our own people, as well
as those we are successfully recruiting, realize that short-range
prospects do not always add up to long-range results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
