<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SIEGFRIED-OPERA-REVIE     04-16 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIEGFRIED-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE `RING' CYCLE CONTINUES, A TEST FOR A TENOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whenever an opera company decides to present a
production of Wagner's four-part ``Ring'' cycle, the major
stumbling block is always the same: who will sing the title role of
the third opera, ``Siegfried,'' the toughest dramatic tenor role in
the entire repertory? Wagner admitted after the fact that he was so
swept up with his vision for the ``Ring'' and his struggle to
complete it that he lost sight of what was vocally possible.
</P>
<P>
   The opera has nearly four hours of music, and Siegfried sings
during most of it. He must portray an impulsive and brawny youth.
Yet it takes most tenors years to develop the vocal heft and
stamina to handle the music.
</P>
<P>
   Only one tenor in the 20th century sang it with the kind of
heroic sound and command than Wagner envisioned: Lauritz Melchior.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday another Danish tenor, Stig Andersen, made his
Metropolitan Opera debut in the title role of ``Siegfried'' in the
first of the company's three complete ``Ring'' cycles this season.
And if he is no threat to the Melchior legacy, Andersen is a
creditable Siegfried, which is no small accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   He does not have a true heroic tenor voice like, say, Ben
Heppner, a great Tristan who has avoided Siegfried, probably
sensibly. Andersen's fine-grained sound, if not enormous, is robust
and backed with solid technique. By skillfully pacing himself, he
managed to summon enough power in the big moments to be heard over
the thick orchestrations, though James Levine, an astute
accompanist of singers as well as a great Wagner conductor, helped
out by keeping the instrumental textures light and clear wherever
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen started his career as a baritone, and his lower voice
is still stronger than his top notes. Vocally this was a solid and
intelligent account of the role, sung with rhythmic incisiveness
and crisp diction.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else about his portrayal was exceptional. He made
this blockhead of a boy seem genuinely sympathetic. When he
questioned Mime, the conniving dwarf who has reared him, about who
his real parents were, this Siegfried seemed painfully vulnerable.
With his reddish-blond hair, husky athletic build and youthful
energy, Andersen looked great.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview he was unwilling to reveal his age. But
during intermission last Saturday, a friend of his, a Danish
journalist, said he was 50. If so, that would mean this performance
is probably the most complete account of the role he will give us.
No backhanded compliment is intended by saying that Andersen is
probably the best Siegfried we have right now.
</P>
<P>
   The final cruelty that Wagner inflicted on Siegfried occurs in
the last 30 minutes of the opera. He arrives on the fire-surrounded
rock where Bruennhilde has been under a sleeping spell since ``Die
Walkuere.'' He wakes her, and they proceed into one of the most
vocally taxing love scenes ever. He has been singing for hours; she
is fresh as a daisy. As Bruennhilde, the soprano Jane Eaglen
certainly sounded fresh, singing with her customary vocal plushness
and presence. Levine seems to elicit the most dramatically involved
work from this sometimes stolid singer.
</P>
<P>
   The great bass James Morris was once again a vocally commanding
and deeply affecting Wotan (here called the Wanderer), surely the
great achievement of his career. The tenor Graham Clark gave a
wily, spry and wonderfully nasal-toned portrayal of Mime. Singing
Mime's bossy brother, Alberich, the baritone Ekkehard Wlaschiha
offered bellowed growls and pitchless shouts in place of honest
singing. The fine mezzo-soprano Birgitta Svenden sang Erda. The
offstage voices of the bass Eric Halfvarson as Fafner the dragon
and the soprano Heidi Grant Murphy as the Forest Bird were
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Eaglen and Andersen return next Saturday as the first cycle
concludes with ``Goetterdaemmerung.'' Here Wagner more evenly
distributed the vocal demands on his ill-fated hero and heroine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
