<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-MARKETPLACE-78     04-16 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-MARKETPLACE-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: MONDAY'S OPENING BELL COULD BE A TEST CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 13 years ago, investors stunned by the worst stock-market
week in memory spent the weekend pondering whether a great bull
market was over. On the following Monday, so many of them decided
to sell that the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 22.6 percent,
or 508 points. Oct. 19, 1987, became known as Black Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, there have been many bad days for the stock
market, but no week as stunning in its devastation as the last
week. Now, as then, investors have large profits that they could
choose to protect by fleeing a market that had seemed so promising
only weeks before.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions made over the weekend by investors, whether at
kitchen tables or in conference rooms at money-management firms,
will largely determine whether last week's slide in stock prices
continues on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, many investors have come to view that year's crash
as the greatest buying opportunity of their lives, and market
setbacks have usually been quickly followed by rebounds. But if the
crash of 1987 is well remembered, what led up to it is not.
</P>
<P>
   The prior week saw the Dow plunge 9.5 percent, capped by the
first-ever 100-point daily decline on Friday. That was the worst
week for the index since 1940, when the fall of France to Hitler's
invading army terrified investors.
</P>
<P>
   There was no such obvious reason for the 1987 decline, which in
a way made it all the more terrifying. News articles blamed a bad
trade report, which put pressure on the dollar, and a legislative
proposal to use tax policy to discourage takeovers, but neither
seemed enough to explain such a big fall. The Federal Reserve Board
had been raising interest rates and there had been numerous
warnings that stocks were overvalued, but neither factor was new.
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous similarities now. The Fed is raising interest
rates, there have been plenty of warnings of overvalued stocks, and
a bad economic report, this one on inflation, played a role last
week, when the Dow fell 7.3 percent while the Nasdaq composite
plunged 25.3 percent in its worst week ever.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the crash was brought on largely because selling simply
overwhelmed the markets. The worst selling came from professional
money managers. Some were reacting to redemptions by mutual-fund
investors, but others were trying to get ahead of redemptions that
were expected but did not occur.
</P>
<P>
   The most important selling, however, came from money managers
who had bought into a brand of hooey known as portfolio insurance.
The theory was that a pension fund or other institution could stay
fully invested in stocks but be protected against declines by
hiring a manager who would react to price falls by selling
stock-index futures.
</P>
<P>
   It was assumed that there would always be buyers for such
futures contracts. But there weren't, and demands to sell at the
market price, when there was no real functioning market, drove
prices far lower than they would otherwise have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to fully assess the sources of selling last
week. Some no doubt came from individuals who borrowed money to buy
stocks, and were forced to sell when prices fell. Margin debt rose
rapidly beginning last fall, just as the Nasdaq market took off on
an explosive surge that has now been largely reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Some also may have come from fund managers who were trying to
raise cash to meet redemptions, real or anticipated. The latest
mutual-fund cash-flow estimates from AMG Data Services, however,
indicate that for the week ended Wednesday investors were putting
money into mutual funds that buy technology stocks. It is not clear
whether that reversed late in the week.
</P>
<P>
   The stock-index futures that the portfolio insurers dumped in
1987 are a relatively simple and visible type of derivative
security _ a security whose value is based on the behavior of
another security. The whizzes of Wall Street have since designed
many more exotic securities, along with computer models to ensure
that they are used safely and that any firm's exposure to risk is
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these securities are traded privately, with no public
disclosure, and the strategies being used are closely guarded.
Portfolio insurance, by contrast, was well known to market watchers
before the 1987 crash, although the way it could devastate prices
was not fully appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock market does continue lower, we may learn whether
some of the computer models used to assess and control risk now are
able to function under extraordinary circumstances, or whether they
may have exposed some firms to large losses. There is no way to
know whether strategies that did not work out will lead to more
selling.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As individual investors contemplated their finances this
weekend, some of them needed to raise cash to pay 1999 income taxes
that were due Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who bought high-flying mutual funds last year, or who
traded in the hot initial public offerings of Internet companies,
wound up with large short-term capital gains, which are taxed at
ordinary income-tax rates. For some of those investors, the profits
may have been wiped out last week, when some mutual funds that
specialized in technology stocks lost more than a third of their
value. But the taxes are still due.
</P>
<P>
   For the Dow, the week was the worst since Oct. 13, 1989, when
the collapse of a takeover plan for UAL, the parent of United
Airlines, led to a 7.8 percent slide that culminated on a Friday.
Over the weekend, however, investors assessed the situation and
decided that it was a good time to buy. The Dow rose 4.7 percent
the next week.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, people remembered 1987 and concluded that buying after
a plunge was a good way to make money. The fate of stocks on
Monday, and over the next several weeks, may hinge on how many
investors still believe that this theory is a good one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
