<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS FEW TRUST PROMISES ON ONLINE PRIVACY  
 FINDING THE ALIGNMENT FOR E-COMMERCE IMPACT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SURVEY SHOWS FEW TRUST PROMISES ON ONLINE PRIVACY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Internet industry may believe that self-regulation is the
best way to handle online privacy, but consumers apparently do not.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new survey by Odyssey, a market research firm, 82
percent of online households agree strongly or at least somewhat
with the statement, ``The government needs to step in and regulate
how companies can use personal information.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust in the Internet industry, it seems, does not run deep
among the online masses. A notable 92 percent of online households
agree or agree strongly with the statement, ``I don't trust
companies to keep personal information about me confidential, no
matter what they promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Donatiello, president of Odyssey in San Francisco, says
the attitudes of online households point to how difficult it may
prove to be for the industry to head off government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's striking is how many people already want the government
to intervene,'' he said. ``The wired households of America are not
a group whose first response is that the government should step
in.''
</P>
<P>
   He described it as a warning shot across the bow of companies
involved in the Internet. ``If they don't do something pretty
quickly to address these concerns, Congress will,'' said
Donatiello, who once worked in Congress as a Senate staff member.
</P>
<P>
   Despite qualms about privacy, though, online shopping continues
to surge, according to Odyssey, which polls 3,000 American
households every six months.
</P>
<P>
   Odyssey says that the 41 percent of the American households that
were online made an estimated 191 million purchases in the last six
months of 1999, dwarfing the 17 million in the comparable six-month
period two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many people, the benefits of online purchasing outweigh
their privacy concerns,'' Donatiello said. ``But privacy is a
serious issue that can slow the development of this medium.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINDING THE ALIGNMENT FOR E-COMMERCE IMPACT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Web site not sticky enough? Might be its yin and yang.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Stark, an expert in feng shui, the ancient Chinese art of
harmonious balance, took on a case in cyberspace last week. He
performed a feng shui ceremony at the Web site of Corcoran.com,
which sells luxury homes, concluding that the site's bits were not
aligned to promote harmony _ or e-commerce. Dissonant elements
included misplaced ``help'' and ``dream'' buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Corcoran, whose Corcoran Group runs the site, said that
after the ceremony she asked her Web designer to retune the site.
Corcoran, who once had her Madison Avenue office ``smudged'' _ a
Native American cleansing ceremony _ is pragmatic about her
rituals. ``Feng shui is all about energy, and a Web site is pure
energy,'' she said. ``If we do $50 billion in sales in the first
month after our relaunch, we'll know what to attribute it to.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-FED-NYT &LR;      04-16 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-FED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED EXPECTED TO CONTINUE SAME COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the markets reopen Monday, one of the biggest questions
weighing on investors' minds is what the Federal Reserve might do.
The answer: no change in policy.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly that is the expectation on Wall Street. Alan
Greenspan, the Fed chairman, has committed the central bank to a
series of small interest rate increases until the economy slows and
stock markets, in response, calm down. The sell-off last Friday
does not alter that policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is evidence that the financial markets are under
more strain than we have seen so far, there is no reason to believe
that the Fed will alter course,'' said John Lipsky, chief economist
at Chase Manhattan Bank. What is required is evidence of a panic in
which lending and borrowing dry up and markets cease to function.
</P>
<P>
   That did not happen last Friday. As Albert Wojnilower, an
economist at Craig Drill Capital and the Clipper Group, put it,
``As long as you were willing to sell at $5 or $10 or $15 down,
there were buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Through statements and actions, Greenspan has locked the Fed
into a fairly predictable approach. He has argued that investors'
enthusiasm for stocks is largely a rational response to rising
productivity and to expectations of rising profits. But even
rational markets can get ahead of themselves, and investors' gains
from rising stock prices have created more demand for goods and
services than the economy can continue to supply. The result is
likely to be inflationary pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Or so Greenspan has argued. As a result, the Fed has raised
rates by a quarter of a percentage point on five occasions since
last June. In this context, last Friday's sell-off can be viewed as
part of the change that the rate increases are intended to bring
about.
</P>
<P>
   Even after last Friday's tumble, the major indexes are still far
from reversing the gains of the 1990s. The Dow Jones industrial
average and the Wilshire 5000, a broad stock measure, are only back
to where they were a year ago, Lipsky noted, and the Nasdaq is up
nearly 34 percent since last spring.
</P>
<P>
   For the Fed to change course _ either cutting rates or even
failing to go up another quarter point at the next Fed
policy-making meeting on, on May 16 _ would be a signal to
investors that the Fed stands ready to bail them out, Roach and
others on Wall Street argued Sunday. That would cause stock prices
to shoot up again, most analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical risk taker will say, `Oh, that is nice, the Fed
will bail us out,''' said David M. Jones, chief economist at Aubrey
G. Lanston, a Wall Street bond firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has supplied relief to offset past panics, which it has
defined as moments in which markets seize up. In panics, buyers all
but disappear despite plunging stock prices. Lenders also pull back
or seek the safe haven of Treasury securities. And markets, in
effect, cease to function.
</P>
<P>
   ``Borrowers won't borrow, lenders won't lend and investors find
themselves unable to buy and sell securities in the desired
volumes, regardless of price,'' Lipsky said.
</P>
<P>
   That happened on Oct. 19, 1987, when the Dow Jones industrial
average fell by 21 percent _ far beyond the 5.66 percent decline
last Friday. Reversing course _ then like now, Greenspan had been
trying to slow the economy through interest rate increases _ the
Fed cut rates and promised lenders plenty of liquidity to stay
afloat if borrowers defaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, appointed Fed chairman only a few months earlier,
fashioned that strategy, and he invoked the same rate-cutting
policy again in the fall of 1998, after Russia defaulted on its
debts and Long Term Capital Management, a hedge fund, almost
failed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
