<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, April 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A big difference is expected in the weather along the Northeast
coast with chilly onshore winds and periods of rain. The
combination of a very cold high pressure system over Quebec and a
strong disturbance moving southeast from the Ohio Valley will draw
colder, moist air inland from the North Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   A few strong thunderstorms will form over the Carolinas and
Georgia in the sultry air mass ahead of the disturbance. Florida
will be dry, but very warm.
</P>
<P>
   Inclement conditions will dominate the Great Lakes and Middle
West as low clouds and light rain linger over the region. Wet snow
or sleet will fall in northern Michigan as colder air arrives on
brisk winds from the north.
</P>
<P>
   Hot air will surge north into the western Plains on balmy winds.
Late-day thunderstorms may erupt near the Rio Grande Valley. A
large disturbance moving into Nevada will promote cooler air and
showers in the West.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: KANSAS CONTRASTS
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the temperature in Goodland, Kan., rose to a record
86 degrees. On Saturday, the mercury reached only 29 for a maximum,
marking a 57- degree change in high temperature in just one day.
Even across the Sunflower State, the temperature varied from the
middle 70s in southeast Kansas to the middle 20s in northwest
sections on Saturday. These large temperature variations are the
fuel that powers strong spring storms, like the one that will
affect the East Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
