<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8506 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-OPERA-SASSY-REVIEW-SF     04-16 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-SASSY-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN OPERA HAS A NEW CLASSIC IN `COLD SASSY TREE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON &LR;   &LR; _ Carlisle Floyd's opera ``Cold Sassy Tree,'' which
had its world premiere at the Houston Grand Opera on Friday night,
is a minor masterpiece of musical storytelling and assured
theatrical know-how.
</P>
<P>
   The score boasts passages of radiant, lyrical beauty, including
a striking number of self-contained arias, as well as stretches of
utilitarian wheel-spinning. But what lingers in the listener's
imagination is not so much the musical specifics as the opera's
overall dramatic mastery _ the efficiency and cunning with which
Floyd shapes this tale of the American South.
</P>
<P>
   In three acts spanning more than three hours and encompassing
comedy and pathos, group dynamics and individual emotion, he never
puts a foot wrong or misjudges a dramatic emphasis. Each scene
plays out with unerring focus, and the work as a whole moves
confidently through its entire arc.
</P>
<P>
   Never underestimate the benefits of a lifetime in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Sassy Tree'' marks the culmination of a distinguished
operatic career for the 73-year-old composer-librettist, one that
began in 1955 with his first and still most popular opera,
``Susannah.'' Since then, Floyd has created such landmarks of
American opera as ``Of Mice and Men'' _ after ``Susannah'' his most
secure addition to the repertoire _ as well as three Houston
commissions, ``The Passion of Jonathan Wade,'' ``Bilby's Doll'' and
``Willie Stark.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd's outlook is distinctively American (only his ``Wuthering
Heights'' is set elsewhere), and the regional strains that first
showed up in ``Susannah'' infuse ``Cold Sassy Tree'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   The opera is based on Olive Ann Burns' best-selling 1984 novel
about a hardheaded old widower, Rucker Lattimore, who scandalizes
the inhabitants of his turn-of-the-century Georgia town by marrying
Miss Love Simpson _ a young employee in his general store _ just
three weeks after the death of his first wife.
</P>
<P>
   Burns' novel was a commodious, rather flabby collection of
reminiscence, period detail, exuberant yarn-spinning and sheer
cornpone sentimentality. What is immediately impressive about
Floyd's opera is the ruthless efficiency with which we has
extracted a stage-worthy libretto from that mass of detail.
</P>
<P>
   Characters by the dozen have been left on the cutting-room
floor, while others have had their identities merged (one of the
novel's more admirable figures, a dirt-poor ``linthead'' employed
in the town's cotton mill who is determined to complete his
education, becomes a villain out of dramatic necessity).
</P>
<P>
   By nudging young Will Tweedy (the opera's narrator and the
widower's grandson) into a romance with another linthead, the
ambitious and lovely Lightfoot McClendon, Floyd creates a telling
dramatic parallelism missing from the source. Other strokes too,
both large and small, help turn Burns' crowded canvas into a
crisply focused tale.
</P>
<P>
   That in turn makes room for the elegantly crafted lyric set
pieces, half a dozen or more of them, that represent the opera's
real glories. Chief among these is ``Rented rooms,'' in which Love
_ who has agreed to keep house for Rucker in exchange for ownership
of his home and furniture _ details her impoverished past to the
scandalized family. The melody is a long-breathed, gorgeously
arching affair, driving to a Puccinian climax before subsiding in a
little coda reminiscent of ``Mi chiamano Mim &LR; i &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   But there are others as well _ a heart-tuggingly tentative love
duet for Will and Lightfoot, Rucker's wonderfully vital and
homegrown sermon when the small-mindedness of the townspeople
compels him and Love to hold a makeshift church service in their
parlor, and another, even more wrenching revelatory aria for Love
later in the opera.
</P>
<P>
   Setting these off are zestful comic elements, from the quartet
of female busybodies who represent the town's judgmental side to
Love's caddish former beau Clayton McAllister, a swaggering Texas
cowboy who bursts on the scene to the strains of a Copland parody.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston production is sheer delight, staged on Michael
Yeargan's picture-postcard sets and directed by film director Bruce
Beresford with the closely observed sense of detail that informed
his 1983 film ``Tender Mercies.''
</P>
<P>
   Music director Patrick Summers (also the San Francisco Opera's
principal guest conductor) led a vigorous, sensitive performance,
briskly paced through the narrative sections (``Cold Sassy Tree''
is a little full of ``Our Town''-style expository voice-overs) but
with plenty of time for the score's more effusive outpourings.
</P>
<P>
   And the cast was nothing short of superb, led by Dean Peterson
as the irascibly appealing Rucker and Patricia Racette as a
luminous Love Simpson. John McVeigh was charm itself as Will
Tweedy, and Margaret Lloyd's beautifully clear soprano gave extra
allure to Lightfoot's music.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Alexander and Beth Clayton made a wonderful team as Will's
mother and aunt, and Christopher Schaldenbrand caught Clayton's
self-infatuation perfectly. Judith Christin contributed a gem of a
comic turn as Miss Effie Belle Tate, the leader of the town's
virtuous crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Sassy Tree'' is the 25th world premiere by the Houston
Grand Opera, an astonishing track record that is testament to this
company's farsighted enterprise under its visionary general
director, David Gockley.
</P>
<P>
   From here it will go on to revivals by its four co-commissioning
companies in San Diego, Baltimore, Austin and North Carolina. And
after that, watch out _ we may well have another American repertory
staple on our hands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
