<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Saturday, April 15, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Dominick Calicchio at 415-777-6206
or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running
in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; STOCKS _  &LR; Investors' weeklong skittishness turned to outright panic
Friday as inflation fears sparked the biggest one-day point losses
ever for the Dow Jones Industrial Average and Nasdaq composite
index. ``A lot of money has gone to money heaven,'' said Bill
Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald in New York. ``It
won't be coming back.''  &UR; BY DAVID LAZARUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MARKET _ &LR;  Looking at the raw numbers, Friday the 14th could very
well join 1987's Black Monday and 1929's Terrible Tuesday as one of
the scariest days in stock market history. However, in percentage
terms, the worst single-day point drops for the Nasdaq, the Dow
Jones Industrial Average and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 do not look
quite so terrifying. &UR; BY PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PERKS _ &LR;  Last week, Oracle Corp. employee Amy Odum did something
that could have gotten her fired at some companies. Using her
office computer, she went online and bought health insurance for
Buster, her miniature schnauzer. Odum didn't get in trouble
shopping on company time because Oracle allows her to buy
discounted goods and services at a new employees-only shop on the
company's internal computer network. It's all part of an employee
Web portal designed and run by San Francisco startup
Perksatwork.com.  &UR; BY CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8509 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-STOCKS-PANIC-SFCHRON &LR;      04-16 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-PANIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STOCK BUBBLE FINALLY BURSTS  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Investors' weeklong skittishness turned to
outright panic Friday as inflation fears sparked the biggest
one-day point losses ever for the Dow Jones Industrial Average and
Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of money has gone to money heaven,'' said Bill Meehan,
chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald in New York. ``It won't
be coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow plunged 617.78 points, or more than 5 percent, to finish
the day at 10,305.77. At one point in the last hour of trading, the
blue-chip index was down 722 points.
</P>
<P>
   The tech-heavy Nasdaq, meanwhile, experienced a complete
meltdown, dropping 355.49, or almost 10 percent, to 3,321.29.
</P>
<P>
   Although this represents a slight rebound from the Nasdaq's
411-point low for yesterday's session, the cascading losses still
bring the index down more than 1,000 points for the week. The
Nasdaq has plummeted more than 34 percent since hitting a record
high on March 10.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 83.95, or almost 6
percent, to 1,356.56.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like investors believed in a magic spell, that
tech could only go up, up and away,'' said Alfred Kugel, senior
investment strategist at Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham in Chicago. ``That has
pretty much come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say it's anyone's guess how the market will behave on
Monday. While some insist that the Nasdaq has just about reached
bottom, others say it could fall by as much as 15 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's sell-off was fueled in part by a government report
showing that consumer prices rose at their strongest clip in nearly
a year during March. This rekindled fears that the Federal Reserve
will move to slow the red-hot U.S. economy by once again boosting
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index, the leading benchmark of inflation,
climbed 0.7 percent last month. Economists had been expecting a 0.5
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding volatile energy and food prices, the CPI was up only
0.4 percent, but that was still twice the expected amount.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the CPI is only part of the story. The wider and, for many
investors, more worrying trend is a growing disenchantment with
technology stocks that has spread from Wall Street to Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a rethinking about the inevitability that you
will make money any time you buy technology,'' Kugel said.
</P>
<P>
   He traced much of this revisionism to the collapse of antitrust
negotiations between the government and Microsoft Corp. earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was the most successful technology company ever invented
and the government was going after them,'' Kugel said. ``People
realized that if it could happen to Microsoft, it could happen to
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically, that really affected the invincibility of
technology,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of many market pundits, the revelation that tech
stocks actually can shift into reverse, as opposed to possessing
nothing but forward gears, served as a wake-up call for numerous
investors.
</P>
<P>
   And once these investors looked closer at the sky-high
valuations and shaky bottom lines of most leading tech outfits,
they quickly realized that, in many cases, there was little more
than wishful thinking propping up share prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good,'' said Steve Adams, managing director of First
Security Van Kasper in San Francisco. ``People were unbelievably
cocky and didn't understand risk.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, they sure do now.
</P>
<P>
   This was the worst week in the 29-year history of the Nasdaq _ a
25-percent decline since Monday. Most traders consider a 10-percent
drop to represent a market ``correction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq is down more than 18 percent for the year. However,
it doesn't hurt to remember that the index surged a whopping 84
percent last year. Many investors, in other words, are still ahead
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   It might not feel that way, though. Some of the biggest losers
in the tech camp this week were also among the sector's brightest
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, Oracle Corp. and National Semiconductor Corp.
each lost about a quarter of their market value over the past five
days.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless technology leader Qualcomm, last year's highest-flying
stock, fell almost 17 percent yesterday alone, to $105.19, while
chipmaker Intel Corp. slid nearly 9 percent, to $110.50.
</P>
<P>
   Such carnage did not sit well with the investors who crowded
into the Charles Schwab office in San Francisco's Financial
District to see how the day's devastation was playing out in their
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Fay Wu arrived at 10 a.m. and remained at one of the lobby
computers for the next three hours. ``I'm trading'' was all she had
to say to a reporter as tech stocks flew by on her screen in the
last few minutes before the closing bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go away,'' said a young man in a black vest who was intensely
scouring the market for bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Archie Thomas, a San Francisco lawyer, said he sold off a number
of stocks early in the morning once he sensed how the wind was
blowing. ``But I'm not selling my long-term holdings,'' he said.
``I'd have to pay too much in taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors shouldn't look to Fed chief Alan Greenspan for a quick
fix to the market's woes. After persistently declaring stocks to be
overvalued, he said in a speech yesterday that ``financial
institutions should expect to look to the central bank only in
extremely rare situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The comment was taken by many to mean that the Fed remains
unsympathetic to the plight of investors and may in fact be
planning to jack up rates again in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who are new to the market believed it just
couldn't go down,'' said Cantor Fitzgerald's Meehan. ``They thought
Greenspan just wouldn't let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lehmann, an economics professor at the University of San
Francisco, blamed part of yesterday's collapse on a recent increase
in margin calls by securities houses _ a demand that customers
return borrowed funds that had been used to buy stocks.
</P>
<P>
   This caught many investors off-guard, he said, and forced them
to sell off holdings to raise cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very gloomy about the prospects for the stock market,''
Lehmann said. ``I think there's going to be a major bear market and
maybe a recession.''
</P>
<P>
   But Janet Yellen, a professor at the University of California at
Berkeley's Haas School of Business and former chairwoman of the
President's Council of Economic Advisers, rejected the notion that
recent market turbulence signals an increased risk of recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy can absorb a correction of this size,'' she said.
``The belief that a recession is around the corner is highly
misguided.''
</P>
<P>
   Yellen, who also has served on the board of governors of the
Federal Reserve, added that investors' losses in the stock market
come ``at a time when the economy is extremely strong. It's
certainly not something I would panic about.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investors, however, will nevertheless require fortification
before facing the damage yesterday's rout did to their nest eggs
and retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to look,'' said Tim Colen, a geologist who was
enjoying a cup of coffee at a downtown cafe shortly after the
market closed. ``Or maybe after a couple of beers.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8510 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MARKET-SCARY-SFCHRON &LR;      04-16 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-SCARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A SOBER LOOK AT DAY'S SCARY NUMBERS  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Looking at the raw numbers, Friday the 14th
could very well join 1987's Black Monday and 1929's Terrible
Tuesday as one of the scariest days in stock market history.
</P>
<P>
   However, in percentage terms, the worst single-day point drops
for the Nasdaq, the Dow Jones Industrial Average and Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 do not look quite so terrifying. On Friday, the Dow fell
5.64 percent and the S&AMP;P 500 fell 5.76 percent, a far cry from
their respective 22 percent and 20.5 percent declines on Oct. 19,
1987.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the two closely watched indices fell more than they did
Friday as recently as Aug. 31, 1998. That's when, alarmed by
Russia's political crisis, the Dow skidded 6.37 percent and the S&AMP;P
dipped 6.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, the damage to the Nasdaq is less easy to downplay or
dismiss. The index of close to 5,000 stocks lost 9.66 percent
Friday. That was second only to the 11.35 drop on Oct. 19, 1987.
But the loss came at the end of a bad run for the index.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq stocks have lost more than $2 trillion in market value _
a whopping 34.2 percent _ since peaking at 5,048.62 on March 10.
That's more than the $1.83 trillion U.S. budget plan approved by
Congress this week. By contrast, the Dow index of 30 large
companies has shed only 12 percent of its value since peaking on
January 14.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of yesterday's decimation, Robertson Stephens
investment banking director Todd Carter said, ``I've been holding a
lot of hands.'' Many investors are worried but few are totally
surprised by the recent market jitters.
</P>
<P>
   After all, interest rates and concerns about inflation have been
creeping up.
</P>
<P>
   So has awareness that stock prices, especially for Internet
startups with more promise than profits, have defied traditional
price-earnings models. ``The pendulum in the market has been
swinging to extremes,'' said Carter.
</P>
<P>
   For example eToys, a recent IPO that soared as high as $86 a
share is down to $4.75. Commerce One, a Web-based business services
company and last year's top-performing initial public offering, has
skidded from $331 to $66 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Carter figures that some sectors may have farther to slide, but
he also believes that some issues have already been ``oversold.''
However, as a sign of caution, Carter said the 27 IPOs that his
firm hopes to bring public currently are in a ``holding pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other analysts and investors remain apprehensive about
where stocks will go next week. Some self-described experts feel
tech stocks should be avoided for years and the Nasdaq could give
up another third of its value.
</P>
<P>
   But Rick Eakle of Eakle Associates in Fair Haven, N.J. expects
things could settle down early next week after the first few hours
of margin calls on Monday. ``Since the inception of Nasdaq in 1971,
there have been eight corrections and the average decline is 32.7
percent,'' he said. ``Nasdaq is down 34 percent in a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current market has a lot of characteristics of the bottoms
in 1987, 1990 and 1998 when there was a period of unrelenting
declines and a lot of speculation was squeezed out of the market.
An attack on the strongest stocks like American Express, Cisco,
Dell, Intel and Hewlett Packard also typically comes at the end of
a selling phase.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Consumer Price Index was up sharply yesterday,
Eakle figures inflation fears are overblown. For example, he said
oil prices are on their way down since the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed to increase production last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Arthur Louis contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
