<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8516 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PERKS-ESHOP-SFCHRON &LR;      04-16 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERKS-ESHOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WORKERS CAN SHOP ON COMPANY INTRANETS  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last week, Oracle Corp. employee Amy Odum did
something that could have gotten her fired at some companies. Using
her office computer, she went online and bought health insurance
for Buster, her miniature schnauzer.
</P>
<P>
   Odum didn't get in trouble shopping on company time because
Oracle allows her to buy discounted goods and services at a new
employees-only shop on the company's internal computer network.
It's all part of an employee Web portal designed and run by San
Francisco startup Perksatwork.com.
</P>
<P>
   Odum isn't alone. Workers at other companies are using similar
employee portals to find real estate agents, arrange to have their
dog walked or buy movie tickets. Almost anything they can buy on
the Internet is available in these shops.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the average Internet mall, the shops are incorporated
into their companies' internal Web sites, and the employees pay as
little as 50 percent of normal prices.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a boss make it easier for the staff to conduct
personal business at work? Perksatwork.com chief executive Jim
Greene says it's all about retaining employees. ``The war for
talent is being lost by companies of all sizes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 percent of Northern California workers left their
jobs or were fired in 1998 and 1999. With turnover this high,
employers are going all out be known as nice places to work.
</P>
<P>
   Employee portals aren't new. Companies such as Epicentric and
Plumtree have been making them for several years. What makes the
new generation of portals different is that they have added
shopping and services to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Perksatwork.com's employee portal makes it easy for
employees to set up discussion groups around topics such as
neighborhood child care. The site also hosts virtual bulletin
boards and classified ads, where employees can advertise for
carpool members or sell a used bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Another employee portal provider, Seattle's ServiceStop, focuses
on linking employees with local providers of such services as auto
detailing. ServiceStop is now setting up a second office in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The employee shopping portal market is still a tiny niche in
e-commerce, with only a handful of young companies vying against
each other. Still, it is getting a vote of confidence from venture
capitalists. Perksatwork.com recently netted $67 million in
funding, while EmployeeSavings.com, a Bellevue, Wash., competitor,
just got $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   At Oracle's Redwood Shores headquarters, online discount
shopping is just one of a multitude of conveniences available to
its workers. It also provides other services such as on-campus
photo processing, a car wash and dry cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller companies that can't afford to build a staff-cradling
village like Oracle's can still offer their workers a shopping
portal, because Perksatwork.com and its competitors are offering
their services for free.
</P>
<P>
   They can do this because they make their money on sales
commissions. Every time a customer uses EmployeeSavings.com or
Perksatwork.com to buy something, the portalmaker gets a
commission, usually ranging from 1 to 5 percent of the item's
price.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ordinary online shopping malls, employee portals can
deliver large numbers of potential customers _ like Oracle's 20,000
employees nationwide _ all at once. In exchange for this influx of
people, the retailers offer their goods at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   For ServiceStop, the formula is a little different. Employees
pay the going rate for services, but the service providers often
throw in extra conveniences _ like picking up a car and taking it
to the service garage _ for free.
</P>
<P>
   Employee shopping portals have a competitive edge over generic
Web malls because the portals have ``a more captured audience,''
said Mike May, a senior analyst for Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   A customer may use an online mall once to buy books from
Amazon.com, but the next time that customer wants to buy books
online, they're likely to go straight to Amazon.com, instead of
returning to the online mall.
</P>
<P>
   The discounts at employee portals are ``an incentive for
customers to make every single transaction through them,'' May
said.
</P>
<P>
   The only cloud on the horizon is the lack of unique technology
behind the employee portals, said Joshua Walker, an analyst with
Forrester Research. For example, if Perksatwork.com makes its idea
look attractive enough, established makers of human resources
software _ such as its client Oracle _ could simply mimic the idea
and beat Perksatwork.com at its own game, Walker warned.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the portals have been popular with employees. Since
Oracle started offering a Perksatwork.com portal March 15, about
half of the corporation's 20,000 employees nationwide have signed
up, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Human resources managers like the employee portals too, because
they make their jobs easier. The portal can be a place to
consolidate a company's existing corporate discounts.
</P>
<P>
   They are also an easy way for companies to reward workers. For
example, a manager using ServiceStop could authorize the employee
of the month to get $50 worth of dry cleaning, charged to the
company's account.
</P>
<P>
   Perksatwork.com plugs itself as promoting a balance between the
demands of work and personal life, but some might wonder if
employers are using the portals to push employees to work longer
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ServiceStop founder Jon Clemens acknowledges that one reason
employers use his service is that they don't want high-paid
employees taking an extended lunch or coming in late if they have
to deal with a problem such as getting a leaky sink fixed at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to see people have some time off,'' said Gloria Dunn,
who wrote ``From Making a Living to Having a Life,'' a book about
balancing work and personal life. ``I don't believe it's good for
an employee to spend 24 hours in front of a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Employers who install shopping portals also run the risk that
some workers will abuse the privilege. Shopping at work is already
more common _ and time consuming _ than some employers might
realize. For instance, Internet users who visited auction site eBay
in January from an office computer typically spent a whopping 157
minutes on the site, while visitors from home only spent an average
of 126 minutes, according to Nielsen/NetRatings, a firm that
measures Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   For some companies, such as Oracle, it's a matter of trust. They
simply count on their employees to responsibly manage their own
time. Other firms monitor their workers' use of the shopping
portals and other nonwork-related Web sites, and intervene if the
employees are spending too much time online.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're excessively shopping on Perksatwork, we would
consider that abuse,'' said Kristi Graning, who directs Web
services at ReMax, a Denver real estate company and a
Perksatwork.com customer. ``But a 10-minute break to buy movie
tickets is fine with us.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of offices where an employee shopping portal
would not be welcome. Indeed, ``stricter'' employers spend lots of
money on software that lets them monitor their employees' use of
the Internet _ often with the express purpose of preventing online
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   According to International Data Corp., employers bought $53
million worth of employee monitoring software last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even an hour of unproductive surfing (a day) is costing
employers hundreds of thousands of dollars a year,'' said Ted Ladd,
spokesman for Websense, a software application that monitors
workers' Web surfing.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of a client, Websense can prevent office
computers from accessing certain categories of Web sites. Although
the company also filters out pornography, stock trading and chat
sites, more and more employers want shopping sites blocked, Ladd
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ladd suggested that employee shopping portals might help
employers limit Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're controlling where they're shopping, maybe it's
better than having people free surf,'' Ladd said.
</P>
<P>
   But Perksatwork.com chief executive Greene bristled at the idea
that his technology could be used as a tool to control employees'
activities. The point, he said, isn't control, it's employee
retention.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
