u f BC-COKE-PROTEST-NYT &LR;      04-16 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER COKE WORKERS START TRIP TO PUBLICIZE RACIAL DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A busload of about four dozen former employees of the
Coca-Cola Co. and activists began a five-day trip on Saturday to
draw attention to their frustrations with the soft-drink company.
Their journey will end Wednesday at the Coca-Cola annual
shareholder meeting in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   The group wants Coca-Cola to settle a racial discrimination suit
brought by eight employees nearly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs are seeking class-action status for
as many as 2,000 past and current employees. They contend that the
company discriminates against African Americans in pay, promotions,
and performance evaluations. The company has denied the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Delaware, we hope to say to Coke, it's time,'' said Larry
D. Jones, a laid-off Coca-Cola manager who organized the trip. ``We
will not go into the 21st century with the same problems.''
</P>
<P>
   At the departure rally outside an Atlanta church, roughly 100
supporters, many wearing red hats emblazoned with ``Freedom
Rider,'' held hands and sang: ``We are riding for justice. Lord,
come by here.''
</P>
<P>
   They bowed their heads in prayer as the Rev. E. Randel Osburn,
vice president of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference,
vowed, ``We are not going to keep spending money where people
disrespect us.''
</P>
<P>
   But just before the passengers boarded the bus, Jones said, ``We
won't call for a boycott unless things don't work out the way they
should.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there were signs that a boycott of Coca-Cola might be
called at some point as the bus stops for rallies in Greensboro,
N.C., Richmond, Va., Washington and finally Wilmington, where Jones
plans to address shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   At the departure rally, one sign held by a little girl asked,
``Will the Real Thing Do the Right Thing?''
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a boycott has loomed over the company since ``The
Ride for Corporate Justice'' held its first news conference and
called for an equitable settlement of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A Coca-Cola spokesman, Ben Deutsch, said, ``We continue to work
toward an expeditious and equitable resolution of the lawsuit.'' He
declined to comment on the prospect of a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Douglas N. Daft, Coca-Cola's chairman, told
employees that he would work ``toward an expedient and equitable''
resolution of the lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
