u s BC-RUN-BOSTON-MARATHON-N     04-16 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-BOSTON-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIAN WOMAN SEEKS HER FOURTH CONSECUTIVE BOSTON MARATHON
TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fatuma Roba's hair is pinched back, and small gold
ovals dangle from her ear lobes, framing a regal face, with eyes
that seem constantly fixed on the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ethiopian runner smiles _ sharing a joke with her male
teammates flanking her at the interview table _ she softens the
serious point of her chin and flashes a glimpse of her sly wit.
</P>
<P>
   Roba is confident and proud of her success. But she would never
tell you that.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy and humility is utmost in her culture, especially for
women, even one of the most famous ones in her country.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old from Addis Ababa is trying to win her fourth
straight Boston Marathon, something no woman or man has ever done.
``I am hoping to make history,'' she said simply, through a
translator. ``I feel like I have made good preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Her remarkable quest highlights the 104th Boston Marathon, but
the men's race also offers an extra incentive. Joseph Chebet of
Kenya hopes to defend his 1999 title (he is also the reigning New
York champion) while accomplishing another goal: Boston serves as
the Kenyan men's Olympic Trials. Two runners will be chosen here,
and another will be chosen later by committee, to compete in
September in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Add the pressure to qualify with the mystique and infamous hills
of the Boston Marathon and Chebet understands the challenge. ``To
win for the second time,'' he said, ``I would be very, very
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   To win for the fourth time would even make Roba's competitors
happy. ``We're very proud of her,'' said Kenya's Lornah Kiplagat,
making her Boston debut. ``She is the only woman from Africa who
has won the Olympics and Boston Marathon three times. She is an
inspiration for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she can win four times, it gives us much more potential to
think we can do it, maybe six times.'' Then, with a smile, she
added, ``After she stops running.''
</P>
<P>
   That will not happen soon, especially since Roba is aiming to
repeat as the Olympic gold medalist. In 1996, she surprised the
field in Atlanta to become the first African woman to win the
Olympic marathon.
</P>
<P>
   The following spring, she proved it was no fluke. She followed
her Olympic title with a victory in Boston, spoiling Uta Pippig's
bid for her fourth straight laurel wreath. In 1998, Roba overcame
pain behind her right knee for a personal best of 2 hours 23
minutes 21 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Roba dominates in Boston (she has won no marathon outside of the
United States) because the maddening hills resemble the terrain she
trains on in Ethiopia. There, she has become an icon. Her portrait
is emblazoned in the five rings in Addis Ababa Stadium, alongside
legends like Abeba Bikila, who became the first black African to
win the Olympic marathon in 1960, and followed it with another gold
in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not really want to be famous,'' Roba said with a shrug.
``But it's nice to be among the renowned athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Before her victory in Atlanta, few knew of her in Ethiopia.
``Then something has happened,'' she said. ``Very many people,
small and big come up to me and thank me.''
</P>
<P>
   She was rewarded by the Ethiopian government with the equivalent
of $7,000 after Atlanta. Last year, like this year, the prize for
the Boston winner is $80,000. With her earnings, Roba built a
three-story house. But for now she stays in her older, smaller
house with four relatives.
</P>
<P>
   She bought a Mercedes, but does not drive it. Her brothers do.
``Definitely everybody likes it,'' she said with a smile. She just
likes to run.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of eight children, Roba grew up in the farming
village of Bokeji and ran the six miles to and from school for one
reason: ``I didn't want to be late,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At 12, she moved to Addis Ababa, but her parents disapproved of
her running. ``They thought I should be doing women things,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Roba was chosen to run for the national prison
police team. Today, she is a paid major in the military, but her
only job is to train. Her parents understand. `` `Now that we see
what the results are, now we're wrong,' they say,'' Roba said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Her competitors know, too. ``She's especially tough in Boston,''
said Elena Meyer of South Africa, who finished second to Roba in
1997. Last year, China's Sun Yingjie began with a blistering pace,
leading at the halfway mark, but Roba caught her and then passed
Kenya's Catherine Ndereba in the Newton Hills to finish in 2:23:25.
</P>
<P>
   In the final six miles, thousands from New England's Ethiopian
community lined the course, waving their green, yellow and red
flags. One threw out a headband for Roba, who wore it to the finish
line. ``It gave me energy,'' Roba said.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is reciprocal. ``I think she is an example for a lot
of women who are discouraged by the culture because it does not
reward you,'' said Misrak Assefa, co-owner of the Addis Red Sea
Ethiopian restaurant in Boston, who left Ethiopia 23 years ago.
Every year she hosts a party for Ethiopian runners after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``For women, she seems like a very special person, she's very
determined,'' Assefa said. ``If she wins four, we don't need
anything else. Someone else can start winning.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-STRATEGY-ART-N     04-16 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-STRATEGY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRATEGISTS ANXIOUSLY AWAIT OPENING OF MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also MARKET-INTERNET, MARKET-ASSESS, MARKET-MARKETPLACE,
MARKET-MOOD, MARKET-ASIA, MARKET-FED) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas McManus, equity strategist at Bank of America Securities,
spent a lot of time on the phone over the weekend talking to
clients and some time thumbing through two books from his library:
``The Great Crash, 1929'' by John Kenneth Galbraith and
``Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds,''
Charles Mackay's 19th-century classic about investment mania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for an analogous time,'' McManus said Sunday from
his home. ``The behavior of individual investors at this juncture
is a very important thing to consider, and all we have is anecdotal
reports and our own conversations with clients.''
</P>
<P>
   McManus and other strategists are trying to divine what owners
of technology stocks are likely to do Monday, after a weekend of
brooding about the market's decline. But because their behavior is
so hard to forecast, those in the predicting business are sticking
with the outlooks they held before the market plunged on Thursday
and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The technology rout sent the Nasdaq down 25.3 percent last week,
its worst weekly decline. But many technology stocks have plunged
much farther. Qualcomm, which makes wireless communications
products, has fallen 33 percent the last two and a half weeks.
Palm, which makes hand-held personal digital assistants, was down
to $31.625 on Friday, off almost 67 percent from its March high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some investors have seen a major portion of their investments
vaporize,'' McManus said. ``What does this cause them to do?''
</P>
<P>
   He expects that the low prices of old-economy stocks _ the
established industrial and consumer products companies _ will draw
investors' attention and help offset further declines in technology
stocks. And he will advise clients to raise the weighting of stocks
in their portfolios to 80 percent from 75 percent. But, he
acknowledges, big losses in technology might force some to sell
other stocks to cover or offset losses.
</P>
<P>
   Now is not the time to panic, said Jeffrey M. Applegate, chief
U.S. strategist at Lehman Brothers and a longtime stock market
bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not gearing up for Armageddon,'' he said, noting that
Lehman would not depart from routine Monday morning, beginning with
a 7:45 meeting on the market's outlook. At 8:45, the firm's
risk-management committee plans to hold its regular meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Applegate said he did alter his routine on Friday by
sending a note to clients as the Nasdaq was heading to a 9.7
percent decline and the Dow Jones industrial average was losing 5.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them this is not the end of the bull market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Byron R. Wien, U.S. investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, spent the weekend deciding what he would say at Morgan
Stanley's Monday morning strategy session. ``Some of us were
looking for this for a long time,'' he said, alluding to his
longstanding view that the stock market was just too overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to say that the market is much less overvalued than
it was, but that I think that technology has further to go and that
the overall market has farther to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the market's performance Monday, Wien said, would be
whether last week's drastic plunge had finally ``broken the
psychology that every dip is a buying opportunity.'' The sharp
declines of the last several years did not accomplish that, he
acknowledged, since they were followed by significant recoveries.
``But this looks more like the kind of move that could break that
psychology.'' If it does, it will take away a cushion for stocks,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Merrill Lynch, David Bowers, chief investment strategist, and
Richard McCabe, chief market strategist, will join the regular
morning meeting of analysts, according to James Wiggins, a
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins added that Merrill would urge its brokers to ``remind
their clients that the best investment approach is to take a
long-term view and to keep their long-term objectives in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in periods of volatility before,'' he said, ``and
this is the approach we take.''
</P>
<P>
   Abby Joseph Cohen, chief market strategist at Goldman, Sachs,
said on Friday that she was sticking to her modestly bullish
outlook. ``As we look at our expectations for earnings, economic
growth and so on, nothing has changed during the past two weeks,''
she said in an interview on CNBC. Cohen's always careful comments
will be scrutinized because some investors think that she helped
sour the mood in the market.
</P>
<P>
   On March 28, she said she had cut the share of stocks in
Goldman's model portfolio to 65 percent from 70 percent. At the
same time, she said that technology stocks were ``no longer
undervalued.''
</P>
<P>
   In the CNBC interview, Cohen said, ``We are very comfortable
with the mainline technology companies with fabulous product
development, revenue and earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Her comfort, apparently, does not include the dot-coms, which
had led the market higher and are now threatening to pull it even
lower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
