A8533 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     04-16 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAN FRANCISCO IN STONE AND STORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   That unexplained commemorative sculpture next to the Beach
Chalet at San Francisco's Ocean Beach finally got its due Friday
with the unveiling of a plaque identifying it as a tribute to
 &UR; Roald Amundsen &LR; . In 1903, the Norwegian explorer completed his
navigation of the Northwest Passage in a converted herring boat,
ending the trip at Point Bonita, just outside the Golden Gate.
</P>
<P>
   Amundsen's boat remained in Golden Gate Park until 1972, when it
was returned to Norway, along with its identifying label. The
remaining sculpture of the explorer puzzled tourists and park
users, including one who told jogger  &UR; Morris Kadish &LR;  that he
thought it was the image of ``that guy who floated on a raft to
Peru.''
</P>
<P>
   Kadish and his wife,  &UR; Ruth &LR; , enlisted the Art Commission and the
Norwegian Consulate in a campaign for the new plaque, which
features an explanation and map _ drawn by  &UR; Dugald Stermer &LR;  _ of
Amundsen's voyage.
</P>
<P>
   - Petaluma stonemason  &UR; Edwin Hamilton &LR;  used 800-year-old stones
from a monastery brought to the United States by  &UR; William Randolph &LR; 
 &UR; Hearst &LR;  for a new stone wall _ dedicated Thursday _ at the back of
the Strybing Botanical Library's patio garden. Pieces of the
monastery, bought in Spain and brought to San Francisco in the
'20s, lay in various places in Golden Gate Park; the stones for the
wall were in a pile behind the Japanese Tea Garden.
</P>
<P>
   - The San Francisco Neighborhood Parks Council begins monthly
nature hikes through local parks with an Earth Day Victory Nature
Walk at Crissy Field at 9 a.m. Saturday. More information is at
(415) 621-3260.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. It's no longer San Francisco Federal that hosts the
post-earthquake commemoration breakfast (tomorrow); the bank, at
the corner of Post and Kearny, is now California Federal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASKING THE BARD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Shakespeare Company _ whose first production
is ``Shylock'' _ has sent a reminder that April 23, the Bard's
birthday, coincides this year with Easter and the fifth day of
Passover.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings to mind four questions:
</P>
<P>
   1) What about the accomplishments of the Clinton administration?
(``Men's evil manners live in brass; their virtues/ We write in
water,'' says ``Henry VIII.'')
</P>
<P>
   2) What will happen to  &UR; Elian Gonzalez &LR; ? (``Contempt and clamor
will be my knell,'' ``The Winter's Tale'' tells us.)
</P>
<P>
   3) Do the Giants have a chance? (``Our wills and fates do so
contrary run,'' we learn in ``Hamlet.'')
</P>
<P>
   4) Will there be more Krispy Kreme stores in the Bay Area?
(``Sweets grown common lose their dear delight,'' says Sonnet 102.)
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Bea Olarte &LR;  forwards a MacFrugal's ad for the ``Musical
`Last Supper' clock that plays `Hallelujah Course' every hour,''
and wonders if that's referring to dessert? And American Greetings
has sent word of its line of L'Chayim Passover greeting cards,
noting that ``cards referring to the Seder service seem to get the
most laughs.'' Typical big fun: A ``seder plate for the new
millennium'' features tofu-on-a-stick instead of a shank bone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Charlotte Church &LR; , a smooth professional singer at 13, sang
an Earth Day concert with the San Francisco Women's Philharmonic
last week. She took time out to be a kid the next day at the
California Academy of Sciences' ``Earthquake'' and ``Venoms''
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Peter Berg &LR; , who created the just-canceled TV drama
``Wonderland,'' consulted for the show with psychiatrist  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Berger &LR;  of Bellevue Hospital Center in New York. When the two
started working together, says Brill's Content, although Berg had
played a doctor for years on ``Chicago Hope,'' ``Berger was
surprised to discover that ... he apparently didn't know what a
`resident' was.''
</P>
<P>
   - Fair-minded  &UR; Ellen Newman &LR;  notes that while the blue and
yellow Ikea building looks like a ``Go Bears'' symbol, all displays
near the entrance are red and white.
</P>
<P>
   - If you look like a criminal or all-around tough guy, the San
Francisco Opera is looking for you. Auditions are at 6 p.m.
Thursday for prisoner and prison guard supernumeraries _ apparently
hard to find in San Francisco _ for ``Dead Man Walking,''  &UR; Jake
Heggie &LR; 's new opera. Albert Goodwyn, at (415) 565-3200, has more
information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I like my mind right now. I feel like I unscrewed my head and
washed my brain.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Sandra Bullock  &LR; in the Toronto Sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
