<HEADER>
A8537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CRASH-INVESTIGATIONS-     04-16 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-INVESTIGATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR OF PROSECUTION HINDERS CRASH INQUIRIES, SOME SAY
</HEADLINE>
  By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Fear of prosecution or civil liability is stopping
people in transportation industries from cooperating with crash
investigators and making them hesitate to collect data that could
aid safety efforts, senior accident investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors are becoming increasingly likely to get involved
with accident investigations and press charges against people for
violating laws and regulations, safety officials are worried that
the trend may hamper their search for the facts after plane crashes
and other accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a slow but steady and growing presence of the law
enforcement authorities in our investigations,'' James Hall,
chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board, said in an
interview. He said the threat of prosecution was creating difficult
questions.
</P>
<P>
   To sort through the issues of balancing law enforcement and
safety investigations, the board, which investigates accidents and
makes recommendations but does not have enforcement powers, is
organizing a symposium for April 24-25.
</P>
<P>
   In March, after the safety board finished its investigation of
the 1997 cargo plane crash near Miami International Airport that
killed five people, two companies involved, Fine Air Services Inc.
and Aeromar Airlines, pleaded guilty to obstruction of justice.
Fine Air acknowledged that its supervisors had ordered subordinates
to doctor cargo manifests after the crash, and Aeromar acknowledged
that it had erased the tape from a warehouse surveillance camera
and destroyed forms, both of which would have shown what was loaded
on the doomed plane.
</P>
<P>
   Safety board officials said they were glad to see companies
prosecuted for falsifying information. Hall said the threat of
prosecution was a deterrent to those who might flout safety rules.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators were dismayed that in their investigation of a
rupture of a gasoline pipeline in Bellingham, Wash., in June,
officials of the pipeline company, apparently anticipating
indictments, refused to let safety board investigators meet with
company personnel. The fire in that accident killed a man and two
boys.
</P>
<P>
   And in the investigation of the crash of Alaska Airlines Flight
261 off Los Angeles in January, maintenance personnel have arrived
for interviews with lawyers in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Hall emphasizes before each hearing of the safety board that his
agency tries to find cause, not fault. People in the aviation
industry have long contended that the openness needed to gather
information and find out why a plane crashed will disappear if
those concerned think they could be prosecuted or sued for what
they say.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the threat of punishment is essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're seeking to obtain compliance with health and safety
and environmental regulations,'' said Steven P. Solow, chief of the
environmental crimes section of the Justice Department, ``the
government needs to have a range of possible responses to
violations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a continuum of responses,'' said Solow, who is scheduled
to speak at the symposium. ``That includes education, compliance
assistance, administrative and civil enforcement, and it includes
criminal enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Solow helped obtain a guilty plea from American Airlines in
December in a case that grew out of a spill at Miami International
Airport. American pleaded guilty to mishandling hazardous
materials, a felony, and as part of the plea bargain, Solow said,
American agreed to accept recommendations that the safety board
made after a 1988 accident, a cargo hold fire aboard an American
Airlines DC-9.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board's mandate may be to find the cause of an
accident and make recommendations so it does not happen again,
Solow said, but he added that ``if what happened is that people
were making conscious decisions to violate the law, that is part of
the cause.'' And the remedy is prosecution, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem does not only arise after airplane crashes. Trucking
companies, for example, may be avoiding installing monitoring
equipment on their vehicles that would help identify unsafe
conditions, like drivers who work too many hours or drive too fast,
Hall said, because doing so could provide prosecutors or plaintiffs
with damaging evidence later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
