<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8538 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FINANCE-PROTESTS-0417     04-16 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-PROTESTS-0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOSTLY PEACEFUL PROTEST FAILS TO SHUT DOWN WORLD FINANCE
MEETINGS
 &HT;    By BOB DART and ALEC SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defiant hordes of dancing and chanting protesters
blockaded part of the nation's capital Sunday but failed in their
quest to shut down meetings of the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were scattered instances of angry demonstrators
being dispersed by police clubbings, pepper spray and smoke
grenades, the long day of constant confrontation was mostly
peaceable and often festive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't no power like the power of the people 'cause the power
of the people don't stop,'' young protesters sang to an audience of
police in riot gear.
</P>
<P>
   Police reported only about 20 arrests _ far fewer than the more
than 600 taken into custody late Saturday for parading without a
permit.
</P>
<P>
   However, police may face a greater challenge Monday morning when
protestors are scheduled to stage more mass demonstrations as tens
of thousands of federal and other workers return to work in
downtown Washington.
</P>
<P>
   District of Columbia Police Chief Charles Ramsey said that
Molotov cocktails were found in the back pack of one protester who
was arrested Sunday. He also said his officers had dispersed
demonstrators earlier in the day when ``they tried to remove
barrels of gasoline from a construction site'' downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, there were sporadic clashes. One one point,
police on motorcycles drove into a small crowd of protesters who
were blocking part of an intersection. At mid-afternoon, police on
horseback trotted into a crowd that had disrupted traffic and
quickly dispersed the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, some of these same activists _ who range from
environmentalists to anarchists _ clashed with police and smashed
windows at international trade meetings in Seattle. But their mood
was more mellow on this sunny Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've tried to do ... was try to prevent a replication of
what happened out in Seattle,'' said Mayor Anthony Williams on CBS'
Face The Nation. ``I think the vast majority of these demonstrators
want to demonstrate peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Police cordoned off a 50-block section of downtown _ including
the White House, the World Bank and IMF Headquarters _ so the
protesters were unable to achieve their goal of sealing off every
street leading to the financial meetings. With the help of decoy
buses and early arrivals, the world's finance ministers bypassed
the human chains of demonstrators. Authorities did not elaborate on
how the ministers were transported.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meetings are going on, and staff are performing the usual
tasks,'' said IMF spokesman Graham Newman.
</P>
<P>
   But the protesters also claimed victory in focusing national
attention on what they claim are oppressive policies of the
international financial organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Bank and IMF are hiding under the guise of helping
countries while their projects really have an atrocious impact on
both poor people and the environment.'' said Shefali Sharma, a
student from New York. ``More people will know that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Police estimated that there were 10,000 protesters, but they
were spread over a wide area of the city. There were dozens of
marches on the streets and separate protests at every corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every intersection has its own flavor, `` said Patrick
Reinsborough, a spokesman for Mobilization for Global Justice, the
umbrella group for the protestors. ``Unlike most Washington marches
where everyone follows a few leaders, this is a bottom-up movement
with a bunch of creative people using arts and culture to get their
messages out on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the corner of 19th St. and Pennsylvania Ave., near the IMF
and World Bank headquarters and only a few blocks from the White
House, protesters were chained to a huge pink pig labeled ``Greedy,
the World Bank.'' A block away, a trio of women wearing red evening
gowns and matching goggles sang from a communist manifesto. Masked
members of the Revolutionary Anti-Capitalist Bloc, another protest
group, guarded another street. They said they were dressed in black
because ``that's the color of anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere the protesters danced to the beat of drums fashioned
from plastic trash cans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody In. Nobody Out. That's what the line is all about,''
they chanted, referring to their goal of preventing the IMF and
World Bank representatives from entering or leaving their meetings.
With their arms linked inside of plastic pipes, they blocked the
streets with human chains called ``sleeping dragons.'' Webs of
colored strings were stretched between sign posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's Streets? Our Streets,'' they shouted joyously.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasts in clothing on the street corners were stark.
Police were outfitted in riot gear _ helmets, gas masks, protective
black gloves extending up their forearms, shin guards, plastic
handcuffs attached to belts, billy clubs in hand.
</P>
<P>
   To protect against tear gas, many protesters covered their
mouths and noses with bandanas soaked in vinegar, giving them an
image of pungent outlaws. However, as sunshine replaced the early
morning drizzle, the demonstrators shed their goggles, hoods,
jackets and other makeshift protective gear and paraded in tube
tops and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after his forces had arrested about 600 protesters
and shut down their training center, Chief Ramsey chatted with
demonstrators and diffused tension in a couple of situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very, very organized,'' he said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   With the protesters promising to return on Monday, Ramsey urged
commuters to stay away from downtown, which had been left largely
to the demonstrations on a Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping for bigger numbers tomorrow,'' said Kevin
Danaher, a protest organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators are united in their belief that the World Bank
and IMF are destroying the environment and burdening impoverished
countries with crushing debt payments.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the protesters came in all ages, shapes and causes.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Engnoth (CQ) and his 14-year-old daughter, Emily, were
dressed as turtles.
</P>
<P>
   The world trade organizations are destroying the breeding
grounds for turtles, said Engnoth, from nearby Springfield, Va.
</P>
<P>
   And a young California woman who said her name was Monkey Dog
said she was wearing a butterfly costume because ``I want to spread
a little bit of beauty and positive energy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Dart can be reached by e-mail at: bobdart(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Schultz can be reached by e-mail at: alecs(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
