<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-LAND-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE PRESIDENT BACKS SQUATTERS IN LAND DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Overruling his own deputy,
President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe announced Sunday that his
government would not ask black squatters to leave hundreds of
white-owned farms despite escalating political violence this
weekend that left three people dead.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's statement came just three days after Vice President
Joseph Msika announced that the squatters should abandon the farms.
The country's high court had ordered the police last week to evict
the squatters if they would not go peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   But Mugabe, who returned to Zimbabwe on Sunday morning from a
weeklong meeting of third world leaders in Havana, vowed to defy
the court order and distanced himself from Msika. Mugabe described
the farm invasions as ``a problem,'' but said that only his
government could correct it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a problem that can be corrected by the courts,''
said Mugabe, as he addressed cheering supporters in Zimbabwe's
capital, Harare, in remarks that were broadcast on local radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a problem that must be corrected by the government and
the people of Zimbabwe,'' Mugabe said. ``We will correct it, and
correct it in the interest of the people of Zimbabwe.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's comments and Saturday's killings of a white
farmer, the beating of several others who came to his defense, and
the killings of two opposition party members dashed the hopes of
many people in Zimbabwe that tensions would ease after Msika's
announcement last week.
</P>
<P>
   The white farmer, David Stevens, was abducted from his farm in
the Virginia farming area and shot to death, said Tim Henwood, the
president of the Commercial Farmers Union, which represents the
4,000 white farmers who own more than half of Zimbabwe's fertile
land.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition party members, Tihaona Chiminya and Talent
Mabika, were killed as they drove away from a party meeting in the
town of Buhera. The assailants, riding in a truck, hurled a
gasoline bomb into their car, said Nomore Sibanda, a spokesman for
the opposition party, the Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was the first white farmer to be killed since the
squatters started invading white farms in February.
</P>
<P>
   But three other people died in political violence last month,
including a black police officer, who was killed on a farm that
squatters had invaded, and two other black opposition party
members, who died after clashes with government supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, we thought peace and justice was starting to take
hold in this country,'' Sibanda said in a telephone interview from
Harare, referring to the court ruling and the vice president's
decision to urge the farm invaders to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are now wondering which way Zimbabwe will go. The
president is encouraging all of this anarchy. He seems to be
condoning violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition party supports land reform but contends that it
should be accomplished by a means other than land invasions.
</P>
<P>
   The escalating violence comes as Zimbabwe prepares this week to
mark the 20th anniversary of its independence from the white-led
government of what was then known as Rhodesia.
</P>
<P>
   And the government's about-face on the farm invasion issue seems
to suggest that this year's Independence Day will be marred by
continued divisions within the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   Some party members have already voiced concern about the land
invasions and the international outcry that followed. And in
February, some members even suggested that Mugabe announce plans to
retire at the end of his term, in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe dismissed that suggestion, which came after voters handed
him his first major defeat, rejecting a draft constitution that
would have expanded his powers and allowed the government to take
white-owned land without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Mugabe revived the land issue in an effort, political
analysts say, to win rural votes in the upcoming elections for
Parliament, which are scheduled for May. In recent weeks, Mugabe
has blamed whites for the slow pace of land redistribution, even
though his own government is partly responsible for the slowdown in
the program.
</P>
<P>
   He has vigorously supported the squatters, who have invaded more
than 1,000 white-owned farms, appealing an order last month by a
lower court requiring their eviction. And he persuaded Parliament
to pass a constitutional amendment that for the first time would
allow the government to seize land without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Msika mentioned that constitutional amendment, which was passed
earlier this month, in his statement last Thursday when he told the
squatters that their presence on white farms was no longer
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   He also mentioned the upcoming talks with the British,
Zimbabwe's former colonial rulers, who say they are willing to
finance land reform if Zimbabwe promises that land will not end up
in the hands of government officials, as it has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Msika had also sent a team of three government ministers to
address the squatters to make sure the new message was clear.
</P>
<P>
   George Charamba, a spokesman for Mugabe, said Sunday that those
ministers were still talking to the farm invaders. But he said the
high court, which ordered the police to evict the squatters last
Thursday, had no right to meddle in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   He said Mugabe had decided that the squatters should stay put
until he can actually sign the constitutional change into law
sometime in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until that has happened there's no point in asking the war
veterans to leave,'' said Charamba in a telephone interview from
Harare, referring to the squatters, who are led by veterans of
Zimbabwe's guerrilla struggle for independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no demonstration which lasts forever,'' Charamba said.
``At some point, the war veterans will leave. What we are differing
on is the method. What the president rejects is the option of
having to send arms of force against the war veterans. That option
is out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
