<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXDAY-OPTIONS0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clock ticks for procrastinating tax filers
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last-minute filers can run into all kinds of
calamities.
</P>
<P>
   But most of them boil down to two problems: Running out of time
or running out of money.
</P>
<P>
   There are alternatives. They may not be attractive, but they
will get the harried taxpayer through the night.
</P>
<P>
   NOT ENOUGH TIME
</P>
<P>
   Some taxpayers discover they don't have all the paperwork they
need. Others find out just how much time it takes to fill out the
forms.
</P>
<P>
   For the basic Form 1040, the IRS estimates the average taxpayer
will need 2 hours and 39 minutes to learn what to do and another 6
hours and 22 minutes to fill out the form.
</P>
<P>
   If you just can't finish, you can get an automatic four-month
extension, until Aug. 15, by filing Form 4868 before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   You won't be alone. The IRS expects 8 million taxpayers to ask
for an extension.
</P>
<P>
   You can get a copy of the form at the IRS Web site, www.irs.gov.
Click on ``Forms and Pubs,'' then click on Search for a Form or
Publication.
</P>
<P>
   But note that the extension covers only the paperwork, not the
tax bill itself. You can estimate how much you will owe and send in
a check with the Form 4868. But you will have to pay interest, and
maybe a late-payment penalty, on any amount you still owe after
April 17.
</P>
<P>
   NOT ENOUGH MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the average balance due was about $3,000. If you
can't raise that much cash, you have three alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   1. An installment plan. The IRS generally accepts installment
payments, assuming you owe less than $25,000 and submit a plan to
pay your bill in less than five years.
</P>
<P>
   You request an installment plan by filling out Form 9465 and
attaching it to the front of your tax return. You can download a
copy from the IRS Web site.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to pay interest and a late-payment penalty on the
unpaid balance.
</P>
<P>
   If you are already making payments under an installment plan,
you won't be eligible for a second installment plan.
</P>
<P>
   2. Charging it. To pay your taxes with a credit card, call
1-888-272-9829 and follow the directions. You can use American
Express, Discover or MasterCard, but not Visa.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to pay a fee to the company that processes the
payments. The fee varies with the amount you owe. It is $25, for
example, for a charge of $600 to $999.
</P>
<P>
   3. Leaving it to the IRS. Some taxpayers can put off the payment
by asking the IRS to figure how much tax they owe.
</P>
<P>
   The details are in Publication 967, available at the IRS Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS will send you a bill. If you pay it within 30 days, you
avoid interest and late-payment penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
