</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-FOOD-ART-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIAN HUNGER: ANOTHER DISASTER AHEAD? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GODE, Ethiopia _ The truly hungry are still the exception, but
that makes little difference here. On Sunday morning, a 2-year-old
boy named Abdi Muhammad Farah died. An old woman covered a hole in
the hut with a dirty pair of pants so the other children could not
peek in as they washed his body. He was very thin, so there was not
much to wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be off!'' another woman shouted at the children. They
scattered, but only for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   Abdi is the fourth child of Muhammad Farah _ who has 10
children, by two wives _ to have died in the last three months here
in the hot southeastern corner of Ethiopia, where once again
chronic poverty and the worst drought to hit the Horn of Africa in
nearly two decades have combined to create hunger, and war has
hampered its solution. Ethiopia's leaders argue that lives might
have been saved if the outside world had been quicker to help.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is calling it a famine yet. And what has already
happened here, everyone hopes, will be as bad as it gets, though
there are no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days the world's rich nations have pledged what
experts say should be enough food to stave off a far greater
disaster: At least 8 million people in Ethiopia face a shortage of
food _ the same number affected in the famine of the mid-1980s that
killed thousands. Another 6 to 8 million in neighboring countries _
Eritrea, Somalia, Sudan, Djibouti, Kenya and Uganda _ also face
hunger.
</P>
<P>
   But much could still go wrong: The next rains may be inadequate.
Relief food may not arrive on time. The war between Ethiopia and
Eritrea may ignite again. So relief officials are urging a
worldwide effort to keep Ethiopia well stocked with food, rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a big problem,'' said Catherine Bertini, head of
the World Food Program and a U.N. envoy to the Horn of Africa. ``We
want to make sure it is not a big problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does need to be done very quickly,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Famine announces itself long before fully arriving, in small
pockets that foretell greater disaster and, when local governments
and the rest of the world are engaged, with enough time to prevent
it. The area around Gode, 750 miles southeast of Addis Ababa, the
capital, is where the messengers of widespread hunger made their
first call.
</P>
<P>
   It has not rained here in three years, but the problems reached
the point of crisis only recently. According to local authorities,
more than 200 people have died of malnutrition in the last three
months around this town, which is dusty and scattered with the
carcasses of hundreds of cows and sheep. Another 500 have died from
conditions related to hunger, such as pneumonia, diarrhea or
measles. Almost all the dead are children, the first to fall sick
without food.
</P>
<P>
   Abdi Ali is 1 year old, so thin and weak that he can barely push
out a cry; what happened to him and his family tells the story of
many people here. Like most others in the Ogaden region of
Ethiopia, his family are nomads of Somali origin who depend on
cows, goats and camels for food and milk.
</P>
<P>
   Abdi's mother, Hani, a 30-year-old mother of six, said their
family's 200 goats and 60 cattle began to die late last year for
lack of water and grazing land. When the last died, in January, the
family walked to the town of Denan, about 50 kilometers north of
here.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are 6,000 refugees here, and another 15,000 in Gode.
Abdi was fine when they arrived, his mother said, but since then he
has slowly withered for lack of food. His top front teeth are just
coming in, but otherwise he is not growing but shrinking inside his
ever-baggier skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had cattle, he was drinking milk,'' she said. ``Now we
have no cattle, and he has no milk.''
</P>
<P>
   While children have been the hardest hit, adults are suffering
too. Four days earlier, Mariama Mose, 35, stopped speaking, and on
Saturday she lay staring up at the top of their hut in Denan. One
of her nine children, a 1-year-old boy, Wali Abdi, died last month.
Her husband, Abdi Sheik Hussein, said she had not eaten for many
days and he did not know if she would live. ``Only Allah knows,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the huts, there were the mounds of at least 250 graves,
some small ones for children; most were covered with thorn bushes
to keep away the hyenas and foxes, who were as hungry as the
people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There has been much contention between Ethiopia and other
nations about whether its government has done enough to help the
starving people. Most of the focus has been on the money spent on
Ethiopia's two-year war with its neighbor, Eritrea, which experts
say cost roughly $1 million a day. Because of the war, Ethiopia has
refused an offer to use the port of Assab in Eritrea, which U.N.
officials say would speed the delivery of relief food.
</P>
<P>
   But here the government did deliver food, most of it wheat, in
January, February and early March, said Muhammad Ugas, the area
manager for a local charity group, the Ogaden Welfare Society,
which has headed the relief effort here. But it was not enough, he
said, and there were no international groups to help.
</P>
<P>
   By late February, the crisis had intensified, and the Ogaden
Welfare Society, along with Save the Children, an international
charity group, opened the first feeding center in Gode for the
worst cases of malnutrition. By Sunday, 280 children had been
treated; 28 of them, or 10 percent, died. The last one was Abdi
Muhammad Farah, who was buried Sunday afternoon in a grave next to
his sister's.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Ethiopia has been criticized, its leaders have harshly
condemned the outside world for not reacting fast enough,
particularly after an assessment in December showed that 7.8
million people were facing food shortages. The United States
responded with large donations of food in January, but Ethiopian
officials criticized the European Union for not making a definite
pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Harbo, the European Union's delegate in Ethiopia, strongly
denied that it had delayed, saying that it had begun to buy food
inside Ethiopia in February but backed off after the government
said there was little food to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the European Union did commit last week to 430,000
tons of food by the end of the year _ just as Bertini began her
visit to the region and the world's news media beamed out images of
the people around Gode who had begun to starve.
</P>
<P>
   Bertini and many other Western officials say they believe that
the outside world did react promptly _ at least before the severe
food shortages moved into actual famine not only here but in the
highlands in northern Ethiopia, which are also suffering from
drought. ``It's not because there has been a slow response,'' she
said. ``It is because there are more people to feed.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of her trip, Ethiopia's prime minister, Meles Zenawi,
who had strongly criticized the West, said he too was satisfied.
``Now all the indications are that the food aid which will avert
disaster may be forthcoming,'' he said in a news conference last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Just as famine follows a more or less predictable cycle, so does
the institutional strategy for overcoming it. Bertini's trip was
meant to spur the outside world to action. Coming as it did when
people here began to die, her appeal seems to have brought results:
Aid groups are coming slowly but in greater numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, any comparison to the 1984 famine is premature. Dr. J.W.
Lee, the medical representative on Bertini's trip, noted that most
of the deaths in the Gode region were not from hunger specifically.
Although the people need food, he said, many are in greater need of
medicine, clean water and vaccinations. ``The situation is
precarious, but it's not catastrophic,'' Lee said. ``A lot of
people are talking about this from television images and sound
bites, not data.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear, though, is that it could get worse. The major worry,
officials say, is that there will not be enough rain this summer.
Moreover, the food pledged so far will feed Ethiopia only through
June, World Food Program officials say.
</P>
<P>
   With a lag of two to five months between a nation's pledge of
food and the actual delivery _ over terrible roads and through
inadequate ports _ the concern is how to keep what aid officials
call the ``food pipeline'' full.
</P>
<P>
   ``The promise is adequate,'' said Ugas, of the Ogaden Welfare
Society. ``It depends on how quick and urgently it reaches here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
