<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last call for tax filers
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At last count, 50 million Americans had yet to file
their income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight they'll have to get serious. The deadline for filing
federal and Georgia tax returns is midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Post offices will stay open until then to accommodate
last-minute filers.
</P>
<P>
   Free help in filling out the forms is available this year, as
the Internal Revenue Service continues its struggle to become a
partner with taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   IRS employees will be stationed at Kroger stores to help with
the paperwork. A spokesman warned that last-minute crowding would
limit how much the volunteers can do for any individual.
</P>
<P>
   As of April 8, IRS employees had helped 47,638 Georgians prepare
their returns.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, a total of 127.5 million returns are expected. About
half of them will be filled in by certified public accountants and
other paid professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Do-it-yourselfers can file online, using low-cost software.
Three of the most popular sites are www.hrblock.com,
www.turbotax.com or www.macintax.com.
</P>
<P>
   Deferring tax returns until the last minute is an American
tradition, only partly because of procrastination. ``Some people
are put off by the perceived complexity of the tax law,'' said Al
Brooke, a former Georgia director of the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Others delay because they owe more taxes. ``The returns that
taxpayers are going to attach a check to _ they tend to come in
later,'' Brooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
