<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-8     04-16 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-885&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK FOCUSES AGAIN ON PEACE WITH PALESTINIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Last week, with Syrian peace talks in a deep stall,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel cleared his desk of Damascus,
unfroze construction on the Golan Heights and swiveled his focus to
the impending deadlines on the Palestinian peace track.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he began a new week with declarations intended to
prepare Israelis for potential concessions to the Palestinians and
to alert the Palestinians to his increased concentration on their
peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Barak indicated that he would be offering a few sweeteners to
break the ice with the Palestinians, who have felt insulted and
neglected by Barak's nearly exclusive focus on Syria. He said he
might tender them immediate gains _ recognition of a Palestinian
state and a ``down payment'' on a future transfer of land _ if the
two sides reached a ``framework'' final peace agreement by the end
of May.
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged publicly, for the first time, that Israel would
not seek to annex the Arab villages near Jerusalem. The right wing
has tried to portray Israeli withdrawal from those towns as a
concession that would endanger Jerusalem itself. On Sunday, Barak,
clarifying a position that he had left artfully unclear, told his
Cabinet that those villages were not important to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always prayed toward Jerusalem and have never directed
any prayer toward el Azariyya and Abu Dis,'' Barak said Sunday,
mentioning two of the Palestinian villages. ``The annexation of
those 50,000 to 70,000 Palestinians serves neither the security nor
any other national interest of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leaders did not respond directly to Barak's
gestures. But they dismissed them generally as ``trial balloons''
and pointed out what they were not hearing: a readiness to withdraw
from all of the West Bank, to dismantle Israeli settlements, to
acknowledge the right of return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian state is a Palestinian right that already has
international support,'' said Nabil Abu Rudeineh, an adviser to
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian Authority's president. ``What we
demand of the Israelis is to be committed to the deadlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak did not specify whether the Jerusalem area towns would be
turned over to the Palestinians as a ``down payment'' with the May
framework agreement. At any rate, the next land transfer _ which
could entail from 10 percent to 12 percent of the West Bank _ is
supposed to take place in June.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Barak emphasized on Sunday that he intended to
transfer territory in a way that would allow the Palestinians to
have a continuous land mass, and not disconnected islands of
sovereignty. That would require abandoning some Jewish settlements,
although Barak did not say this explicitly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is portraying these feelings to the other side, the
Palestinians, saying he's willing to pay a price,'' said Yossi
Beilin, the justice minister. ``The question is whether this price
is big enough.''
</P>
<P>
   By revealing what he would be willing to give, Barak is seeking
to nudge the Palestinians out of a stalemate on the core issues
that divide the two sides and to improve the chances that the May
deadline _ unlike past deadlines _ will be met. The final
comprehensive deal is supposed to be concluded by September.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel and the Palestinian Authority, some politicians are
saying the final deal cannot be completed and are advising their
leaders to resolve some issues, put aside the thorny question of
Jerusalem's future status and settle on another long-term interim
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we can bridge the gap on all the issues but
Jerusalem,'' said Haim Ramon, the Israeli minister who oversees the
Jerusalem issue. ``It would be very clever of both sides to agree
not to agree and delay this issue for the future, maybe five or 10
years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Others disagree strongly. ``That would be the biggest mistake on
earth,'' Beilin said. ``What is needed is for both sides to touch
the fire, to say, `This is the compromise, this is the peace.' For
that, we need but two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is to travel to Washington this week to meet with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has just returned. The Americans are deeply and directly
involved in the substance of the negotiations for the first time
since Barak took office in July, an indication that he has given up
his original ambition to forgo direct U.S. involvement. U.S.
mediators are preparing proposals to bridge the gaps between the
two sides, Barak told the Cabinet on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot be said that Barak lingers in the doldrums when his
plans fall through. Last week, his ambitious hopes of making peace
with Syria were essentially _ but not explicitly _ pronounced dead,
and along with them the grand blueprint for a new Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``While everyone is recovering from the shock and grieving over
the deceased, the prime minister has already gotten up from the
mourning period, moved on from page one to page two, activated the
switch in his brain, changed channels, and zapped to the
Palestinians,'' Chemi Shalev wrote in his column in the newspaper
Maariv. ``The same way he totally immersed himself in the Syrian
issue, he will now immerse himself in the Palestinian issue. Barak
is a person with a single goal, and the present project is Yasser
Arafat.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the stillbirth of the Syrian peace deal seems to open the
way to progress on the Palestinian track, it is not so simple. Some
think that it will complicate dealings with the Palestinians,
speculating that Arafat will not want to make concessions after
President Hafez Assad of Syria stood firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian experience certainly affects the road ahead with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Critics here say Barak at once overestimated and underestimated
Assad, gambling that he was so hungry for a deal that he would
suddenly turn malleable. In retrospect, the critics say that Barak
may have mishandled the negotiations in Shepherdstown, W.Va., in
January, embarrassing the Syrians into a harder line.
</P>
<P>
   Arab-world critics also saw a failure by Barak _ a failure of
nerve and a political weakness that held him back from making the
key concession that would allow the momentous peace deal of his
aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   If he were a stronger leader, they said, he would have found a
way to compromise on the sliver of territory _ along the northern
rim of the Sea of Galilee _ that lies between continued conflict
and peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and many others here portray it differently. He is not a
magician, his advisers say. He went with Syria as far as he could,
taking a variety of creative concessions to the table. Even the
Americans believe that the ball was left in Syria's court, they
say.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, said Gadi Baltiansky, Barak's spokesman, even an
impasse is ``a historic accomplishment.'' Previous negotiations
with Syria were interrupted _ first by the assassination of Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, and then by a wave of terrorism under his
successor, Shimon Peres. This time, Baltiansky said, Israel will
have learned how far Assad is willing to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
