<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-DAY2-0417-C     04-16 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-DAY2-0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talk cheap to Claridge, who just wants to play
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Upon listening to Travis Claridge, the first
inclination is to worry that he might be an oddball similar to
another famed Southern Cal football player.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Marinovich, the former Trojans quarterback, was talented
but aimless, at least when he got to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Claridge, the Falcons' first selection in the draft Saturday,
likewise seems to be polished at giving ambiguous, meandering, even
disinterested answers.
</P>
<P>
   But the more Claridge talks, which apparently is never much, the
more obvious it is that he speaks with a unique conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood grows that he's not a man lacking answers as much
as he happens to have a very simple agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to play,'' he said Sunday, when the Falcons
trotted out the 6-foot-5, 305-pound offensive lineman for his first
news conference. ``I just like playing football. Football has
always been a real constant thing in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his strengths, his weaknesses and so on, Claridge
said, ``I don't know'' at least half a dozen times after the
Falcons picked him in the second round, 37th overall.
</P>
<P>
   But one look at him, with his broad shoulders, high cheekbones
and buzz haircut, and Claridge looks every bit like a football
player from years past, before image meant so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never sat on the bench before in my life,'' he said,
explaining that the three hours of sleep he got on the red-eye
flight Saturday night from Los Angeles was the most he got in two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nerves. Everything you have worked for your whole life.
Everything you ever dreamed of playing was professional football.
It was judgment day.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves fell in love with the simplicity and
mean streak in Claridge. The fact he's a two-time, first-team
Pac-10 selection is a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travis is impressive to me because it is important to him,''
said Reeves, who will give Claridge an opportunity to compete with
Ephraim Salaam for the starting job at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not all about money. It is about loving to play the
game. It excites me to listen to Travis talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Claridge's ability to move from right guard to right tackle as a
senior and then be named the most outstanding offensive lineman in
the Pac-10 was icing on the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Toughness?
</P>
<P>
   He was a starter at USC less than two weeks after arriving on
campus. He has required two shoulder surgeries and an ankle
surgery, but played through the injuries and had the operations
after seasons ended.
</P>
<P>
   He did something no Trojans offensive lineman _ not Anthony
Munoz or Tony Boselli _ has ever done. He started every game of his
USC career, beginning as a true freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first game, in the Kickoff Classic against Penn State,''
he said, ``the center had to tell me what to do every play because
I just got there.''
</P>
<P>
   So how did he end up a starter?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was better,'' he said. ``I came into camp in shape, and I
wanted to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Claridge has a reputation for strength, bench-pressing 225
pounds 29 times.
</P>
<P>
   He's definitely candid. He wrote a couple of diaries for
FoxSports.com. On-line last week, he ripped the concept of mock
drafts.
</P>
<P>
   Check out this entry: ``What really upsets me are the `in-depth'
evaluations that are on these (Web) sites. I can run a 4.86-second
40-yard dash, vertical jump 35.5 inches and out-lift a bunch of
guys, and the next week I'm reading that, `Travis Claridge lacks
athleticism.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding me?''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he said, ``Hardly any of those mock drafts came true,
did they?''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, he wrote for Fox- Sports.com again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised I wouldn't watch the draft. I didn't lie. I refused
to sit there and listen to a bunch of guys who think they are
experts, but who really don't know anything ... because they never
played the game. Instead, a few of my friends and I ... played
video games, mostly NCAA 2000. Don't worry, I never played with
USC.''
</P>
<P>
   Claridge began his journey to this point long ago, living in
Michigan, where his father was a high school football coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played Pop Warner football,'' he said. ``I only played one
year because I couldn't make the weight limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Next came a divorce, then a move to California, and then a move
to Vancouver, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   His nickname of ``Trapper'' came from an eighth-grade coach who
lauded him for sacking quarterbacks while playing defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Claridge is engaged to be married, and his brother, Ryan, is a
linebacker at UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Claridge is a pro football player who is still working to
earn a college degree. He took a 4:10 p.m. flight back to Los
Angeles Sunday to finish work on a history major with a geography
minor.
</P>
<P>
   He's not worried that his answers are bland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' he said. ``I'm 22 years old and
I've just been thrown into professional football. It's like, OK,
what do I do now? The strangest thing is that I'm sitting here
talking to you. I just want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
