<SLUG> BC-VICTIMS-SHIRTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW ORLEANS, MOURNERS WEAR THEIR TRIBUTES ON T-SHORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., eliminated earlier, this story is now restored) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Most of the people who gathered for Donald Ray
Davis' funeral were dressed in their Sunday best. But younger
mourners, like Tara Lewis, 21, wore matching white T-shirts printed
with a picture on the front of Davis, 25, who died in a motorcycle
accident last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're young,'' Lewis said Sunday, ``and we're not used to all
that dressing up and stuff. Wearing the T-shirt helps us remember
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In this city where rituals surrounding the dead are often more
plentiful and more elaborate than anywhere else, the T-shirts,
sometimes called ``dead man shirts,'' have become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   The shirts, which commemorate the lives of young murder victims
who often have died in gang-related killings, are especially
popular with younger blacks, and began to be seen here in the late
1980s. By 1994, when New Orleans had one of the highest murder
rates in the country, the shirts had become ubiquitous here and
have since become popular in other cities as well, like
Philadelphia and Detroit. Today, when the murder rate in New
Orleans has dropped substantially, by 55 percent since 1994, many
say the shirts are even more popular here.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we would see the T-shirts only when young people were
killed,'' said the Rev. Norwood Thompson, pastor of the First Zion
Baptist Church in New Orleans. ``Now it has escalated into a kind
of tradition and you can see T-shirts when anyone dies, it's almost
like an obituary.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Rhodes, owner of Rhodes Funeral Home, said, ``The
T-shirts have become a part of African American culture in New
Orleans. Each step of the way, the time people take to prepare for
a funeral helps them let the person go. The T-shirt is now often
one of those steps.''
</P>
<P>
   The shirts are designed and made at shops like Video Images on
the east side of the city, where Ricky Lewis, 44, has been
producing the memorial shirts since 1989. Lewis also used to make
buttons and bandannas to match the shirts. But now, solely making
the shirts is keeping him in business.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis stores the template design for his shirts in his computer.
It includes space above and under the picture of the deceased for
song lyrics or other sayings, like ``Thuggin Eternally'' or ``The
Wrong Man Died.'' The name or nickname goes at the bottom of the
shirt along with a gravestone that says ``RIP'' and the words,
``sunrise'' and ``sunset,'' accompanied by the birth and death
dates.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Wiltz, a professor of sociology at Dillard University in New
Orleans said: ``The whole notion of the dead man T-shirt might have
gotten its impetus in rap music. Because there is a tendency in rap
to sanctify the deceased and make them almost bigger in death than
they were in life. The shirt is a way of expressing that in
something tangible.''
</P>
<P>
   The shirts are so popular they have figure in the lyrics of rap
artists in New Orleans. Master P, perhaps the city's most famous
rapper, mentioned the shirts in his song ``Is There a Heaven 4 a
Gangsta.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has hopped on the trend. Thelma Washington, 55, a
nursing assistant, said her family chose not to make T-shirts when
her cousin, who she said was a major drug dealer, died. ``I don't
approve of the shirts,'' she said, ``because of where they came
from. It started with gang members, I wouldn't want to accept
anything coming out of that world. I don't see the point of wearing
the T-shirts. It doesn't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis recently moved his T-shirt business into a new building.
On Friday morning, he and his son, Torrey, 21, were unpacking. As
they sifted through hundreds of shirts and buttons with faces and
dates and names of dead people on them, Lewis was remembering the
details behind his collection's morbid chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drive-by. Drive-by,'' he said, placing two buttons on a
display case. Holding up a third button with the picture of a
smiling toddler on it, he said, ``This was a three-year-old kid,
killed in a drive-by.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the picture of another teen-ager on a memorial
T-shirt from a few years ago, Lewis said, ``He was real bad. He
killed a lot of people, and they finally got him.''
</P>
<P>
   One T-shirt showed a young man in his coffin with his mouth sewn
open to display his gold teeth. Another T-shirt of a dead teen-ager
showed him holding his AK-47 and smiling.
</P>
<P>
   But those were the most extreme examples. Just as common now are
T-shirts like the one commemorating the death of Davis, who was a
barge cleaner in New Orleans, and by all accounts had no gang ties.
</P>
<P>
   For Tara Lewis, wearing Davis' shirt this morning was nothing
new. She said she had 16 other dead men shirts at home,
memorializing friends and family. She always wears them to
funerals, she said, but also puts them on whenever she wants to
keep her memories of the person on the shirt alive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, ``It makes me sad, every time I wear one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
