<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mulholland's win gives Braves warm feeling
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Once their hands thawed from the 19-degree wind
chill Sunday, the Braves could start scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Which to be more pleased about _ leaving the frigid Midwest or
finally getting a quality game from No. 4 starter Terry Mulholland?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves headed home to the warmer climate of Atlanta after
Mulholland's best start since being traded from the Cubs last July
31. It followed his two worst, and it helped the Braves salvage a
2-1 victory and finish the road trip with a 2-4 record. ``It was
bigger for me to pick up a win for the team (than for myself),
being able to leave Milwaukee on a winning note,'' said Mulholland,
who allowed one run in eight innings after giving up 13 runs and
six home runs in 8 1/3 innings in his first two starts. ``You want
to keep things rolling in a positive direction. That was the
biggest thing for me, coming in and giving us a chance to win the
ballgame and go home happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The game turned into a shocker of a pitching duel with
Mulholland taking on his recently released former teammate Everett
Stull, the Fort Riley, Ga., native who was making his first
major-league start. The Braves scrambled to get just two unearned
runs off him.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez got the clutch hit, lining a single past Mark Loretta
to score Andres Galarraga in the fourth inning. It was the
difference in the game. In a similar situation in Saturday's loss,
Lopez grounded into a double play to Loretta.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves made the 2-1 lead stand up for the next five innings,
with Mike Remlinger working the ninth to earn his third save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly, but we'll take it right now,'' said Chipper
Jones, who went 1-for-4 in his return to the lineup from a sore
elbow. ``Terry did a great job of not letting them get anything
going. We still stink offensively, but we'll get better.''
</P>
<P>
   After unsuccessful outings against the Giants and the Cubs,
Mulholland switched tactics against the Brewers, not going after
every hitter inside. How well did it work? If it weren't for a
bobble by Galarraga that cost him an inning-ending double play in
the third inning, Mulholland would have allowed no runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty drastic change,'' Mulholland said. ``(When I
came inside) it was more for effect, more as a reminder. ''
</P>
<P>
   Stull, meanwhile, allowed only three singles over six innings
but had to settle for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling he would match up well against the Braves, and
he did,'' Brewers manager Davey Lopes said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
