<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-HAVANA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HAVANA, CONFLICTING EMOTIONS OVER CUBAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
  By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Elian Gonzalez was not only shipwrecked but kidnapped,
in the official point of view here, which was on display in all its
revolutionary fervor during the weekend at a demonstration by
thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a downpour, protesters of all ages brandished Cuban
flags, danced, sang and spoke, with a sixth-grader, Yisel
Viamontes, taking on the question on many minds in the United
States and to some degree here as well. Would Elian have a better
life here or there?
</P>
<P>
   ``They say he could be a millionaire there,'' Yisel shouted from
the stage at a rally Saturday night in Las Tunas, 400 miles
southeast of here. ``Here he will be a millionaire, but with
millions much different than over there, with more dignified
millions. Here he has millions of brothers and sisters and friends
and classmates.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian is certainly a cause celebre here _ the 39th anniversary
of President Fidel Castro's proclamation of a socialist state
perhaps has added to the ferment _ but in everyday conversation
people do not speak about the case as much with revolutionary
passion as with apparently conflicting emotions.
</P>
<P>
   In the markets, squares and bustling streets of this capital _
its late 1950s cars and colonial buildings a backdrop both dreary
and charming _ the latest twists and turns in the case have
provoked a range of reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans acknowledge feeling frustration and confusion over the
American justice system, puzzled that one judge may rule one way
and another judge another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that has happened in the courts, it's very bureaucratic
and hard to understand,'' said Fernando Suarez, an engineer who,
like many professionals here weathering hard economic times,
supplements his income by selling books at a market. ``Can you
explain to me why not even the attorney general could take the boy
out of the house in Miami?'' Suarez asked about Attorney General
Janet Reno's failure last week to obtain the transfer of Elian from
his great-uncle to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Silvia Romay, 35, another vendor who is an engineer, said she
could relate to the case because her father left Cuba in 1980
during the Mariel boatlift in which 125,000 Cubans left for Florida
in a matter of months. Romay's father, with whom she has sporadic
contact, lives in New York City but she prefers to stay in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be separated from your parent,'' Romay said.
``The situation is so politicized now. Elian is just an instrument
for all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Hernandez, a construction worker, said the more time the
boy spends out of Cuba the more likely he will become a national
hero, ``although I do not know that he should be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just a boy who by chance ended up in the United States
and, sooner or later, will come back and go on,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials have said there are no plans to parade the boy
when he returns, and few people doubt the case will end with Elian
living anywhere but in Cuba. Celebratory rallies welcoming him
back, however, seem inevitable, and a huge plaza was recently
completed on the grand Malecon, the famous seaside drive in Havana,
near the United States Interests Section.
</P>
<P>
   Some may celebrate reluctantly, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   For all the sympathy there may be for Elian's father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, there is also understanding of Elian's mother,
Elizabet Brotons, who took the boy with her on her fatal boat trip
to Florida. Those who say they understood why she took such a
drastic move mention the lure of bountiful, higher-paying jobs in
the United States and freedom merely 90 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, he made it out and that is where he may
belong,'' said a 24-year-old student who said he had thought about
rafting to Florida but feared drowning. ``Do you know how many
people would like to switch places with him?''
</P>
<P>
   Another man, a musician, referred to the increasingly prominent
``Liberan a Elian'' _ free Elian _ placards on display around town.
`` `Free Elian' has two meanings, you know,'' the musician said.
``There are people here who believe now he is free.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone here, despite the impression in much of the United
States, is clamoring to cobble together a raft and flee. Many here
appear to believe that the United States' economic embargo, now 40
years old, will ultimately end, opening the way to better economic
times.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, who has become closely involved in the Elian case, has
not addressed the subject in recent days. Castro was the host of a
summit meeting of third world leaders that ended here on Friday
night. Sunday he was concluding talks with President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika of Algeria, who extended his stay after the summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But the case did not escape the notice of some foreign leaders
here for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be happy, as will the Venezuelan people, the day that
child again breathes Cuban air and sets foot on this heroic Cuban
soil,'' said President Hugo Chavez of Venezuela, whose hard-line
policies on the rich, affinity for military greens and criticism of
the United States have drawn comparisons to Castro.
</P>
<P>
   State-controlled media outlets like Granma, the official
newspaper of the Communist Party, provide a daily dose of
full-blown Elian news from the official standpoint. And for two
hours every afternoon Cuban television broadcasts round-table
discussions on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Said the moderator on Friday evening: ``Indignant and combative,
we continue the fight for a boy who is all the children of the
world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
