<SLUG> BC-GORE-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HAS AWKWARD MOMENTS IN REAPPEARANCE WITH CLINTON AT
FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ The sweet scent of jasmine wafted up the
leafy hillsides, the lights of Los Angeles twinkled below, and the
cash register cachinged until it was stuffed with $2.8 million. The
Bill and Al Show reopened Saturday night, a star-studded gala under
the baton of the DreamWorks SKG trio, after being dark for five
months.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Vice President Al Gore has wrapped up the Democratic
nomination for president, his campaign has deemed it safe for him
to start reappearing with President Clinton. Wearing light brown
sports jackets and open-necked polo shirts, they ventured out
together for the first in a series of joint appearances to raise
money for the Democratic National Committee. (The show goes to New
York on April 24.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore is naturally relying on the successes of the Clinton
administration to sweep him into office. As he told his audience
here, the nation's prosperity is ``the wind at my back.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has also been campaigning at a slight distance from the
impeached president. And on Saturday night, Gore seemed still not
have resolved his feelings toward him.
</P>
<P>
   On the slate patio of the fortresslike Greystone manor, with
amber lanterns slung from overhanging branches and stars like Jimmy
Smits, Whoopi Goldberg, Kevin Spacey, Antonio Banderas, Melanie
Griffith and Jay Leno listening, an odd ambivalence toward the
president emerged in Gore's remarks. In trying to praise Clinton,
Gore seemed to give him the back of his hand.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he wanted to say that the president was a man of
big ideas. But he introduced that thought this way: ``Of all the
criticisms of President Clinton that I've heard, the one that rings
the most hollow is that he has pushed small ideas, little
proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said the job of president was so difficult, Clinton
had nearly snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the good things I could say about President Clinton _ I
could tell you about the many, many times when I have seen him,
especially in the early years, nearly buckle under the pressure of
his office but never do so,'' Gore said. He paused here at length,
as if surprised by what he had just said and wondering how to
smooth it over.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I say this,'' he began anew, ``I don't want to pretend that
I know how heavy his burdens have been because there is no other
position like the one that he has held on our behalf. But I've been
close enough to it to see first-hand that those burdens are very
heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience was full of people infatuated with Clinton, and
they seemed a bit relieved when their man took the stage. He was
casual and charming and had them laughing almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   He played off a reference that Gore had made in which he
disparaged one of Hollywood's biggest flops, the $35-million 1986
disaster ``Howard the Duck.'' Noting that the news media was always
``obsessively'' seeking differences between Gore and Clinton,
Clinton said: ``I liked `Howard the Duck,''' bringing chuckles from
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Jokes aside, the buzz was whether Gore could ever live up to the
Hollywood-friendly standards set by Clinton, a natural performer
and movie junkie. (As one production executive said of Clinton:
``He is into the creative process.'')
</P>
<P>
   So far, Gore is doing just fine in the cash department. There
was an assumption that the vice president, because of his high-tech
proclivities and because DreamWorks is leaving the money-raising
field, might find Silicon Valley more lucrative. And on Friday
night, he raised an eye-popping $2.6 million from 70 venture
capitalists at the Silicon Valley home of Joel Hyatt, a party
fund-raiser and successful entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday night's Hollywood haul brought in $2.8 million from
100 people who paid at least $25,000 a couple _ more than any
recent event for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And in California, Gore appears ahead of Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, the likely Republican nominee. The latest Field survey put
Gore 10 points ahead, prompting speculation that Bush may be unable
to wage a serious contest here.
</P>
<P>
   That is essential in raising money. A top Democratic fund-raiser
put it this way: ``You have a tough act to follow with Clinton. But
poll numbers help a lot. When polls show you're going to win, it's
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest problems for Gore, and other Democrats, is
that the DreamWorks trio of Steven Spielberg, David Geffen and
Jeffrey Katzenberg, longtime Clinton promoters and experts at
extracting millions from their friends in the entertainment
industry, plan to retreat from the fund-raising galaxy when Clinton
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore is just not as natural a guest here as Clinton. While
Gore has visited California 66 times since he became vice president
seven years ago, Clinton seems more at home here. And there is talk
that he will spend much of his post-presidency in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has a bond here, and Gore has just never worked
California the way he has,'' one insider said. ``There is no
question that Gore can never get to the level Clinton has here
among the two or three thousand people in the fund-raising world.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton, Gore's biggest promoter, seemed a bit worried that
donors here might be lulled into a sense of complacency and flag in
their commitment to getting Gore elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think it doesn't matter, when you get tired, when you
wish somebody wouldn't call you again between now and November,''
the president told them, remember that the Republicans ended the
economic expansion of the 1960s. ``Take a deep breath and bear
down,'' he implored them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
