<HEADER>
A8605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOMA-TATE-WEB-NYT     04-16 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMA-TATE-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN AND TATE TEAM UP FOR COMMERCIAL WEB SITE
</HEADLINE>
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unusual marriage of the nonprofit museum world and the
money-hungry e-commerce industry, the Museum of Modern Art in
Manhattan and the Tate Gallery and its branches in Britain have
formed a partnership to create an Internet business for art,
culture and design.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the company include a Web site to sell commissioned
design products and to offer such educational programs as live
Webcasts of lectures and concerts. It will also carry archival
material on art.
</P>
<P>
   Profits from the site will help pay the museums' escalating
operating expenses. This will be the first time any art museum has
used its reputation, expertise and outreach to start a
profit-making company.
</P>
<P>
   But the Modern and the Tate are not the first nonprofit
institutions to do so. In the last few months several academic
centers _ Columbia University, the New York Public Library, the
British Library, the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of
Natural History, the London School of Economics and Political
Science and Cambridge University Press _ have teamed up to start
Fathom.com, a Web site designed to provide specialized information
and general knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   To preserve the museums' tax-exempt status as nonprofit
institutions, the venture by the Modern and the Tate (as yet
unnamed) will be a separate entity with its own staff, board of
directors and offices. A chief executive is being sought to run the
business from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This venture is not just two guys dreaming in their garage,
but a company built on two institutions' history, stability and
knowledge,'' said Glenn D. Lowry, director of the Modern. ``The
Internet is a world of strange, overlapping and intersecting
interests. We're all exploring how to operate in that world, and
there's a scramble for the design and culture dot-com space.
Between us we have the engine to found this new company, which will
not only have a major presence in the United States but in England
and Europe too.''
</P>
<P>
   The project comes at a crucial time for both institutions. The
Tate is opening the $208 million Tate Gallery of Modern Art in
Bankside, just opposite St. Paul's Cathedral in London, next month,
while the Modern is embarking on a $650 million expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both realized that to have a steady stream of income to
ensure a strong future is crucial,'' Lowry said. ``This company
will have long-term value for both of us.'' Eventually, Lowry
added, the company could go public.
</P>
<P>
   While officials from both museums said it was too early to
project how much money they could expect from the company, they
expected revenues from advertising, licensing, merchandise sales,
pay-per-view for certain types of events and information, as well
as syndication of original content.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry said he and Sir Nicholas Serota, director of the Tate, had
been discussing ways they could collaborate beyond joint
exhibitions when they realized that each was separately
investigating the possibility of a profit-making Web site. ``We
were on parallel tracks,'' Lowry said.
</P>
<P>
   Serota said: ``I don't think one should underestimate what a big
move this is for us. For two fiercely independent institutions that
hitherto have been competitors to join forces like this takes a
huge degree of trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Though neither museum would discuss the costs needed to start
the company or the profits it expected to earn, a source close to
the venture said that the Modern had raised several million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The next stage would involve raising about $50 million from
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The company is scheduled to set up its Web site later in the
year or early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Both museums have independent Web sites (www.moma.org and
www.tate.org.uk) that they plan to keep. Each museum had more than
5 million visitors last year, and each institution's Web site
received an additional 4 million visitors. Together the museums
manage retail operations with $50 million in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Their joint site would be drastically different from either
their Web sites or their stores, both directors said. For starters
it would have ads, which the museum Web sites do not have. It would
also sell products like furniture, design objects and books
exclusive to the site and commissioned by designers and architects
from many sources. The items would be more varied than those
available on the Modern's current Web site, which offers
merchandise mainly from its store on West 53rd Street. While the
site would not offer original artworks, it would sell
multiple-edition prints or photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the educational programs it would offer are customized art
tours, virtual-reality tours of collections and exhibitions,
archival material, Webcasts of live lectures, concerts and
performances from around the world and critical essays. There will
also be ticketing for art events and courses.
</P>
<P>
   Lowry does not see the venture as a conflict of interest to the
museums' missions as educational institutions. ``We have built in
all the appropriate fire walls,'' Lowry said. ``No trustee or their
family and no staff member of either museum can invest in this
company should it go public. It will have an independent board.
There will also be licensing arrangements to safeguard our
interests.'' Still, the museums intend to control the site's
content. Two members from the boards of the museums will sit on the
company's board.
</P>
<P>
   In the curatorial world the formation of such a company may be
looked down upon by some as being overly commercial, but Mary Lea
Bandy, chief curator of film and video at the Modern and its deputy
director for curatorial affairs, thinks otherwise: ``Museums, like
libraries and universities, are filled with curators, professors
and scholars who are eager to share their expertise to as many
people as possible, which is something a project like this can do.
For those of us in film, video, architecture, design or photography
_ any art form that exists in multiple forms _ the possibilities
are fantastic.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0144 </DOCNO>
