r a BC-VA-KC-KAN &LR;      04-16 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-KC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS PROPOSE RAZING FORMER VETERANS HOME TO EXPAND CEMETERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEAVENWORTH, KAN. _ Reveille in the morning. Taps at night. A
brass band playing John Philip Sousa in the afternoons. Veterans
sitting in wicker wheelchairs, their tobacco-stained white beards
hiding their faces. A movie house. An ice cream parlor.
</P>
<P>
   These were the trappings of a community that once was called the
Western Branch of the National Home for Disabled Veteran Soldiers
in Leavenworth. That community has long since vanished. And now
many of the home's old buildings _ vestibules to a nearly
120-year-old history _ could vanish too.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at what is today known as the Eisenhower Veterans
Affairs Medical Center have proposed razing 39 structures.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven of those structures _ ranging from outbuildings to
a grand Romanesque Revival mess hall _ were put on the National
Register of Historic Places last year. Together they make up a
district that is one of more than 71,000 listings on the National
Register. Missouri has 1,336 listings, while Kansas has 703.
</P>
<P>
   Getting on the register requires demonstrating a site's historic
or architectural significance.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 39 structures stand vacant. So when officials
learned last year that the adjacent Leavenworth National Cemetery
would run out of grave space in about six years, they proposed
razing the buildings and transferring 54 of the acres they stand on
to the cemetery. The demolition would cost about $5 million, money
that would come from the national VA's major construction budget,
not the Leavenworth VA's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists and VA officials will meet Tuesday at the
medical enter to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Nieweg, a lawyer with the Mountain//Plains Region of the
National Trust for Historic Preservation, said that if the
demolition proceeds, it would be one of the largest of its kind in
recent years. But it's a distinction he thinks Leavenworth could
avoid if the community focuses on reusing the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want the Leavenworth VA to become a precedent for
downsizing by clear-cutting,'' he said. ``There are developers out
there who are experienced with historic projects.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Trust recently made the Leavenworth VA buildings a
candidate for inclusion on its annual 11 Most Endangered Historic
Places list. If they make the list to be announced in June, the
buildings will be featured on the History Channel, which had a
camera team in Leavenworth on April 2 to get footage of the
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The VA says it spends about $100,000 a year just to keep the
buildings in their current state. Its focus on outpatient care and
less hospital treatment is, to a large degree, what has forced the
VA to close most of the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, more than 1,000 veterans received long-term care
in Leavenworth. Today, fewer than 200 veterans get such care. As a
result, the Leavenworth VA and others around the country have
vacated many of their buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the VA say they want to work with
preservationists to come up with other uses for the buildings. But,
said Leavenworth VA spokesman Jim Gleisberg, ``we don't want to
spend health care money on empty buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren L. Reed Jr. counts himself among those who would lament
the loss of the VA's history. Reed was born at the Home for
Disabled Veterans in 1924, 12 years after his father accepted a job
there as secretary to the home's general. In those days, civilian
administrators lived on the home's grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who lived on those grounds until 1946, remembers
accompanying his mother to dances in the Ward Memorial Building,
whose conical metal roof distinguishes it from the VA's other
buildings. He remembers watching the veterans _ ``members'' as he
called them _ lining in military formation to eat at Franklin Hall.
He remembers seeing veterans lounging on the balcony of the
barracklike domiciliaries during the day, and the drinking some did
in an amusement hall, known as the Dugout, at night.
</P>
<P>
   To Christy Davis, with the Kansas Historic Preservation Office,
all those buildings have architectural and historic significance.
Most of them were the products of Leavenworth builder James
McGonigle, who built part of the Kansas Capitol and whose skills
would later achieve national renown. McGonigle began construction
shortly after Leavenworth was chosen as the National Home's Western
Branch site in 1884.
</P>
<P>
   It was a major project, an economic gem, for Leavenworth.
</P>
<P>
   McGonigle built 13 domiciliaries, plus Franklin Hall, which
Davis considers a good example of Romanesque Revival architecture,
and the Ward Building, which Davis says is one of the few examples
of a brick Queen Anne building in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The Dugout, which McGonigle did not build, has touches of Gothic
Revival architecture, giving it a haunted look. Built in 1898, the
building was, in 1901, a target for Carry Nation's protest against
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The setting _ picturesque rolling hills and a lake _ added to
the buildings' appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was constructed, there weren't any city parks,'' Davis
said. ``So the landscape drew people from around the community. It
was an attractive place.''
</P>
<P>
   Today most of the buildings are still structurally sound. Only
the Ward Building, with a shifting foundation, suffers major scars.
Officials with the VA estimate it would cost $2.5 million to return
it to its former glory.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, neglect has led, at most, to chipped paint, some
rotting wooden porches and, in some cases, crumbling ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no matter what state the buildings are in, the VA cannot
order them demolished without first soliciting the concerns of
people or organizations that may have a stake in the demolition.
The National Historic Preservation Act requires that.
</P>
<P>
   To date, 16 ``consulting parties,'' ranging from the city of
Leavenworth to the National Trust, have joined the effort to save
the buildings. Among the first to join was the Preservation
Alliance of Leavenworth.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance proposed that Leavenworth offer the VA 80 acres of
underused park space that abuts the VA's property; its members see
it as an alternative site for the National Cemetery's expansion. In
March, the city said it would do just that, if donating the land
would prevent the demolition. VA officials in Washington are
reviewing the offer.
</P>
<P>
   But the alliance mostly focuses on finding alternative uses for
the buildings. A few years ago, the law wouldn't have allowed
private development on any VA campus, Gleisberg said. But new laws
do, provided that the development is compatible with the VA's
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's members have floated ideas that range from
creating subsidized housing for veterans or the elderly to
establishing a culinary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have more reuse ideas than there is space to
reuse,'' said alliance member Sally Hatcher. ``We realize that some
of the old domiciliaries will have to be sacrificed for parking, if
some of these ideas work. But we're committed to saving as many of
the buildings as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true of the Ward Building, Franklin Hall and
the Dugout. But Hatcher, other preservationists and the VA know
that saving the buildings depends largely on the will of potential
developers.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said numerous examples of developers taking on older
buildings existed. Tax credits, she said, often serve as an
excellent incentive for such projects.
</P>
<P>
   But the scale of the VA project is larger than most. What's
more, the VA can't advertise its properties, making it difficult to
let developers know that they exist.
</P>
<P>
   The Preservation Alliance of Leavenworth, however, is more than
willing to help spread the word. A Web site that it recently
posted, www.toto.net/leavenworthvalor, is designed for that
purpose. ``A great place to reclaim the past and reclaim your
future,'' the home page reads.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher invests her optimism in efforts such as these.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this can be worked out so everybody is happy,'' she
said. ``We can't afford to throw our history into a landfill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
