<SLUG> BC-KC-BLOCK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK CORRECTS GLITCH IN COMPANY'S TAX CUT SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ H&AMP;R Block has corrected a software glitch
that affected more than 3,000 customers who file their taxes
online, a spokesman for the Kansas City-based company said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Block, the nation's biggest tax preparer, on Friday notified the
customers, who were using the company's Tax Cut software. They each
owed more than $1,000 and had authorized the Internal Revenue
Service to take payments from their bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman Neil Getzlow said the glitch caused the
software to misinterpret the placement of a comma, so $1,000 could
be read as $1. As a result, the IRS could take the wrong amount out
of a person's account, and the taxpayer would be charged a penalty
and interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to note that (the problem) won't affect people
filing their returns today or Monday,'' Getzlow said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Block officials told the company's customers that they would
have to mail the correct payments to the IRS. Getzlow said Block
had already told the IRS about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working with the IRS to make sure there are no
penalties,'' Getzlow said. He said Block would assume
responsibility for penalties and interest that resulted.
</P>
<P>
   Getzlow said Block officials learned of the glitch from a
customer who used Tax Cut. He said he didn't know why the glitch
occurred or how technicians corrected it.
</P>
<P>
   Block officials said affected taxpayers should include the
notification from Block with their tax payment.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 million people a year use Block to do their taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
