<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FALL AS WETTELAND FALTERS IN 9TH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Esteban Loaiza yesterday pitched what was possibly
his best game ever with the Rangers. John Wetteland knows that as
well as anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel terrible for him,'' Wetteland said. ``I don't know what
more you can do to win a ballgame. It's my responsibility, and I
didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Wetteland gave up consecutive home runs to Manny
Ramirez and Jim Thome with one out in the ninth inning, two
devastating blows that gave the Cleveland Indians a 2-1 victory
against the Rangers at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, after a weekend of near-brilliant pitching, took a
1-0 lead into the ninth but squandered a chance for both a sweep
and a winning road trip. The Indians, dominated by the Rangers
staff until the last moment, openly expressed their good fortune at
having pulled one out against Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' All-Star closer had a 1.08 career earned-run
average at Jacobs Field and a career-high 21 saves against the
Indians before yesterday. He had also converted his past 18 save
opportunities dating to last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you would have said we were going to hit two home runs off
him, I would have said you're crazy,'' Thome said. ``He's had so
much success against us. He and \RMariano\S Rivera are the top two
closers in baseball, much less the American League.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took two of three from the Indians, but Wetteland
said: ``I haven't forgotten we dropped two to the Yankees. A 2-3
road trip doesn't look as good as a 3-2 road trip. If I'd have
executed like I should, we would have come away with a pretty good
road trip. I'm very disappointed at that aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza pitched brilliantly for 71/3 innings, allowing two hits
and two walks. But Indians starter Chuck Finley, fulfilling his end
of a dazzling pitching duel, kept the Indians close by allowing one
run on five hits while striking out 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both pitchers made a lot of quality pitches, and neither one
would give in,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``You probably
won't see many games pitched that well from both sides, not in this
league anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Loaiza: ``You never knows what's going to happen in this
game. You just want to throw strikes and get people out. Sometimes
it goes the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez and Thome were as ineffective as any hitter in either
lineup, at least until the ninth. Ramirez struck out three times
against Loaiza, and Thome struck out twice and grounded out weakly
once.
</P>
<P>
   But their day took a turn for the better in the ninth after
Wetteland retired Roberto Alomar on a grounder to second to start
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland went 2-2 on Ramirez before throwing a slider that
barely missed, a pitch that more than one Ranger hinted later was
strike three. Wetteland came back with a fastball but not where he
wanted. He wanted it up, but it sank low, and Ramirez blasted it
into the bleachers in deep center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty good at hitting the low ball,'' Wetteland said.
``That's not where I've had success with him. You can be the
smartest pitcher in the world, but if you don't execute, it doesn't
do you any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland also went 2-2 to Thome and came in with a low slider.
Just like Ramirez, Thome went down and smacked it over the
right-center-field wall for the game winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I was just looking for a good pitch,'' Thome
said. ``Maybe getting two strikes helped ... make me cut down on my
swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland said he couldn't remember a game in which he gave up
two consecutive home runs to blow a save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've given up home runs in my career; that's nothing new,''
Wetteland said. ``You hope to keep them to a minimum. You hope it
doesn't hurt you. ... This one hurt.'' / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
