<HEADER>
A8622 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-NASCAR-TALLADEGA0417-     04-16 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-TALLADEGA0417-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Gordon stops his skid
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Carvell
</P>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ NASCAR fans in Alabama are known for their
unabashed worship of Dale Earnhardt and for wearing the infamous
``Anybody But Gordon'' shirts in the stands at Talladega
Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   However, the tide turned neon green, red, yellow and blue after
Sunday's race in Earnhardt country. Jeff Gordon took the checkered
flag for the DieHard 500 to snap the longest winless streak of his
Winston Cup career. Earnhardt finished third as Chevrolets claimed
the top four positions.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was able to block runner-up Mike Skinner over the final
three laps and _ surprisingly _ was greeted with cheers by the
estimated crowd of 188,000. Hundreds of fans waited outside of
victory lane to cheer on Gordon and repeatedly chant loudly ``We
Want Jeff.''
</P>
<P>
   At least eight Alabama state troopers were required to escort
Gordon through the hordes of adoring devotees, something that even
astonished the driver himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow ... I'm not used to this here (Talladega),'' said Gordon
with a grin. ``But I guess everyone likes to root for an
underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   To win for the first time since last October at Charlotte,
Gordon enlisted a nifty ``pass almost in the grass'' on the fourth
turn with five laps remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin, who won at Martinsville a week earlier, looked to
be on the way to his second victory in a row when he assumed the
lead at lap 163 of the 188-race. Dale Jarrett _ who was barely on
the lead lap and just in front of the leaders _ appeared to be in
position to help Martin hold off his Chevy-driving challengers.
</P>
<P>
   But that all fell apart when Jeremy Mayfield tried to pass
Martin on the outside on lap 183. Martin shifted right, leaving
Gordon an opportunity to drive on the apron of the track and into
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Earnhardt's teammate, Skinner, who gave
Gordon the aerodynamic push in the draft to go in front. Skinner
inadvertently bumped Gordon over the final few laps, but choose not
to knock Gordon out if the way _ even if it would've given Skinner
his first career victory on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy (Skinner) didn't do anything to spin me out,''
Gordon said. ``It was emotional for me to win. I know it hadn't
been forever, but it had been a while.''
</P>
<P>
   By Gordon's own standards, this season had been a major
disappointment. He posted only one top-five finish in the eight
races before Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   It was his 50th career victory and first under crew chief Robbie
Loomis, who has been with the team since January. Loomis appeared
to be crying after the race, but claimed his eyes were teary after
Gordon sprayed champagne in the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's win extended NASCAR's record of having no repeat
winners to start a season to nine races.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
