</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-NEWMUSEUM-2TAKES-N     04-16 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GUGGENHEIM'S NEW VISION IS AN ICEBREAKER OF A DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
 MUSEUM-2TAKES-NYT  (Architectural Appraisal) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How many ways can you say ``Wow''? In the weeks ahead
New Yorkers will certainly find more articulate words to describe
Frank O. Gehry's design for a museum that the Solomon R. Guggenheim
Foundation hopes to build along the East River in Lower Manhattan.
Silence would be eloquent, too. But only for the repressed.
Otherwise, this is the moment to look for noisemakers left over
from New Year's Eve and give them one more toot. Here comes
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Models of the design by Gehry, the architect of the acclaimed
Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain, will be presented in ``Project
for a New Guggenheim Museum in New York City,'' which opens on
Wednesday at the Guggenheim's main building on Fifth Avenue at 89th
Street, designed in 1959 by Frank Lloyd Wright. The featured
attraction is a large model, 12 feet long and 5 feet high, which
displays the design in close-up detail. Other models present the
project as it would appear in the Lower Manhattan cityscape, though
there is no guarantee it will ever be built. The proposed site,
near the foot of Wall Street, is occupied by three piers scheduled
for development by the New York City Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a purely speculative idea, however, this museum project
performs an important civic service. A steel-plated vessel,
floating atop a vast outdoor skating rink, this is an icebreaker of
a design, a plan for crunching through rigid streetscapes and
frozen minds. And it is a test of the city's willingness to think
big.
</P>
<P>
   Will it get built? The question is a waste of energy. Like other
sideshows that have kept New York in denial about the mediocrity of
the buildings it puts up, the feasibility question distracts from
the challenge presented by the design. This is the top form
architecture comes in these days. Want some?
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Krens, the director of the Guggenheim Museum, said that
the institution is committed to building another museum in
Manhattan. The Fifth Avenue building is too small to display more
than a fraction of the museum's permanent collection, which also
includes examples of large-scale contemporary art. Krens envisions
an arrangement in which the Wright building would display work from
the late 19th century to 1945 while the downtown building would
present art from 1945 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Project for a New Guggenheim Museum in New York City''
presents the record of a creative process leading to the birth of
an idea. If this one doesn't fly, we can count on Krens to have
others. In 1998 he set his eye on another waterfront site, on the
Hudson River. Local opposition helped deflate that dream and it
could shatter this one, too. Financial and government support are
also hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Lower Manhattan is well stocked with cherished landmarks like
the Brooklyn Bridge, the World Trade Center, the Woolworth
Building, Trinity Church and 70 Pine Street. But it has been some
time since the district's architecture has risen to their iconic
level. One of the charms of Gehry's design is that it would recast
mediocre towers in the supporting roles for which they are better
suited.
</P>
<P>
   If New York is a perpetual gift to the future, this design is
its bow: a flourish of titanium ribbons ( Gehry calls them
wrappers) curled around half a million square feet of gallery
space. The composition is roughly triangular, a pediment on square
columns. The triangle is anchored at the northern and southern
corners by two low-rise structures of boxy silhouette. The southern
structure houses a terminal for a ferry that would take visitors to
a sculpture garden on Governors Island. The northern structure
contains a 1,200-seat theater.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six galleries, ranging from 1,300 to 20,000 square feet,
would be housed on three levels within the cloudlike tangle of
ribbon and a 450-foot tower rising above it. The galleries would
serve various uses: in addition to the permanent collection and
temporary shows, they would present exhibitions for three
departments: education, architecture and design, and art and
technology. As at the Guggenheim in Bilbao, the previous
collaboration between Krens and Gehry, the museum's major space
would be an atrium bathed in natural light; 26,000 square feet of
gallery space would overlook the atrium's well. Escalators, forming
a dramatic diagonal at the base of the space, would move visitors
up from the open areas beneath the museum into the building's
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Six massive square columns, steel and concrete superpylons,
would hold the mass aloft. Gardens, bridges, a waterside promenade
and other public spaces would occupy petal-shaped platforms
extending into the river. The free-form rink, beneath the museum's
soaring underside, would be equipped with ``Knife Ship I,'' a
kinetic sculpture by Claes Oldenburg that was the focus of a
performance piece created by Gehry, Oldenburg and Coosje van
Bruggen for the 1985 Venice Biennale.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the models could give you whiplash. In New York
architects have spent the last two decades viewing the present
through a rearview mirror, as if the city came to a halt in the Art
Deco era.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Bilbao Guggenheim, Gehry shows that one of the
purest ways to honor context is to play against it. Many have seen
the Manhattan skyline as a geological formation of cliffs, peaks
and canyons. Gehry treats the site as a natural wonder, a spot
where mountains cascade into the sea. He has raised the horizon of
the water, in waves that lap against the base of the cliffs, and
pulled the sky down to the canyons, with changing light reflected
in the museum's wavy metal surface. Expanses of glass, articulated
with diagonal mullions, splash upward like jets of water formed by
a Manhattan-bound meteor's narrow miss.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
