<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-NEW-MUSEUM-2NDTAKE     04-16 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEW-MUSEUM-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: narrow miss.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the tower, the vertical dimension of the skyline
reverberates into the foreground. The tower's leaning silhouette
and flaring top talk back to the World Trade Center's scaleless,
impersonal thrust. Some architects, who still regard the Trade
Center as an aesthetic abomination, have championed a revival of
building crowns, by which they mean paperweights blown up to
skyscraper scale. Here is another way to top a tower. Rip off roof.
Cut jaggedly above penthouse. Let curtain walls droop. Instead of
hiding structural spines behind marble and steel, as Mies van der
Rohe did with the Seagram Building, just let them hang out there in
the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Ordered complexity, not chaos, is the fundamental principle of
this work. We should be used to this by now. It has been 35 years
since Robert Venturi introduced the concepts of complexity and
contradiction as an alternative to the unified simplicity of the
International Style. Gehry's work, like Venturi's and Denise Scott
Brown's, aims for the maximum complexity that can be transmitted
through habitable space.
</P>
<P>
   The wrappers are the most eye-catching element of the Guggenheim
design, but it would be a mistake to think the project's importance
rests entirely on Gehry's ability to sculpture arresting shapes.
What matters here is the physiognomy of the shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Intersubjectivity _ the idea that multiple perspectives can
render a truth _ is the central concept governing this and other
projects that Gehry has designed for the last 25 years. It is also
the idea that many people find hardest to take. We still look to
architecture to embody some ideal of external authority: history,
science, nature and religion, to name a few. This Gehry declines to
provide. Though he makes fleeting formal allusions to other times,
other buildings, these images are mutable. They rise to the surface
and sink back. Tell me what you see and I will tell you _ with wild
inaccuracy, no doubt _ who you are.
</P>
<P>
   Scale and relationship to context are two of the Rorschach tests
this project must pass in the eye of the beholder. But the
Guggenheim faces even bigger obstacles. Some will object that the
design looks too much like Bilbao; New York, ever mindful of its
uniqueness, deserves better than a remake of something designed for
provincial Spain. Some will not want to invest hope in a project
that has yet to obtain the required permits and financial and
government support.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't worry too much about the design's uniqueness. To
philistines all modern glass towers are identical. When you've seen
one titanium wrapper, you've seen 'em all. A model of the Bilbao
museum, included in the exhibition, will enable viewers to compare
the designs. But carping about formal similarity may just be part
of the Nimby syndrome. Architecture is fine for Bilbao, but we
don't want it here.
</P>
<P>
   Since the demolition of Pennsylvania Station, the troops can be
counted on to protest tinkering with a lamppost. We've only begun
to awaken to the loss of heritage that occurs when a city is frozen
in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
