<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TRADE-FUND-ART-NYT &LR;      04-16 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-FUND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF POINTS TO SUCCESS: IT MET ON SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TRADE-PROTEST, TRADE-VOICES) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 4-9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Delegates looked bleary-eyed after their predawn
wake-up calls, and a handful arrived several hours late. But the
member nations of the International Monetary Fund achieved a major
breakthrough Sunday: They met.
</P>
<P>
   That was perhaps the one definitive accomplishment the world
finance ministers could announce after a full day of meetings to
discuss global financial stability and to set the course for the
monetary fund. After globalization-wary protesters briefly shut
down world trade talks in Seattle last year and threatened to do
the same to finance ministers gathered in Washington Sunday, the
simple fact of the meeting was presented as a triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting went on as normal,'' announced Gordon Brown,
Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, the chairman of the fund's
steering committee. ``It started on time and it was completed in a
normal way.'' That included a relaxed lunch in the IMF's soaring
marble and glass atrium, where formally attired waiters served
jumbo shrimp and offered a selection of red and white wines.
</P>
<P>
   The shouts of protesters could not be heard inside the
earth-tone conference rooms of the fund's downtown Washington
headquarters. But participants said the varied complaints of the
fund's many critics in Congress, in academia and on the streets
resonated in many of the policy proposals discussed during the
sessions, including those for streamlined lending procedures and
expedited debt relief for poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   A carefully worded day-end communique gave credit to outside
critics for stoking a public debate about the future of the fund.
And many of the finance ministers stressed that they had heard the
protesters' messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is going through a period of profound change, and
that has made for debate here and some debate outside,'' said Paul
Martin, Canada's finance minister. ``Ultimately our aims are the
same,'' he said, adding that both parties want to figure out how
best to deal with poverty.
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be modest progress on a range of issues
confronting the fund, some of which are high on the agenda of
outside critics. The finance ministers asked the fund's managers to
continue a review of their lending programs with an eye to
eliminating some. The fund was also told to review whether to use
variable pricing on some loan programs so as to discourage
repeated, long-term borrowing. Those proposals are favored by the
United States and some members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But some poor and middle-income countries expressed strong
reservations about proposals that would make it more difficult for
them to obtain loans or force them to pay the loans back faster.
Their opposition highlighted how difficult it is to institute
changes quickly at the fund, which consists of 182-member nations,
though its board is effectively controlled by the United States and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find some of these proposals unacceptable and have serious
concerns about them,'' said German Suarez, who chairs a coalition
of developing countries known as the Group of 24. He was referring
primarily to a proposal put forward by a congressional commission
that studied ways of changing the IMF and the World Bank, its
sister lending agency.
</P>
<P>
   The finance ministers' communique ruled out the possibility of
completely eliminating the fund's long-term lending programs and
expressed strong support for the fund's involvement in working to
reduce poverty. The congressional panel, known as the Meltzer
Commission, had urged that the fund cease both types of lending.
</P>
<P>
   On debt relief, finance ministers reiterated their longstanding
pledge to free the world's poorest countries, including many in
Africa, of their crushing foreign-debt burdens. One major problem
is that some legislatures around the world, most notably Congress,
so far have failed to allot all the necessary funds to allow the
fund and the World Bank to forgive past loans.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee 2000, a religious coalition, has called for stepping up
the effort and for total forgiveness of debt owed by the world's 40
poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the discussions Sunday said the ministers also
considered proposals that would make it easier for the poorest
countries to qualify for debt relief and to put the plans into
effect faster once they do.
</P>
<P>
   Of 27 nations considered under a debt-relief program approved in
Cologne, Germany last summer, only four have begun a qualification
process and just one, Uganda, has actually had some debt forgiven.
Many others have faced difficulties proving to the fund and the
bank that they have the good governance and adequate programs in
place to meet the criteria for debt forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Most finance ministers, traveling in police-escorted bus
convoys, had little trouble winding their way through barricades to
the fund's headquarters. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, the
top-ranking American official at the meetings, was whisked by
limousine from his office a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   But the protests made life difficult for some officials. The
Japanese delegation, fearing a tardy arrival, left its quarters at
the Madison Hotel a few blocks from the IMF at 4:30 a.m., arriving
a short time later and waiting more than three hours for the start
of the formal proceedings, a Japanese official said.
</P>
<P>
   The French finance minister, Laurent Fabius, who had told IMF
and World Bank staff members that he wanted to conduct a dialogue
with demonstrators during his stay, got full exposure. Protesters
surrounded his limousine just before the 8 a.m. start of the
morning session, forcing him to turn back. Fabius then waited for
nearly six hours at a luxury hotel for bus transport through the
barricades, arriving only at the conclusion of lunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
