<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-16 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: VALENTINE REVISITING MISTAKES OF MARTIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The similarity is inescapable. Call them birds of a
feather or two of a kind, two peas in a pod, psychological twins.
Billy Martin was and Bobby Valentine is one of the most tactically
accomplished managers in baseball. Both, however, have had damaging
ways of undermining their talent. Martin did it and Valentine does
it with his mouth. For Martin, it was ingesting alcohol; for
Valentine, it is disgorging words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's problem is he's a very good tactical manager,'' a
former teammate of the New York Mets' manager said Sunday, ``but
the other stuff overshadows that. He can't not do it. He's always
been like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine believes he is the smartest manager in the game.
Whether or not he is, he cannot allow his managerial moves to speak
for themselves. At seemingly every opportunity, he has to let
everyone know that he is the smartest manager in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He also has to make sure at least some people _ usually selected
reporters covering the team he's managing _ know where he differs
with the front office. He has long done it. In case something goes
wrong, he wants those people to know where the blame lies,
certainly not with him.
</P>
<P>
   The manager's latest oral indiscretion came when he appeared
before a group of graduate students last Wednesday and apparently
expressed disagreement with some of the moves made last winter by
the Mets' general manager, Steve Phillips. Valentine's purported
comments wound up on the Internet and sent him another giant step
down the path that Martin often took with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's comments also caught the attention of Yankee Manager
Joe Torre, who was dismissed earlier in his managerial career not
for a poor choice of words but for poor collections of players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see this whole Bobby Valentine thing,'' Torre said
Sunday before the Yankees beat Kansas City, 8-4, at Yankee Stadium.
``I've made remarks about my players at different places that I've
spoken. I've made fun of my players. But I've made fun of my
players to my players, nothing that they haven't heard from me
first-hand. But there's no question you have to be aware of what
you're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he was reluctant to talk about anybody even if he was
having lunch or dinner with someone, ``much less speaking to a
group of people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't want someone to have anything,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be good advice for Valentine, if he ever felt he
needed advice. People used to tell Billy Martin to reduce his
alcohol intake. Knowing his five-time manager wouldn't follow that
advice, George Steinbrenner, both a benefactor and a manipulator of
Martin, tried to get him to drink privately. That way, at least, he
could avoid the fights that too often erupted in bars that Billy
visited.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin didn't take his drinking private any more than
Valentine has kept his thoughts to himself. By now, the Mets
probably have enough of a case to send Valentine on his way, if
they wanted to take that step. They obviously don't, not yet
anyway. If they have as good a team as they think they have _ not
that the team's play has supported that view _ they wouldn't want
to make a change now and disrupt what they think they have. On the
other hand, Valentine is doing a good job of that by himself.
</P>
<P>
   He did a good job of it last September, too, doing a magazine
interview that appeared just as the Mets were scrambling to reach
the playoffs. That was the interview in which he said that he had
five losers in the clubhouse and that other managers feared
appearing on a panel with him because they would be exposed. He
didn't mean to chickenpox.
</P>
<P>
   Martin never felt the need to put down other managers; he harmed
only himself. Valentine is a double threat.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine hasn't denied making the comments that were attributed
to him from last Wednesday at the Wharton School of Business. He
could have denied them and let his word stand against any student
who would have said differently. But he apparently knew that his
show was videotaped, and if the tape were to surface, he could have
been shown to have been lying.
</P>
<P>
   It was lying that did Martin in the first time of the four times
Steinbrenner fired him. That occurred after Martin's fight with a
marshmallow salesman in a Minnesota hotel after the 1979 season. He
wasn't fired for fighting but for telling Steinbrenner the fight
never happened. The owner found out otherwise. The Mets, if they
had wanted, presumably could have located the smoking tape.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Valentine would have been wiser to stage a
different act for his Wharton audience. Like his negative views
about the front office, this one would have been a repeat, but it
would have been visual, not oral. He could have done a mime act,
donning the fake mustache and glasses he used to reappear within
sight of a television camera after he had been ejected from a game
last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
