<HEADER>
A8635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     04-16 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JOHN MCMULLEN'S LAST TIME AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ During a Devils game, John McMullen sits
in the back row of the owner's suite at midice. Quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very vocal,'' he said, ``unless somebody stands up in
front of me; then I ask them to sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Devils' sale to YankeeNets for $175 million due to
be completed in July, this is the 81-year-old McMullen's last time
around in that owner's suite. He will be ensconced there only as
long as the Devils remain alive in these Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a chance to win the cup again,'' he was saying
before Sunday night's game with the Florida Panthers. ``I think we
corrected the slump.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the slump. Two months ago the Devils were atop the Eastern
Conference standing in the National Hockey League, but they
finished the season in a 9-14-2 tailspin that dropped them into the
fourth-seeded spot in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   During that slump, while still in first place, the Devils
suddenly discharged Robbie Ftorek as coach and promoted Larry
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I concurred,'' McMullen said, alluding to Lou Lamoriello's
decision to change coaches. ``I felt Robbie was losing control of
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello, the Devils' president and general manager, also made
two significant trades that brought in the sharpshooter Alexander
Mogilny and defenseman Vladimir Malakhov.
</P>
<P>
   ``The slump probably cost us the first seed,'' McMullen said,
``but we've been the first seed and it didn't do us any good.''
</P>
<P>
   In each of the past two years, the top-seeded Devils were
embarrassed and eliminated in the first round of the playoffs by
their eighth-seeded opponent _ the Ottawa Senators two years ago,
the Pittsburgh Penguins last year. ``Last year was devastating,''
McMullen said.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what the Devils do or don't do in these playoffs,
they are now considered one of the NHL's premier franchises. Over
the 18 seasons since McMullen purchased the Colorado Rockies and
transplanted that franchise in the Meadowlands, where the Empire
State Building can be seen even on a cloudy night, the Devils have
succeeded despite the Rangers' existence on the other side of the
Lincoln Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rangers,'' McMullen said, ``are in the most dominant
position of any New York team from the standpoint of fan base and
adoration. I've had to live in their shadow all this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. On the ice, if not on the books, the Devils have
towered over the Rangers in the standing in six of the last eight
seasons, while producing the same number of Stanley Cup
championships, one _ in 1995 for the Devils after the Rangers ended
their 54-year famine in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should've won it in 1994, too,'' McMullen said. ``If we had
won that seventh game in overtime with the Rangers in the
conference final, we would have won the cup that year.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Rangers, the Devils, dollar for dollar, have been one
of the NHL's most cost-efficient teams. With a $37.6 million
payroll, the Devils are a bargain, especially when compared with
the Rangers' wasteful $61.2 million payroll for a team that not
only didn't make the playoffs but also performed in the last few
weeks as if it didn't care if it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our legacy,'' McMullen said, ``is the proliferation of
junior hockey in New Jersey. I think more kids under 15 can name
more Devils players than they can any other professional team in
this area. Just look at all the Devils jerseys you see kids
wearing. That's why I never wanted a third jersey. I want those
kids to wear their older brother's Devils jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   But in July, the Devils' era under McMullen's ownership will be
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to sell the team; I was in a dead end,'' he said. ``You
have to have your own arena. I was willing to build one in Hoboken
just for the Devils, but the state wouldn't let me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christine Todd Whitman refused to grant McMullen the air
rights over the train shed there. Eventually, the Devils are
expected to join the Nets in YankeeNets' proposed arena in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about the Devils' future,'' McMullen said. ``The
YankeeNets is going to be a very businesslike deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the YankeeNets organization apparently wants to keep
Lamoriello in charge, his contract expires with the July sale. He
will be available to join the front office of other NHL teams,
possibly the Rangers. And with YankeeNets as the Devils' landlord,
George Steinbrenner will surely be involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can he not be?'' John McMullen said. ``George is George.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
