<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT &LR;      04-16 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR METS AND PIRATES, IT WAS A LONG AND UGLY AFTERNOON 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Rick Reed does not want to be a doomsayer, but he
does not see any way Bobby J. Jones can recover quickly from the
calf strain he suffered Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones faced only two Pirates in the Mets' 12-9 victory, hitting
the first batter _ almost certainly as retaliation for the Pirates'
hitting the Mets' leadoff man, Rickey Henderson _ and allowing a
single to the next. As he left the mound to back up third, he felt
the muscle pull, and when he stopped limping, he felt a burning
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have to rest it, treat it and then start doing
exercises to strengthen the area again,'' said Reed, who missed
three weeks with a similar injury last year. ``Right now, he can't
walk on it, and it's going to be a while, I'm sure, before he can.
It's not fun. It's going to be a long, long process, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The team doctor will evaluate Jones on Monday. The trainer Fred
Hina said there was no chance that Jones, who left Three Rivers
Stadium on crutches, could make his scheduled start on Saturday.
Manager Bobby Valentine was considering several pitchers to replace
him, with Pat Mahomes a logical choice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' injury was not the first ugly play in a game that third
baseman Robin Ventura compared to a boxing match. ``They're more
like rounds than they are innings _ whoever's the last man
standing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura had three hits, including a home run, and six runs
batted in. He raised his batting average 98 points in this series
by getting 7 hits in 15 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the game, Henderson was hit on the right thumb by a
95-mile-an-hour fastball from the Pirates' Kris Benson. He ran the
bases _ being thrown out advancing from second to third on a
grounder to shortstop _ but left the game with a bruise under his
fingernail. He said after the game that he expected to play on
Tuesday, when the Mets return home against Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   A three-run homer by Ventura gave Jones a 3-0 lead, but Jones
put himself in trouble by plunking the Pirates' leadoff man, Jason
Kendall, with an 0-2 pitch. Jones would not respond when asked if
he hit Kendall on purpose, but it seemed clear he was upholding an
unwritten code of conduct: if our leadoff man goes down, so will
yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make of it what you want, I guess,'' Jones said. ``I think he
kind of threw his elbow in front of it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones hurt himself when Pat Meares singled Kendall to third, and
Kendall scored when Brian Giles doubled on the first pitch from the
reliever Mahomes. Mahomes, who earned the victory, said he did not
warm up properly and allowed six hits and four walks in four
innings. The Pirates scored four in the first, and a messy game had
begun.
</P>
<P>
   --Because of two-out errors, scoreless innings became three-run
innings for both the Mets (in the first) and the Pirates (in the
third).
</P>
<P>
   --It took the teams 1 hour 57 minutes to play four innings; they
played nine in the same time on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   --The first six pitchers in the game each allowed at least two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   --Mets infielders made three errors, two by third baseman
Ventura, who bobbled a grounder and threw one away, and one by
shortstop Rey Ordonez, who made a wild throw after ranging far to
his right to backhand a grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Both those players won Gold Gloves last season, when the Mets
had only one game in which their infielders made two errors. This
season, they have had two. Ordonez has four errors, as many as he
had last season, Ventura and first baseman Todd Zeile have three,
and Valentine acknowledged that the Mets have not found a rhythm
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had the best infield,'' said second baseman
Edgardo Alfonzo, who has one error. ``I think we still have it.
Things aren't going well for us, but those are the best two guys on
the team, and that's going to happen. We're all human.''
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Derek Bell saved the Mets in the fourth inning
when he backpedaled, leaped and caught a fly ball by Aramis Ramirez
with a man on second to end the fourth. Bell played exceptionally
in the field and at the plate on this six-game trip, and he has 12
hits in 24 at-bats since correcting a flaw in his timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of a little thing we found out I was
doing wrong,'' Bell said. ``I wouldn't call it a streak. I righted
my ship.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
