<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-VOUCHERS-710&AMP;AD     04-16 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-VOUCHERS-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTREPRENEUR PUSHES PLAN TO FIX CALIFORNIA SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _ In Timothy Draper's world, change occurs
at a breakneck pace. A billionaire venture capitalist, he finances
Internet start-ups that grow from business plan to public company
in mere months. He came up with the concept of ``viral marketing,''
instantaneously circulating advertisements by e-mail the world
over.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, the pace is known as Internet time. So it is
no surprise that Draper wants to transform overnight an institution
that has long been dragged down by myriad problems _ California's
school system.
</P>
<P>
   Draper has spent $2 million to try to get the United States'
most far-reaching school-voucher plan onto the November ballot.
Under it, parents would be eligible for $4,000 a year per child for
tuition at private schools, including parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education reform has to happen from the outside,'' said
Draper, 41. ``I have to be the one to make sure it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Draper's mantra has a familiar ring in Silicon Valley, where
free-market and libertarian strains and new-found wealth have
inspired a rush of interest in California's initiative process. But
as they would say here, Draper's politics are a few standard
deviations from the mean.
</P>
<P>
   He calls public education ``socialistic'' and advocates
free-market solutions at every turn, even advocating the
legalization of drugs. He said his plan would empower parents to
act as consumers shopping for the best education possible for their
children.
</P>
<P>
   The plan reflects his extreme strain of laissez-faire economics.
It calls for the use of existing educational money for the $4,000
vouchers. But according to the latest National Education
Association figures, California spent $5,627 per student in 1997-98
_ 40th in the nation and roughly $1,000 less than the national
average.
</P>
<P>
   Critics call the plan a drastic and simplistic solution to
difficult problems _ overcrowded and outmoded buildings, a lack of
qualified teachers, textbooks and equipment, and a growing number
of students for whom English is a second language.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dealing with very complex subjects and it runs the risk
of totally undermining school funding in California,'' said Bob
Cherry, associate executive director of the California Teachers
Association, a powerful organization with 300,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The association will provide stiff opposition to Draper. In 1993
it spent $16 million to defeat a similar initiative that voters
rejected, 70 percent to 30 percent. This year it is gathering
signatures to put on the ballot a measure requiring the state to
spend at least as much per student as the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, it is an earlier voter initiative that is blamed
by many for creating the state's educational quandary. Proposition
13, passed in 1978, capped some property taxes, thus limiting a
major source of school financing.
</P>
<P>
   Draper's initiative does not even have the support of all
proponents of vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Moe, a professor of political science at Stanford
University, supports vouchers but said they should be narrower than
Draper's proposal. ``There is a reason why around the country,''
Moe said, ``the kinds of vouchers that are successful are targeted
at low-income children, and are limited programs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate at this time when a well-designed voucher
initiative could win,'' Moe added, ``he comes up with this, and he
does it on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Draper's campaign said they were still gathering
signatures on a petition to qualify for the November ballot though
few believe that they will qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Draper says his proposal would bring California spending up to
the national average per pupil.
</P>
<P>
   But the language of the proposition does not guarantee that.
Rather, it says it would ``permit'' the Legislature to amend the
law to raise spending, leading some political scientists to say the
measure implies that it will accomplish more than it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bait-and-switch,'' Cherry said. ``It's not about
raising it to the national average; it's about installing a voucher
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Draper says he has an interest as a ``frustrated parent'' of
four children in private schools and as a businessman who knows
that high-tech firms cannot find sufficiently educated engineers
and scientists.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He is not the first Silicon Valley entrepreneur to use the
initiative process to seek change.
</P>
<P>
   On the March ballot, California voters rejected propositions
drafted or sponsored in Silicon Valley that would have banned
corporate campaign contributions and allowed votes for ``none of
the above'' in federal and state elections. Officials of high-tech
companies also supported an unsuccessful measure that would have
lowered the vote to pass a school bond measure to a simple majority
from a two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign-finance reform measure was sponsored by Ron Unz, a
software millionaire, whose initiative against bilingual education
was approved in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Schnur, a Republican strategist in California and the former
Republican political director of TechNet, a bipartisan Silicon
Valley lobbying group, said the region's entrepreneurs do not have
the patience for the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to subcommittee hearings gets boring really fast,'' he
said. ``They figure they can achieve the results through a ballot
measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Draper said he planned to create a broader political coalition
than the conservatives and religious groups that backed the 1993
proposition, though he has not disclosed any backers. He said he
was prepared to raise $40 million, an atypically high amount, but
would not say how much he was prepared to spend himself.
</P>
<P>
   Draper is less the political novice than other
referendum-backing valley residents. He has been a prominent
fund-raiser for George W. Bush's presidential campaign and has
hired as his spokesman Barry Hutchison, the former press secretary
for Newt Gingrich. Draper's father, William H. Draper III, ran for
Congress in 1969 and in 1981 was appointed chairman of the
Export-Import Bank by President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Draper spent a year on the state board of education,
where, he said, he learned that ``the system is failing the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Californians embrace such a far-reaching
initiative, colleagues of Draper say he will put enough money and
personal influence into the race to force people to think about it.
Draper said he hoped the result would be a legacy that promoted his
near-religious belief in the free market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will have lived a great life if I can be known for viral
marketing and school vouchers,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
