<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8641 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     04-16 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARGAS DELIVERS WHAT OSCAR HASN'T
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Fernando Vargas isn't as marketable as Oscar De La
Hoya. His promoter, Gary Shaw, admits it. He said he and others
must continue to push his client into the public consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's time to put Vargas in De La Hoya's class as a
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Oxnard resident did what De La Hoya has never
been able to do: beat an elite opponent convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   His performance against Ike Quartey here left onlookers shaking
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   He took everything a strong, fit challenger had to offer and
then returned the favor two-fold. And the way he did it - so
methodically, so professionally, so thoroughly - makes it difficult
to believe he's only 22 and has had a mere 19 fights.
</P>
<P>
   One word to describe the effort: Wow! When's the last time we
used that exclamation after a De La Hoya fight?
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya deserves tremendous respect as a fighter. His
accomplishments are considerable. At the same time, he had great
difficulty in his three biggest tests - Pernell Whitaker, Quartey
and Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   He was able to beat Whitaker and Quartey - but barely. The
Whitaker decision was widely disputed and utterly uninspired, while
he had to rally to outpoint Quartey in another controversial fight.
</P>
<P>
   And, against Trinidad, he blew a chance to make a significant
statement when he outboxed the Puerto Rican but lost a close
decision when he ran in the final rounds.
</P>
<P>
   After all three fights, we were left wanting more out of De La
Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Vargas' detractors will make predictable comments.
</P>
<P>
   They'll say that Quartey had fought only once in 2 years,
inactivity that had to have had some impact on him. (He hadn't
fought for 16 months when he faced De La Hoya.)
</P>
<P>
   They'll say Quartey was at a disadvantage because he was
fighting for the first time at 154 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   They'll say Vargas was unable to seriously hurt or knock down
Quartey, as De La Hoya was able to do.
</P>
<P>
   They'll say this performance doesn't entirely erase his disputed
victory over Ronald ``Winky'' Wright in his last fight, in which he
had to rally to beat the relatively unknown, but slick left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   And all such comments will have some validity.
</P>
<P>
   However, we saw what we saw Saturday and it made a powerful
impression.
</P>
<P>
   If the Quartey who fought Vargas was rusty, he certainly didn't
look it. He looked stronger at 154 than he had at 147, at least in
part because he said he had difficulty making the lighter weight in
his most recent bouts.
</P>
<P>
   His jab, his most noted weapon, was crisp and powerful while his
right caught Vargas' attention on many occasions.
</P>
<P>
   It seems so obvious that precious few junior middleweights
could've stood up to him.
</P>
<P>
   That Vargas was not only among those few but dominated Quartey -
which no one had done - is convincing evidence of where Vargas
stands: He's one of the best fighters in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has been able to beat him convincingly and I did it
after only 18 fights. That has to say something,'' Vargas said.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad talk: As much as we learned about Vargas on Saturday,
we'll know much more if he fights Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas is expected to take a relatively easy fight in July -
possibly against former contender Tony Ayala, who is recently out
of prison and resurrecting his career - and then could tangle with
Trinidad in September or October.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations started before the Quartey fight and continue,
although both promoters - Shaw and Don King - are optimistic that
terms will be reached.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the biggest-money matchup for both at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   They could make more fighting De La Hoya, but the welterweight
champion is as comfortable at 147 as Trinidad and Vargas are at
154. No one will be willing to budge, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas-Trinidad might not be as interesting to the public as a
fight involving De La Hoya. However, fight fans drool over the
prospect of two immensely talented young boxers they know will
stand and fight one another.
</P>
<P>
   If Vargas wins? Any doubters who remain after the Quartey fight
would have to concede.
</P>
<P>
   Correction: The date on which Vargas' trial on assault charges
begins was incorrect in Sunday's editions. He'll be in Santa
Barbara Superior Court beginning Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas and four friends allegedly beat up a man in a home
outside Santa Barbara in August. He could face up to eight years in
prison, but one legal expert said he'd be very surprised if Vargas
spent more than a few months in jail if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas insists he did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be fully exonerated. You'll see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Quartey, who had said before the fight that De
La Hoya is ``far better'' than Vargas, refused to respond when he
was asked to compare the two after the fight. ...
</P>
<P>
   Vargas threw 909 punches, or roughly 76 per round, according to
CompuBox statistics.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be an eye-opening number for a flyweight but is
unusual for a fighter as big as Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas worked with a personal fitness trainer, John Philbin, for
the first time in preparation for this fight. To say he's sold on
the concept is an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's earned a ticket for life,'' Vargas said of Philbin.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas connected on 389 of his punches. Quartey was 272 of 645.
...
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Diaz, who put on a very impressive, machine-like
performance in his 11th-round knockout of tough Ivan Robinson on
Saturday's undercard, has won 23 consecutive fights and has emerged
as one of the most capable junior welterweights in the world.
</P>
<P>
   One observer compared the Coachella resident to a young Julio
Cesar Chavez because of the way he chopped down Robinson. ...
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vaden, who lost a decision to Shibata Flores, was coming
off a fight in November in which he delivered the blows that killed
Stephan Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Vaden, the former IBF champion, reportedly has had a very
difficult time coping with the tragedy and hinted after Saturday's
fight that he might retire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
