<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BBA-YANKEES-ROYALS-NY     04-16 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SWEEP THEIR THREE-GAME SERIES WITH THE ROYALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ These were your defending World Series champion
Yankees Sunday. The starting pitcher had not started a game in
almost four years. The starting catcher had not started behind the
plate in 10 months and had no hits this season. The starting left
fielder had managed a grand total of four hits. The first pitcher
out of the bullpen was making his second major league appearance.
Welcome to Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But all that these truncated descriptions of Jason Grimsley, Jim
Leyritz, Ricky Ledee and Darrell Einertson prove is that the
Yankees are very deep and that it is still very early in the
season. It seemed as if everyone except the bat boys contributed
something as the Yankees subdued the Royals, 8-4, to sweep their
three-game series and finish their first homestand at 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are deep enough to summon Grimsley from the bullpen
and have him pitch five sturdy innings. Deep enough to get a
tie-breaking home run from Leyritz after Jorge Posada was given
most of the day off. Deep enough to watch the blossoming Ledee
produce two hits and three runs batted in. Deep enough to have
Einertson secure three important outs on nine pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you just saw is what we are,'' Ledee said. ``We don't
rely on one or two guys. Everyone is prepared to play. Even guys
who aren't playing are up in the clubhouse swinging a bat. It's
teamwork. That's why we're so good.''
</P>
<P>
   With Andy Pettitte on the disabled list, the Yankees needed a
replacement starter Sunday. Rather than promote Jake Westbrook from
Class AAA Columbus, Torre started and ended his search for a
starter in the bullpen. Torre recalled how Grimsley pitched a
five-hit shutout against the Yankees as a member of the Angels on
May 28, 1996, hardly caring that Grimsley had not started since
July 25, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley sprinted out of the dugout to begin the game and
admitted that it felt bizarre to hear the national anthem while he
was on the mound because he is usually in the bullpen at the start.
Using his hard sinker and an improved curveball, Grimsley stifled
the Royals until Mike Sweeney's two-run homer in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But that lead did not last long, only a half-inning, because
Royals starter Chad Durbin failed to handle a bad-hop grounder and
also made a throwing error to allow one run. Ledee sliced a double
off the warning track in left field to knock in two runs, clapping
his hands three times as he stood on second. Grimsley left with the
3-2 lead in the sixth and was obviously the right man for Sunday's
starting job and maybe for several other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything I could do, I'll do,'' said Grimsley, who worked from
the stretch position, as relievers usually do. ``If they want me to
sweep the floor, I'll do it if they let me wear this uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Einertson said that he would gleefully join Grimsley in lifting
a broom if he could remain in pinstripes. When Einertson was
summoned to replace Grimsley with one out and the potential tying
run on second, he did not know there was a runner on base until he
got to the mound. Einertson used mostly sinkers to retire three of
four batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to stay here as long as I can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Ledee's bloop double in the sixth made it 4-2, Jeff Nelson
destroyed Grimsley's chance for the victory when he allowed two
runs in the seventh. Nelson appeared to pick the snoozing Carlos
Beltran off first base for what would have been the third out and
would have maintained a 4-3 lead. But Beltran was called safe and
Sweeney followed with a run-scoring single. Nelson slammed the
rosin bag behind the mound, angry at the first-base umpire, Jim
Reynolds, and himself.
</P>
<P>
   That simply gave Leyritz a chance to play the hero, a role that
anyone who is nicknamed Elvis and King relishes. Leyritz said he
felt lost at the plate on Saturday and had been unsuccessful for
his first 11 at-bats. That changed when he drove Chris Fussell's
0-1 pitch over the fence in right-center field in the seventh,
giving the Yankees a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody will pretty much do anything that's asked of them,''
Grimsley said. ``Nobody is set in their ways. There's not an ego to
say: `This is my job. This is all I do.' These guys want to win
and, three out of the last four years, you see the results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
