<HEADER>
A8645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-DAY2-04171S     04-16 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-DAY2-04171STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    49ers' Hearst needs another operation
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former Georgia running back Garrison Hearst of the San
Francisco 49ers has suffered another setback in his comeback from a
leg injury that forced him to miss last season.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst broke his left ankle on the first play from scrimmage in
an NFC playoff game against the Falcons in the Georgia Dome on Jan.
9, 1999. The Lincolnton native hasn't played since, and his
recovery has been slowed by circulatory problems in the leg.
</P>
<P>
   The poor blood flow has left the bones in Hearst's foot
susceptible to necrosis, a bone deterioration condition that
developed in Bo Jackson's hip after an injury and forced him to
retire from football.
</P>
<P>
   Niners officials said Hearst will undergo more surgery this
month, but said he still has a ``70 percent chance'' of returning
to the field sometime this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a rare injury,'' San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci
said. ``I don't think the NFL has had to deal with this sort of
thing before. (The doctors) feel this would help get him back on
the field sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Team physician Michael Dillingham noticed problems in Hearst's
ankle after the running back underwent an MRI last week.
</P>
<P>
   (It) showed that the injury is healing slowly but the healing is
not complete,'' Dillingham said in a statement. ``We feel an
additional surgery is necessary to speed up the healing process to
give him a chance to play this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, who ran for a team-record 1,570 yards in 1998, hasn't
yet run at full speed and won't participate in the team's mini-camp
at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, who last year signed former Eagles starter Charlie
Garner to replace Hearst, drafted another running back Sunday. San
Francisco used a fifth-round pick on Texas-El Paso's Paul Smith,
who ranks fourth on the school's career list with 2,539 yards
rushing.
</P>
<P>
   MR. IRRELEVANT
</P>
<P>
   Michael Green, a safety from Northwestern State in Louisiana, is
this year's ``Mr. Irrelevant,'' the title affectionately given to
the last pick of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Green was the 254th choice overall by the Chicago Bears, who
traded down with the Cleveland Browns for the second year in a row
to make the last pick. Chicago gave up the 209th and 225th choices,
getting the 223rd, 232nd and 254th picks from the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nice,'' Green told the Associated Press. ``We play
golf, we go sailing, have a banquet in honor of me. I'll be treated
like a king.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who runs the 40-yard dash in 4.46 seconds, had 99 tackles
last season, broke up 14 passes and had two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like this kid has as good as speed as (anybody),''
said Mark Hatley, Chicago's vice president of player personnel.
``He's a physical kid for 190 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Green thought he would be drafted higher, perhaps as early as
the fourth or fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited,'' he said. ``I just wanted to see my name
called on TV. It was a lot of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   JUST FOR KICKS
</P>
<P>
   One day after spending their first-rounder on Florida State
kicker Sebastian Janikowski, the Raiders selected the first punter
of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland took Texas A&AMP;M punter Shane Lechler, who set an NCAA
record with a 46.7-yard average in his career, in the fifth round,
142nd overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we needed to improve on,'' Raiders coach
John Gruden said of his team's kicking game.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders aren't the first team to spend relatively high picks
on kickers. In 1976, their first year in the NFL, the Seattle
Seahawks spent two third-round picks on kickers _ punter Rick
Engles and kicker Don Bitterlich.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING SPREE
</P>
<P>
   In their attempt to replace All-Pro receiver Keyshawn Johnson,
the New York Jets gambled on a pair of wideouts with troubled
pasts.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Jets traded Johnson to the Buccaneers for a pair
of first-round selections. New York became the first team in NFL
history to make four first-round picks, using them to take a
defensive end, outside linebacker, quarterback and tight end.
</P>
<P>
   In the third round, the Jets took Florida State receiver
Laveranues Coles. Coles was involved in a much-publicized
shoplifting incident with FSU star Peter Warrick. Coles was kicked
off the team by Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden, while Warrick was
suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Jets grabbed Southern Cal receiver Windrell Hayes in
the fifth round. Hayes, who spent time at San Jose State and San
Joaquin Delta College in California, played two seasons for the
Trojans. He was arrested in an illegal check-cashing scheme last
year.
</P>
<P>
   RATTAY ALSO WAITS
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton wasn't the only high-profile passer
who had to wait a long time to get drafted this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Rattay, the record-setting quarterback from Louisiana Tech,
was the 212th pick, going to the 49ers in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough couple of days at times,'' Rattay said. ``I
thought I might have gone higher, but it was worth the wait. I'm
really happy to be going to the 49ers.''
</P>
<P>
   In three seasons at Louisiana Tech, Rattay finished No. 2 in
NCAA history in passing yards (12,746), total offense (12,645) and
touchdown passes (115).
</P>
<P>
   But scouts were concerned about his height (6 feet 1) and the
offense he operated in at Louisiana Tech, in which he played in
shotgun formation and never took a snap under center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard all that stuff,'' Rattay said. ``I'm not really
worried. I just plan to keep working hard and do whatever it
takes.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has some options if star quarterback Steve Young
decides to retire because of recurring concussions. In the third
round, the 49ers drafted Giovanni Carmazzi, the record-setting
quarterback from Division I-AA Hofstra. Carmazzi rushed for 1,044
yards and 32 touchdowns in his college career.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
