u s BC-RUN-MARA-DALESSANDRO-     04-16 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARA-DALESSANDRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US OLYMPC TRIALS IN BOSTON? WHY NOT? SAYS D'ALESSANDRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He was candid, frank, and irreverent as always, saying
he will be in Sydney for the second week of the Olympics. And, yes,
he has received invitations from the International Olympic
Committee to attend some of their events. Gala, as always.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been invited,'' David D'Alessandro, eyebrows raised, said
in mock astonishment. ``To the big ones, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And will he _ one of the most damning critics of rampant
corruption in the IOC _ attend?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably go,'' he replied. ``I mean . . . you know . . .
Rasputin was allowed to go to places, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   And on the eve of the Boston Marathon, D'Alessandro was equally
as frank about US Track &AMP; Field's reluctance to use Boston as its
venue for the US Olympic Trials, even though Kenya, for one, will
use the race as its Olympic qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   USA Track &AMP; Field was formerly known as The Athletics Congress
(TAC).
</P>
<P>
   ``TAC is afraid,'' said D'Alessandro, president of John Hancock
Financial Services Inc., the Marathon sponsor that also puts out
about $2 million and 1,200 volunteers annually for the event.
``They can only make money by going to Pittsburgh (for the men's
qualifier) and South Carolina (women's).''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Marathon has never been used as the US Olympic
qualifier ``because they have this ridiculous rule that the course
is too hilly,'' said D'Alessandro. ``They have this rule about how
much grade you can have in the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my point is that if (the United States) is supposed to
post up its best three runners who can run against international
competition, then why do we insist on this incestuous race with
just Americans?''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the world's best marathoners are in Boston today, he
said. ``This is the only event in America where enough of the
international players come in in the time frame to qualify for the
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   What better race to qualify for the Olympics than one of the
world's more competitive marathons, said D'Alessandro. Even more,
it would be an ideal measuring stick for Americans to use against
many of the competitors they will be facing in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disservice to all those potential athletes who dream of
winning the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   The only sure thing about the US Olympic Trials ``is that an
American is going to win,'' he said. ``Since when do American
athletes run _ or compete _ out of safety? It's not the American
mentality and, supposedly, not our heritage. We're supposed to be
risk-takers and out front in everything we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The result? American marathoning continues in its sad state
because US runners are not tested against the world's best in their
trials. ``It's like Americans are racing in a bubble. It's like the
bubble boy in that movie. (The US Trials) are a controlled
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   According to D'Alessandro, Ireland's John Treacy said it best
``when he said, `You haven't run a marathon until you've run
against the best.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The ``old TAC crowd was much more interested in money than the
new TAC crowd, but money is still the driver,'' he said, noting
there are far too many people in TAC more interested in showcasing
Americans in US-only trials in dreadfully slow times than in
preparing them to do well in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Marathoning ``is one of the few sports I know of where American
athletes, from a competition standpoint, are so frightened. Even in
soccer, we've made a more valiant try. The fact that we're not good
at it makes us not want to compete against the others. Therefore,
every four years, we take America's premier race'' and don't use it
as the US trial. It's ludicrous, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, D'Alessandro pitched the idea of using Boston as the US
trials to US Track &AMP; Field and US Olympic Committee officials. He
said a marathon is not like the 100 meters, or 400 meters. ``You
can see where they could say in those events, `Line up the best
Americans and let them run against each other.' That concept
doesn't work in a marathon because it's not a 9.3-second race. It's
a long, strategic race over varying conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The result?
</P>
<P>
   ``They actually promised us the race verbally back in '88,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But with a catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted the Americans to run ahead of everybody else,''
D'Alessandro said. ``So I made one of my comments. I said, `If you
want the Americans to run ahead of the pack, we'll probably have to
start them at least 45 minutes ahead. Because the Italians, the
Kenyans, and the Japanese are going to run them over.' The BAA
(Boston Athletic Association) actually was considering it,
considering an 11 a.m. start for the Americans, even though they
didn't want it, either. The BAA was just trying to be flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   He again was brutally . . . ah, candid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `That reminds me of when you have a big dinner and you
have a kiddie table for the kids. You know you have those little
card tables. You're putting the Americans at one of those little
card tables.' Then I said that some of the (top international
runners) would still beat some of the Americans, even with their
one-hour headstart. I said, `You guys would love that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Not since Joan Benoit won the gold medal in the 1984 Olympics
has an American won a medal in marathoning. Frank Shorter was the
last US male to win a medal _ in 1976 in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond ``incestuous'' trials, D'Alessandro said US marathoning
has slumped for other reasons. There is no true feeder system in US
colleges for marathoners. ``Colleges get a cross-country kid and
what do they do right away? They put him on a track,'' he said,
pointing out there have to be more scholarships for marathoners.
</P>
<P>
   The more poorly US marathoners do in international competition,
the less interest there is among Americans, he said. The cycle has
to be broken by American improvement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when marathoning in this country . . .
actually was a much more consumer-popular sport,'' said
D'Alessandro. ``When Chicago was a bigger race, when New York
wasn't a fun race, when Los Angeles wasn't a Hollywood race. Now,
there is only one pure marathon left that attracts enough
world-class athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, John Hancock and D'Alessandro first became
involved with the Boston Marathon. ``If you had told me in 1988
that marathons would be less of a sport for American consumers, I
would have thought no,'' he said. ``But I think there has been a
dilution over the last 10 or 12 years where the bigger marathons
have . . . well, not collapsed . . . but have become fun races.''
</P>
<P>
   And is it getting old for D'Alessandro to help shepherd Boston
from Hopkinton to Copley Square?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't have the time anymore,'' he replied. ``But it's
actually what I prefer to do, since I spend much of my time on the
(John Hancock) business, of course. It's not so much getting old .
. . but I do think the Boston Marathon could use some freshness.
The freshness I'd like to see is the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   No shortage of Americans in this year's race. But a very real
shortage of Americans doing well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
