<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE BLUE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Zaher ``Zack'' Zahrey was a police detective with a
spotless record when certain malevolent forces of the criminal
justice system in New York began to close in on him. It was a case
of a corrupt and treacherous system devouring one of its own.
Zahrey would spend several humiliating months in jail and his
career would be ruined before he was finally exonerated by a jury
that took only 10 minutes to reach a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The problems for Zahrey, an undercover narcotics detective,
began early in 1994 when a man named William Rivera was murdered in
a nightclub in Brooklyn. Zahrey and Rivera, a former auxiliary
police officer, had grown up in the Sunset Park section of Brooklyn
and had been friends.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera had been shot with a gun that belonged to an off-duty
police officer and the matter was being investigated by the Police
Department's Internal Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Zahrey told police officials that he had once been close friends
with Rivera and he was asked by Detective Sgt. Robert Boyce of
Internal Affairs to assist in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Zahrey agreed.
</P>
<P>
   It was apparently at that point that a web of incredible lies,
some of them encouraged by the police and other investigators,
began to be woven. Rumors circulated among police officers that
Zahrey had been involved in criminal activities with Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   This was around the time the Mollen Commission was issuing its
report about police corruption. The Internal Affairs Bureau seemed
anxious to come up with a case that would demonstrate its
willingness to go after corrupt cops.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently, a former police informant was found to parrot the
rumors against Zahrey. The informant was a drunk who had once been
arrested when he showed up at a police officer's funeral with a
hand grenade. He was known to be unstable and utterly unreliable.
Nevertheless, Boyce used this man's nutty stories to launch an
official investigation of Zahrey.
</P>
<P>
   What came next was much worse. Rivera had, indeed, been a
criminal. But there was no evidence that Zahrey was involved in any
way. When investigators located a man who really had been linked to
Rivera's illicit activities _ a dangerous career criminal named
Sidney Quick _ they didn't try at all to nail him. They tried
desperately to get Quick to nail Zahrey.
</P>
<P>
   On March 16, 1995, with the investigation of Zahrey going
nowhere, Boyce and another detective visited Quick at Sing Sing
Prison. By then he was serving a sentence of six years to life as a
persistent, violent felony offender. He was ready to tell the
police whatever they wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The cops said they were interested in an armored-car holdup and
the murder of a drug dealer nicknamed J.R.
</P>
<P>
   Zahrey's lawyer, Joel B. Rudin of Manhattan, noted in court
papers that the holdup occurred while Quick was in prison and that
Quick himself was a suspect in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   So here's what Boyce told Quick in a conversation tape-recorded
at Sing Sing: ``If you did something, fine, you did it. If someone
else pulled the trigger when you were there, we can get around it.
You understand what I'm saying?''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what else he said: ``If you give me Zack, I'll drive you
home.'' He said: ``If you tell me Zack was there when J.R. was
killed, he's (expletive) and, and you are looking at a very sweet
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``The deal is Zack. That's what your deal is. You
understand that?''
</P>
<P>
   Quick understood. He told the detectives that Zack most
certainly was involved in the holdup and the murder and some other
crimes as well. There was no other evidence, just the transparent
fantasies of Sidney Quick.
</P>
<P>
   Having encouraged them, the cops now embraced them. And so did
the Brooklyn DA's office, which did its best to keep the Sing Sing
tape hidden, and the office of the U.S. attorney for the Eastern
District, which eventually prosecuted Zahrey on corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   A jury saw through the madness and acquitted Zahrey in June
1997. But the Police Department has never given him back his badge
or his gun. And his only hope for some kind of justice rests with a
lawsuit against the system he once served well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
