<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TRADITIONAL ORGAN MUSIC MAKING A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Lou Lamoriello, that old boat rocker,
wants to change the system. A conservative on many hockey issues,
the president and general manager of the Devils is bucking a trend
by expanding the role of a real, live organ player for the Stanley
Cup playoffs in Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello has not completely eliminated the noisy rock
recordings that have increasingly polluted the aural atmosphere
around the National Hockey League in the last decade. But he is
leading a counterrevolution against what he calls ``the loud and
aggressive music'' that blares mindlessly whenever a whistle stops
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's the traditionalist in me,'' Lamoriello said of the
organ music that was the primary sound of hockey rinks until the
1990s. ``It just brings a different type of environment.'' He said
the organ music during Game 1 against the Florida Panthers on
Thursday night ``brought the old goose bumps'' to his skin and
reminded him of how buildings used to sound. For now, Lamoriello
said, the Devils will blend recorded rock music with live organ
playing. A complete switch to the organ could come next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention is to get the organ to take over,'' Lamoriello
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello said Devils fans reacted positively to the new sound,
sending their thanks through e-mail. The organist, Robert Shaheen,
said fans gave him the thumbs-up signal of approval and one man
told him he called the front office between periods to express his
gratitude for the organ music.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of the younger fans have never been exposed to it,''
Shaheen said Sunday before Game 2 of the Eastern Conference
quarterfinals against the Panthers. His keyboard produces the
traditional tones that he called church and movie theater as
opposed to the horn sounds and other synthetic effects used even
when live musicians perform.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen, who used to play for Islanders games at the Nassau
Coliseum, grew up listening to live organ music in the old Boston
Garden. ``I'm partial to live music,'' Shaheen said. ``I'm a member
of the musicians' union.'' Both Shaheen and Lamoriello used the
phrase ``old-time hockey'' to describe the mood evoked by the
music.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL is monitoring the switch in the Meadowlands as well as
the overall presentation of music and special effects at all rinks.
Frank Supovitz, the NHL's vice president of special events, said
the league does not order specific play lists of recorded music,
though many of the same, annoying songs are played in many cities.
Somehow Queen's ``We Will Rock You'' always seems to be heard,
sometimes even when the home team is down by three goals in the
final minute of play.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the only inappropriate selection. At a Ranger game at
Madison Square Garden, while a player lay writhing on the ice with
a broken leg, the speakers blared ``My Sharona,'' an upbeat song
from the late 1970s. Supovitz, who concerns himself with all
aspects of the NHL experience in the arenas, acknowledged that
overused recordings can have the wrong effect, such as when there
are three face-offs in quick succession and the music blares. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be jarring,'' Supovitz said. ``People know they are
being manipulated, and they don't react to that. You have to pick
the right piece of music for the right moment.'' He said the intent
of using recorded rock songs is to attract ``the young, male
demographic.'' But when they play it, it often makes it impossible
for young men or old women or children or anybody else to talk to
the person sitting next to them.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the league is listening to direct feedback. In the April
issue of Talk magazine, a story about Ted Leonsis told how the new
owner of the Washington Capitals chatted during an intermission
with fans who ``urge the boss to lower the earsplitting volume of
the PA system.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen, so far, plays longer songs before the game and during
intermissions. His repertory includes ``Hello, Dolly,'' ``Isn't She
Lovely?'' and ``Got To Get You Into My Life.'' He also played
``Hungry Heart,'' explaining that playing Bruce Springsteen in New
Jersey is as important as playing Billy Joel on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   When whistles stop play for face-offs, Shaheen stays
traditional, playing various rhythms that lead to shouts of
``Charge!'' or ``Let's go, Devils!'' Some teams play these tunes on
tapes. ``The canned stuff will run short or too long and has to be
stopped in a place that is not appropriate,'' Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
   By listening and interacting with the fans, he said he can
respond immediately to their mood ``if they feel like a certain
cheer or they are riding the opposing goalie in a certain key.'' In
Game 1, Shaheen said, the fans rode a Panthers player ``by singing
in C-sharp.'' It is important, he added, to stay in good taste and
not lead profane taunts. ``Always try to stay appropriate,''
Shaheen said. ``You don't want to overstep. These things are common
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine: Common sense in hockey-rink music. What a concept. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
