<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-MILLER-NYT &LR;      04-16 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER HAS SMALL FEET AND SOME BIG DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALNUT, Calif. _ Inger Miller jogged down the track at UCLA the
other day when her coach, John Smith, began teasing her about her
tiny feet. Earlier, he had pulled one of her shoes out of his
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got those tiny feet on today?'' Smith called out. ``I
can't see them from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoe size, of course, has nothing to do with speed. Miller won
the 1999 world championship at 200 meters in 21.77 seconds, the
fastest time of the year, and finished second to Marion Jones in
the 100 in 10.79 seconds, her best time. She enters this season as
the biggest impediment to Jones' attempt to win five gold medals at
the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The whirlwind of publicity surrounding Jones is fine with
Miller, even beneficial, allowing her to train in relative
anonymity, without the same pressure, expectation or burdensome
news media attention. In September, it is possible that Miller will
match or exceed Jones' gold medal total in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the pressure is on her,'' the 27-year-old Miller said.
``There is no pressure on me. No one cares if Inger Miller wins or
loses. The only thing they care about is whether Marion wins. My
job is to show that it is not a one-woman show. That's a lot easier
than trying to show that it is a woman show.''
</P>
<P>
   A crack in Jones' sprint dominance appeared at the 1999 world
championships in Seville, Spain. Jones withdrew from the 200 during
the semifinals with back spasms, and Miller won the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``People question whether Marion would have won if she had
run,'' Miller said. ``In my mind, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Already Miller is in the Olympic record books as part of the
only father-daughter combination to win medals in track and field.
Her father, Lennox Miller, won a silver medal for Jamaica in the
100 at the 1968 Mexico City Olympics and a bronze medal at the 1972
Munich Olympics. Inger Miller won a gold medal for the United
States in the 4x100-meter relay at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and
finished fourth in the 200. Her godfather, Don Quarrie, won the 200
meters for Jamaica at the 1976 Montreal Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still resentment from Jamaicans in general that she
didn't compete for Jamaica, but considering everything, she is well
received,'' said Lennox Miller, a dentist who, like his daughter,
attended the University of Southern California. He was a relay
partner of O.J. Simpson on a team that set the world record for the
440-yard relay.
</P>
<P>
   Inger Miller's running career became serious when her mother had
a chance encounter in a grocery store with the coach of John Muir
High in Pasadena, Calif., a scholastic power in track and field.
But her college career was interrupted by a broken navicular bone
in her foot in 1994, and just before the Olympic trials for Atlanta
in 1996, she flipped a sport utility vehicle on a California
freeway in a scary accident. She recovered to make the team and won
a gold medal in the relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the culmination of a lot of things we had dreamed of,''
Lennox Miller said. ``Finally, she had reaped the benefits in
athletics. We thought she had the ability, but she never realized
those performances we thought she should have been achieving.''
</P>
<P>
   Lennox Miller coached his daughter until 1998, during lunch
breaks from his dental practice in Pasadena, but the arrangement
was not satisfactory to the career either of the father or
daughter. Last season, she switched amicably to Smith's group,
Handling Speed Intelligently, known by its initials as HSI, which
includes the world's fastest man, Maurice Greene, and Ato Boldon, a
bronze medalist at 100 and 200 meters at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being around us, you can't help but be confident,'' Boldon
said. ``And you can't get away with a bad practice in this group.
Someone will let you know.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Lennox Miller said, his daughter was mainly
interested in sprinting because of her speed and the social aspect
of track and field. ``You're tremendously talented; you've got to
work harder,'' he would exhort her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now she's at the point where she doesn't need that pep talk
anymore,'' Lennox Miller said. ``It's in her.''
</P>
<P>
   Training with HSI has focused and calmed Miller _ ``She's hyper;
a lack of energy is not her problem,'' Smith said _ and has allowed
her to attain her best times in the 100 and 200. Winning the world
championship at 200 meters has also given his daughter the
assurance that she can compete at the elite level, Lennox Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   For motivation she has to look no farther down the track than
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marion has done a wonderful job,'' Smith said. ``You have to
acknowledge it. But you do have the right to dismantle her.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
