<SLUG> BC-TRADE-PROTEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL LEADERS MEET AS PROTESTS CLOG WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 4-9 and locator map are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thousands of protesters looking to shut down
meetings of world financial leaders swarmed through the streets of
the capital Sunday, clashing briefly with police who moved firmly
to quash any unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The finance ministers and other delegates from around the world
were loaded onto buses early Sunday morning and escorted by police
so that their meetings could take place as scheduled. Sunday
evening, they tacitly acknowledged the shouting on the streets by
conceding in a communique issued by the International Monetary Fund
that their role had become a matter ``of growing public debate.''
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledged a widespread fear that ``the benefits of the
world economy'' are ``not reaching everyone, especially in the
developing countries.'' But they offered no new prescriptions,
other than some reforms of the IMF's internal operations that are
already under way.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Saturday, when police arrested some 600 people, on Sunday
they arrested fewer than 20, but responded forcefully to any
challenges, wielding clubs and pepper spray against protesters who
defied them. Several were injured.
</P>
<P>
   All weekend long, the police acted sternly and preemptively,
shutting down the protest headquarters early Saturday morning,
arresting as many as 600 marchers by that evening, and shunting
hordes of protesters around Sunday. The combination allowed police
here mostly to avoid the kind of widespread chaos that disrupted
world trade meetings in Seattle last year, a feat the protesters
said they hoped to repeat.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,500 or so police from city and federal agencies, many in
full riot gear, completely sealed off an area for many blocks
around the buildings housing the World Bank and the IMF, standing
shoulder-to-shoulder behind fencelike metal barricades.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the barricades, demonstrators roamed the
streets almost at will, hoisting giant puppets and signs _ a pig
labled IMF with the world in its mouth like an apple, red hands
that said ``spank the bank'' _ and accusing the financial
institutions of burdening poor Third World countries with crushing
debts, impoverishing peasants, destroying rain forests, and
supporting sweatshops and other policies that, as one sign put it,
``saps the poor to fatten the rich.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the day, the protests were peaceful, if vociferous.
Perhaps 10,000 gathered on the grassy Ellipse near the White House
for a legal rally calling for changes in the world financial
systems.
</P>
<P>
   But there were at least two short, sharp clashes between police
and demonstrators, where the police used pepper spray and what
appeared to be a form of anti-riot gas or smoke grenades and
charged into protesters, beating them with long sticks. And there
were other moments of tension.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Anthony Williams said Sunday evening that the police
``have got this under control as much as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is like steering a raft down a raging river,'' he said.
``You can control it, but then the unexpected can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the police had acted Sunday with appropriate force when
challenged, and that the mass arrests of peaceful protesters
Saturday night were justified as a matter of prudence. And he urged
the city's workforce to ``stay out of downtown if at all possible''
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a serious situation,'' he said. ``It is simmering down,
but again, people have been on the street for a long time, so
nerves are frazzled. There is a sense of anxiety and
anticipation.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite failing to achieve their avowed goal of blocking the
finance ministers from attending the meeting, by late afternoon
many of the protesters were jubilant at the attention drawn to
their sometimes diffuse cause, which drew many of the same groups
that descended on Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a victory party in the street,'' said Patrick
Rensborough, one of the spokesmen for the Mobilization for Global
Justice, the umbrella organization coordinating the protest
</P>
<P>
   ``We're celebrating that this movement has come about,'' he went
on, standing at the edge of the rally in the Ellipse that went for
most of the afternoon. ``A few days ago most Americans didn't know
the first thing about the World Bank or the IMF. These institutions
can't survive public scrutiny. This is the first step toward
shutting them down.''
</P>
<P>
   While the marchers paraded below with their signs bearing
slogans like ``Defund the Fund,'' the leaders of the IMF were
upstairs arguing over different issues _ including who should get a
bigger voice in running the institution.
</P>
<P>
   Japan staged a minor rebellion aimed at winning a larger voice
for itself and other Asian nations in the fund's operations. Tokyo
had put up a candidate to run the IMF earlier this year, although
by tradition the managing director has always been a European. (An
American has always run the World Bank.) Though the effort did not
get very far Sunday, the world's second-largest economy was clearly
laying down a marker that it no longer planned to acquiese to the
old order. ``There's a sense that this has always been a white
man's club,'' one senior Japanese official said recently, ``and
that needs some rethinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several leaders of smaller nations said during the
meeting that they were alarmed by reform proposals _ including
those developed by a congressional commission _ that would limit
the size and duration of the fund's loans during economic crises.
They fear it would reduce the funds made available to them.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast with the message being delivered by demonstrators
outside could not have been sharper. While developing nations fear
that the IMF money could dry up, many of those on the street were
arguing that those same funds hurt the poor because they often come
with so many strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   The communique issued at the end of the meeting bore no
surprises. But it clearly anticipated the din outside. It
acknowledged that the growing debate over the future of the fund
and the World Bank ``reflects a concern that the benefits the world
economy is deriving from freer trade and more integrated and deeper
international capital markets are not reaching everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8659 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TRADE-PROTEST-ART-2ND     04-16 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-PROTEST-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: reaching everyone.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But in the end, it prescribed the kind of changes the fund says
it is already pursuing: more disclosure about the financial state
of member countries, more involvement of the private sector in
international bailouts, a crackdown on the kind of misreporting of
financial data that took the IMF by surprise in its dealings with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   It called for closer work with the World Bank ``to lead in
helping countries to develop policies to combat poverty and improve
social conditions,'' carefully steering around the arguments over
how much of that responsibility should fall to the bank _ the
traditional poverty-fighter _ and how much to the fund, which
manages international financial crises.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the sun came up, clumps of 20 or 30 demonstrators
were moving through the streets toward assembly points at Farragut
Park and Washington Circle. By seven o'clock they had blocked all
of the intersections around the police perimeter, erecting
barricades near the George Washington University campus made with
tipped-over garbage dumpsters, old furniture and about a dozen bags
of mulch intended for the university's gardens, which they used
like sandbags.
</P>
<P>
   But the police were up even earlier.
</P>
<P>
   They began picking up the finance ministers and other delegates
at the Watergate, the Four Seasons and other luxury hotels as early
as 5 a.m., loading them into buses and vans and shuttling them in
caravans escorted by police motorcycles and cars, lights flashing
and sirens wailing, on circuitous routes that eventually took them
through the sealed-off stretch of Pennsylvania Avenue past the
White House and two blocks farther to the IMF meeting.
</P>
<P>
   With the meeting safely under way, the police tactics for most
of the day consisted mainly of maintaining their perimeter.
Saturday, they had moved aggressively, shutting down the
protester's headquarters, declaring that it was a ``fire hazard,''
and arresting some 600 people after they had boxed them in on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Taking their cue from the Seattle protests, the police were far
better prepared this time. They have been training for weeks, have
bought $1 million worth of new equipment, including shin guards,
chest protectors and big gauntlets, and expect a $1.6 million
overtime bill.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, including several hundred self-styled
anarchists called the ``Black block,'' dressed solidly in black
down to their combat boots, most with sweatshirt hoods and bandana
masks obscuring their faces, marched and wandered throughout the
largely deserted downtown.
</P>
<P>
   At the midpoint of a sunny afternoon, protesters from the
Ellipse rally merged with a crowd coming from the George Washington
campus into a huge parade through Foggy Bottom and back to the
Ellipse, chanting, ``This is what democracy looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was overwhelmingly young; many of its elements were
organized on college campuses. And there were a few graying
veterans of 1960s demonstrations, including the comedian Dick
Gregory and Tom Hayden, one of the organizers of the 1968
Democratic convention protests and now a California state senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inspiring,'' said Dan Swanson, 47, who marched with
Students for a Democratic Society in his youth. ``They're much more
disciplined and aware than we were at that age.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
