<HEADER>
A8664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-IMF-PROTESTS-BOS &LR;      04-16 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-PROTESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMONSTRATORS CLOG CAPITAL'S STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thousands of chanting activists, some wearing
combat boots and gas masks in preparation for violent clashes with
police, mobbed the streets of the nation's capital and tried to
disrupt meetings of world finance leaders Sunday, the first such
demonstration since the riotous protests against the World Trade
Organization in Seattle last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Police fired tear gas at one point, and an isolated group of
self-described ``anarchists'' repeatedly tried to break through
police barriers, smashing security car windows and splashing
emergency vehicles with red paint. But the feared repeat of Seattle
did not occur, and at times the event took on a carnival
atmosphere, as an estimated 10,000 marchers shouted and danced
their way through otherwise deserted downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the finance officials were successfully whisked into
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund for a day of
meetings. From there they could see the giant banners on display
outside, among them ``Make Love, Not Debt,'' ``Shut Down
Capitalism!'' and ``Economic Justice Now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the protesters perhaps have some points,'' said Mario
Vicens, the treasury secretary for Argentina, who was attending a
meeting at the IMF. ``But this is not the way to change things.''
</P>
<P>
   As in Seattle, the demonstrators came bearing a wide range of
complaints, from the impact of globalization on the environment to
the domination of a ``prison-industrial complex'' to human rights
abuses in East Timor. But they were unified against a single enemy:
the financial institutions of the developed world, whom they accuse
of creating economic policies that concentrate power and money
among a wealthy few.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to speak for those who can't speak,'' said Deepinder
Mayell, 20, a sophomore political science major from Boston
College. The problem, he said, is the increasing ``top-to-bottom''
structure of world economics, in which the poor in struggling
countries suffer for the benefit of everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are starting to realize the whole idea of economic
liberalization is the liberalization of exploitation of the poor,''
agreed Thomas Redman, a protester from California. ``Hopefully
people will get out and vote now.''
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested only about 20 people Sunday _ a mere shadow of
the 600 protesters detained on Saturday for parading without a
permit. Throughout the day, authorities kept a 50-block area of
downtown blocked off from protesters, but confronted the roaming
masses of activists only when they tried to break within the
security zone.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few violent outbursts. Several hours after police
successfully escorted the finance officials into their meetings _ a
mission accomplished, in some cases, in the predawn hours _ a group
of the ``anarchists'' tried to lunge through a police barricade not
far from the White House. The police responded with tear gas and
pepper spray, riding their motorcycles into the group until the
crowd dispersed. Many demonstrators were also beaten with clubs,
witnesses said, even as they shouted: ``Peaceful protest!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of tear gas is something we don't resort to unless we
absolutely have to,'' Washington Police Chief Charles Ramsey said
later at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   At around noon, another group dressed in black clothing and
combat boots tried to storm a line of police several blocks from
the IMF, chanting, ``Whose streets? Our streets!'' But because the
protesters were not threatening either the World Bank or the IMF
buildings, the police decided to simply drive away. Several
demonstrators then overturned Dumpsters, and one youth smashed the
rear window of a George Washington University police car.
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, the protests were overwhelmingly peaceful.
Thousands of people converged on a park near the White House known
as the Ellipse to attend the ``legal demonstration,'' an event
involving planned speeches. Elsewhere, the streets resembled a
college campus quad, or even the colorful Washington Square Park in
New York, more than the site of an angry political protest.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 1,000 students from Massachusetts _ and more than 300
from the Boston area _ made the pilgrimage to Washington, joining
thousands of young activists from across the country who converged
on the nation's capital at the end of last week.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Nugent, 20, a junior at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst, was among them. He said he was motivated by ``human
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're trying to alleviate here,'' Nugent said, as
a group of protesters chanted nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Nugent admitted he had made the trip _ along with 500 students
from the five-college consortium of schools in Western
Massachusetts _ in part because of what he saw happen in Seattle.
Before that, he said, he ``didn't really know what it was all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Alex Cheney, 20, a sophomore from Boston College
who knew all about last year's WTO protests: He witnessed them,
having traveled to Seattle as part of a sociology project on global
justice. Sunday, Cheney said the police in Washington appeared far
better prepared _ and restrained _ than the Seattle police.
``They've stayed out of it for the most part,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's almost a festival atmosphere,'' said Mayell, his
friend.
</P>
<P>
   There were sideshows everywhere. In a park across the street
from the World Bank, three women wearing shiny red formal gowns did
an interpretive performance of ``The Communist Manifesto.'' A block
away, a group of about a dozen protesters performed t'ai chi on a
lawn. One man played the clarinet on the sidewalk on 21st Street.
Several protesters carried giant puppets representing the heads of
the WTO, the IMF, and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In an angrier display, one demonstrator vandalized a bust of
George Washington at the entrance to George Washington University,
scribbling the word ``racist.'' Demonstrators hung a sign across
the entrance to a Chinese restaurant that read: ``World Bank + IMF
(EQ) Starving people.''
</P>
<P>
   There was even a protest for Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Burkhart, 40, of Arlington, Va., wore a sign that read:
``USA. Stop the Delay. Send Elian home now.'' Burkhart, who is
deaf, then wrote on a piece of paper that the greed of global
capitalists and the Miami relatives of the 6-year-old Cuban boy
were intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote: ``I am here to protest the IMF, Elian and the WTO.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
