<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 04/16/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- April 16, 2000 -- TRADE-VOICES -- Mike
Saltz, 22, a student at the University of Oregon in Eugene, sitting
on a park bench Sunday in the middle of downtown Washington.
Saturday, however, was a totally different experience for Saltz,
who was swept up in a mass arrest of roughly 600 people near the
IMF and World Bank headquarters. While simply trying to find some
friends at a rally, Saltz says he was corralled, arrested, cuffed
wrist to ankle and charged with parading without a permit, an
infraction legally less serious than a misdemeanor. ``I was really
shocked,'' he says. ``When it comes to disagreeing with the
dominant view, your rights are really out the window. They can do
whatever they want, they're the police.'' (Stephen Crowley/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- April 16, 2000 -- SIEGFRIED-OPERA-REVIEW --
Graham Clark, left, as Mime and Stig Andersen, a Danish tenor, as
Siegfried at the Metropolitan Opera, part of Wagner's four-part
``Ring'' cycle. The opera has nearly four hours of music, and
Siegfried, the toughest dramatic tenor role in the entire
repertory, sings during most of it. He must portray an impulsive
and brawny youth. Yet it takes most tenors years to develop the
vocal heft and stamina to handle the music. (Sara Krulwich/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 16, 2000 -- JESUS-THEATER-REVIEW --
Glenn Carter has the title role in ``Jesus Christ Superstar,'' the
Andrew Lloyd Webber musical at the Ford Center for the Performing
Arts. ``Jesus Christ Superstar,'' which began as a concept record
album in 1970 before its varied reincarnations on stage and film,
has never been easy to translate into visual terms. Staged by the
Australian director Gale Edwards, the play follows a fairly
straightforward approach, clearly aimed at young audiences and
awash in emblems of youth-courting topicality. (Sara Krulwich/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- April 16, 2000 -- TRADE-LEVIN -- Rep.
Sander M. Levin is a liberal Democrat from the Detroit suburbs who
proudly owns a 94 percent career voting record with organized
labor. Levin hardly fits the classic free-trade profile. Yet, the
68-year-old legislator is fine-tuning a plan that could give
wavering House Democrats the political cover they want to vote yes
on a the biggest trade deal of the decade, an accord with China.
``I'm an activist internationalist who's worked on both sides,
expanded trade and expanded issues of trade,'' says Levin. (Susana
Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- April 16, 2000 -- TRADE-PROTEST-6 -- Police
stand near the IMF and World Bank headquarters in downtown
Washington on Sunday, where the international lending agencies'
meetings are taking place. Sporadic violence flared in the nation's
capital as thousands of anti-globalization protesters, including
anarchists and environmental radicals, massed in the streets in an
effort to disrupt the meetings. The demonstrations were mainly
peaceful but in some incidents police resorted to riot tactics to
quell protests that threatened to get out of hand. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- April 16, 2000 -- TRADE-PROTEST-5 -- Police
and protesters clash Sunday morning during a protest attended by
hundreds against the World Bank and International Monetary Fund
meetings in Washington. The demonstrations were mainly peaceful but
in some incidents police resorted to riot tactics to quell protests
that threatened to get out of hand. Thousands of activists from
anarchists to environmental radicals, have flocked to the nation's
capital vowing to shut down the meetings. (Susana Raab/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- April 16, 2000 -- TRADE-PROTEST-4 --
Sporadic violence flared in Washington on Sunday, as thousands of
protesters massed in the streets of the nation's capital in an
effort to disrupt key meetings of the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund. Protesters attempt to block the path
of a van taking global financial officials to their meetings,
Sunday. (Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- April 16, 2000 -- TRADE-PROTEST-3 -- Masses
of shouting anti-globalization protesters, including anarchists and
environmental radicals, march in the nation's capital Sunday,
trying to disrupt meetings of IMF policymakers and the World Bank.
But early sessions got under way as delegates were spirited to work
under extreme security. An estimated 2,000 police officers from
Washington and elsewhere are reported to have been mobilized for
the demonstrations, which are expected to continue on Monday when
World Bank policymakers are due to meet. (Susana Raab/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- April 16, 2000 -- TRADE-PROTEST-2 --
Thousands of activists, from anarchists to environmental radicals,
have flocked to Washington vowing to shut down the meetings of IMF
policymakers and the World Bank. Protestors accuse the institutions
of impoverishing developing countries by imposing programs which
benefit multinational companies. Many of the demonstrators, with
tear gas masks in hand, were ready to take on local police, but
failed to stop the IMF policy meeting which went ahead as planned,
Sunday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- April 16, 2000 -- TRADE-PROTEST-1 --
Recalling an earlier era, protesters threw flowers at policeman
gathered to contain crowds on the streets of Washington during a
protest attended by hundreds against the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund meeting, Sunday. As crowds swelled,
police fired tear gas and clubbed and kicked demonstrators
attempting to disrupt the meeting, witnesses said. Protestors
accuse the institutions of impoverishing developing countries by
imposing programs which benefit multinational companies. (Susana
Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- April 16, 2000 -- COMPUTER-BRIEFS -- Alex
Stark, an expert in feng shui, the Chinese art of harmonious
balance, conducts a ceremony at the cyberspace premises of the
Corcoran Group, Corcoran.com., which sells luxury homes. ``Feng
shui is all about energy, and a Web site is pure energy,'' says
Barbara Corcoran, owner and founder of the Corcoran Group. ``If we
do $50 billion in sales in the first month after our relaunch,
we'll know what to attribute it to.'' (Barbara Alper/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 16, 2000 -- WEB-SPEEDUP-2 --
Anyone who has ever watched a complex Web page paint itself onto
the computer screen, image by grudgingly slow image, can attest
that the World Wide Web should be faster. On that simple
proposition there is virtually unanimous agreement. Akamai,
co-founded by Daniel Lewin, seated at left, with Paul Sagan, uses
the content distribution technique to improve Web performance. (Jim
Bourg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) FOSTER CITY, Calif. -- April 16, 2000 -- WEB-SPEEDUP-1 --
Anyone who has ever watched a complex Web page paint itself onto
the computer screen, image by grudgingly slow image, can attest
that the World Wide Web should be faster. On that simple
proposition there is virtually unanimous agreement. Inktomi, based
in Foster City, Calif., co-founded by Eric Brewer, 33, chief
scientist, right, with president and chief executive David
Peterschmidt, 52, uses ``caching'' to improve Web performance.
(Thor Swift/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
