<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KOMANOFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANNAH KOMANOFF, 89, A POLITICAL PIONEER  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hannah Komanoff, the first woman elected to the board of
supervisors in Nassau County, N.Y., died on April 9 at a hospital
in Long Beach, on Long Island. She was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Komanoff, a Democrat, was elected to the board from Long Beach,
where she lived much of her life, in 1973, and served three terms
from 1974 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
   She opposed nuclear power development on Long Island and a
proposed bridge across Long Island Sound from Oyster Bay to Rye.
She was also a trustee and president of the Long Beach Board of
Education from 1957 to 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Komanoff, who lived in Lido Beach, N.Y., for the last 11 years,
was born in the Bronx on July 28, 1910, and graduated from New York
University in 1931.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to to Long Beach in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Isidore Komanoff, died in 1985. She is survived by
two daughters, Frederica Miceli of Manhattan and Ruth Underwood of
Studio City, Calif.; a son, Charles Komanoff of Manhattan; a
brother, Stanley Winters of Port Charlotte, Fla.; and five
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
