<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY STOCK SELL-OFF CAUSES A WAVE OF ANXIETY
</P>
<P>
   The steep drop last week in the price of technology stocks,
punctuating a three-week slide, seems to mark a turning point in
perceptions. Unless the technology shares rebound quickly, the
Internet industry will no longer be seen as a sure thing for
investors and entrepreneurs hoping to cash in quickly.
</P>
<P>
   A few bad days are one thing, but with the shares of many
leading technology companies down by 40 percent or 50 percent in
less than a month, the sell-off is causing anxiety across the New
Economy.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA ECONOMY SURGED IN QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   China's economy showed surprising signs of strength in the first
quarter, with gross domestic product rising 8.1 percent, suggesting
that a slide in growth rate may be ending.
</P>
<P>
   FINDING BALANCE FOR E-COMMERCE
</P>
<P>
   Alex Stark, an expert in feng shui, the ancient Chinese art of
harmonious balance, brought his talents to cyberspace last week. He
performed a feng shui ceremony at the Web site of Corcoran.com,
which sells luxury homes, concluding that the site was not aligned
to promote harmony _ or e-commerce. Dissonant elements included
misplaced ``help'' and ``dream'' buttons. Barbara Corcoran, whose
Corcoran Group runs the site, said that she asked her Web designer
to retune the site.
</P>
<P>
   RALLY SUPPORTS A COKE SETTLEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Former employees of Coca-Cola and activists who want the
soft-drink company to settle a racial discrimination suit began a
five-day bus trip that will end Wednesday at the company's annual
shareholder meeting.
</P>
<P>
   NEW EFFORTS IN JOURNALISM DIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Forum and the John S. and James L. Knight Foundation
are underwriting at least $5.5 million of new efforts to increase
the number of blacks, Asian-Americans, American Indians and Latinos
entering journalism.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA PRESS BARON ASSAILS BISHOP
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Black, the Canadian press baron, attacked the local
bishop in Calgary, Alberta, early this month, writing in The
Calgary Herald that the bishop was a Leninist-style ``useful
idiot,'' among other things. Calgary's Christian leaders condemned
the statement.
</P>
<P>
   PARENTS DISPUTE A DAUGHTER'S TALE
</P>
<P>
   The article ``Party's Over'' in the April issue of Allure is
full of family intrigue, sex and alcohol abuse. In the article,
Taylor Stein _ blond habitue of the New York party circuit, speaks
at length about how the childhood neglect she suffered contributed
to her alcoholism. But there is one question of ethics raised by
the article: The magazine never checked out Stein's stories with
her parents, and in fact points out that it obtained the interview
on the condition that it would not do so. Her parents now say the
tale is a fabrication.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY HURDLES FOR ONLINE MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   The record companies BMG and Sony Music Entertainment recently
announced long-awaited plans to sell their music online through
digital downloads. But the fine print suggests that mainstream
Internet users are not going to buy their music digitally any time
soon. Despite the promise of digital downloads for the masses, the
technical challenges could continue to confine the audience mainly
to college students.
</P>
<P>
   NEW APPROACH TO `AFFINITY PORTALS'
</P>
<P>
   A fresh spin is emerging on ``affinity portals'' _ gateways
aimed at every slice of the Internet population. Rather than spend
millions persuading group members to come to a portal designed for
them, companies are working with associations that already cater to
such groups to build portals for their members.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND CAREERS FOR `SEINFELD' ACTORS
</P>
<P>
   The second bananas of ``Seinfeld'' are turning up in campaigns
for products ranging from cars and candy to soft drinks and
prescription drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
