A8683 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-PROTESTS-SCENE-BOS &LR;      04-16 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROTESTS-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE, PROTESTERS BOTH MAKE THEIR POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With gas masks on their faces and nightsticks in
hand, riot police Sunday peered across a steel barricade near the
White House at a surging wave of protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Police Chief Charles Ramsey, who had vowed that the
demonstrators ``aren't burning our city like they burned Seattle,''
edged closer as the crowd advanced across the remnants of broken
bottles that officers had dodged earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the protesters wore bandanas over their faces. They had
etched their lawyers' phone numbers on their arms. And some had
spoken of anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   But as Ramsey prepared to issue a command, the demonstrators
stopped short, inches from the police line and several blocks from
the targets of the crowd's wrath: world financial leaders who were
at the headquarters of the World Bank and International Monetary
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   No mayhem. No mass arrests. No black mark on the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what democracy looks like!'' the demonstrators
chanted, as Ramsey issued the ``all clear.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the ominous buildup, the first major demonstration
against the World Bank and IMF since a disastrous riot last year in
Seattle began with only isolated and relatively minor violence.
Police clubbed several protesters, squirted pepper spray in the
eyes of several others, and unleashed tear gas to quell another
skirmish.
</P>
<P>
   But in a city where generations of Americans have aired their
grievances, day one of the two-day ``Mobilization for Global
Justice'' may be remembered as a footnote in the annals of social
protest, a pale successor to the tear-gas clouded antiwar rallies
of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, organizers failed to shut down or substantially
disrupt the meeting of world economic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this march on Washington had the flavor of a new
revolution for a new century. Steelworkers stood shoulder to
shoulder with socialists. Environmental activists shared the
streets with protesters seeking freedom for a convicted police
killer. A banner promoting the Progressive Librarians Guild
fluttered near a placard that said, ``Poodles Before Profits.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial leaders of the richest nations have become symbols
of all that the demonstrators detest, from Third World poverty to
the shrinking polar cap. And the number of grievances was nearly as
vast as the size of the crowd, about 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the convergence of a lot of groups that finally have
found they have more in common than what was dividing them,'' said
Will Miller, a philosophy professor at the University of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, hoisting a ``Green Mountain Veterans for Peace'' sign
across from the White House, arrived in Washington with two
busloads of Vermonters. A longtime social activist, he said he was
heartened by what he considered the most exuberant protest movement
since ``the disinvestment struggle in the mid-1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that graying veterans of the 1960s counterculture
clasped hands with teenage vegans. There were antiviolence
activists and avowed agitators. Some flashed peace signs at riot
police as others set upon unoccupied police cruisers, smashing
windows, flattening tires, and spray-painting the vehicles with an
``A'' for ``anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   They converged from across the country for a burst of street
theater, played out amid the scream of sirens and the whir of a
hovering police helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the hurly-burly, the peaceful took solace in their
solidarity despite their failure to ruin the economic summit. ``The
fact that so many people came out makes it less disappointing,''
said Karen Benson of Andover, N.H., a student at Gordon College in
Wenham, Mass. ``We've come a long way in educating people about
what's wrong so something can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that there were so many issues to cover: the Navy
bombing range in Puerto Rico, the Singrauli power plant in India,
human rights abuses in Ethiopia, Kenya, and Cameroon, among other
consequences of ``neocolonialism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a big statement,'' said Rebecca Riofrio, a union
organizer from Hartford. ``But speaking with one voice is the best
way to challenge institutions that are working to make sure things
don't change.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the message was simple. As the economic ministers
dined on shrimp and chicken entrees amid extraordinary security,
protesters who were cordoned off blocks away hoisted signs that
said, ``Eating is political.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
