<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-DIEHARD-NYT &LR;      04-16 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DIEHARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON TAKES DIEHARD 500 TO END LOSING STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Seconds after he crossed the finish line as
the winner of the DieHard 500 Sunday, Jeff Gordon began yelling and
screaming and waving his arms, a sustained outpouring of emotion
that once was reserved for clinching his three Nascar Winston Cup
Series titles.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a different time for Gordon, and Sunday's victory
spelled relief with a capital R. It also helped silence many of
Gordon's budding critics. He came into Sunday's race without a
victory in his last 13 races, conspicuous futility for a driver who
had won 40 races from 1996 through 1999. It was his 50th victory
over all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it hasn't been forever, but it has been a while and
we've had to listen to a lot of things,'' Gordon said after taking
the lead with five laps to go and holding on to edge Mike Skinner
by less than a fifth of a second _ about two car lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The criticisms take a toll on you eventually,'' Gordon added.
``When you get knocked down a notch, it's tough. I think this
showed what we're made of when we're down.''
</P>
<P>
   What made this victory even sweeter for the 28-year-old Gordon
is that he won after starting from the 36th position, a Talladega
record. He broke the mark for the worst starting position for a
winner, held by Dale Earnhardt Sr., who won from the 27th spot in
last year's Winston 500.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon learned during the race that the middle lane in the
sometimes three-wide racing gave his car more kick. He first
surfaced among the top 10 racers by Lap 40. After being shuffled
back for most of the next 40 laps, he re-emerged for good among the
contenders by Lap 90.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were in the middle lane, you could go to the front,''
he said. ``If you weren't, you'd go to the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon took the lead for the first time on the 103rd lap and led
another 23 laps of the 188-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think coming from 36th that we could do what we did
today,'' he said. ``I was just in shock that I got the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The shock had worn off by the time he reached victory lane,
$159,755 richer.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the ninth different winner through nine races this
season, moved from 12th to seventh in the Winston Cup standing.
Mark Martin, who finished sixth despite leading 99 laps, took the
overall point lead from Bobby Labonte, who was part of a 16-car
pileup and finished 21st.
</P>
<P>
   No leaders were involved in the wreck, which came on Lap 137
heading into the track's 2.66-mile trioval. The rookie Scott Pruett
caused it after he suddenly dropped low on the track. There was one
problem with that move: Michael Waltrip occupied that spot. The
affected cars quickly began ricocheting off one another, with smoke
creating a haze over the crunching sounds of high-powered
machinery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was minding my own business _ they just ran into me,'' said
Waltrip, who planned to run Monday in the Boston Marathon as a
diversion from ``this craziness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real proud of this group of drivers to that point,''
Waltrip said. ``But just one mistake and you get a wreck like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Musgrave, one of four drivers treated and released from the
infield medical center, said he thought he had dodged the mess
until he was hit from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``From there we were just a Ping-Pong ball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other drivers treated were Tony Stewart, Steve Park and Dick
Trickle. ``I never liked restrictor-plate racing,'' Stewart said,
referring to the devices used to reduce speeds. ``It's not real
racing to me. Eventually, this was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 16 of the 43 cars completed all 188 laps.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, the defending Winston Cup champion, persevered,
though the race turned sour for him on the 120th lap. Running
second, Jarrett ran out of gas before he could reach pit road. He
compounded that by getting flagged for speeding as he left pit
road, drawing a penalty that left him 33rd when he rejoined the
field. He finished 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt flirted with his third straight Talladega victory
before finishing a close third, helping Chevrolet gain the top four
places. It was the sixth top-10 performance this season for
Earnhardt, who will be 49 later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt had faltered for several years after a 1996 wreck
here, the most severe of his career. His car was bumped into a
wall, flipped and slid down the track on its side as two other cars
buffeted him around. He fractured his sternum and collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been eating his Wheaties or something,'' Rusty Wallace
said Sunday. ``I don't think he ever thought he'd be this strong.
It's pretty inspiring.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 2217EDT &QL; 
