<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8685 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-MUGABE-BOS &LR;      04-16 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-MUGABE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUGABE GIVES BLESSING TO VETERANS' FARM TAKEOVERS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ One day after a white farmer and two opposition
leaders were killed in separate acts of political violence,
Zimbabwe President Robert Mugabe defied rising domestic and
international pressure to restore the rule of law in his country
and called on supporters yesterday to continue invading white-owned
commercial farms.
</P>
<P>
   Returning from a week in Cuba, Mugabe reversed a call by his
deputy for an end to the farm attacks carried out by veterans of
Zimbabwe's liberation war and others loyal to the president. The
invasions twice have been ruled illegal by the country's High Court
since they started two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is an expectation that I will say to the war
veterans, `Get off the land.' I will not say or do that,'' Mugabe
said, blaming white farmers and opposition supporters for the
country's turmoil. ``To my supporters, I say retaliate. Hit back,
but don't kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe has slid into a state of near-anarchy as Mugabe
struggles to fend off a rapidly growing opposition movement that
poses the first real threat to his rule in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago the Movement for Democratic Change, or MDC, which
has its roots in the labor sector, rallied workers to reject a new
constitution proposed by Mugabe and his ruling Zimbabwe African
National Union-Patriotic Front. A nationwide survey conducted by
Gallup last February found that 68 percent of rural and urban
adults had ``not much, very little, or no confidence'' in Mugabe,
giving movement leaders confidence that they can win at least 65
percent of the seats in upcoming parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Rattled by the defeat of his draft constitution, Mugabe resorted
to the emotional issue of land to shore up his support, inciting
war veterans, a tiny but influential constituency, to invade
white-owned farms. The veterans fought against colonial Rhodesia to
recover land, the most fertile of which lies predominantly in white
hands, but remain landless 20 years after independence.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's supporters have invaded more than 900 farms since late
February. The police, widely seen as progovernment, have done
little to intervene or comply with the High Court's orders to
remove the squatters. Although the attacks were hostile, damage was
restricted mostly to property until late last week, when political
violence escalated sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The first farmer to be killed, David Stevens, was hauled off his
land Saturday by about 40 government supporters and taken to a
police station in the town of Morowe, northeast of the capital,
Harare. Five fellow farmers followed Stevens to the station, where
they were handcuffed and handed back over to the angry mob.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving white men said they were beaten repeatedly with
metal pipes. Stevens, reported to be an MDC activist, and a friend,
John Osbourne, were then taken to the headquarters of the war
veterans association, where they were beaten again. The two men
were moved a third time, to a location outside town, where Stevens,
a father of four, was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Lying in a hospital bed Sunday, Osbourne told reporters that
``they took David around the back'' of a building, ``they beat him
up very badly and then they shot him'' with a shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not about land,'' Osbourne said. ``It was about
politics. None of those vets was interested in land. The major
pummeling we got was trying to get us to say we're all MDC.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Saturday, two movement officials were burned to death
when their car was hit with a Molotov cocktail, according to
opposition spokesmen. That attack follows an ambush late last week
that remains somewhat murky.
</P>
<P>
   According to Job Sikhala, the movement's head of security and
intelligence, three buses carrying opposition leaders and
supporters from a rally was attacked last Tuesday near Mt. Darwin,
a town nearly two hours from Harare. Sikhala, who received injuries
in the attacks, said five people were killed, 66 were injured, and
33 more went missing. Zimbabwean defense forces broke up the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The chief police inspector in Bindura, where many of the victims
were taken to a hospital, denied that anyone was killed.
</P>
<P>
   There are growing indicators that Mugabe is becoming
increasingly isolated at home. Last week the military chiefs said
publicly that Zimbabwe's armed forces, long a formidable ally of
Mugabe, would be loyal to whoever won the parliamentary elections,
which must be held before Aug. 11, according to constitutional
rules. Last week, the High Court rejected the government's
assertions that it could not stop the farm invasions, and ordered
police to evict the squatters.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the court's ruling last Thursday, Vice President
Joseph Msika, acting on Mugabe's behalf, called for an end to the
campaign against the farmers. Government sources said Msika had
consulted with Mugabe prior to issuing his statement, and that
three top ministers held meetings throughout the weekend to
persuade the veterans to comply with the court order. Reversing
those efforts Sunday, Mugabe increased his government's
antagonistic stance. ``We have warned the white farmers not to be
provocative, not to take up arms, not to resist,'' he said. ``If
they do not they will suffer the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in India on Sunday, British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said Mugabe was overseeing ``the destruction of his own
country.'' Mugabe accuses Britain, Zimbabwe's colonial power, of
blocking land reform, even though London has donated roughly $70
million for farm transfers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
