u k BC-EDIT-SC-FLAG-NYT &LR;      04-16 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SC-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE REBEL FLAG IN SOUTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, April 17:
</P>
<P>
   When South Carolinians brag about their state, they typically
talk about the beautiful beaches and the bustling industrial
corridor between Spartanburg and Greenville. But the attempt to
portray the Palmetto State as a good place to vacation and do
business has been tarnished for years by the Legislature's refusal
to remove the Confederate flag from the Statehouse dome.
</P>
<P>
   The flag continues to fly despite condemnation by the state's
major business leaders and an economic boycott that has prompted
sports figures and entertainers to decline appearances in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for keeping the flag have tried to portray it as an
important historical symbol of Southern pride. But in recent
decades the Confederate battle flag has been used primarily as a
symbol of resistance to civil rights and full equality for black
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The flag's defenders seemed to relent last week, when the state
Senate advanced a plan that would remove this emblem from the
Capitol's dome and place it near a Confederate memorial in front of
the building. Unable to block the measure, black senators agreed to
the plan, saying it was the best they could hope for.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate compromise has generated protest from black
lawmakers in the state's House of Representatives, who rightly
point out that every black person who does business in the
Statehouse would be required to walk directly by this emblem of
segregation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the NAACP's South Carolina branch has unanimously
rejected the deal. The group's national president, Kweisi Mfume,
issued a blistering statement, saying the deal ``added insult to
injury'' and threatening to expand an economic boycott that is
clearly hurting the state.
</P>
<P>
   In principle, a flag that symbolizes racism and segregation has
no place at all on state property, much less at the Statehouse
door. If those who govern South Carolina fail to grasp this, the
state will continue to suffer in the court of public opinion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
