<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-BUSH-NYT &LR;      04-16 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BUSH'S NEW LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, April 17:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Gov. George W. Bush was a battered victor in the
presidential race, seemingly beholden to right-wing leaders who had
rescued his candidacy. Vice President Al Gore appeared set to
dominate the issues with proposals on health, children, schools and
the environment. But lately Bush has shifted tactics _ releasing a
barrage of domestic proposals, appearing at urban schools and
meeting with gay Republicans. He seems eager to retrieve the
``compassionate conservative'' label and flesh it out. The
governor's proposals have good features and flaws. They are also
costly and somewhat undercut by his Texas record. But they bring a
welcome new phase to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   After clinching the GOP nomination, Bush has proposed an
increase in education spending, a tax credit to help families buy
health insurance, a proposal to clean up toxic ``brown fields'' and
other measures. His military and domestic spending proposals would
add $86 billion to the budget over five years. But it is fair to
ask how the governor would pay for everything while saving Social
Security and Medicare, retiring the debt and cutting taxes. Indeed,
both Gore and Bush may have to be more careful about using up
surpluses that could shrink because of declines in the stock market
or a possible economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore has begun to point out, it is also worth examining what
Bush tried to accomplish in Texas to determine if he has been as
good as his word. On education, the governor's record is rated as
solid by many independent analysts. He has increased school
spending and tried to enforce standards. A profile of Bush by
Nicholas Lemann in The New Yorker said the governor's childhood
resentment of being stigmatized as a low achiever has led him to
reach out to minorities and others left behind by a failed school
system.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush record on health and the environment is something else,
however. As Adam Clymer reported in The New York Times last week,
Bush appears not to have even tried to expand health coverage, even
though he had the money to do it. The Gore campaign has also begun
charging that the reason Texas has one of the poorest environmental
records in the nation is that the governor's campaigns, along with
those of others in the Texas political establishment, have been
bankrolled by the state's worst polluters. Bush may have a tougher
time defending himself in these areas.
</P>
<P>
   The healthy aspect of these proposals is that the public will be
able to weigh the exchanges on the merits. It is good that Bush,
while embracing the mistaken idea of vouchers for schools, has at
least recognized _ as no recent GOP presidential candidate has _
that there is also a role for increased federal involvement and
expenditures in education. A debate about market-oriented versus
government-oriented health care plans is also welcome. Bush's push
toward moderation may well invite charges of hypocrisy by Gore, who
has had a long record on the environment, health care and
education. The vice president can also make the claim that he knows
how to do these things and still produce fiscally sound budgets.
But such exchanges are what campaigns are for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
