<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOROTHY HART, 94, WHO COMPILED FAMOUS BROTHER-IN-LAW'S LYRICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC PACE   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dorothy Hart, the editor of two highly praised books of song
lyrics by her brother-in-law, Lorenz Hart, of Rodgers and Hart
fame, died April 11 at a hospital in Ontario, Calif. She was 94 and
lived in Rancho Mirage, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Hart was the widow of Lorenz Hart's brother, Theodore, a
comedian. She and Robert Kimball edited ``The Complete Lyrics of
Lorenz Hart'' (Knopf, 1986), containing some 670 of the songs
Lorenz Hart wrote before his death in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   The book was lauded by the cabaret singer Bobby Short in The New
York Times Book Review. He said Hart ``took on the herculean task
of compiling Larry Hart's historic works a decade ago'' for her
other book, ``Thou Swell, Thou Witty,'' which Short said was ``an
admirable effort on its own, but, as it turns out, it was merely
the tip of the iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Short wrote that Hart and Kimball, an expert on the musical
theater, ``left no stone unturned in their search for every lyric
ascribed to Hart,'' and ``what has been achieved here is something
monumental.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart edited ``Thou Swell, Thou Witty'' (Da Capo, 1976) and wrote
a memoir included in the book. One critic said that work was
``indispensable for anyone interested in Hart, which is to say
anyone interested in Broadway musical comedy, and Hart's words are
honest, unpretentious and affecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son, also named Lorenz, said ``Thou Swell, Thou Witty'' had
played a critical role in the growth of the popularity of Rodgers
and Hart songs that he said had taken place since then. The
best-known Rodgers and Hart songs include ``The Lady Is a Tramp,''
``Manhattan'' and ``Blue Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart, the former Dorothy Lubow, was born in Brooklyn. She left
school at 16 and became a dancer. Then she spent years as a writer
and columnist for show-business fan magazines. She married her
husband in 1938. He died in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Besides her son, of Arlington, Va., she is survived by a
granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
