<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8690 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-MOTO-DIEHARD-HNS &LR;      04-16 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTO-DIEHARD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Sunday was a day of vindication for Jeff Gordon,
who proved he can win with the new version of the Rainbow Warriors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gordon had equaled his longest losing streak at 13 races, but he
made it back to Victory Lane in the No. 24 Dupont Chevrolet by
outdriving the competition in the final laps and winning the
DieHard 500 at the Talladega Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time Winston Cup champion became a record ninth winner
in nine races this year, taking the lead for good with five laps to
go when he passed Mark Martin coming out of turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   More than 180,000 spectators were on their feet as Gordon
managed to hold off a pack of cars behind him in the final laps to
earn his first victory since October of last season at Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty emotional for me,'' Gordon said of his 50th
career win. ``It hasn't been forever, but it has been awhile. We've
had to listen to a lot of criticism, and it takes a toll on you. I
think this shows what we're made of.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon held off Mike Skinner, who finished .189 seconds back in
second. Dale Earnhardt, trying to win his third consecutive race at
Talladega, was third by edging Kenny Irwin at the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a day when Gordon silenced the critics who wondered
if the Wonder Boy could win without former crew chief and mentor
Ray Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon also lost five members of the pit crew who switched to
Dale Jarrett's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down, but I never lost faith in this team,'' Gordon
said. ``Nobody pointed fingers or got mad. We brought in some new
guys, and I'm so proud of them. They have been able to overcome a
lot of stuff and keep their heads up to do what we had to do to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   It also was a special day for Robbie Loomis, who left Petty
Enterprises to become Gordon's crew chief this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the best night's sleep I've had in a long time,''
Loomis said. ``I said from the beginning I didn't expect to fill
Ray's shoes, but there has been a lot of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Loomis made the right adjustments on a day when the cars in the
draft were running about 190 mph _ 10 mph slower than last year at
Talladega _ because of NASCAR-mandated smaller air holes in the
carburetor restrictor plates.
</P>
<P>
   But it made for exciting racing within a bunched field, with 27
lead changes among 10 drivers. It also enabled cars in the back to
work their way to the front.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon started 36th, the lowest starting spot for any winner in
the 31-year history of Talladega racing.
</P>
<P>
   With 20 laps to go in the 188-lap event, 20 cars still were in
the lead pack. At least eight cars still had a chance to win when
Gordon went to the front for the final time.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was running third when second-place Jeremy Mayfield
bumped leader Martin and went outside on the backstretch. That gave
Gordon a chance to push forward while Martin had to contend with
Jarrett, who was in front of Martin, trying to stay on the lead
lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked to get the lead,'' Gordon said. ``Martin had
Jarrett in front of him, and I think that hurt him. I was able to
take advantage of it. I had some momentum and made the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, Skinner went with me to push me ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who led 98 laps, finished sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 12 car (Mayfield) was real anxious and made a move too
soon,'' Martin said. ``That's what cost us.''
</P>
<P>
   After Gordon took the lead, Skinner stayed right on his bumper
the last five laps, but he couldn't get around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff has a lot of experience in situations like that,''
Skinner said. ``I wasn't going to wreck him to win the race. I
didn't want to win my first race by spinning out a guy who raced me
clean all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny Irwin tried to push me to the front, but it just didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt was running fourth and went outside in turn 3 to try
to catch the leaders, but it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Dale get a run on Kenny, I pulled in front of Dale
and was going to make him wreck me to pass me,'' said Skinner,
Earnhardt's teammate. ``But I got to the finish line before he got
to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to finish ahead of him because he's the best in
the draft I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who has won a record nine times at Talladega, wasn't
pleased with the new restrictor-plate rules for the 2.66 mile
tri-oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place has gone from speedway racing to short-track
racing,'' Earnhardt said. ``It's getting worse and worse. The more
we slow the horsepower down, the more we get bunched up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was bumping like it was Martinsville. I almost got
turned around two or three times. It was a rock-em, sock-em day.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who won $159,755, managed to survive the bumper-banging
and take the checkered flag. Gordon, 28, usually hears a lot of
boos when he wins, but the Talladega fans cheered the man they used
to love to hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really surprised me,'' Gordon said. ``I always understood
why there were times when they pulled against us, because nobody
likes someone who wins too much. It's normal to pull for the
underdog, and that's what we were this time.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
