<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NYC-CONTRACTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A JUDICIAL REBUKE FOR NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, April 17:
</P>
<P>
   A state judge last week issued a sharp rebuke to the way the
Giuliani administration has awarded private contracts to operate
the city's welfare-to-work program. State Supreme Court Justice
William Davis concluded that the administration's granting of two
contracts worth $104 million to Maximus, a job placement company,
was corrupted by favoritism and other improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   Since February City Comptroller Alan Hevesi has been battling
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani over the truncated, biased process by which
the administration awarded some $470 million of contracts to
private firms hired to place welfare recipients in private-sector
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi charged that the city failed to meet legal requirements
in the contracting process by negotiating the contracts instead of
putting them out for competitive bidding. He refused to give final
approval to 17 contracts. But an odd provision in the City Charter
allows the mayor to override the comptroller's judgment and require
approval of contracts despite charges of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi eventually approved 15 of the contracts under protest,
but he refused to sign off on two contracts with Maximus, the
largest winner.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani sued Hevesi to force him to register those two
contracts, arguing that the comptroller had no power to refuse the
mayor's direction. Davis refused to order Hevesi to approve the
Maximus contracts on the grounds that ``to do so would place a
judicial imprimatur on a process that has been corrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   The justice agreed with Hevesi that there was no rationale for
using a less competitive process than normal in awarding the
contracts. He found that there had been extensive meetings between
city officials and Maximus executives prior to the formal
contracting process that gave the company an unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that Maximus had misled city administrators about
the role that Richard Schwartz, a former senior adviser to the
mayor on welfare policy, played in its contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is appealing the decision. And for some
related policy and research contracts, the city is said to be
seeking an alternative financing plan that would not require
Hevesi's approval. Maximus has announced that it will suspend its
operations in the city for now.
</P>
<P>
   Further litigation against the comptroller will not help the
city put into place an effective welfare-to-work program. Instead
of fighting in court, Giuliani should restart the competitive
bidding process, making sure that it is not tainted by favoritism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ETHIOPIA-NYT &LR;      04-16 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ETHIOPIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IMPENDING FAMINE IN ETHIOPIA  
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, April 17:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The images from the Horn of Africa are sadly familiar _ the
hollow eyes of emaciated mothers, the stick-like limbs and
distended bellies of dying children cradled in their arms. Fifteen
years after a million of its people perished in a devastating
famine, the specter of famine looms again in Ethiopia. A repeat of
that disaster need not happen if the world reinforces a relief
effort that could save hundreds of thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has warned that as many as 16 million people
in 10 countries across East Africa are threatened by renewed
famine. Half of them are in Ethiopia, primarily in the Ogaden
region bordering Somalia, where three years of drought has parched
the land and dried up wells. Casualties thus far are relatively
limited, but in some towns children are dying at a rate of a dozen
a day. During the last famine, the dictatorship of Mengistu Haile
Mariam prevented the distribution of food to areas that supported
rebel armies. The current government, led by Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi, has been more cooperative with international relief
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has promised to send 432,000 tons of food to
Ethiopia. The European Union has pledged to send more than 400,000
tons. But the U.N. estimates that it may need twice that much to
avert widespread famine by the end of June. It takes two to three
months for food to reach the stricken areas. So the time for urgent
action is now.
</P>
<P>
   Though the famine has been caused by drought, it is compounded
by Ethiopia's calamitous border war with Eritrea. The war is far
from the famine areas, but it has sapped the economies of both
these impoverished countries. Prime Minister Meles and the Eritrean
leader, Issaias Afwerki, have agreed to participate in talks this
month in Algiers, backed by Washington and the Organization of
African Unity. They owe it to their long-suffering countrymen to
negotiate in good faith and refrain from further military action.
In so doing they could help save thousands of lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
