<HEADLINE>
USC PUTS BEST FOOT FORWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's kicking woes this spring could lead to a big
summer surprise, as Trojans coach Paul Hackett said this weekend he
is considering letting punter Mike MacGillivray take a shot at
winning the place-kicking job.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely a possibility,'' Hackett said. ``He's
game-tested and it's something he could do. I think a guy who is a
veteran guy might be able to do it. It's hard to do but not
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is mulling the switch because neither David Bell nor
David Newbury distinguished themselves in spring practice. They
made 1 of 6 field goals in light scrimmaging Saturday, and were 1
for 5 in last week's scrimmage at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This spring practice was about these two guys having a chance
to show what they could do, and it was very dismal,'' Hackett said.
``We're going to continue to use those two guys but also have to
bring someone else into the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   MacGillivray has yearned to kick since he came to USC, and made
a 54-yard field goal at Loyola High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did both at Loyola and it was no problem,'' MacGillivray
said. ``If the coaches approach me, I'll work hard. I've worked on
it before. When I first came here, I didn't know what I was going
to be doing so I prepared for both.''
</P>
<P>
   Depth chart adjustments: As USC closed spring practice, some
positions cleared up, while others remain open.
</P>
<P>
   At tailback, Hackett said junior Malaefou MacKenzie took a
slight lead but he and sophomore Sultan McCullough will split time.
Another spot that will platoon players is defensive end, where
senior Sultan Abdul-Malik took the lead over junior Lonnie Ford.
</P>
<P>
   One position that firmed up is strongside linebacker, where
junior Kori Dickerson beat out freshman Chris Prosser and junior
John Cousins.
</P>
<P>
   At strong safety, sophomore Troy Polamalu appears to have beaten
out senior Ife Ohalete, but Ohalete will probably start at free
safety. At fullback, junior Charlie Landrigan held off a strong
challenge from sophomore Chad Pierson, though both will play.
</P>
<P>
   And at right tackle, freshman Jacob Rogers has won the job at
least until true freshman Joe McGuire arrives in August.
</P>
<P>
   Three drafted: USC wide receiver Windrell Hayes was selected by
the New York Jets in the fifth round, tailback Chad Morton was
chosen by the New Orleans Saints in the fifth round, and strong
safety David Gibson went to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers in the sixth
round Sunday in the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting a little worried,'' Gibson said. ``It was a
little later than I had hoped, but I'll take it. I like the coaches
and (former USC cornerback) Brian Kelly is there, and it's a lot
better to go where you know someone. I can make my car payments
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those attending Gibson's draft-day party was Mater Dei
quarterback Matt Leinart, who was offered a scholarship by the
Trojans last month.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Cornerback Antuan Simmons, who missed spring
practice after undergoing back surgery in November, is expected to
be 100 percent by Aug. 1. Outside linebacker Markus Steele, held
out of contact drills after undergoing shoulder surgery, has begun
upper body weightlifting and expects to be cleared for full contact
by Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll know how I feel the first day of training camp,'' Steele
said. ``I'll try to hit somebody. I can't wait to hit somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Training camp: The Trojans begin practicing at UC Irvine on Aug.
6, and will spend nearly three weeks there before heading for the
Meadowlands to play Penn State in the Kickoff Classic on Aug. 27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
