<HEADLINE>
GIANTS GO LONG SHOT IN THE THIRD ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: The following story, previously eliminated from NYT News
Service budget, is now restored)  By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ For all but one pick during the
weekend's National Football League draft, the Giants made choices
that were reasoned, rational and, perhaps most surprising of all,
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants took a Heisman Trophy winner, the first in franchise
history; a linebacker from Penn State; a tackle from Alabama and a
cornerback from Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the third-round selection, the choice that
fits the mix like a canary yellow Nehru jacket in a closet full of
blue and gray suits.
</P>
<P>
   He was Ron Dixon, a wide receiver from tiny Lambuth University,
a former women's college in west Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon is a speedy, slender, long-legged receiver and
kick-returner whom the Giants consider a discovery and most would
label a colossal long shot. Dixon played one year at Lambuth, which
belongs to the National Association for Intercollegiate Athletics,
a class of football comparable to Division III in the National
Collegiate Athletic Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' 2000 draft may ultimately be remembered for Ron
Dayne, the first-round pick who could bring an end to the tumult
that has enveloped the team's running back position since Rodney
Hampton retired. But it was Dixon who brought the spice and
intrigue to the Giants' draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's inexperienced, but he's an electrifying player and you
just have to take some risks in this business,'' Giants General
Manager Ernie Accorsi said of Dixon, who scored 22 touchdowns in 11
games last season for Lambuth.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1-inch, 183-pound Dixon, the last pure speed receiver
the Giants had listed on their draft board, also caught 89 passes,
averaged 19.5 yards a catch and returned three kicks for
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get speed from this draft,'' Accorsi said. ``Other
people probably had Dixon targeted at a later round, but we wanted
him, so we took him.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants chose Dixon late Saturday night as the 73rd pick
over all, they insisted he was not a secret in the NFL. And Sunday,
in a conference call with reporters, Dixon said several teams had
contacted him, including the Jets, who recently flew him to New
York for a physical.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, 24, acknowledged that he was surprised when he heard his
name called in the third round because he had been told he might be
taken in a later round. But Dixon was convinced he deserved to be
taken in the second or third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was at Florida or someplace, I would have been a
first-round or second-round pick,'' Dixon said. ``The only reason I
was at Lambuth was because of the bad judgment calls I made in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon was ruled academically ineligible at various stages after
graduating from a Florida high school. He attended three community
colleges _ Lake Sumpter and Tallahassee in Florida and Itawamba in
Mississippi _ as well as Western Georgia, an NCAA Division II
school. He also agreed to attend Central Florida, but substandard
test scores kept him from keeping that commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't grown up yet,'' Dixon said of those years. ``I wasn't
into my books when I should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   With one year of football eligibility left, Dixon earned enough
credits to enroll at Lambuth. He was referred there by an
acquaintance of Lambuth's head coach, Vic Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess the level of competition he faced at Lambuth,
Dixon answered, ``It was NAIA level, and I was above that _ put it
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the Giants provided reporters with a videotape of one of
Dixon's games, which showed him catching several passes and
returning a kickoff for a touchdown virtually untouched. Dixon
displayed a high-stepping running style and an ability to catch the
football.
</P>
<P>
   As an aside, it was easy to notice that the rows of bleachers
next to the field were almost empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize to Giants fans because I'm sure they were looking
for a big-ticket guy,'' Dixon said. ``But give me a little time and
I'll show them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon's presence muddles the future for Brian Alford, the
receiver the Giants selected for his speed in the third round two
years ago. And it is worth questioning how Dixon is going to make
an impact when Alford played four years of Big Ten football at
Purdue and has not been able to get on the field in two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But Accorsi said the Giants needed more than one quick receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rams have about eight of them,'' he said of the Super Bowl
champions. ``Everyone is going to multiple-wide-receiver sets
now.''
</P>
<P>
   In Rounds 4 through 7 Sunday, the Giants followed a routine
course, taking two linebackers, a cornerback and a defensive end.
Brandon Short, the fourth-round pick from Penn State, may have the
best chance to make an immediate contribution. He is projected as a
strongside linebacker because of his quickness.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-round pick was Ralph Brown, a four-year starter at
cornerback for Nebraska. He will challenge Dave Thomas, a recently
signed veteran free agent, for the nickel cornerback spot. The
club's sixth-round selection, Dhani Jones, a Michigan linebacker,
figures to play mostly on special teams. Jeremiah Parker, the
defensive end from California taken in the seventh round, provides
depth where the Giants need it.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius Griffin, Saturday's second-round pick, is being
counted on to make the team as either a third tackle or a third
end. He is almost guaranteed playing time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
