<DOCNO> NYT20000416.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8707 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LIVERY-DEATHS-600&AMP;     04-16 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIVERY-DEATHS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABBIES EYE STREETS WARILY ON TENSE NIGHT SHIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's Sunday morning, just after 2 _ a scant 24 hours
after Jean Scutt, the new driver at Commodore Car Service, was shot
dead _ and Brandi Turner is frazzled because Car 72's driver is
squeezing the radio transmitter as he barrels across Brooklyn in
his Lincoln Town Car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy-two, seventy-two,'' Turner says, raising her voice as
she speaks into the worn Motorola microphone in Commodore's grubby
dispatcher booth, in a small, drab storefront with overhanging
wires and dusty counters in East Flatbush. ``Why you squeezing your
mike and not shouting back at the base?''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who was on duty the morning before, when Scutt was
killed with a gunshot to the neck in Flatbush, knows all too well
that holding down the button on a mike, which lights up the driver
ID box in her booth, is a distress signal that can mean a driver
has a gun to his head.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Car 72's driver is inadvertently squeezing the
mike, an honest mistake for any driver. But with the death of Scutt
fresh on Turner's mind, the oversight prompts a gentle scolding
from an edgy dispatcher. ``It's not right to play games,'' Turner
tells him. ``It's not right to play wolf.''
</P>
<P>
   At Commodore one day after violence struck close to home, no one
_ not Turner, the other dispatchers, the 20 drivers on duty early
Sunday or management _ could be too careful through Saturday's
overnight tour, the busiest night of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said she had turned away 30 callers who had asked for
rides between midnight and 3 a.m., most of them people who had
failed to give an exact address for their pickup or destination.
About 10 drivers did not show up to work. Those who did frequently
ignored people who tried to wave them down or phoned for service
from dark, desolate streets in the heart of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're scared, afraid,'' said Gasner Racine, owner of
Commodore. ``Some of them chose to take the day, to stay home. They
feel very bad about what happened. The ones that worked, they're
more careful. They keep talking to each other, telling each other
to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, livery drivers and dispatchers at Commodore know
danger is ever present for people who make their living ferrying
strangers to wherever they wish to go in the middle of the night.
Many have been robbed in the past, they said. Most knew that before
Scutt's death, six livery drivers in the city had lost their lives
this year, a pace expected to easily surpass the total of 11
drivers killed in all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're easy targets, and people know we're out there,'' said
Shelby Oliver, the Commodore manager and a driver who was robbed at
gunpoint about two weeks ago. ``Everyone needs cab drivers, and
you're always picking up someone, and so you're always carrying
money. You understand it. If you're working a full shift, they
figure that in the wee hours of the morning, you have a nice amount
of change.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Commodore's drivers and dispatchers said Sunday that
Scutt's death had shaken them to the core. Never before had someone
from Commodore been killed. That he was new to the company _ on the
job just two days _ and thus a stranger to the other workers,
seemed to make no difference to drivers who consider their network
akin to a brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Scutt, a Haitian immigrant like many Commodore drivers and a
father of three, was shot dead shortly after a young man walked
into the car service about 2 a.m. Saturday and told Turner he
needed a ride. About 20 minutes later, Scutt's car crashed against
the wrought-iron fence outside a candy store, his body slumped
inside.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scared or not, Commodore's drivers still gravitated throughout
Saturday night to their base. The drivers, who in a good week can
make $700, said they have families to support. So they worked,
driving their Lincolns and Fords on a rainy night across all
corners of Brooklyn and beyond, from the gritty streets of East New
York to the Port Authority Bus Terminal in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do the job, someone else has to do it,'' said
Charles Cyprien, 45, a driver for 10 years. ``So it's like you do
it. It's like soldiers going to war: You've got to go. To make a
living, you have to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   So Commodore was a blur of activity on the Saturday overnight.
</P>
<P>
   This was no more apparent than in the dispatcher's booth, a
6-by-6-foot space where dispatchers sit before a pink Formica
counter; a sign taped to the wall warns them not to stay on the
phone more than three minutes. Nimbly juggling as many as 10 lines
at once, the dispatchers quickly logged the addresses where callers
needed to be picked up and then put out the information to drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-five, ninety-five, Dean Street and Stone,'' said Melody
Taylor, a dispatcher with a Jamaican lilt, trying to reach Car 95
and direct the driver to a fare. Meanwhile, Fajr Smith, who favors
gold necklaces and rings and was outfitted from head to toe in
fatigues, fielded a call from someone on Seaview Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Under this system, drivers respond to calls for service put out
by dispatchers _ if they wish. But with calls for service coming in
at a furious pace and the number of drivers down for the night, the
dispatchers had to tell dozens of people to call back. Other calls
never went out to the drivers; there was something about the pickup
location, something about a caller's voice that alerted skittish
dispatchers.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers, meanwhile, said they were especially wary. Over the
weekend, that meant being mindful of a prospective passenger's
appearance or the location where a pickup or a drop-off was to take
place. Most of the drivers said they avoided picking up people
trying to wave them down, a common but dangerous practice in
certain neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that guy outside, the young guy, the way he's dressed,
the baggy clothes and stuff,'' Wilner Charlemagne, 45, a driver for
25 years, said as he looked out to a group of young men milling on
the corner outside Commodore's office. ``He flags me down, I don't
pick him up. I go to the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   The drivers were also especially conscious of young men who
walked into the base, requesting a ride in person, as Scutt's
killer apparently did.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some walk-ins were eagerly welcomed, like Trevlyn
Atkinson, a nurse leaving a church function in an elegant black
dress late Saturday night and requesting a ride to her home in
Borough Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she would do me harm; I can trust her,'' Norman
Stoll, 32, a Commodore driver, said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll, a driver for eight years with Commodore, said he had
never been robbed, an accomplishment he attributes to street smarts
and caution. Stoll, an immigrant from Guyana, said he had never
given much thought to the dangers inherent in his job, until his
co-worker was shot dead. That has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, I don't think I'm going to pick up no guys in
the night after a certain time, even though I have the partition,''
he said, as his 1991 Ford sliced across the wet pavement. I have a
lot of fear in me right now. This guy lost his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
