<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8708 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-POLITICOS-1     04-16 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-POLITICOS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI POLITICIANS TESTED BY ELIAN GONZALEZ CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to give job title of Marvin Dunn and elaborate on his quote.
Changes Anglo to non-Hispanic white. Rewrites last two grafs.)  
(See also CUBAN-BOY-SUPPORTERS, CUBAN-BOY-HAVANA) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ What excites Miami's Cuban-Americans about the Elian
Gonzalez case is that it is the best opportunity since the failed
Bay of Pigs invasion in 1961 to humiliate Fidel Castro. But
domestic conflicts are stirring this pot, too, and threatening
Miami and its two top politicians with their own Bay of Pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Penelas, 38, a Democrat, was elected mayor of Miami-Dade
County four years ago with the huge support of normally
Republican-voting Cuban-Americans, as well as the support of many
blacks and non-Hispanic whites. Once perceived as a future governor
or senator, Penelas faces a re-election race in the fall against a
Republican Cuban-American, Miguel Diaz de la Portilla, a county
commissioner who is more conservative than Penelas.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Carollo, 45, a Republican, was elected mayor of the city
of Miami three years ago. In a city where Cuban-Americans make up
the majority of the vote, he survived an attempt by his own city
commission to oust him in a special election last year that the
courts overruled. Accused of taking his Cuban-American support for
granted, Carollo faces a challenge next year from a former mayor,
Xavier Suarez, also a Cuban-American.
</P>
<P>
   In the local political arena, said professor Kenneth W. Goodman,
director of the ethics program at the University of Miami, ``Fidel
Castro is not even an issue.'' Alberto Duran, a board member of the
Cuban Committee for Democracy, which favors the boy's return to his
father, said, ``This is a political struggle, a show of political
muscle more than a stance against Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to prove they can keep this child here,'' Duran
said. ``Penelas is in a very tough political race, so he's taking
extreme stands to get the Cuban-American vote, and Carollo is going
to have a tough race in November next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in both mayors' participation in the dispute
came late last month when Penelas, with Carollo beside him at the
microphones on the steps of the federal courthouse here, lashed out
at federal law and its enforcers.
</P>
<P>
   Penelas, until that moment a man known as a consensus-building
moderate, declared that he would not let the Miami police help
federal agents move Elian from his temporary home and would blame
President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno for any ensuing
violence and civil disorder. He and Carollo, who is better known as
a firebrand, have since promised to maintain order. But they will
not let their police join federal marshals in moving Elian from his
great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez's white stucco house in Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the mayors have alienated all other ethnic groups,
sullied their images as emerging leaders of their national
political parties, and diminished the stature of their city. At
moments in the Elian saga, analysts say, the mayors have let
emotions trump federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they both have at stake,'' said Dario Marino, a pollster
and associate professor of political science at Florida
International University here, ``is the good name of Miami and the
ability to attract business. No one in the business elite wants
civil disobedience.'' But as passions over Elian have begun to boil
over, Marino said, ``their first priority is not to alienate their
Cuban-American base. If they alienate their Cuban base, they're
both gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Gladwin, director of the Institute for Public Opinion
Research at FIU, said: ``The first level of political impact, until
it's resolved and people start reflecting on it, is this huge
polarization. People are going to remember.'' Because of the
mayors' ``pandering to popular sentiment,'' said Mayor Neisen O.
Kasdin of Miami Beach, just across Biscayne Bay, ``Miami has taken
it on the chin. It's not going to stop Miami's emergence as the
capital of the Americas. But this is a setback for two or three
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The two mayors have impeccable Cuban and American political
credentials. Penelas' father, a labor organizer in Cuba, was in a
Castro prison facing a death sentence when he escaped with his
family to Florida, where Alex was born. Joseph Carollo came at the
age of 5 or 6.
</P>
<P>
   They soaked up American culture, got educations and entered
careers in politics. Penelas was elected to the Hialeah city
council at 25. Carollo, briefly a Democrat and a police officer,
was elected a Miami city commissioner at 24. Both dress in the
crisp suits and tightly knotted ties of members of the board of a
chamber of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the Elian case, following Elian's rescue at sea in
November when he and his mother, who drowned, were fleeing Cuba,
the mayors stood on the fringe of the custody debate while their
Cuban-American constituents weighed the issues.
</P>
<P>
   As views coalesced to the point where many now support Lazaro
Gonzalez's defiance of a federal order to release Elian to his
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who awaits him in Bethesda, Md., the
mayors have declined to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll this month that stunned analysts here, The Miami
Herald found an acutely polarized city, with 85 percent of
Miami-Dade County's Cuban-Americans supporting efforts to keep
Elian in the United States and 92 percent of African-Americans and
72 percent of non-Hispanic whites supporting his return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   With a Cuban majority in the city and a plurality in the county,
said Lisandro Perez, director of the Cuban Research Institute at
Florida International University, ``Carollo and Penelas want to
make sure they're in the front of this movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The 4,000 or 5,000 people who demonstrate in front of Lazaro
Gonzalez's home may represent only a small fraction of the county's
743,000 Cuban-Americans, Perez said, but when things get emotional,
Carollo and Penelas are going to have to take up the banner or get
trampled. ``The fact that this is foreign policy is academic,''
Perez said. ``They're doing what their constituency wants them to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   In responding to the passions of a single constituency, the
mayors have alienated blacks and non-Hispanic whites. Marvin Dunn,
a black who is the chairman of the psychology department at FIU and
the author of a book about the black experience in Miami in the
20th century, said the Miami Herald poll showing that 92 percent of
blacks want Elian repatriated was stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see far too many fathers abandoning their children,'' Dunn
said. ``When we see a dad stand up for his son, that's
impressive.'' That such views are ignored, he said, ``is for me,
for a lot of African-Americans, reprehensible. We feel we are a
less important part of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not hurt Carollo because of the city's Cuban-American
majority. ``But Penelas has more of a problem,'' Dunn said. James
W. Corey, a political scientist at the University of Miami and a
veteran of the Bay of Pigs, said, ``I would say strategically, he's
put himself in a precarious position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban-Americans, said Susan MacManus, a professor of
political science at the University of South Florida in Tampa,
``forced him to go so far over to the right that it makes it
difficult for him to win.'' The only winners, she said, are the
aging leaders of the Cuban exile community, who had been losing
influence. The Elian affair, she said, ``has galvanized them and
emboldened them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
