<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CASINO-(1850)2TAKE     04-16 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CASINO-(1850)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAINST ALL ODDS, A COMPLICATED CASINO PROPOSAL ADVANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTICELLO, N.Y. _ Robert A. Berman stalked across the cavernous
grandstand at Monticello Raceway on a recent afternoon just as the
trotters breezed across the finish line to the desultory cheers of
two dozen bettors and a couple of children scattered among the box
seats.
</P>
<P>
   He winced when the tote board showed that a mere $6,223 had been
bet on the race, including the off-track action. It had hardly been
worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   With the scruffy racetrack, and the empty parking lot, it was
hard to picture the tens of thousands of vacationers who once
flocked here from borscht belt hotels. But it is here that Berman
wants to build a $500 million casino for the St. Regis Mohawk
tribe, a project that he says will bring prosperity back to the
Catskills and a windfall to him and his partners.
</P>
<P>
   And on April 7, after six years of public hearings,
environmental reviews, negotiations and nearly $30 million, he
finally won the federal Interior Department's approval for his plan
to donate 30 acres to the Mohawks for the casino. He and his
partners would build and operate it under a management contract
with the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing here,'' said Berman, who grew up here and
heads an investment group that owns the track. ``This area has been
devastated. The casino would create thousands of good-paying jobs.
It'll drive demand for hotels and the people who work there will
spend money in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with the victory in Washington _ one that many thought
would never happen _ Berman still feels embattled.
</P>
<P>
   The casino venture still needs the approval of Gov. George E.
Pataki, whose longstanding support for the project is now open to
question, and possibly the State Legislature. Although Berman's
partners include top Republican campaign contributors with close
ties to the state's top economic development official, Charles A.
Gargano, the battle in Albany will be joined by a combative group
of gambling opponents, Atlantic City casino interests, unions and
real estate developers.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the intrigue, casino proponents and tribal officials
say that a new force has sought to curry favor with the Mohawk
tribe in an effort to gain control of the casino, or kill it:
Arthur Goldberg, president of Park Place Entertainment, the largest
gambling operator in the country, and his adviser, Alfonse M.
D'Amato, the former senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The casino could revive an historic area,'' Berman said. ``We
hope the governor will judge this project on the merits and ignore
all the political noise in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman's friends and critics in Sullivan County described him as
a ``wheeler dealer'' who was always trying to get some project
going in the county, even after business took him to New York and
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always very enterprising,'' said Ira Jay Cohen, the
Sullivan County attorney. ``Very inventive. I wasn't surprised
years later when he surfaced as the head of this casino venture. He
was always willing to take a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of local contractor, Berman, 40, was 19 when he opened
the Bananas nightclub in nearby Woodridge at one of the county's
many shuttered hotels. In 1981 and 1982, he ran Music Mountain, a
successful concert series that included the Allman Brothers Band
and the Grateful Dead at Avon Lodge, a former hotel owned by his
girlfriend's family.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, he and four partners revived a twice-failed ski resort
in Sullivan County called Davos. The county's resort industry had
foundered badly in the competition with Atlantic City and
relatively inexpensive air fares to Europe. But there was a boomlet
in second-home construction. Berman's group expanded the ski trails
and built a clubhouse, a lodge and hundreds of condominiums, town
houses and single-family homes.
</P>
<P>
   The recession in the early 1990s, however, brought construction
to a halt, and the project's lender pushed Davos into bankruptcy
court, leaving some residents and local contractors angry with
Berman over unfulfilled promises. Berman eventually wrested back
control of the property.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1990s, Berman was involved with Watermark
Investments, a holding company based in Manhattan that invested in
real estate projects, an Internet lottery and hotel renovations. He
said he stepped down from those ventures last month to concentrate
on the casino.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of that project date back to 1994, when the State
Legislature had once again did not approve casino gambling in New
York. Berman told Cliff Ehrlich, whose family had owned the Pines
hotel and was an advocate of gambling as a way to revive the
county's beleaguered economy, that he had a way to get around the
state's prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, who had worked with the Coeur d'Alene tribe in Idaho on
an Internet lottery venture, said that a seldom-used provision of
federal law allowed for the creation of a casino on land donated in
trust for a tribe. The trust would establish a tax-free sovereign
Indian territory outside tribal lands expressly for a casino.
</P>
<P>
   Berman and Ehrlich bought the failing racetrack in Monticello
and approached the Oneidas, one of only two tribes in New York that
had a gambling contract with the state and the wherewithal to both
finance and operate a casino. When a deal with the Oneidas fell
apart in 1995, Berman and Ehrlich struck an alliance with the St.
Regis Mohawks, whose reservation is on the Canadian border, 350
miles north of Monticello. But the Mohawks could not finance or
operate the casino.
</P>
<P>
   For financial support, Berman enlisted an old friend, Joseph
Bernstein, a developer based in New York City who had gained
notoriety in the 1980s when he secretly bought skyscrapers in
Manhattan on behalf of President Ferdinand Marcos of the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Berman also picked up another partner, Alpha Hospitality, a
gambling company that already had a deal with the Mohawks to run an
off-reservation casino. Alpha was run by Stanley S. Tollman, a New
York businessman who owned a number of hotels. Its directors and
major stockholders included Gargano, who was appointed chairman of
the Empire State Development Corp. in 1995. Gargano's connections
to Alpha, whose casino project was being reviewed by the state, set
off a storm of protest in the Legislature. He ultimately resigned
from Alpha and sold his stock, although he and Tollman remain good
friends.
</P>
<P>
   `` Gargano divested his holdings many years ago so there
wouldn't be any reason to question anything,'' said Thomas Aro,
executive vice president of Alpha. ``But you don't resign your
friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman added: ``Nobody is doing anybody any favors on this
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Tollman may have other problems that could reflect poorly on
Alpha and the contract with the Mohawks. The United States attorney
in Manhattan is investigating his Tollman-Hundley Hotels company,
which bought the Days Inn chain in 1989 in a highly leveraged $765
million deal. Less than two years later, Days Inn filed for
bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors recently obtained indictments of a former company
executive, Howard Zukerman, on charges of tax evasion. In a
declaration filed in that case, an assistant U.S. attorney, Stanley
J. Okula Jr., stated that he was investigating Tollman's friend and
former partner, Monty Drew Hundley, and three other unnamed
executives at Tollman-Hundley in connection with ``a massive scheme
to defraud certain financial institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was a founder of both the hotel company and Alpha.
Tollman did not return numerous telephone calls requesting comment
and Larry Horn, a lawyer for Hundley, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with Alpha,'' Aro said. ``I have no
knowledge of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the group drew up plans for the casino over the
last five years and met with county legislators and federal
regulators. Berman promised to expand the track when the casino was
built. The two-story gambling and entertainment complex, which
would include 200 gambling tables, a 12,000-square-foot poker room,
a bingo room and 3,000 video lottery terminals, is expected to
attract 9 million visitors a year and generate 5,300 people. In a
series of negotiations, the tribe has agreed to give the county $5
million a year and to provide the state with up to 25 percent of
the gross revenues from electronic gambling machines.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 years of talk about gambling in the Catskills, few
people thought the Monticello casino would ever materialize. But
last year, David Flaum and Louis R. Cappelli, developers who are
also heavy Republican campaign contributors, began buying property
for resorts the likes of which had not been seen in Sullivan
County. Gambling foes and Atlantic City casino owners like Donald
J. Trump opposed the project in advertisements attacking Pataki as
a pro-gambling politician.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has long said that Indian casinos could be an economic
boon in traditional resort areas like the Catskills and western New
York. He has also maintained that he has the power to approve
Indian casino proposals. But last month, he filed a bill that would
require the State Legislature to approve Indian gambling
operations, a proposal that casino advocates believe would mean
almost certain doom. Since then, the Pataki administration has
refused to say whether the bill covers the Mohawks, a tribe that
already has a gambling compact with the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last best hope for the area,'' said United States
Senator Charles E. Schumer, who had lobbied the federal government
on behalf of the casino.
</P>
<P>
   A top state official said in a recent interview that the
Monticello casino would be reviewed in the context of the state's
overall relations with the tribe. In a meeting last Thursday, state
officials made a settlement offer concerning the Mohawks' land
claims. The offer got a favorable reception, according to one
person who was briefed on the talks.
</P>
<P>
   That gave casino proponents hope. But they must still get their
management contract with the Mohawks approved by the National
Indian Gaming Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent break with the Atlantic City casino owners,
Goldberg of Park Place Entertainment has been negotiating for six
months to take over management of the Mohawks' small, money-losing
casino in Hogansburg, N.Y., according to tribal officials, the
current casino operator and others. And last week, he made
overtures to Alpha concerning the proposed Monticello casino.
</P>
<P>
   It is this kind of maneuvering that gives Berman headaches. He
fears that Park Place does not truly want a casino in Monticello
that could take business away from Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe for a minute that they want a casino in
Monticello,'' he said. ``They've got too big a stake in Atlantic
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing rests on Pataki's shoulders,'' Berman added. ``He
has the power with a stroke of the pen to say yes to thousands of
jobs and millions of dollars in revenue that now flows out of the
state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
