u v BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT     04-16 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR MONDAY, APRIL 1 7 
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Monday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(ss) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-AFRICA-DIAMONDS-NYT (moved Wednesday, April 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, April 5
about the role of diamonds in fueling wars in Africa misstated the
life expectancy in Botswana, the world's largest diamond producer.
The United Nations says that because of AIDS, the figure has fallen
sharply and is 41, no longer close to 70.
</P>
<P>
   BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT (moved Thursday, March 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service report in the World Briefing
column sent on Thursday, March 30 about invitations to human rights
groups to visit Algeria in May and June misstated the Algerians'
position on such visits. Several rights groups have been admitted
since the guerrilla war began, with varying freedom of access; the
country has not been closed to them since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-STADIUMS(2TAKES)-NYT (moved Wednesday, April 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service Circuits article sent on
Wednesday, April 12 about high-tech baseball stadiums misidentified
a company talking with the San Francisco Giants about a plan to let
fans buy tickets online and print them on home computers. It is
Tickets.com, not Ticketmaster.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NC-FILM-NOTEBOOK-NYT (moved Sunday, April 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on moved Sunday,
April 9 about the Double Take Documentary Film Festival in Durham,
N.C., referred imprecisely to a suggestion from the audience. A
member proposed that an award category be created for short films _
not that it necessarily be given to Eugene Richards. (The jury
created the award and gave it to Richards, for ``But, the Day
Came.'')
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated the HBO position of Sheila Nevins,
who received the festival's first industry award. (The error also
appeared in a brief report in some copies on April 6.) Nevins is
executive vice president for original programming, not vice
president for documentary programming.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-WEINTRAUB-NYT (moved Sunday, April 9)
</P>
<P>
   An New York Times News Service obituary sent on Sunday, April 9
about the Hollywood producer Sy Weintraub, who modernized the
adventures of Tarzan after acquiring screen rights in 1958,
misidentified the actor who played the role in the first two
Weintraub productions. He was Gordon Scott. (Jock Mahoney was the
first of Weintraub's Tarzans to appear in a non-African setting, in
the 1962 film ``Tarzan Goes to India.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
