<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' comments on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   As an improvisational violinist, I have noticed that gigs really
pick up at this time of year, and that spring seems to bring the
quirkiest jobs. A unique one was a call from a forlorn fellow who
had been rejected by his true love. He rented the Central Park boat
house _ not yet open for the season _ and hired a famous chef and a
jazz violinist, namely me. When the girlfriend arrived, she found a
romantic setting that even a heart of steel wouldn't have been able
to resist.
</P>
<P>
   But my story really isn't about that couple. As I stood on the
dock playing standards like ``Lover Man'' and ``You'd Be So Nice to
Come Home To,'' my violin wove a spell that no one could have
predicted. All the ducks in the pond gradually migrated to the dock
and formed a semicircle around me. The highlight came when my time
was up and I started packing up the fiddle. Until you've been
surrounded by a dozen mallards quacking gleefully as they gaze at
you, you haven't known the heights of artistic fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   _ JULIE LYONN LIEBERMAN
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   While delivering his sermon at a children's Mass timed to
coincide with the Gospel account of Christ calling each of his
disciples, the priest posed this question: ``Can you think of any
way in which he could call you to follow him?'' Silence reigned.
Then a voice from the congregation piped up. ``Cell phone!'' Given
confidence by this tyke's response, two more ways to be called came
forth. ``E-mail,'' said one. ``Beeper,'' said the second.
</P>
<P>
   _ SISTER CARMEN AURECCHIONE
</P>
<P>
   Michael Salaycik was taking a lunchtime walk around Wall Street
when he noticed a man approaching, carrying a large bottle of
spring water. The man signaled him to stop, and as they faced each
other, it was obvious that he was a tourist and spoke no English.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, with one arm he raised the bottle of water over his
head. He then raised his other arm behind his head, where the hands
and fingers began to imitate a spiked crown. Salaycik, initially
startled, needed no language to understand the mime movement. He
pointed the man toward the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The setting: A performance of ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' at the
Ford Center for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Time: Intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The players: Two women, and Jean-Claude Baker, who overhears the
following conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 1: ``I know he's a good actor, but he waves his arms
around so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman No. 2: ``That's why I like radio. You don't have to look
at them.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MEN OF SPRING
</P>
<P>
   It's opening day of the season,
</P>
<P>
   Of course it's on Tokyo Bay,
</P>
<P>
   The once great American pastime
</P>
<P>
   Has now jolted far away.
</P>
<P>
   The Polo Grounds and Ebbets,
</P>
<P>
   Are housing developments now,
</P>
<P>
   Where Leo the Lip made merry,
</P>
<P>
   Have taken their ultimate bow,
</P>
<P>
   How dare they call them the Dodgers?
</P>
<P>
   No trolleys to dodge in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have long left Boston,
</P>
<P>
   What became of the Bees anyway?
</P>
<P>
   As long as the TV gets sponsors,
</P>
<P>
   Who gives a damn what's the score?
</P>
<P>
   I'm buying some Rheingold to cry in,
</P>
<P>
   The game's not a game anymore.
</P>
<P>
   _ SANDRA W. JACOBSON
</P>
<P>
   It's undoubtedly one of the most unusual cabs in the city and,
much to her regret, Sandra Priest Rose neglected to take down the
name of the driver.
</P>
<P>
   The ceiling of the cab is covered with pictures of suffragettes
and famous women _ Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Susan B. Anthony and
Eleanor Roosevelt among them _ placed there at the request of the
driver's 11-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all. Also in the cab is a sign that says ``All
rides under $5 on the meter are free to senior citizens.'' The
driver explained that it was his gift to the city to repay what he
receives from it.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Klimerman was on a crowded express train going uptown,
and as it left the Wall Street station she decided to work on a
crossword puzzle. By the time she reached 34th Street, she had
filled in five answers, but after a tiring day, couldn't
concentrate further.
</P>
<P>
   She was putting away her pen when the man next to her looked up
from his book and addressed her. ``Excuse me,'' he said. ``I had to
tell you before you got off the train that the answer to the clue
for 10 Across is `nail-biting,' not `nitpicking.' It will ruin your
whole puzzle so I had to tell you before you went any further.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. When she got home and filled in his answer,
finishing the rest of the puzzle was a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Wellisch's friend Cathy Mesa has two sons, Michael, 6,
and Christopher, almost 3. Recently, Mesa told Michael that after
finishing his prayers, he should say, ``And please, God, give food
to the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher, listening intently, joined in. ``And a knife and
fork,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I was, until recently, a reverse commuter to Jersey City and
traveled across the Hudson by ferry. As one of the few passengers
in the morning, I had come to know some of my fellow riders and,
occasionally, had the ferry entirely to myself.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, for two days in a row, the boat had already left
the dock when the captain saw me standing there, looking forlorn,
and he returned to pick me up. It illustrated to this Manhattanite
the sense of community that small-town dwellers must feel.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARCI ALBOHER NUSBAUM
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I was walking down West Broadway behind a man with a black
blazer, red scarf and decided bounce in his step. As he stepped off
the curb to cross an intersection, a tractor-trailer swung
perilously close to him and he stepped back in alarm. The truck
stopped, blocking the entire intersection. The burly driver leaned
out the window, pointed his cigar at the man and said effusively,
``It was a bee-oo-tiful movie!''
</P>
<P>
   The man waved to the driver, who then pulled away. I stepped up
next to the man. ``He's right, it was a bee-oo-tiful movie,'' I
said. He directed his signature smile at me and threw out his arms
in a charming flourish. I turned down a side street as Roberto
Benigni continued on his way.
</P>
<P>
   _ MAGGIE GRIFFIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
