<SLUG> BC-RUN-LONDON-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINTO WINS LONDON MARATHON AND KHANNOUCHI IS THIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEAL ALLEN   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Lontonio Pinto of Portugal won the London marathon
Sunday in 2 hours 6 minutes 36 seconds, defeating Khalid
Khannouchi, the world record-holder, who finished third.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto, who finished in the first three in this race six times,
earned $180,000 for the victory, which was the fifth-fastest
marathon in history. Morocco's Abdel Cader El Mouaziz, last year's
London champion, finished second in 2:07:33.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi, who set the world record with a 2:05:42 in October
in Chicago, finished third in 2:08.36.
</P>
<P>
   A Moroccan who lives in Ossining, N.Y., Khannouchi is trying to
gain citizenship in order to compete for the United States in the
Olympic Games in September. His wife, Sandra, said Sunday that his
lawyers believe he will obtain his citizenship on May 3 after
fingerprint procedures and a test on his knowledge of American
history. Khannouchi complained that the London air was too cold for
him Sunday, though the temperature was 51 degrees after an hour and
a half of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending upon how soon Khalid recovers from this race, he
will either aim to compete in the American Olympic trials for the
marathon in Pittsburgh on May7 or the 10,000 meters trial for the
Sydney Olympics on July 14 in Sacramento,'' said Sandra Khannouchi,
who is also his manager and coach. ``I reckon we'll know which
within the next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinto, 34, who won the London Marathon in 1992 and 1997, and was
runner-up last year, took control of the race with a 25th-mile
split time of 4 minutes 32 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto's time was the fastest ever by a European, surpassing the
2:07:12 by his compatriot Carlos Lopes back in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Tegla Loroupe of Kenya, the women's marathon world record-holder
(2:20:43), finished 13 seconds ahead of Romania's Lidia Simon in
2:24:33 to win the women's race, which was the Olympic trial for
the Kenyan women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
