<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PANTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENS' GOAL GIVES DEVILS A 2-0 PLAYOFF LEAD ON PANTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The big, lively crowd cheered Scott
Niedermayer when he first took the ice Sunday night in Continental
Arena and they cheered the Devils defenseman the first few times he
touched the puck. They cheered later in the first period when he
nearly scored on a rebound and they cheered again when he bumped
Peter Worrell, the big Panther with whom Niedermayer has a history.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest cheer came early in the second period, when the
Devils were two men short and Niedermayer was on the
penalty-killing team. Rushing down ice with John Madden on a
two-on-one rush, Niedermayer pounced upon the loose puck after
Madden's shot was stopped by goalie Mike Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting the rebound with a backhanded motion, Niedermayer
pushed the puck over the goal line to tie the score at 1-1. The
Devils went on to a 2-1 victory when Scott Stevens scored his
second goal of the playoffs 3:42 into the third period. That gave
the Devils a 2-0 lead in the four-of-seven-game series with Games 3
and 4 in Sunrise, Fla., on Tuesday and Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just jumped and basically rushed down as hard as I could,''
Niedermayer said, describing the goal, during a television
interview at the second intermission. He seemed to hit the puck in
the air, as it bounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just swung at it,'' Niedermayer said. Describing his first
few shifts, Niedermayer said: ``I didn't have the confidence'' to
pass accurately. After a while, he said, it felt like he had not
missed a game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic return for Niedermayer, who had missed the
previous 10 games for using his stick to hit Worrell on his
helmeted head during a March 19 game on the same playing surface.
Niedermayer was allowed to practice with the Devils during his
suspension, but it is difficult for a player in these conditions to
maintain the necessary sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer's evening had many interesting moments. In the first
period, when the Devils were on a power play, Niedermayer lost his
grip on his stick. Noticing this was his brother, Rob Niedermayer,
a forward for the Panthers. In a subtle move, Rob Niedermayer used
his own stick to push away the stick of his brother. Perhaps it is
a trick they used on each other on the neighborhood rink in
Edmonton, Alberta, where they grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the second period, when Florida's Mike Sillinger
appeared to have a step on Niedermayer during a rush down ice,
Niedermayer caught up to him with a smooth skating stride and poked
the puck away before the Panther forward could shoot.
</P>
<P>
   When the Devils prepared for this game and Niedermayer's return,
Coach Larry Robinson was asked whether he thought Niedermayer might
be too ``hyped up.'' Robinson smiled at the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he's too hyped up,'' Robinson said. ``In all the years
I've known Scotty Niedermayer, I don't think I've ever seen him too
hyped up. If anything, it's the other way, not hyped up enough.
He's a pretty laid-back individual - very intelligent,
philosophical about what he does. Being too intense, I don't think
he'll have a problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Inefficiency on the power play reached a rather high level for
the Devils, who failed with the man advantage five times in the
first two periods. They were presented with a grand opportunity for
a four-minute manpower advantage just 84 seconds into the gane,
when Rob Niedermayer of the Panthers was assessed a double minor
for high-sticking Bobby Holik.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took four shots with the manpower advantage, but none
of high quality. They had a good chance on their third manpower
advantage, when Scott Niedermayer's backhander was thwarted by
Vernon. But the Devils proved more productive playing short not
just one but two men.
</P>
<P>
   A penalty against Ken Daneyko for high sticking at the end of
the first session left the Devils two men short for 78 seconds at
the start of the second period. But the Devils managed to score 56
seconds into the period to tie the score. Florida had taken the
lead in the opening period on Sillinger's goal.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Niedermayer scored the tying goal on a rebound after a
shot by John Madden during a two-on-one break. Niedermayer jumped
into the play the moment Madden gained possession on the left and
beat the sprawled Vernon to celebrate his return after his
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Sillinger's goal came with 5:15 left in the first period, and it
was primarily the work of Pavel Bure that created it. Getting the
puck behind the line on the right, Bure went to the net with
authority and Sillinger capitalized on the rebound in a crowd in
front of Martin Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   There were few chances for either team to take the lead going
into the third period _ two attempts by Bure that Brodeur turned
aside with seven minutes left, and a shot off the crossbar by the
Devils' in the waning seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were pleasantly surprised this morning when Daneyko
and Jason Arnott reported for the morning skate in much better
health than a day earlier. Daneyko did not work Saturday, and
Arnott skated only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Daneyko's strained abdominal muscle felt much better and he kept
intact his streak of playing in every playoff game in Devils
history. Daneyko, who will celebrate his 36th birthday on Monday,
played in his 110th playoff game and showed no ill effects of the
injury he sustained on Thursday in the first period of the opening
game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott's sprained right wrist, which forced him to miss the
third period of the opening game victory, played in his usual spot,
centering for Patrik Elias on the left and Petr Sykora on the
right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
