<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURED ANDERSON TAKES RARE DAY OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Anaheim Angels' Garret Anderson missed his first
game of the season Sunday, sitting out with a tender left ankle.
Anderson rolled the ankle over when batting in the first inning
Saturday but played the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like (Anderson playing in) center field would be a
stretch today,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``DH was a possibility
because he's swinging the bat well, but he can't plant and turn the
way he wants to. You don't want to mess up a guy's swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, the former Kennedy High of Granada Hills star, has
played in at least 150 games in each of the past four seasons,
including a career-high 157 games last year. Anderson prides
himself on playing every day, but Scioscia says everybody needs a
day off now and then.
</P>
<P>
   ``This schedule is the most demanding in professional sports, I
don't care what position you're playing,'' he said. ``You talk
about keeping the lineup together 150-some games, but 162 is not
realistic. There are going to be days a guy needs a day off, and
today was one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Centered: Darin Erstad played center in Anderson's place, and
made a spectacular diving catch in left-center field of a ball hit
by Chicago's Paul Konerko leading off the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ran as hard as I can, and if I get to it, I get to
it,'' Erstad said. ``I'm going after it hard, and whatever happens,
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't find a better catch in left-center field anywhere,''
Scioscia said. ``That was some play.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said there will be no center-field controversy.
Anderson has the job, and Erstad will get an occasional start in
center when Anderson needs a day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garret's our center fielder,'' he said. ``He's comfortable in
center and he's done an outstanding job. We think it gives us a
solid outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``G.A. throws a little better and is more accurate. Erstad
charges the ball hard and gets rid of it quickly. There are pros
and cons, but in our estimation, Garret's a better fit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the field: With Erstad moving from left to center, Edgard
Clemente got his first start in left field Sunday, having started
two previous games as the DH. He got his first hit as an Angel on
Sunday with an infield single in the fourth inning, and got his
first RBI with a groundout in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Positive step: Pitcher Tim Belcher's rehab start at Single-A
Lake Elsinore went well Saturday night. Belcher, recovering from
offseason elbow surgery, pitched three hitless innings, striking
out four while making 30 pitches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
