<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8833 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-L     04-16 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' SCHOENEWEIS BEATS WHITE SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- Scott Schoeneweis isn't exactly a household name. In
fact, most people can't even pronounce his name.
</P>
<P>
   But the pitcher is making observers take notice, his performance
Sunday in the Anaheim Angels' 3-1 victory over the Chicago White
Sox the latest to turn heads. Schoeneweis limited the majors'
top-hitting team to three hits in eight innings to earn the win and
improve to 3-0. He lowered his ERA to 2.35, best among the club's
starters.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's outing before 10,929 at Comiskey Park followed the
left- hander's three-hit shutout of the Toronto Blue Jays. And it
followed Kent Bottenfield's performance (7 innings, 0 runs, 5 hits)
one day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job Bottenfield and Schoeneweis did the last two (days)
against a team not only the hottest in baseball, but a talented
offensive group, is a great sign,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia
said. ``That order is power- packed from the right side. What Scott
did today was a tremendous job of pitching. He used all his pitches
and moved the ball around.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Schoeneweis allowed a run Sunday, he said he felt
better than when he threw the shutout last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm was a little tired coming out of spring training,'' he
said. ``Also, I'm learning. Every time out I learn something new
about how my stuff works, how to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The only run he allowed came on Ray Durham's two-out, RBI double
in the third inning. After that, no White Sox baserunner got as far
as third base and only one reached second. Schoeneweis is gaining
confidence with each outing but is focusing on keeping a level
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really trying to keep everything in perspective, go start
to start,'' he said. ``In between starts, keep an even keel. The
more I'm out there, the more confidence I have, but after I talk to
you guys, it's over. I'm looking toward my next start against
Tampa.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense supported Schoeneweis with 13 hits but scored
only three runs. Scott Spiezio had an RBI double in the fourth off
former UCLA and Crescenta Valley High star Jim Parque (1-1), then
scored later in the inning on a sacrifice fly by Bengie Molina for
a 2-0 lead. After the White Sox cut the lead to 2-1, the Angels
scored in the sixth when Troy Glaus doubled, went to third on a
single by Spiezio and scored on Edgard Clemente's groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival pitched a 1-2-3 ninth for his fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio and Darin Erstad each had three hits, but Erstad's
biggest play of the day might have been his diving catch of a liner
to the left-center-field gap hit by Paul Konerko leading off the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player,'' Schoeneweis said of Erstad. ``That just
pumps you up, pumps up the whole team. He does it all. He's the
hardest-nosed player I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   As a whole, the Angels are pumped up about their start, thanks
to their starting pitching, which is 7-3 with a 3.01 ERA in 12
games. Expectations for the starters were low going into spring
training, but Scioscia and others promised it would be better than
advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of `I told you so,''' Scioscia said. ``It's
a matter of a group of pitchers stepping up and living up to our
expectations. Throw Kent Bottenfield into the mix and you have a
solid rotation. We're pleased with where our pitching has been,
needless to say. But we're also just scratching the surface when
you talk about contending for a championship. We're not at all
where we need to get to. We have to keep grinding it out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to know we can win tight ballgames,'' first baseman
Mo Vaughn said. ``The offense will click. Right now we're doing it
with good defense and pitching. What we need until guys start
swinging the bat is to win these types of ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn credits Scioscia for the team's play and positive
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard people say, `You've got a good mix, a great
chemistry.' It's a different feel,'' Vaughn said. ``That guy right
there (Scioscia) doesn't mess around. It's nice when you have that
type of feel in the dugout. I've never seen a guy never miss a
thing. He sees everything. ... Everyone wants to do well for
ourselves, but you also want to do well for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
