<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-CHAYES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABRAM CHAYES, HARVARD LAW PROFESSOR   AND JFK ADVISER, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Abram J. Chayes, an original member of President John
F. Kennedy's ``best and the brightest'' who had a profound
influence on US foreign policy and international law, died Sunday
at Brigham and Women's Hospital. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chayes enjoyed an extraordinary career in both law and
politics, most of which was spent at Harvard Law School, where he
had served as one of the school's most distinguished and respected
experts in international law since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret H. Marshall, chief justice of the Massachusetts Supreme
Judicial Court and a student of Mr. Chayes's in 1975, described him
Sunday as a ``brilliant, challenging, beloved professor'' who
``brought his own experience and great learning into the
classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chayes was born on the North Side of Chicago on July 18,
1922, to Edward and Kitty Chayes. After graduating from Senn High
School, Mr. Chayes followed his lifelong passion for law and
politics into, as a profiler once wrote, an ``admirable humdrum of
grand slams.''
</P>
<P>
   He received a bachelor's degree, magna cum laude and Phi Beta
Kappa, from Harvard in 1943. He served in Army field artillery
units in France, the Netherlands, Germany, and Japan from 1943 to
1946 and was discharged with the rank of captain.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chayes married Antonio (Toni) Handler on Christmas Eve 1947,
when he returned to Cambridge, and graduated magna cum laude from
Harvard Law School in 1949. He served as president of the Law
Review and was at the top of his class.
</P>
<P>
   His first job out of school was serving as legal adviser to
Connecticut Governor Chester Bowles from 1949 to 1951. After
Bowles's unsuccessful bid for reelection, Mr. Chayes went to
Washington, D.C., where he served as associate general counsel of
President Truman's Materials Policy Commission, clerked for Supreme
Court Justice Felix Frankfurter. He then went to work for the law
firm of Covington &AMP; Burling.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chayes returned to Cambridge in 1955 to join the Law School
faculty. ``Since then,'' he wrote in the 25th anniversary report of
Harvard's Class of 1943, ``with a single if lengthy break,
Cambridge has been my home.''
</P>
<P>
   That break came when, after working for Kennedy's unsuccessful
vice presidential bid in 1956, Mr. Chayes was among the first wave
of departures from Cambridge to Washington after Kennedy won the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   From 1961 to 1964, he served as chief legal adviser in the
Department of State. His duties included advising about the
blockade during the Cuban missile crisis, about which Mr. Chayes
wrote ``The Cuban Missile Crisis, International Crisis and the Role
of Law,'' published in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, especially in retrospect, an extraordinarily
exhilarating time to be in Washington,'' Mr. Chayes wrote. ``Much
was possible and almost everything seemed fun. Whether this is
truth or incurable utopianism, I'll leave to others.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, he went to the law firm of Ginsburg &AMP; Feldman in
Washington, before coming back to the law school in 1965, where he
remained. In 1976, he became the Felix Frankfurter Professor of
Law, and in 1993, he added emeritus to that title.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chayes went on to serve as chairman of George McGovern's
foreign policy panel, where he spoke out against President Richard
Nixon's incursions into Vietnam and Cambodia. Mr. Chayes also
served as foreign policy and defense task force adviser during
Jimmy Carter's presidential campaign in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Mr. Chayes followed his wife to Washington after Carter
appointed her the first female assistant secretary to the US Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
   One of the highlights of his legal career occurred in the 1980s
when Mr. Chayes represented Nicaragua in that country's World Court
case against the United States, attacking the Reagan
administration's policy of support for the contras and the attempt
to overthrow the Sandinista government. Reagan administration
officials walked out of the trial over a technical glitch and never
returned, giving Mr. Chayes and the case an empty victory.
</P>
<P>
   Anne-Marie Slaughter, director of the Graduate School of
International and Legal Studies at Harvard Law School, assisted Mr.
Chayes during the Nicaragua trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believed with passion that the US had to adhere to the
rules of international law,'' Slaughter said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mr. Chayes was the recipient of the Harvard Law
School Association Award, the school's most prestigious honor. He
also recently joined joined the Boston office of the international
law firm of McDermott, Will &AMP; Emery.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he leaves four daughters, Eve and
Abigail of Los Angeles, Sarah of Paris, and Angelica of Canaan,
N.Y.; a son, Lincoln of Los Angeles; and a sister, Judith
Chayes-Neiman of Baltimore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
