<HEADLINE>
STOCKS CONTINUE SHARP SELL-OFF IN WORLD MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Friday's rout on Wall Street reverberated across
Asia on Monday, with so-called old economy stocks sliding together
with technology-related issues as investors worried about the
potential fallout of declining stocks on the U.S. economy and its
demand for Asian exports.
</P>
<P>
   In early trading, stocks in South Korea fell 9 percent, Japan's
benchmark Nikkei index dropped more than 8 percent and the Hang
Seng index in Hong Kong slumped nearly 8 percent. Analysts were
predicting more of the same when markets opened in Hong Kong and
elsewhere overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more than we anticipated,'' said Joe Lee, an analyst
at Daiwa Securities in Seoul, South Korea. ``It's not just the tech
stocks. Everything is falling right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The reverberations across the Pacific came despite efforts by
financial officials to calm investors, who were responding to a
9.67 percent drop in the Nasdaq composite index on Friday, which
capped the worst week in its history. Australia's All Ordinaries
index dropped by more than 5 percent even after Prime Minister John
Howard went on the radio to remind shareholders of the strength of
Australia's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Officials attending the meeting of the seven major industrial
nations in Washington issued a statement on Saturday saying the
global economic outlook was continuing to brighten. And Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa of Japan predicted that Wall Street's
declines would not spread to Japan's stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts shared Miyazawa's optimism that stronger economic
fundamentals and a smaller number of Internet stocks would help
reduce the effect in Tokyo and that markets would recover ground
during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude of the sell-off won't be anywhere near where it
is in the U.S.,'' said Kathy Matsui, a strategist at Goldman, Sachs
in Tokyo. Japan is far behind the United States in terms of
adopting information technology, she said, giving its technology
companies much more room still to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some analysts said a shift away from high-technology
investments was likely to rekindle interest in emerging markets
like Indonesia, Thialand and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Despite positive economic growth forecasts, a dearth of
Internet-related stocks in those markets has left them far behind
those in North Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Currency markets echoed such optimism as Asian currencies
rallied against the dollar in spite of the tailspin on stock
markets. On Monday morning, the dollar fell to 104.66 yen from its
settlement price in New York on Friday of 105.09 yen.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts said their concern was that so much wealth
had evaporated with last week's declines _ more than $2 trillion _
that it could touch off waves of selling in Asia's smaller markets,
with the potential for even more drastic price declines. Any such
landslide in prices was likely to test government commitments to
free-market dynamics and resist the temptation to intervene to
protect asset values.
</P>
<P>
   Rising stock prices over the last year made it easier for Asia's
heavily indebted companies to service their loans and, in the
process, reduced the pressure on governments to reform their
banking sectors. A sharp decline in stock prices, analysts said,
was likely to refocus attention on the need for such restructuring
for Asia's long-term economic health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
