A8837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-CORZINE-2TAKES-NYT     04-16 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CORZINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORZINE'S PLANS ARE GREAT SOCIETY-LIKE IN NEW JERSEY CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Jon S. Corzine may be running only for the
Senate, but his proposals sound as sweeping as any president's
since Lyndon B. Johnson's Great Society.
</P>
<P>
   He envisions a national health care system, with insurance for
everyone. A national program of long-term care for the aged and
infirm. And enough new federal education spending to cover college
tuition for every high school graduate with a B average or better,
and preschool for every toddler.
</P>
<P>
   Even a cursory look at this breathtakingly expansive platform
raises some obvious questions: How much would it cost? Where will
the money come from? And are New Jersey voters, historically
moderate, ready for a candidate who seems so much like a throwback
to the 1960s?
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, the former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., says he
is running ``because it's time to get bold things done.'' In an era
when fiscal conservatism is almost synonymous with patriotism, he
has outlined programs that could cost hundreds of billions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   He has said much less about how he would pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   His candidacy rests on two propositions: that a society awash in
prosperity, its confidence in government buoyed by rising
surpluses, should be ready to spend liberally to solve its most
vexing social problems; and that the ideal guardian of the nation's
purse strings is someone like him _ a Wall Street-hardened
financier.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after President Clinton, a Democrat, said that ``the
era of big government is over,'' Corzine is perhaps the only
prominent Democrat in America arguing forcefully for a reversal of
the last two decades' steady shift in power from the federal
government to the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a generation of Democrats that is understandably
afraid to get out on any tree limb at all,'' said Susan Estrich,
who managed Michael S. Dukakis' 1988 presidential campaign and now
is advising Corzine. ``He isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's stands on social issues, meanwhile, make his fiscal
plans seem middle of the road. He supports allowing gays to marry
legally and to serve openly in the military. He favors greater
curbs on firearms than even the advocacy group Handgun Control. He
opposes the death penalty and any restrictions on abortion rights,
even for late-term procedures. And he supports affirmative action,
including set-asides for minority contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, his opponent in the Democratic primary, former
Gov. Jim Florio, is dying to meet Corzine head-on in a debate.
``The people of this state do not want extremes,'' Florio said.
``They do not want someone who's going to go out there promising
them the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine, 53, insists that more voters will be attracted by
his authenticity than repelled by his positions. ``Why should
someone run for political office if they're only going to shape
their views to poll-driven responses?'' he said in one of two
recent interviews. ``I actually think that's why people are
frustrated with politics in America. They know politicians tell
them what they want to hear to get elected. I have to have a
purpose in this exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's purpose in running for Senate begins with the
so-called social safety net. He endorses President Clinton's plan
to allow investment of up to 15 percent of the Social Security
trust fund in the stock market instead of only in safer, but
possibly less lucrative, government securities. He supports setting
aside $680 billion from future federal surpluses to cover rising
Medicare costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take on getting these safety-net programs properly
structured in a businesslike fashion,'' he said. ``These things are
vital. And if we don't pay attention to the details of how they are
organized, our society's going to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   It is on health care, however, that Corzine has focused the most
attention in his speeches and television commercials. Unlike Vice
President Al Gore, who wants to extend health care to the uninsured
in increments, he speaks of ``universal health care coverage'' for
all 44 million uninsured Americans as something that can and should
be done immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hillary Rodham Clinton's ill-fated 1993 national health
care plan, Corzine's proposal relies on employer mandates. All
companies would be required to offer insurance to their workers,
who would have to bear some of the cost themselves through
premiums. Smaller businesses would join regional insurance pools to
negotiate for discounts. The federal government would reimburse
businesses with fewer than 200 workers for the costs through
subsidies under a sliding scale.
</P>
<P>
   But while Corzine continues to speak in universal terms, he
leaves himself room to retreat to a half-measure. Pressed for weeks
to detail his approach and its costs, he released late on Friday a
one-page financial summary of two options. It stated that he
favored making health insurance a matter of individual choice, and
projected that half of America's uninsured would choose to remain
uninsured, limiting the government's costs to $21 billion. To cover
everyone, it said, would cost the government $42 billion and
employers $36 billion more than they already spend.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said that more than half the uninsured might well choose
to enroll up front, ``depending on how aggressively the system
markets itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it is affordable,'' he added, ``people will more
willingly volunteer to take up the opportunity. We could ultimately
move to some kind of requirement, but I don't think we should move
there on the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Corzine's heart clearly is in truly universal health
coverage. At a recent forum before nurses and other health care
professionals, he was asked if he supported a single-payer system.
He carefully avoided answering (though he later told a reporter
that he opposed it). ``Running around as a newcomer to politics and
talking about what is generally labeled socialized medicine would
probably be the kiss of death,'' he told the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said he was proudest of his proposals for long-term
care, an issue that has few champions in the national debate.
``This is something that when I get there, I will be an advocate
for the next 10 years, till we get something done,'' he said. ``I
think I can make a deal out of this, because I think it's something
our society needs.''
</P>
<P>
   He supports Clinton's latest proposal for a $3,000 tax credit
for patients or their caregivers, though he says it should be
refundable and still dismisses it in the next breath as too little.
``It's nuts,'' he said. ``That's one month of assisted living.''
</P>
<P>
   As a more meaningful step, Corzine says he admires programs
begun by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation in New York,
Connecticut, California and other states that were intended to
entice people to buy their own long-term care insurance. Those
pilot programs, which under existing federal law cannot be expanded
to other states, assure participants that they will not need to
exhaust all their assets before qualifying for Medicaid in old age.
</P>
<P>
   But reviews have been mixed. ``Policy analysts like it a lot,
but people don't like these policies,'' said Joshua M. Wiener, an
expert on long-term care at the Urban Institute in Washington.
``Insurance agents don't like to sell them, either. It's opposite
the way they normally sell. They usually say, `Buy this product and
you'll never go on that horrible Medicaid.' Now, they're saying,
`Buy this and, should you use up your benefits, we'll get you on
Medicaid faster.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Corzine said he believed that a national long-term
care system should be folded into Medicare or a Social
Security-like program. Wiener said that this could cost $70 billion
or more.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said the tab should be much less, because individuals
and employers would both contribute, but he could not elaborate.
``I'm very admitting that it's the formative stage, but I think
we've got to encourage our society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he deliberately set his sights higher than his
expectations but that he was not unrealistic. But his grand plans,
outlined on his Web site at www.votecorzine.org, do come at a
price.
</P>
<P>
   In education, for example, Corzine said he would raise spending
by $30 billion to cover initiatives for preschool and kindergarten
through the 12th grade. Beyond that, he wants to copy a scholarship
program in Georgia, which pays for two years of tuition at a state
college for any student who maintains an average of B or better. If
students qualify for a national scholarship program at the same
rate they do in Georgia, the cost could reach $16 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine also favors a fully refundable college tuition tax
credit for low-income families. That would cost more than $9
billion after three years, according to the Progressive Policy
Institute in Washington. All told, his education programs alone
could add $55 billion to the nation's annual budget, roughly five
times what Gore has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, the combative former governor, says Corzine's proposals
are irresponsible or naive. ``At the very beginning, when he was
out there, I chastised him gently, saying, `You've got to be
specific,''' Florio said of his opponent. ``Then he came forward
with this set of specifics that are unaccounted for in terms of the
costs, and that's the opposite extreme. It's irresponsible to say,
`I'm for everyone having a good life, elect me.' Or on the other
side, `I'm for everybody having 17 Cadillacs in their driveway,'
without saying how they're going to pay for them.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Corzine's Web site does omit any bottom-line dollar
figures, Corzine asserted that his proposals could all be paid for
with the $750 billion in non-Social Security surpluses projected by
the federal government over the next 10 years. Where necessary, he
said, senators could always cut pork-barrel spending. And in an
economic downturn, he would favor deficit spending, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
