<HEADER>
A8842 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GIGASIDEBAR-POWERMAC-     04-16 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIGASIDEBAR-POWERMAC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 POWER MAC BESTS THE GIGAHERTZ PCs  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ During the past 18 months, while top PC
processor speeds have jumped from 450 megahertz to a gigahertz, the
PowerPC chip used in Apple Macintoshes has climbed only from 400 to
500 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   But the PowerPC has always been able to get more work done in
each clock cycle than Intel and Advanced Micro Devices processors.
</P>
<P>
   That's all the more true with the latest PowerPC, the G4,
especially with programs updated to take advantage of its key
innovation, a ``vector-processing unit'' Apple calls the Velocity
Engine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, running at half the clock speed of the competition is a
significant handicap, and as I tested the performance of the new
gigahertz PCs, I wasn't at all certain Apple's machines could keep
up. So I set out to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, none of the major benchmarks of real-world
performance runs on both platforms, so I turned to Adobe Photoshop
5.5, a program available in virtually identical versions for Mac
and Windows. It's not only a widely used application, but also a
pretty good indicator of overall processor performance.
</P>
<P>
   Using the same test file _ a 50-megabyte scanned image of
Yosemite _ and an Adobe plug-in that tells Photoshop how to take
advantage of the PowerPC G4's Velocity Engine, I clocked a series
of seven processor-intensive operations _ the same ones I had
earlier run on the PCs _ on a 450-megahertz Power Mac G4. (Apple
announced a 500-megahertz version of the same machine in February,
but I didn't have access to one of those.)
</P>
<P>
   When I first ran the tests on the Power Mac, it ``only'' had the
128 megabytes of memory that comes standard with this model. In
this configuration, it handily outperformed one of the gigahertz
PCs, a Hewlett-Packard 1G with Intel Pentium III and 128 megabytes
of RAM. The Mac beat the Pavilion on six of the seven tests; its
total time for the whole sequence was 118 seconds, nearly a third
faster than the 185 seconds the Pavilion required.
</P>
<P>
   But the other gigahertz PC, Polywell Systems' Poly 800K7-1000
with an Athlon processor from Advanced Micro Devices, had done even
better, finishing the sequence in just 82 seconds. The Poly,
however, had a big advantage: 256 megabytes of memory. To level the
playing field, I swiped a 128-megabyte memory module from the
Gateway Select 1000, which was already idle because its screen had
gone blank. I restarted the Mac, adjusted Photoshop's memory
settings to use the additional RAM and tried the tests again.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there was no ambiguity: the 450-megahertz Power Mac
blew both gigahertz PCs out of the water, completing the
seven-operation sequence in just 55 seconds. Whereas the
Athlon-based Poly had scored about a third better than the Mac when
the former had twice the memory, the Mac cut its time in half and
finished a third ahead once the two systems were configured
equally.
</P>
<P>
   Applications differ, of course, and no doubt there are
legitimate comparisons where the PCs would come out ahead. But in
spite of Adobe's roots on the Mac, it can hardly be accused of
optimizing its products only for Apple hardware _ at times in the
past Photoshop has run better on the PC.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Mac partisans have no reason to panic about the
PowerPC's current clock-speed shortfall, and graphics professionals
who rely on Apple have no reason, at least in terms of performance,
to doubt their choice of platforms: The Mac's resounding victory in
this particular test is strong evidence that the PowerPC remains
more than competitive with the best Intel and AMD can produce.
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail Henry Norr at hnorr(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
