<SLUG> BC-NJ-PASS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-ZPASS SYSTEM: EASY FOR SOME STATES, DIFFICULT FOR NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's supposed to work like this: You get into your car in Boston
with an electronic toll tag affixed to the windshield like your own
personal herald. And you end up as far away as Philadelphia without
ever having to wait in a line or fumble with a single quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, something very big is standing in the way of this
seamless regional transportation vision. It is called New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   After years of delays in installing the E-ZPass toll collection
system on the Garden State Parkway, the New Jersey Turnpike and the
Atlantic City Expressway, state officials announced earlier this
month that the system would not be completed at all parkway toll
plazas by June, as promised, and that the job would probably drag
on into the fall.
</P>
<P>
   This came three weeks after officials had already pushed back
the deadline for the turnpike, the most difficult part of the
project, from May 22 to August or even September. In both cases,
officials did not announce exact new completion dates, and their
critics say the reason is that they were still wincing from the
last time they set dates only to miss them.
</P>
<P>
   For a state that almost voted its governor out of office three
years ago because of high auto insurance rates, a state whose
car-centered identity is rivaled perhaps only by California's, the
delays have become a running joke, one that people laugh at to keep
from cursing.
</P>
<P>
   And the problems have only added to the auto-related woes of
Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, whose administration's efforts to
install a tougher statewide emissions testing system have also been
plagued by delays and breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has more cars per square mile than any other state.
It has the nation's second-highest toll revenues, after New York.
And it was testing the concept of electronic toll collection before
any other state, dreaming of the day when a human toll collector,
who can process 250 cars an hour, would be replaced by a chunk of
electronics that can handle as many as 1,100 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But most of New Jersey's drivers can still only look enviously
north, where New York finished installing E-ZPass on the Gov.
Thomas E. Dewey Thruway three years ago, and northeast, where the
Massachusetts Turnpike has Fast Lane, a system compatible with
E-ZPass. (Delaware also has E-ZPass, and the system has been
proposed in Pennsylvania and Maryland.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a real black eye for the state,'' said
Assemblyman John S. Wisniewski, a Democratic member of the New
Jersey Assembly's transportation committee. Wisniewski has long
criticized the selection of Adesta Transportation, a subsidiary of
a troubled Georgia company, Able Telcom, as the contractor to
perform the $500 million installation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once problems surfaced,'' Wisniewski said, ``we had denial
after denial. We had an administration that refused to believe
there were problems when they were told.''
</P>
<P>
   But state officials overseeing the project contend that most of
the delays came even before a contractor was selected, and that
those delays were largely beyond anyone's control. The state's
contract with Adesta, for example, was held up for a year after a
rival bidder filed an unsuccessful lawsuit maintaining that the
selection process had been tainted.
</P>
<P>
   The State Legislature also had to pass a law allowing cameras at
toll plazas, so that the cars of drivers who failed to pay the
tolls could be identified.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the project's contract was not signed until 1998,
the same year the Whitman administration had said that the system
was supposed to be completely up and running.
</P>
<P>
   The delays since then, the officials say, have not been
unreasonable, considering that the job is perhaps the largest
electronic toll collection project in the world, predicted to
process a billion electronic tolls a year and eventually involve
more than 750 toll lanes, more than in any other state.
</P>
<P>
   An additional complication is the fact that because the New
Jersey Turnpike is what is known as a closed-ticket system, with
tolls that vary according to where drivers get on and off, it must
activate E-ZPass at all toll plazas at once, like a string of
lights.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden State Parkway and the Atlantic City Expressway charge
a flat fee, so workers are able to activate the system one plaza at
a time. On the parkway, work crews have been steadily marching
south, and E-ZPass is operating as far down as the Raritan toll
plaza in Middlesex County, the busiest on the highway. E-ZPass has
been working on the 44-mile Atlantic City Expressway since the fall
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing that could happen,'' said James Weinstein, the
state transportation commissioner, referring to the turnpike, ``is
to open it up and then have to shut it down. So we're being
especially cautious and diligent.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All these explanations mean little to drivers, and not just to
New Jerseyans, but also those for whom the turnpike is a major
commercial link. Don Spaulding, a truck driver based in Maine,
hauling a load of apples from Cape May to Massachusetts, waited 25
minutes to pay his toll on a recent Friday at the northernmost toll
plaza, near Ridgefield.
</P>
<P>
   Spaulding, 56, makes at least two trips a week through New
Jersey and said he did not want to think about the hours that have
evaporated over the years in the slow march toward turnpike toll
plazas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst,'' he said at the Vince Lombardi service area.
``We were jammed in there like sardines today. It's never this bad
in other states.''
</P>
<P>
   The very congestion that the system is meant to alleviate is one
of the biggest obstacles to installing it on time, engineers say.
The turnpike is one of the busiest highways in the world, with an
estimated 560,000 vehicles a day.
</P>
<P>
   By 5 a.m., the lanes had to be cleared and ready for traffic
again.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems with the company and the contract have long
been much more than logistical.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the contract was awarded, Adesta, then known as
MFS Network Technologies, was sold to a Georgia holding company
called Able Telcom, which soon began to struggle with its finances.
By this February, the company's debts were so high that it was
having difficulty getting loans and issued a warning that there was
``substantial doubt about the company's ability to continue as a
going concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, it managed to receive financing commitments from
private investors worth $90 million that it said would keep it
afloat. But the New Jersey contract was not helping matters: Able
Telcom said in a filing last week that the E-ZPass project was
responsible for $8.2 million of the $10.7 million in losses the
company reported for the three months ending on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Adesta, its subsidiary, had handled several big electronic toll
collection projects in Virginia, Colorado and elsewhere around the
country. But less than a year into its contract for New Jersey's
highways, Adesta almost lost the job when it was unable to make a
major component of the toll system _ the part that processes
violations _ work properly.
</P>
<P>
   The Regional Consortium, the group of five New Jersey area
transportation agencies that control the contract, began to fine
the company $25,000 a day _ $4.9 million in all _ for the delays.
And in April 1999, the company had to bring in a competitor to help
it finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   But problems persisted even after the violations center opened:
pictures of license plates taken by video cameras at the toll
plazas turned out too dark for officials to read; in the first four
months of operation, only 13 percent of toll violators were issued
tickets. (E-ZPass users prepay a selected amount; the system
automatically deducts the toll through a small toll tag when the
car passes through the toll lane.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company was also missing deadlines for finishing
the highways. In 1998, the company promised to finish every lane on
all three highways by early 2000. When the company failed to meet
that deadline, officials agreed to let it install the system in
fewer than half the lanes to begin with, and then finish the rest
after the system was running. But even that scaled-back plan has
not worked.
</P>
<P>
   Philip A. Kernan Jr., the president and chief executive of
Adesta Transportation, said the biggest problem was simply that New
Jersey officials, after getting such a late start beginning the
project, wanted it done faster than was realistic. And the company
agreed to the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was mutual delusion on that,'' said Kernan, who
took over as president two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The delays have grown so troubling to politicians in both
parties that the state Senate president, Donald T. DiFrancesco, a
Republican, recently formed a task force to investigate how Adesta
won the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The group will also look into the $488 million contract awarded
for an auto emissions testing system that has been plagued by
computer breakdowns and equipment failures, creating long lines of
angry drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator DiFrancesco's questions are no different than what any
normal person who is reading the papers, anybody riding on the
highways, is asking,'' said Rae Hutton, a spokeswoman for the
senator. ``You have to put yourself in the position of the average
motorist in New Jersey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
