<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8848 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MUSIC-TALENT-SFCHRON &LR;      04-16 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TALENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEB SITE HELPS ASPIRING ARTISTS FIND THEIR MUSICAL MUSE  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When she was just 5 years old, Alysha Antonino
knew she wanted to become a singer like her idol, Celine Dion.
</P>
<P>
   Alysha even made up her mind that just like Dion, she would one
day work with famed record producer-songwriter David Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 12-year-old Scotts Valley, Calif., girl is seeing her
dreams come true, thanks to a new Web startup called Tonos.com,
which has the backing of Foster and other top recording industry
heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   Alysha won a singing contest sponsored by the Web site, which
flew her to Hollywood for a recording session with Foster. During
the session, Foster phoned Dion and let her listen to Alysha sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said something like, `You've got a beautiful voice and
you're working with the best,''' Alysha said, still giddy about the
encounter weeks later. ``I was in shock. I didn't know what to say.
I think I almost passed out. It was so cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a 10-time Grammy award winner, is a co-founder of
Tonos.com, a Culver City, Calif., site that bills itself as a
``music insider's network,'' where aspiring artists and music fans
can seek the advice of top stars like songwriter-singer-producer
Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   Budding musicians can also receive online piano and guitar
lessons, collaborate via the Internet on new songs and, eventually,
watch live Web casts of recording sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first Internet site where music industry hopefuls,
professionals and fans can meet and work together,'' said Carole
Bayer Sager, the Grammy-award winning singer-songwriter who hatched
the idea for Tonos.com one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sager is best known for co-writing enduring pop tunes like
``That's What Friends Are For,'' ``Groovy Kind of Love'' and
``Don't Cry Out Loud.'' Now she hopes to compose another career as
an Internet entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has opened new avenues for unknown artists and
undiscovered garage bands to gain exposure by making their songs
available in formats like MP3.
</P>
<P>
   Although the music industry frets over how to contain music
piracy on the Web, major players like Sony and BMG are speeding up
the tempo on plans to use the Internet to increase sales.
</P>
<P>
   And numerous Web sites have formed to try to help new artists or
groups get exposure. One company, idealive Inc. of San Francisco,
recently launched a Web site designed to match musicians, painters,
filmmakers and other artists with investors.
</P>
<P>
   But Sager said she wanted her Web site to fill musicians' need
for professional mentoring and career advice.
</P>
<P>
   Sager, inspired by the consumer-oriented Motley Fool stock
investing site, said the site could ``demystify'' an industry
structured around knowing the right contacts to get through the
right doors.
</P>
<P>
   Tonos.com, named for the Greek word describing how musical notes
come together on a scale, seems to have a lot of the right people
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Sager, along with Foster and Edmonds, formed the company in
September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they loved about it was the mentoring aspect, the idea
that we could give back,'' Sager said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tonos' board is Sager's husband, Bob Daly, CEO of the
Los Angeles Dodgers baseball team and former chairman and co-chief
executive officer of Warner Bros. and Warner Music Group.
</P>
<P>
   Tonos has assembled a roster of mentors and talent scouts that
includes hot R&AMP;B producer-songwriter Rodney Jerkins, who has
produced hits for the likes of Whitney Houston, Jennifer Lopez and
Matt Serletic, who produced Carlos Santana's Grammy-award winning
``Smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   And Tonos garnered about $7 million in investments from venture
capital firm Sequoia Capital and Shockwave.com Inc., the online
entertainment spin-off of San Francisco's Macromedia Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring musicians and hobbyists can chat via the Internet with
professionals to learn about the inside of the business, like
contracts, royalties and percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Sager said she hopes to help others avoid the mistake she made
earlier in her career when she needlessly signed away large
percentages of royalties to songs like ``Nobody Does It Better.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the more subtle lessons about the music business,
Tonos offers more basic instructions. Tonos bought Net startup
NetMusic School, which offers interactive guitar and piano lessons
online.
</P>
<P>
   Tonos also uses a program called the Tonoscorder, developed by
well-known audio company Emagic of Germany, which allows singers,
musicians and songwriters to collaborate on songs via the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Tonos CEO Matt Farber said that as the site becomes more
popular, he plans to generate money through ads, sponsorships and
by selling products and services.
</P>
<P>
   To promote the site, Tonos has launched continuing ``You Sing
the Hit'' or ``You Write the Hit'' contests using the Tonoscorder.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Antonino, Alysha's mother, stumbled upon the Tonos
demo site in February and realized her daughter had the chance to
meet her idol Foster if she entered a singing contest.
</P>
<P>
   Alysha is no stranger to the stage. She has been working the
state fair circuit for a couple of years, has done a few weddings
and has performed the national anthem before big crowds at Oakland
A's, San Francisco Giants and San Francisco 49ers games.
</P>
<P>
   In a friend's trailer home in Soquel (Santa Cruz County), Alysha
recorded Celine Dion's ``Love Is on the Way'' and sent the tape to
Tonos.
</P>
<P>
   Sager said she was blown away when she heard the tape and called
the Antonino home on March 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the phone rang, it was Carole (Bayer Sager), and I was in
shock when she told me I won,'' Alysha said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Damian Fontana, a 34-year-old bread distributor from
Brick, N.J., submitted lyrics to an original song he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   On March 12, both Alysha and Fontana found themselves in
Foster's home studio in Malibu. Surrounded by a wall full of gold
and platinum records, Alysha spent six hours recording a
professional demo of Fontana's song with the coaching and producing
of Foster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love working in a studio and I love performing live,''
Alysha said.
</P>
<P>
   Tonos officials say country star Tim McGraw is considering
recording Fontana's song, and Edmonds has offered to sing backup
vocals for the track.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Alysha is getting more time in the spotlight. Foster
invited Alysha back to perform with him at a benefit concert two
weeks ago at the ritzy Beverly Hilton in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   What lies in the future for Alysha and Fontana, of course, is
still in the stars. The same can be said for Tonos, even for all
its star power, said analyst Mark Mooradian of Jupiter
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult time to build a consumer destination site
from scratch,'' Mooradian said. ``In terms of business models,
they're casting a wide net right now.
</P>
<P>
   The site might have trouble building a lucrative business model
from a limited audience of music insiders and music aspirants, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the site could succeed in drawing revenues from
business-to-business services for other music industry companies or
by finding other revenue sources from companies wanting to sell to
the niche music audience drawn by the NetMusic School or
Tonoscorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm looking forward to seeing from them is a great deal
of partnerships,'' Mooradian said.
</P>
<P>
   Sager and Alysha hope they both have seen the start of something
big.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has always been my dream, since I was 5 or 6, I always
wanted to be a singer,'' said Alysha. ``Even at 2, I was always
singing Disney stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Now's she's almost rubbing elbows with stars like Celine Dion.
``She's like my idol,'' Alysha said. ``I didn't know I was ever
going to get to talk to her. I can't wait to meet her someday.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
