<SLUG> BC-TECH21-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH21: FUEL CELLS COULD BE NEW WAY TO POWER GADGETS  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &LR; Editor's note: Tech21 is a new column that will appear in &LR; 
 &LR; this space on Mondays. Written by Chronicle staff writer and &LR; 
 &LR; technology buff Henry Norr, it will focus on developments in &LR; 
 &LR; computing and communications that will shape our lives in the &LR; 
 &LR; 21st century: gadgets and gizmos, tips and tricks, fundamental &LR; 
 &LR; innovations and important issues. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sometimes I wonder how long it will be before
we've covered the planet pole-to-pole with plastic water bottles
and used-up batteries. With recycling lagging and Miller putting
its beers in plastic, the outlook isn't good on the bottle front.
</P>
<P>
   But a solution may be in sight for the battery problem: Replace
them with ``fuel cells,'' devices that produce energy by putting
hydrocarbons such as methanol and ethanol through a catalytic
process, producing only heat, carbon dioxide, and water vapor as
byproducts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the buzz about fuel cells involves the automobile,
because Detroit, with help from Washington, is spending billions to
see whether the devices will someday provide an alternative to the
internal-combustion engine.
</P>
<P>
   To Robert Hockaday, that's starting from the wrong end of the
stick. It'll be years, most experts agree, before fuel-cell
technology is up to the huge challenge of powering cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Hockaday, a former Los Alamos National Laboratory scientist who
says he has been fascinated by fuel cells since childhood, thinks
it makes more sense to start small _ with ``micro-fuel cells'' just
big enough to charge cell phones, digital cameras, pocket
organizers and other miniature devices.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade ago, Hockaday formed a company, Energy
Related Devices, to pursue that idea as well as solar-energy
research, and in 1995 he left Los Alamos to devote himself full
time to his startup. Two years ago, he won funding from Manhattan
Scientifics, a New York technology incubator.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Manhattan Scientifics announced that Hockaday's
group had reached an important milestone: a micro-fuel cell that
puts out three times as much energy as conventional cell-phone
batteries. The long-term target, according to Hockaday, is 10-times
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   A complete engineering prototype of a product based on the
technology, aimed at the hot cell-phone market, will be ready in
the fall, he says. Assuming Manhattan succeeds in finding a
manufacturing and marketing partner for the technology, it should
reach the market sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   In its initial incarnation the device will supplement rather
than replace conventional batteries _ it won't deliver enough power
to run a phone by itself, but it will provide a steady trickle
charge to keep the regular batteries (any kind but NiCad) from
running down. It'll weigh only a couple of ounces, according to
Hockaday, and users will be able to attach it directly to the
phone, like the secondary batteries some phonemakers already offer,
or keep it in a ``power holster'' in a purse or clipped to a belt.
</P>
<P>
   All users will have to do is replace a tiny cylinder containing
methanol and water every three weeks or so. In return, they can
expect at least three times as much talk time and standby time as
current batteries deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Is Hockaday just another dreamer with a tiny startup and a
cockamamy scheme that'll never make it to market? Could be, but
after spending an hour or two on the phone with him, I don't think
so. Industry Week magazine last year named his micro-fuel cells
``Technology of the Year.'' And industry giants such as Motorola
and Samsung are reportedly working hard on similar projects, though
Hockaday says he's pretty sure he's still in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is not whether Hockaday is on to some important
technology, but whether he and his associates will be able to line
up the resources needed to commercialize it before competitors
catch up. I'm rooting for him.
</P>
<P>
   You can find out more about Hockaday and his fuel cells at his
Web site ( &LR; www.energyrelatedevices.com &LR; ) and Manhattan Scientifics'
site ( &LR; www.mhtx.com). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Locking down the PC
</P>
<P>
   I have DSL at home, the kind of ``always-on'' connection that
theoretically makes my computers (I have lots of them) a potential
target for hackers. But because I usually turn my systems off when
I'm not using them, and I don't have any deep, dark secrets on them
anyway, I never worried much about security.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one night in February, I accidentally left a PC on
overnight. The next morning I found a bizarre dialogue box on its
screen: ``Fetch callback failed,'' it said. The only button was
labeled ``Ouch.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Yahoo, then a list of other high-profile Web
sites, began falling victim to a wave of denial-of-service attacks.
Experts said the floods of data that shut them down came from
computers where hackers had, without their owners' knowledge,
planted malicious applications.
</P>
<P>
   I decided it was time to get serious about security, or at least
about assessing the magnitude of the threat.
</P>
<P>
   My first move was to do some online research on ``personal
firewall'' software, programs that monitor network traffic and
attempt to block unauthorized intrusions. Symantec's entry in that
category, called Norton Internet Security 2000, got good reviews,
but most of the sources I checked said BlackICE, a $39.95 program
from a San Mateo company called Network ICE, was considerably
simpler and at least as effective.
</P>
<P>
   So I got an evaluation copy of the program, loaded it up, and
left my PC on for a month to see what would happen. BlackICE, which
runs constantly in the background, logs everything it considers an
intrusion, recording the IP address the suspect data packets came
from and what the program thinks they were up to.
</P>
<P>
   I was astonished at the results. In just a month, BlackICE
recorded 23 intrusions from sites all over the world, the first
from a domain called  &LR; celery.mit.edu &LR; , but most from abroad _
Taiwan, Japan, Germany, Israel, Brazil and a lot of other addresses
I didn't recognize.
</P>
<P>
   One nice feature of BlackICE is its ``AdvICE'' button: You can
click it after selecting an entry in the program's log, and it
opens your browser to a page on the publisher's Web site with
details about the kind of attack in question.
</P>
<P>
   None of those it recorded on my machine were actually
destructive; they were all just ``probes'' attempting to elicit
responses that would indicate a security hole the hacker could come
back to exploit in the future. In most cases, according to the
explanations BlackICE provided, the probes were looking for known
vulnerabilities in Solaris, Linux or other forms of Unix, not for
Windows problems.
</P>
<P>
   I can't be sure that the packets BlackICE considered suspect
really were ill-intentioned, nor that the addresses it recorded
were those the probes really came from. And as best I can tell,
none of the intrusions would have actually produced a harmful
result even if I hadn't had BlackICE to protect me.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of PCs and Macs with always-on cable and DSL
connections is exploding, and it seems it's only a matter of time
before hackers start finding ways to penetrate such machines and
hijack them for nefarious purposes. Under the circumstances,
running a firewall program seems only prudent. Personally, I've
gone back to shutting down my PCs when I'm not using them, but I'm
keeping BlackICE installed just in case.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to learn more about PC security, one excellent
resource is the ShieldsUp Web site ( &LR; grc.com/x/ne.dll?bh0bkyd2 &LR; ),
where Steve Gibson, a well-known PC programming wiz, offers lots of
useful and clearly presented information, as well as free software
that quickly tests your PC for security vulnerabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson also provides detailed assessments of a number of
software firewalls ( &LR; grc.com/su-firewalls.htm &LR; ). Although he used
to be partial to BlackICE, I should note that he's found some flaws
in it; his current favorite is ZoneAlarm 2.1 from Zone Labs of San
Francisco ( &LR; www.zonelabs.com &LR; ). It's free for personal and
nonprofit use and just $19.95 for business use.
</P>
<P>
   None of these programs runs on the Mac, but I know of two others
that do: OpenDoor Networks' DoorStop ( &LR; www2.opendoor.com/ &LR; 
 &LR; doorstop/ &LR; ) and Intego's NetBarrier. DoorStop is available in
several versions, but the ``Personal Edition'' is $59; NetBarrier
is $74.95. OpenDoor, which is headed by a former Apple networking
guru, also provides a useful white paper about Mac OS Internet
security issues at  &LR; www2.opendoor.com/doorstop/macOSsecurity.html.
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Judge Jackson
</P>
<P>
   Breaking Microsoft or imposing restrictions on its business
practices might be effective ways to prevent Gates &AMP; Co. from
expanding their monopoly into new areas, but they won't do anything
to reduce Windows' overwhelming dominance in PC operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Even splitting the company into multiple ``Baby Bills,'' each
with the right to market all of the current company's products,
won't do that. Competition of that sort might result in lower
prices, but it wouldn't create any new alternatives to Windows or
bolster the chances of existing alternatives such as Linux or BeOS.
On the contrary, lower prices for Windows would actually make it
all the more difficult for challengers to gain any ground.
</P>
<P>
   Some would argue that this is a lost cause _ that Windows is by
now so firmly established as the OS standard that nothing the judge
could do would really reopen the desktop market.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but I think it's worth a try. And it seems to me that
one relatively simple step would go a long way in this direction:
Make Microsoft publish, or at least license on reasonable terms,
the Windows application programming interfaces (APIs), together
with all the supporting code libraries that are needed to make
Windows applications run, to current or future developers of
alternative OSes.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as the good judge argued so convincingly in his
``findings of fact'' last fall, the key to Microsoft's power is
``the applications barrier to entry.'' Few users choose Windows
because it manages hardware so efficiently, and even fewer, I'm
sure, because it's so stable and reliable. People need it because
it's required for most of the applications they want to run.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of IBM's OS/2. Technically, it was far
superior to the Windows versions, but it couldn't run Windows 95
applications, and that killed it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, most people don't pick Windows at all _ they get it
simply because it's what comes with a PC. But any PC-maker
contemplating switching to an alternative would have to face the
fact that such a move would instantly cost it most of its
customers, because its machines would no longer run the programs
they want and need.
</P>
<P>
   Now suppose Microsoft had to disclose the code and technical
information Windows applications require, and keep doing so as it
developed new versions. Linux distributors, Be and anyone else who
wanted to play _ maybe even IBM again _ could incorporate that code
into their systems, making it possible for customers to run
off-the-shelf (and off-the-Web) Windows applications in these
alternative environments, without rebooting, adding emulation
software or any other special burdens.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this wouldn't trigger any large-scale abandonment of
Windows; if nothing else, inertia would prevent that. But other OS
developers would at least have a chance to demonstrate the merits
of their products without asking customers to give up all the
applications they depend on.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, that might lead to some real competition to Windows _
and isn't that what the case was supposed to be about in the first
place?
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear from you
</P>
<P>
   Make this new column an interactive experience _ pass on your
reactions to what I write, or your own insights about the
technology scene and your tips about cool new products and
services. I can't provide individual tech support or buying advice
_ I don't get paid to do that _ and though I'll respond, either
directly or in print, to as much of your mail as I can, odds are I
won't have time to reply to everyone. But I'll read everything you
send, and I'll take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
