 STILL TIME LEFT TO FILE TAX FORMS  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's April 17, and still you haven't turned in
your tax forms. In fact, you haven't finished them. Perhaps _ sigh
_ you haven't even started them.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly a healthy dose of self-flagellation is in order. But
what then?
</P>
<P>
   First of all, take heart. You may be a procrastinator, but
you're in good company: 25 to 30 percent of Americans turn in their
tax forms on the last possible day. That's not expected to change
this year, even though filers have a two-day reprieve, since April
15, the usual day for filing taxes, fell on a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   If it is impossible to finish your paperwork on time, you need
to get an extension using IRS Form 4868. Like other tax forms, it
must be postmarked or sent electronically by midnight tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Along with hundreds of other IRS forms, 4868 can be printed out
from the agency's home page at &LR;  www.irs.gov &LR; . Click on the Forms &AMP;
Pubs button at the bottom of the page.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, the IRS has an automatic fax number for the 150
most common forms and for answers to frequently asked questions.
You must use a telephone attached to a fax machine; follow the
recorded instrucTions to have documents faxed to you. The number,
(703) 368-9694, is not toll-free.
</P>
<P>
   Many last-minute filers owe the IRS money, since people
expecting refunds tend to file earlier in the year. If you owe,
don't forget to include a check with your extension form.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, you can pay via MasterCard, American Express or
Discover for a fee by calling (888) 272-9829, a commercial service.
Visa does not participate in the program, which charges a small fee
based on how much your tax bill is.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Many libraries, post offices, community centers, copy shops
and IRS branch offices carry paper tax forms, although supplies may
be running low by today. People without Internet access can log on
at the library and print out forms from the IRS site.
</P>
<P>
   IRS staff will be handing out forms at San Francisco's
Montgomery Street BART and Muni station today from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m.
and from 4 p.m. to 6 p.m. The IRS branch at 55 Market St. in San
Jose will be handing out forms curbside from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Once your forms are ready to go, you still have to get them
postmarked by midnight. Otherwise, you'll be assessed a monthly
penalty of 0.5 percent of your total tax bill until you pay up,
even if you're requesting an extension.
</P>
<P>
   Several area post offices will be open late this evening.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As you do your tax return, try to get the math right: If you
send a payment that is at least 10 percent less than the amount
owed, you may be penalized.
</P>
<P>
   People who have Internet access (and even some who don't) have
the option of filing their tax forms electronically. The IRS site
includes a list of commercial software providers, which typically
offer interactive instructions along with electronic forms. Click
Electronic Services at the bottom of the home page, and then click
Online Software Filing Companies for a list of links.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS urges taxpayers to ``e-file'' to cut down on paperwork,
lost documents and other problems. The main advantage to filers is
that refunds typically take three weeks, compared with 10 weeks for
paper filers.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of individual federal tax forms are expected to
be e-filed this year, up from a quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;R Block, Jackson Hewitt and Intuit are the most popular
software services. Most charge a fee of at least $10. Your
neighborhood accountant may also agree to key in the data from your
paper tax form and file it for you electronically, but expect a
charge of up to $60.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income individuals can ask their local IRS office to file
for them electronically if their forms are less than 12 pages long,
said Larry Wright, a spokesman for the IRS in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   If you are e-filing from home, don't wait until 11:58 p.m. to
try to send your documents. E-filings must be routed through a
third-party ``electronic return originator,'' since the IRS is not
set up to receive individual files. Send your e-filing as early as
possible to avoid electronic logjams, Wright advised.
</P>
<P>
   If you are e-filing for the first time, you will need to send a
copy of Form 8453 via snail mail to the IRS; this is your official
ignature, which the IRS keeps on file. In the following years, you
can simply include a personal identification number that the IRS
will assign you in lieu of a hard-copy signature.
</P>
<P>
   And what about your employer's W-2 or other official forms you
typically send in the mail with your tax filing? You don't need to
send them when you file electronically, but you do need to keep
them in case you are audited.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions about filling out your forms, several
resources are available today.
</P>
<P>
   Answers to the most common questions _ such as the address you
should send your tax forms to _ can be found at  &LR; www.irs.gov &LR;  or
via fax at (703) 368-9694. Recorded answers to more than 140
questions can be found at (800) 829-4477. You'll need a touch-tone
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Live assistance is available via the IRS' toll-free information
line, (800) 829-1040. However, it will be extremely difficult to
get a live agent today on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   IRS agents and volunteer accountants will be staffing local
branch offices today from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. You can't make an
appointment in advance, though, so if you want help, expect to wait
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area IRS offices are at 450 Golden Gate in San Francisco,
1301 Clay St. in Oakland, 185 Lennon St. in Walnut Creek, 55 S.
Market St. in San Jose, 777 Sonoma Ave. in Santa Rosa and 1761
Broadway in Vallejo.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to submitting federal tax returns, many Californians
will file their state returns today. It's not necessary to file an
extension request if you can't file today. The state grants an
automatic extension until October 16. However, if you owe money,
your payment is due today, along with form FTB 3519.
</P>
<P>
   The Franchise Tax Board Web site provides downloadable forms and
information about e-filing and other topics at  &LR; www.ftb.ca.gov &LR; .
Refunds will be mailed to e-filers in seven to 10 working days.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
