<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE-STOCKS-SFCHR     04-16 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-STOCKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOSCOPE: FRIDAY'S DEBACLE MAY HAVE CREATED VALUES IN
BIOTECH  STOCKS 
 &HT;     BY TOM ABATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The market free fall finally pulled biotech
stocks into negative territory last week and now the question is
when and where they'll hit bottom.
</P>
<P>
   All year, biotech issues had outperformed tech stocks, but
Friday's selling frenzy proved too strong to resist.
</P>
<P>
   The largest biotech stock index, which covers 203 companies,
sank 13 percent Friday. That plunge wiped out the last of the gains
chalked up since January and put the index down nearly 3 percent
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotech is certainly not divorced from the overall market
mentality,'' said Tom Dietz, senior managing partner of Pacific
Growth Equities, a biotech specialty bank in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Friday's debacle, jitters in the broader market had
closed the window on initial public offerings in biotech. Although
Exelixis Inc. of South San Francisco snuck in just before it shut
last week, neighboring Rigel Pharmaceuticals wasn't so lucky. It
postponed its IPO indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a gross abandonment of biotech,'' Dietz said.
``But even the guys who play long term are letting the market hit
bottom before they start buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Where biotech bottoms obviously depends on the overall market
psychology. But Bob Adler, president of AMG Services, which tracks
mutual fund money flows, offered one ray of hope: Money flowed into
biotech mutual funds last week after four straight weeks of
outflows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only $130 million, the smallest inflow of the year, but
it was positive nevertheless,'' Adler said.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests that investors are sitting on the sidelines
waiting to buy, he said. Of course, his figures came before
Friday's bloodbath. If spooked investors withdraw money from
biotech funds, it could deepen and prolong the slide in share
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McCamant, editor of the Medical Technology Stock Letter in
Berkeley, said he'll be buying next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday's plunge was so big it created values,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCamant thinks biotech stocks will get a lift from news on the
horizon. Cancer researchers will gather in New Orleans next month
for the American Society for Clinical Oncology, the most
prestigious scientific gathering in the field. Cancer is enormously
important to biotech firms. Roughly half of the 369 biotech
medicines now undergoing human trials are cancer related, according
to the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies release their best clinical trial results
at this meeting,'' said McCamant. Such news often gives companies a
lift.
</P>
<P>
   Another blast of positive news will come sometime in the next
two months, when public and private scientists complete a
preliminary map of the human genome. Excitement over genomics
sparked the earlier biotech rally and McCamant thinks it could help
biotech recover.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, perhaps, the market should eventually realize
that biotech firms are better bets than the Internet stocks whose
weakness sparked the sell-off, said Steve Burrill, who runs his own
biotech investment bank in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have real companies with real products, not like the
Internet companies that are still dreaming of becoming
businesses,'' Burrill said.
</P>
<P>
   But since it might take a couple of weeks for the broader market
to stabilize, biotech is probably in for continued uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see big moves like this, the market bounces around so
much that I wouldn't expect to see a bottom until the end of
April,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're interested in biotech, do what the pros are doing.
Wait, watch and focus on the two P's: profits and products.
</P>
<P>
   Profitable biotech firms like Amgen, Biogen, Immunex and
Genentech have all been clobbered, somewhat indiscriminately. When
the rebound comes, they'll lead the bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ignore the vast majority of biotech firms that are still
losing money. But check out the product pipeline charts on their
Web sites before you start bottom fishing. Firms with several
products in Phase II or, even better, Phase III trials are your
best bets. There are no guarantees, but the later in the testing
process you buy into a company, the less the risk.
</P>
<P>
   And don't worry about getting in too late. Dave Flores,
publisher of the BioCentury newsletter in San Carlos, Calif., likes
to say that the stock chart of a biotech firm with a newly approved
drug looks like a hockey stick.
</P>
<P>
   There's a little rise as the company nears the end of the
testing process. But the real gains come after the drug gets past
the FDA and delivers revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, don't worry that biotech is facing some huge
reckoning like the dot-catastrophe stocks. When biotech was
overvalued earlier in the year, I warned the bubble couldn't last.
</P>
<P>
   Now I can't predict where the sector will bottom, but I can tell
you this: Biotech has real products. It will come back.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITOL CONNECTION: Some 40 members of the House of
Representatives have reactivated a biotech caucus, led by Rep. Tom
Ewing, R-Ill., and Rep. Cal Dooley, D-Hanford (Kings County).
</P>
<P>
   The caucus first formed in the early '90s, during the last big
bout of public and Wall Street fascination with biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   But as public interest in the sector waned, the caucus fell
idle. In recent months, however, issues like genetically engineered
food labeling, concerns over gene patents and the privacy issues
surrounding the release of genetic information have all heightened
congressional interest. It hasn't hurt that biomedical research and
drug development are seen as high-paying industries akin to
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech industry representatives are delighted. ``Any time you
can get 40 members in a room at one time to explain your issues,
that's great,'' said Nancy Myers, a lobbyist for the Biotechnology
Industry Organization.
</P>
<P>
   INCIVILITY: Last week, I moderated a debate over the risks and
benefits of genetically modified foods. As strong as emotions run
over the issue, it was a polite affair until the end, when someone
came up and assaulted one speaker with a pie.
</P>
<P>
   No charges were pressed. It was not that big a deal. But it
seemed so foolish and counterproductive that I wonder why it
happened at all.
</P>
<P>
   Understand the setting. A hundred or so people in a room. Two
speakers on stage for an hourlong discussion. I can imagine no
better example of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what passes for free speech isn't really free. It's
filtered through the media, through people like me who have
shortcomings and biases. So why penalize someone who is willing to
stand up in an open forum? Why inhibit the freest form of free
speech we have available?
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Othello, he who steals my purse steals trash. But
he who filches another's free speech robs that which enriches him
not, but makes us all the poorer.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at abate(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
