r a BC-TAX-HUMOR-KAN &LR;      04-16 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-HUMOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS KIND OF SEASONAL HUMOR CAN BE TAXING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ You're nursing a migraine, snapping pencils
and up to your elbows in 1099-Bs. How funny is that?
</P>
<P>
   It's tax time and, once again, America insists on opening its
tattered bag of tax jokes. As today's filing deadline nears, it may
seem that everyone but you is laughing it up, even when the jokes
stink.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one from Tom Antion &AMP; Associates, sales consultants:
</P>
<P>
   ``A tax return is like a girdle. If you put the wrong figure in
it, you're likely to get pinched.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Wide Web's got a million of them.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City-based Hallmark Cards has joined the party, allowing
Internet users to send free electronic messages sure to tickle the
ribs of that special tax preparer. The e-cards say, ``Happy Tax
Day,'' and Hallmark expects to move at least a quarter-million. One
card features the ``The Adventures of IRS Man,'' who holds a
taxpayer upside down to shake out his change.
</P>
<P>
   You never knew that tax time was such a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   OK. We all know it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it's not terribly tough to find something humorous
about W-2s in a world where even presidential adultery can put
late-night audiences in stitches for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call tax day a celebration,'' said Hallmark.com
spokeswoman Kathi Mishek. ``But there's nothing wrong with taking
your medicine with a spoonful of sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why those kooky accountants at CPAdvantage.com came up
with a list of accounting jokes. More than 100 in all, they range
from pickup lines, such as ``Nice assets,'' to jokes only
number-crunchers would love, such as ``You might be a CPA if ... at
the movie `Indecent Proposal' you did an NPV calculation.''
</P>
<P>
   NPV calculation. Get it?
</P>
<P>
   Try this, then: What's the difference between the short form and
the long form?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you use the short form, the government gets your money. If
you use the long form, the CPA gets your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop, you're killing us.
</P>
<P>
   If any kind of humor is hit or miss, it's tax-time humor. A
mouse click to www.4comedy.com proves it.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site features ``Spotlight: Taxing Humor.'' It mixes the
rather clever _ ``A harp is a piano after taxes'' _ with a clunky
rim shot _ ``Americans are now in a daze of intaxication.'' Half
the lines are bitter: ``If our president wants to abolish poverty,
he can do it by abolishing the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   Far funnier, accountants will tell you, are the true stories
about tax preparation. A favorite at H&AMP;R Block Inc. involves a
California client who donated his deceased wife's body to science
and wished to write it off as a charitable contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``True story,'' company spokesman Todd Ransom said. ``The
preparer had to come up with a fair-market value on the cadaver.''
</P>
<P>
   So the tax preparer calls up some medical colleges and
hospitals. ``The strangest part of it,'' Ransom said, ``is, yes, he
could take a deduction. The IRS accepted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's funny. But is this?:
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is an income tax, the just man will pay more and
the unjust less on the same amount of income.''
</P>
<P>
   The Greek philosopher Plato said it 24 centuries ago, and even
now it's too true to be funny.
</P>
<P>
   In cyberspace, where everyone's a comedian, Web masters have
been taxing their noggins to one-up Ben Franklin's classic line,
``Nothing is certain but death and taxes.'' So at
www.taxspecialists.com, they came up with ``Death: to stop paying
taxes suddenly.''
</P>
<P>
   Another site that bills itself as Ammo for Freedom Fighters
offers a quote from Will Rogers. ``The difference between death and
taxes,'' Rogers said, ``is death doesn't get worse every time
Congress meets.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, talk show host David Letterman weighed in with
his ``Top 10 Dumb Accountant Tax Tips'':
</P>
<P>
   10. Don't file a W-2 form unless your name begins with ``W.''
</P>
<P>
   9. Answer every question ``Wouldn't you like to know?''
</P>
<P>
   8. Hide all money in mattress and on return write, ``No money
hidden in mattress.''
</P>
<P>
   7. If you've just eaten, don't do taxes for at least half an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   6. Hire yourself as an employee, fire yourself, sue yourself for
discrimination, deduct court costs.
</P>
<P>
   5. Report $1 billion in income so IRS will think you're some
sort of big shot.
</P>
<P>
   It's downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   Enough with the tax jokes?
</P>
<P>
   Please, said Laura R. Ingraham, assistant professor of
accounting at North Carolina State University. She, after all,
knows the meaning of NPV calculation. It stands for net present
value, and refers to the time value of a dollar. No, she said, that
joke isn't very funny.
</P>
<P>
   Ingraham used to give her students copies of a letter supposedly
written to the Internal Revenue Service by a woman whose children
were denied as deductible dependents. The woman wrote in jest, ``I
have questioned whether these are my children for years. They are
evil and expensive. ... This year they are yours!''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ingraham: ``Besides that letter, I haven't come up with
anything that made me laugh at taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to an intriguing question making the rounds: How
do you make an IRS auditor laugh on a Monday?
</P>
<P>
   Tell the auditor a joke on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rollie Woods, an IRS spokesman in St. Louis, didn't even giggle
at that last week. ``You work for the IRS, you best develop a thick
hide,'' he said. ``By and large, we're willing to go along with a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not easy, Woods said, when the jabs gets vicious.
``I've seen editorial cartoons with scenes of IRS employees being
maimed, shot at ... and that's when it gets personal.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate irony is that IRS workers _ the butt of so much bad
humor _ are forbidden from using their computers to pass along
their own jokes. And take it from Woods: What they know about tax
cheats is hilarious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
