<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON URGES DELAY IN ARMS SALES TO TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon has recommended deferring for at least
a year a decision on Taiwan's request to purchase four
sophisticated American destroyers, as well as diesel submarines and
surveillance aircraft, a senior defense official said on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Clinton administration officials are expected to discuss
on Monday Taiwan's request for advanced arms, which officials in
Taipei say are needed to defend against what they perceive to be a
growing threat from China, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   No final decision has been made on the request, but the
Pentagon's recommendation is expected to prevail since defense
officials had argued more strenuously than other parts of the
administration for doing more to help Taiwan's military.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's recommendation, first reported in The Washington
Post, would postpone for at least a year consideration of a request
by Taiwan that had caused serious diplomatic strains between the
United States and China, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, China has strongly warned against the
sale of advanced weapons to Taiwan. At the same time, Taiwanese
military officials have made it clear that they consider the
weapons essential to the island's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of granting Taiwan's request to purchase four destroyers
equipped with the Navy's advanced Aegis radar systems, the Pentagon
has recommended a study of the island's maritime defenses, which
have grown increasingly weak. The Pentagon is already examining
Taiwan's air defenses and its anti-submarine warfare strategies.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pentagon called for deferring a decision on the most
advanced weapons, it has recommended going ahead with sales of a
number of other weapon systems, including air-to-air missiles and
ground-based radar, the official said. Details of those sales must
still be worked out, the official said, so there is not yet a cost
figure attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a robust package that will meet Taiwan's defense needs,''
the official said, ``but there are other things that need to be
studied further.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's request for the advanced weapons, particularly the four
Arleigh Burke cruisers with their sophisticated Aegis air defense
radars, have put the administration in a tough spot politically.
China, which considers Taiwan a renegade province, has signaled
that it would consider such a sale a violation of its sovereignty.
But Taiwan has considerable support in Congress, where the island's
strongest supporters seek a weapons sale as a price for one of
Clinton's other goals, improved trade ties with China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
